<HEADLINE>
SANTANA DOMINATES GRAMMY AWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Some may have laughed when Carlos Santana, the
psychedelic guitarist of the '70s, informed the public that an
angel called Metatron had prophesied his return to pop dominance.
After Wednesday night's 42nd Grammy Awards at the Staples Center
here, there are going to be a lot of young musicians praying to
Metatron.
</P>
<P>
   Santana was unbeatable. In every category that his group,
Santana, was nominated, it won, including the night's top honors _
album of the year (``Supernatural''), record of the year (an award
given to his single ``Smooth'') and song of the year (``Smooth''
again). By night's end, Santana had walked away with eight awards,
tying Michael Jackson's 1983 record for the most Grammys won in a
single year. Santana's ninth award, for song of the year, was
presented not to Santana, but to the song's writers, Rob Thomas of
Matchbox 20 and Itaal Shur. (The winners were selected by the
10,000 voting members of the National Academy of Recording Arts and
Sciences.)
</P>
<P>
   The night was one of vindication for Santana, who never won a
Grammy when he did his most important work with his bilingual,
polyrhythmic psychedelic jam band in the early '70s. (He had only
received one previous Grammy, for best rock instrumental in 1988.)
</P>
<P>
   With guest appearances from pop stars like Lauryn Hill, Eric
Clapton and Thomas, Santana's new album, ``Supernatural,'' rose to
No. 1, and became an across-the-board commercial, critical and now
Grammy triumph after years of diminishing returns on his recordings
and tours.
</P>
<P>
   Backstage, Santana said he was proud Wednesday night ``to be
able to demonstrate to the people that deepness and class can be as
profitable as shallowness and crass.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This validates the idea that quality and quantity can go
together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Santana's success was a running joke on stage before the
televised portion of the awards show even began. ``First, I want to
say thanks to Carlos Santana,'' Sheryl Crow said on accepting her
Grammy for best female rock vocalist, ``for not being in this
category.''
</P>
<P>
   Backstage, Santana was the main topic of conversation for
award-winners including Sting, B.B. King and Tito Puente, who
thanked Santana for the royalty checks he had received from ``Oye
Como Va.'' Chris Perez of the Chris Perez Band, which won an award
for best Latin rock or alternative album, said, ``I think I was
conceived to his music.''
</P>
<P>
   With strong performances early in the show from Marc Anthony and
Ibrahim Ferrer, as well as another fiery Ricky Martin production to
compete with his star-making appearance last year, the Grammys
Wednesday doubled as a victory parade for Latin music's latest
invasion of the American pop consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Martin, despite having leaped to pop stardom after
his performance at the Grammys last year, was not shown much love
by Grammy voters. In all four categories he was nominated in, he
lost, including best pop album and best male pop vocal performance,
both of which went to Sting.
</P>
<P>
   The fast-rhyming white rapper Eminem took both best rap album
and best rap solo performance. The Roots with Erykah Badu won for
best rap performance by a duo or group. The smooth-singing trio TLC
also had a strong night early on, collecting three rhythm-and-blues
awards, including best R-and-B album. The upbeat country
neotraditionalists the Dixie Chicks, who performed their murder
ballad ``Goodbye Earl,'' won two country awards, including best
country album for ``Fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with Latin-tinged music, the other major trend of last
year was the dominance of bubblegum teeny-pop. The genre, which
received poor representation live when the Backstreet Boys showed
their limitations with a medley of past Grammy-winning hits,
received one major award: the 19-year-old Christina Aguilera won
for best new artist. Representing the youth genre, her acceptance
speech was like that of a schoolgirl late with a homework
assignment. ``Omigod, you guys,'' she said. ``I seriously do not
have a speech prepared whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the veterans receiving their first Grammys were Cher for
best dance recording with her comeback hit ``Believe''; the hard
rock pioneers Black Sabbath, for best metal performance; June
Carter Cash, for best traditional folk album; Caetano Veloso, for
best world music album; and Barry White, for best male R-and-B
performance and best traditional R-and-B vocal performance.
</P>
<P>
   Sting sprang an upset in the male pop vocal category with a
victory for ``Brand New Day,'' beating out Anthony and Martin.
Sting also won for pop album.
</P>
<P>
   The award for best Mexican-American performance was given to a
Spaniard who was brought up in Mexico, Placido Domingo, for ``100
Anos de Mariachi.'' Tom Waits won for best contemporary folk album
with ``Mule Variations.'' And Diana Krall picked up best jazz vocal
album with ``When I Look In Your Eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   In other fields, Stravinsky was the Santana of the classical
world: Michael Tilson Thomas and the San Francisco Symphony's
performance of his ``Firebird'' and ``Rite of Spring'' won best
classical album, best engineered classical album and best
orchestral performance, while his ``Rake's Progress,'' conducted by
John Eliot Gardiner, won best opera recording.
</P>
</TEXT>
