<HEADLINE>
GEDNEY GETS HIS MEETING, SIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chris Gedney just wanted the Cardinals' brain trust to look him
in the eye and account for deserting him in his time of need. He
needed the closure.
</P>
<P>
   To his surprise, they took him up on it, and because they did,
he took them up on a one-year, make-good contract offer. He signed
Wednesday for the NFL minimum $440,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gedney's agent, Howard Bush, arranged a meeting for Gedney with
Cardinals General Manager Bob Ferguson, general counsel Michael
Bidwill, special assistant to the president Rod Graves, and Coach
Vince Tobin after Gedney passed a team physical three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   He needed that meeting before he would sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just my chance to vent, have them hear me, and treat me
as a person,'' Gedney said.
</P>
<P>
   Gedney missed last season following two major surgeries for
ulcerative colitis. As the second surgery approached last July, he
received a phone call from Ferguson telling him the final two years
of his contract had been voided. He'd been cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand it's a business, but the way they handled it was
what I was so appalled at,'' said Gedney's wife, Kathy.
</P>
<P>
   She seemed to speak for the community. It was perceived publicly
as a cold-hearted move, and the team took a huge public relations
hit.
</P>
<P>
   The move was unpopular with the players and coaches as well.
According to Gedney, Tobin told him in their meeting that the
organization embarrassed itself by severing Gedney's support
system. He no longer had access to the team's medical personnel,
training facilities, nor was he allowed to come to practice after
recovery to be with his former teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Coach Tobin said meant a lot to me, to have someone say
that to my face,'' Gedney said.
</P>
<P>
   Gedney said he was further chafed when the Cardinals called in
December and made overtures about bringing him back for the final
month last season and then failed to follow through. So he and his
family were skeptical when the team expressed renewed interest this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Yet on Wednesday, Gedney, his wife and their two children were
at a place they said they never expected to be, on center stage at
the Cardinals' Tempe facility. Even team owner Bill Bidwill, who
claimed he didn't know the Gedneys were coming over for a news
conference, stumbled across them on their way out and shook
Gedney's hand.
</P>
<P>
   Gedney has received a clean bill of health not only from his
personal physicians but also those of the team. He is believed to
be the first professional athlete to come back from this condition.
</P>
<P>
   To Gedney's surprise, the Cardinals, suddenly short on tight
ends and perhaps wanting to stop the public relations bleeding,
were a willing partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been easy for them to ignore me and not open up
that can of worms again,'' Gedney said. ``My hat's off to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Gedney lost his salary, the Cardinals continued to pay
his medical benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5 Gedney, 29, has returned to his playing weight of
257 pounds after dropping to 215. Dr. Wayne Kuhl, a Cardinals
physician, described his recovery as ``remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Cardinals continued their run at unrestricted
free-agent defensive end Marco Coleman, who became expendable with
the Washington Redskins after they signed Pro Bowl free agent Bruce
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman's Atlanta-based agent, Brian Ransom, listened to a
last-minute offer from the Redskins after the Cardinals seemingly
had gained the inside track.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working on a couple of things,'' Ransom said. ``We're
trying to sort through it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
