<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY BRINGS UNDERDOG CAMPAIGN TO WASHINGTON STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT McCLURE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Seeking at least a symbolic victory for his campaign,
underdog Democrat Bill Bradley on Wednesday launched an intense,
five-day bid to come from behind with the help of
independent-minded Washington voters.
</P>
<P>
   After losing to Vice President Al Gore in Iowa, New Hampshire
and Delaware, Bradley jetted to Seattle in a longshot bid to look
like a winner in the non-binding primary vote here next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Calculating that a win here could catapult him to victories a
week later in delegate-rich New York and California, Bradley made a
beeline for a campaign rally Wednesday night at Seattle Community
College.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington state has a real opportunity to send a message
across the country,'' Bradley said. ``The independent voter of
Washington is going to decide who's going to be the next
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Facing an enthusiastic group of about 350 people _ mostly of
student age and young professionals _ Bradly spoke of ``a world of
new possibilities, guided by goodness.''
</P>
<P>
   He repeatedly emphasized his support for handgun registration,
universal health care, improved race relations, environmental
protection and better schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're living in a time of unprecedented prosperity
when we can do things we could never do before, and I personally
think we should be fixing our roof when the sun is shining.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley spent five minutes of his 28-minute speech on the vice
president's record, recalling among other things, Gore's votes in
Congress supporting tax breaks for segregated Southern academies
and Gore's entanglement in the 1996 campaign fund-rasing scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley emphasized that while Gore supports registration of new
handguns, he is for registration of all handguns. And Bradley said
his health care plan would insure all Americans while Gore's would
leave millions uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   Although pundits have begun to write off Bradley because of his
early Eastern losses, fewer than 250,000 Democrats have actually
voted so far. Here in Washington, approximately 1 million votes are
expected to be split between the Democratic and Republican
presidential candidates next week.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington primary is a non-binding ``beauty contest.'' But
it is Bradley's last chance to shine before primaries March 7 in
New York, California and primaries or caucuses in 14 other states.
Those states include Washington, where caucuses will select most of
the state's delegates to the Republican and Democratic conventions
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   In the week after that, another 11 states hold primaries or
caucuses, effectively deciding the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Bradley swung into Washington late Wednesday, his
campaign had started firing away at frontrunner Gore, who is backed
by much of the state's Democratic political establishment,
including Gov. Gary Locke.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to slice into Gore's double-digit lead in the polls,
Bradley launched a radio ad questioning Gore's votes in Congress on
abortion and gun control, and his stance on health care in the
current campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington has the distinction of being the first state where
(Bradley) has run these negative radio attack ads,'' said Todd
Webster of the Gore campaign. ``He is a desperate candidate running
a desperate campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley staffers acknowledged they are banking a lot on
Washington, but denied they are desperate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Bradley is a man of longstanding conviction who has been
honest with the American people about who he is and who he always
has been,'' said Bradley campaign spokesman Mo Elleithee.
</P>
<P>
   Elleithee said Gore has mis-stated several of Bradley's
positions. In a debate Monday night, for example, Gore said
Bradley's plan for medical care would stick Medicaid recipients
with $150-a-month vouchers, Elleithee said, when in fact Bradley's
plan would put Medicaid recipients on the same medical plan enjoyed
by federal employees.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether Bradley will stick with his
previous strategy, seeking votes in the relatively liberal Seattle
area, or whether he branches out to the rest of the state.
Wednesday, he opened campaign offices in Spokane and Vancouver.
Another is planned in Tacoma.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley plans to campaign in Washington at least until Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's anything Washington voters have made clear in past
elections, it's that they are fiercely independent,'' Elleithee
said.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, Bradley was introduced by Seattle Mayor Paul Schell,
who Bradley said was the first elected official to endorse him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We in Washington don't take our orders from Iowa or New
Hampshire or the national media,'' Schell said. ``We have a chance
to send a message next Tuesday that will be heard around the nation
and will affect New York and California and all the other states
and change the course of this election.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Joel Connelly contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
