<HEADLINE>
BELTRE A DODGER AT HEART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ After an offseason of distraction in which
Adrian Beltre eventually had his request for free agency denied _
though the appeal process continues _ he's finally found a place to
get away from it all. He's found peace on the field.
</P>
<P>
   So with his allegiance still pledged to the Dodgers _ and all
signs pointing toward the Dodgers retaining his rights _ there is
one uncertainty in Beltre's mind. The 20-year-old third baseman is
wondering how he's going to be treated by the home fans when the
club begins the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they understand that I wasn't trying to do anything,
that it was my right,'' Beltre said as he took part in his first
spring workout Wednesday. ``I hope they still like me. I want to
get in there and have things be normal like they were last year.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other issues, but Beltre doesn't wish to discuss them.
There's a pending hearing on a grievance filed by the players
association, and also ongoing contract talks that could end the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides are eager to end the case and that could happen by
the end of the week, sources said. Beltre's agent, Scott Boras, and
Dodgers managing partner and CEO Bob Daly are expected to talk
either today or Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite not needing to lock up Beltre with a long-term contract,
the Dodgers seem willing to do a deal if it eats away an
arbitration year. To do that, it would have to be a three-year
deal. But it's unlikely the Dodgers would spend more than $4
million since Beltre has less than two years major-league
experience. There is time to make a deal because a hearing is weeks
away.
</P>
<P>
   All of this has been difficult on Beltre, who missed the first
month of winter ball waiting for commissioner Bud Selig to make his
ruling in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a little bit tough because I'm one of those guys who
likes to concentrate on just baseball,'' Beltre said. ``I don't
like to be worrying about what's in the paper or whatever. I just
like to come here and practice and play baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to stay here. I'm happy to be here. What's happened is
in the past. I came here to practice. The business part is between
(agent Scott Boras and Dodgers managing partner Bob Daly.)''
</P>
<P>
   __ Short(stop) and long of it: Jose Vizcaino wants a chance to
win the starting shortstop job, and manager Davey Johnson said
he'll give Vizcaino a shot. But for the second consecutive season
it appears Vizcaino will be the Dodgers' primary utility infielder.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's invaluable in the role I envision him in,'' Johnson said.
``Can he play every day? I'm sure he'd like to. But I like him in
the role of moving around.''
</P>
<P>
   Vizcaino started 40 games at shortstop, 15 at second base and
five at third base last season. Instead, Alex Cora is the favorite
at shortstop with Juan Castro and Kevin Elster in position to
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   __ Addressing the troops: Before Wednesday's first full-squad
workout, Johnson addressed the team during a 30-minute session on
one of the practice fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them I've been waiting for this a long time, to get
back here and get with it,'' Johnson said. ``I explained that I
probably had the worst year of anyone in the group and I want to
change that, and I need their help.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
