<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6800 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-BAGWELL-HN     02-24 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BAGWELL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ Never has a season outlook been clearer for Jeff
Bagwell.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As he unpacked Wednesday afternoon at the Astros'
spring-training complex, Bagwell had a few items less to worry
about, i.e., glasses and contact lenses. For the first time in his
professional career, the All-Star first baseman will take the field
this season without needing any vision aids after undergoing laser
eye surgery in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have a clearer look on life,'' Bagwell said on
the eve of full-squad workouts. ``It's the best thing I've ever
done. I'm hoping this will be the year I'm able to see all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell, who is entering his 10th season with the Astros, is the
latest in a growing list of pro athletes who have sought improved
vision through the surgical procedure known as Lasik, which stands
for laser in-situ keratomileusis.
</P>
<P>
   Now, just as impressive as Bagwell's twice being a 30/30 man in
home runs and stolen bases is his 20/15 vision.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell, who has worn contacts throughout his career, only
recently began considering the laser surgery. His contacts were
constantly irritating his eyes, and he often would have to step out
of the batter's box to readjust them. Dirt would also get into his
eyes, causing more problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was horrible,'' he said. ``It was part of the game I
dreaded night in and night out. It's frustrating when you're up at
the plate and sometimes you can't see the pitcher's face. That's
scary.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of ups and downs you go through with your eyes
over the course of a major-league season. Each city brings
different problems: allergies, pollens, dryness, wind. That stuff
gets old.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert B. Gillett, team ophthalmologist for the Rockets,
Comets and Aeros, performed Bagwell's Lasik surgery Dec. 29 at the
Laser Center-Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's painless and quick,'' said Gillett, who has also
performed the procedure on pro golfer Steve Elkington. ``Hopefully,
it will improve Jeff's comfort level.''
</P>
<P>
   Known as ``flap and zap'' in the medical industry, Lasik treats
the middle layers of the cornea to correct nearsightedness,
farsightedness and astigmatism. The procedure involves a surgeon's
folding back tissue from the surface of the eyeball while a laser
reshapes the cornea to improve the patient's vision to 20/20 or
better. The actual application of the laser takes 10 to 90 seconds,
in most cases.
</P>
<P>
   Total cost: about $2,400 per eye.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts predict more than 1.5 million Lasik procedures
will be done this year in the United States, an increase from an
estimated 1 million in 1999 and 500,000 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Lasik has been widely considered a success, and its low risk _
complication rates are less than 1 percent, Gillett says _ has it
gaining popularity among professional athletes. Among those to have
undergone the procedure are major-league players Greg Maddux and
Bernie Williams, Dallas Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman, and pro
golfers Tiger Woods, Corey Pavin and Tom Kite.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux, the ace of the Atlanta Braves' pitching staff, underwent
the procedure last July and made his scheduled start two days
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It flat-out fixed them,'' Maddux said. ``I see good now. I
think I'm better than 20-20. Incredible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather go get my eyes done again than go to the dentist.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell, who is nearsighted with astigmatism, spoke with other
big-leaguers and learned of potential risks before making a
decision. He decided the rewards outweighed the risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard all about it and really was going to do it, but my
wife (Ericka) was my guinea pig. She did it first,'' Bagwell said.
``I felt the worst thing that could happen was for me to wear
contacts. I already do that. I was very confident going into it
that everything would be all right. Fortunately for me, everything
has worked out perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 31 years old, Bagwell can throw away the contacts after
wearing them since seventh grade.
</P>
<P>
   So how will this affect his on-field performance for the
upcoming season? Consider this: Even with vision problems, Bagwell
is a career .304 hitter with 263 home runs since breaking into the
majors in 1991. He was the National League Rookie of the Year that
season and added Most Valuable Player honors in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the difference will be,'' Bagwell said.
``Only time will tell. The only thing I was after was being able to
see well or 20/20, as everybody pushes as the benchmark, instead of
seeing 20/20 for a while and seeing 20/40 for a while. I just want
to be more consistent with my eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   As of now, there is no certified correlation between Lasik
surgery and improved athletic performance. And in some cases, the
correction might not be permanent.
</P>
<P>
   But for those willing to take the risk and spend a few bucks,
the results can be astonishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is any question that eyesight is one of
the primary attributes of all good hitters,'' Astros general
manager Gerry Hunsicker said. ``Ted Williams was arguably the best
hitter that has ever played the game, and he was the first one to
emphasize that. It's impossible to be a good hitter without having
superior eyesight. With that said, I don't think this is the
cure-all. I don't think we can look for something magical to
happen, but I think it's definitely an asset.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Dr. Gillett will monitor Bagwell's progress. In
his Houston office, an autographed picture of Bagwell hangs on the
wall with the following inscription:
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks for making my life more enjoyable. In the year 2000 I
might actually see what I hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Joked Gillett: ``We're expecting 85 homers this season.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
