r a BC-ASSAULT-AZR &LR;      02-24 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASSAULT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 AIR TRAVELERS PLEAD GUILTY TO FLIGHT-ATTENDANT ASSAULT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER CORBETT  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two men face up to a year in prison for verbally assaulting two
America West flight attendants on an October flight, an incident
that reveals the growing tensions in air travel.
</P>
<P>
   John Carlucci, 25, and Brian Scalcione, 26, both of Queens,
N.Y., entered guilty pleas Feb. 8 in U.S. District Court in Kansas,
according to U.S. Attorney Jackie Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Their arrest stems from an incident Oct. 21 when they were
returning to New York from Las Vegas. After a brief layover in
Phoenix, Carlucci and Scalcione, who admitted that they had been
drinking, clashed with the flight crew, the attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   They both verbally assaulted the two flight attendants when
Scalcione was refused a drink, and Carlucci admitted that he
threatened the flight attendants, according to Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The flight was diverted to Wichita, Kan., and the two men were
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Air rage has become an occupational hazard for flight attendants
and threatens the safety of passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The Association of Flight Attendants is pushing for federal
legislation to increase penalties to $25,000 from $10,000 for
passengers who assault flight crew members.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to tolerate it,'' said Phil Dixon, an America
West flight attendant and union representative.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, there were 272 unruly-passenger incidents reported to
the Federal Aviation Administration and 140 last year, FAA
spokeswoman Kathryn Creedy said.
</P>
<P>
   The decline is probably because of more publicity about how
airlines are pressing charges against unruly passengers, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent case involved a US Airways passenger who became
belligerent and tried to open a door during a Feb. 9 flight before
he was wrestled to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   In another incident last year, a Las Vegas-based flight
attendant was punched by a passenger on a Cleveland-to-Las Vegas
flight.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA has added security inspectors at eight airports,
including Phoenix Sky Harbor International Airport, to investigate
incidents, Creedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Air-travel tensions have also increased the number of complaints
from passengers about airline employees, among other things.
Customer-service complaints more than doubled last year, to 4,175,
according to U.S. Department of Transportation records.
</P>
<P>
   In the America West assault case, the two unruly passengers,
Carlucci and Scalcione, face a maximum one-year sentence in federal
prison.
</P>
<P>
   However, a plea deal is likely to result in a lighter sentence,
Dixon said.
</P>
<P>
   The union approved of a plea bargain that would sentence
Carlucci to 45 days in jail, three years of probation, a $1,427
fine for diverting the flight, alcohol-abuse and anger-management
treatment, and a written or verbal apology to the flight crew,
Dixon said. Scalcione faces the same sentence except he would serve
no jail time, under the deal. No sentence date has been set. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
