<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6803 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      02-24 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO GETS PROMOTED, AND WHY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If we all made widgets, it would be easy to tell who deserved
the biggest raise or the next promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Chris makes eight perfect widgets a day. Lee makes six. Pat
makes 10, but three have quality-control problems. Chris wins.
</P>
<P>
   Most of our jobs aren't that easy to measure. In the real work
world, co-workers often wonder why one person is promoted and
another is not, or why one employee gets rave reviews and big
raises while another hard worker does not.
</P>
<P>
   Two court cases involving tenure decisions _ one at the
University of Missouri and one at the University of Kansas _ offer
a public glimpse into the squishy ground on which hiring and
promotion decisions are made.
</P>
<P>
   A federal appellate court last week upheld MU's denial of tenure
to Carol M. Lawrence, a faculty member in the accountancy school.
This week, a different federal court trial is focusing on KU's
tenure denial to Cynthia Annett, a member of the ecology and
evolutionary biology faculty.
</P>
<P>
   Both cases involve allegations of sex discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Employment laws being what they are, leveling charges of
discrimination _ because of sex, race, ethnicity, age, religion or
disability _ is the legal recourse for workers who think they are
unfairly passed over for promotion.
</P>
<P>
   The tenure-track world of academia may be a tad different from
other workplaces. But when the plaintiffs' cases alleged mixed
signals and flexible criteria for evaluations in their departments,
their complaints mirrored those of many in the work force and are
worth a further look.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the three appellate judges reviewing Lawrence's case
agreed that there was no evidence of sex discrimination in her
tenure denial. They used one paragraph to affirm the lower court's
decision. What's interesting is that the third appellate judge used
nine pages to dissent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence suggests that Lawrence met the expectations which
were presented to her, and she only fell short when the critical
decision-makers changed the standards as they applied to her,''
wrote Judge Theodore McMillian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the evidence ... indicating that Lawrence was misled
into believing that she was meeting the applicable tenure standards
and that male tenure candidates were not held to the same standards
_ a genuine factual dispute remains as to the truthfulness of the
Curators' proffered reasons for the adverse tenure decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again: Why does one person get promoted and another
doesn't?
</P>
<P>
   Does he or she fail to make as many perfect widgets as the
worker at the next desk? Is there a stinky personality problem that
doesn't show up on evaluation checklists? Do standards shift
because of intentional or unintentional discrimination?
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence and Annett thought they worked as hard, as well and in
as good faith as others who were granted tenure. Even when
dissecting their cases in court, fine minds disagree as to whether
they were or were not wronged.
</P>
<P>
   Why is one person promoted and another not?
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, after the widget counting is complete, not even a fly
on the wall knows for sure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-00 0023EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
