<HEADER>
A6806 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-PHYSICIAN-THERAPY-KAN     02-24 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHYSICIAN-THERAPY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE RULES IN FAVOR OF PHYSICIAN PRACTICING CHELATION THERAPY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An administrative judge has rejected charges of fraud and
negligence leveled against Gladstone physician Edward McDonagh over
his use of a treatment known as chelation.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Board of Healing Arts wanted to discipline McDonagh
for the way he uses chelation _ a therapy long accepted to treat
metal poisoning _ to treat circulatory diseases.
</P>
<P>
   An Administrative Hearing Commission judge found that on each of
13 counts leveled by the board McDonagh ``is not subject to
discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 70-page ruling, Willard Reine noted last month that the
board contemplated in 1989 making a specific rule against the uses
of chelation employed by McDonagh and decided against such a ban.
If the healing arts panel was opposed to the unconventional
approach, Reine wrote, it should have said so rather than penalize
McDonagh for a longstanding practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board should have informed the doctors...about its
position on chelation therapy rather than filing a discipline case
against a doctor who has practiced with the board's knowledge since
1962,'' Reine wrote in his decision.
</P>
<P>
   But last week the healing arts board appealed the ruling in
Circuit Court in Jefferson City. Its attorney said the case will
help to clarify when the state can stop a physician from using
methods it finds scientifically invalid even if those methods
maintain support from part of the medical community.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamental goal is to stop (McDonagh) from practicing
this kind of medicine,'' Kansas City lawyer Glenn Bradford said.
``We also want to see if we can make some law on what Missouri law
accepts as a bona fide school of thought on medical issues.''
</P>
<P>
   By pursuing the McDonagh case, Bradford said, the board can
better establish those areas where it can prohibit some forms of
alternative medicine it believes are based on flawed science, even
when the methods might be popular among some doctors.
</P>
<P>
   One of McDonagh's attorneys, Jefferson City lawyer Max
Humphreys, said that appeal could backfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Board of Healing Arts is taking a chance if it wants to
make law,'' Humphreys said. ``The administrative hearing commission
isn't overturned very often. The law they make might not be the law
they want.''
</P>
<P>
   The board has tried to discipline McDonagh since 1991, when he
was subjected to a series of questions about basic medical
practices in an oral exam. When McDonagh failed to provide correct
answers about cardiopulmonary resuscitation, antibiotics,
hypertension and a handful of other topics, the board ordered him
to take a written exam. He failed twice and his license was revoked
in January 1995.
</P>
<P>
   That revocation, however, was put on hold while McDonagh pursued
an appeal. Then McDonagh was recertified by the American
Osteopathic Board of Family Physicians and the board reinstated his
license.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the healing arts board pursued McDonagh for a
handful of chelation cases they claim he mishandled. In a case
first filed in the summer of 1995 _ later dropped and refiled in
late 1996 _ the board made the allegations dismissed by Reine.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, now under appeal by the board, McDonagh was
accused of botching the care of a patient who came to him suffering
from gangrene, later fell into a coma and eventually lost his right
leg to amputation. Other patients discussed in the charges received
chelation after coming to McDonagh for memory loss, joint pain,
depression, lightheadedness and a series of other complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Most at issue in all the cases was McDonagh's use of chelation.
</P>
<P>
   Chelation first came into medical use in pre-World War II
Germany to cure shipyard workers exposed to lead-based paints.
Given by intravenous drip, chelation delivers ethylene diamine
tetra-acetic acid, or EDTA, to the bloodstream. That chemical mix
bonds with metals in the blood and then leaves the body harmlessly
in a patient's urine.
</P>
<P>
   A minority in the medical community believes chelation also can
clear plaque that forms on artery walls and reverse many
circulatory problems.
</P>
<P>
   The healing arts board contends that chelation, as used by
McDonagh and a growing number of physicians, is worthless for those
kinds of ailments.
</P>
<P>
   In taking that position, the board stands with the mainstream of
American medicine. Among those rejecting chelation as a treatment
for vascular disease are the U.S. Food and Drug Administration, the
National Institutes of Health, the American Medical Association,
the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention and the American
Heart Association. Those groups reject both the theory behind the
practice and case studies used to support its validity.
</P>
<P>
   But McDonagh, with support from sizable alternative medicine
advocates such as the American College for Advancement in Medicine,
counters that chelation is a medical breakthrough capable of
sparing millions from more dangerous stopgap treatments such as
heart bypass surgery and angioplasty.
</P>
<P>
   Reine took no position on the effectiveness of McDonagh's
methods. Rather he noted that both the board and McDonagh offered
studies to bolster their evaluations of the treatment and that none
was definitive.
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that the osteopath's use of chelation was at least
not dangerous, that all his patients were well aware that it was
unusual treatment and that it came with no guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who go through this treatment revise their diet,
give up smoking, exercise and undergo the chelation treatments,''
Humphreys said. ``And they're getting relief. Something is working
for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
