r a BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      02-24 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRINGING BULLETS TO A BARBECUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ There was something missing, some minor detail I'd
overlooked and couldn't quite put my finger on.
</P>
<P>
   I'd packed a basket and gone to Encanto Park in central Phoenix
for a picnic. There was a table available under an olive tree.
Nearby was a barbecue grill. The cooler was stocked with burgers
and coleslaw and the appropriate beverages. There were buns and
chips and a bag of charcoal briquettes.
</P>
<P>
   I'd remembered to bring the radio and the Frisbee, the baseball
gloves and a ball, extra napkins, a blanket, condiments,
silverware, a book to read, marshmallows, skewers on which to cook
the marshmallows. Still, there was something lacking.
</P>
<P>
   Then it hit me _ firearms.
</P>
<P>
   What I needed was a gun. A 9mm, maybe. Or a shotgun. Perhaps
even one of the ``pre-ban'' assault rifles I see advertised for
sale in the newspaper. And of course lots of ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, that would be illegal in a Phoenix city park, at
least for now.
</P>
<P>
   Within the next week or so, however, the Arizona Legislature may
act to put the bullets back in our barbecues.
</P>
<P>
   A bill passed by the state House of Representatives would
prohibit any government entity except the state from restricting
firearms or ammunition in public places.
</P>
<P>
   A number of local government officials and police organizations
complained about the proposal, but it didn't stop the
necktie-wearing militia at the state House from putting the
Saturday Night Special back into the Sunday morning picnic.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Senate has yet to act on the measure, and the
governor may also have a say. In the meantime, lawmakers are being
bombarded with the most potent ammunition militant gun owners have
at their disposal _ e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earlier this week I got hundreds,'' Sen. Chris Cummiskey said.
He'll get more before it's over. Cummiskey supports the right to
bear arms, but, like some others, says the proposed new law goes
too far.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he's unfamiliar with the words of the poet:
</P>
<P>
   `` A loaf of bread, a jug of wine and . . . a loaded Glock 17.''
Or was it a Ruger P97? Or a .45-caliber Colt Defender?
</P>
<P>
   The authors of the new gun law are the same politicians who
preach less big government and more local control; the same people
who, at the same time, decided it's the state's job to close every
strip club and adult entertainment establishment in Arizona, going
so far as to make it illegal to display what one bill describes as
``male genitals in a discernibly turgid state even if completely
and opaquely covered.''
</P>
<P>
   Should that law pass, along with the one allowing weapons in
public places, the following two assumptions could be made (a la
Mae West) about any man approaching you in a park.
</P>
<P>
   1. That IS a gun in his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   2. He's NOT glad to see you.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill McGibbon and other sponsors of the
guns-guns-everywhere bill didn't want to speak with me. If they
had, I'm sure they'd have said their intent is to protect our
constitutional rights.
</P>
<P>
   It's the criminals we need to worry about, they'd say. It's the
criminals we need protection from, not law-abiding citizens. As
such, these brave legislators believe their constituents should be
permitted to carry weapons wherever they want.
</P>
<P>
   Except, of course, at the state Capitol, where firearms are
strictly prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   Near as I can tell, not one of Arizona's constitutionally
sensitive legislators has proposed a law that would allow armed
citizens to visit the offices of elected officials.
</P>
<P>
   Really, can you blame them? &QL; 
Reach Montini at Ed.Montini(at)Arizona &QL; 
Republic.com or (602) 444-8978. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-00 0026EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
