<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 00:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6808 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-KAN &LR;      02-24 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KC MAN CHARGED IN DRAGGING DEATH OF 6-YEAR-OLD BOY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TANYANIKA SAMUELS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City man accused of stealing a Chevy Blazer and
dragging a 6-year-old Independence boy to his death Tuesday had
been released from jail just hours earlier, despite an outstanding
warrant for his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Kim L. Davis, 34, was arraigned Wednesday in Jackson County
Circuit Court and charged with second-degree murder, second-degree
robbery, abuse of a child and kidnapping. He was denied bail.
</P>
<P>
   If found guilty on all charges, he could be sentenced to at
least two life sentences. Davis is due back in court at 9 a.m.
March 8 for a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The incident started when Christy Robel of Independence parked
her 1991 Chevrolet Blazer in front of the Mr. Goodcents Subs &AMP;
Pastas at 3010 S. Missouri 291.
</P>
<P>
   Robel left the keys in the ignition and went inside the eatery,
leaving her son, Jake, strapped in his seat belt in the back seat,
according to court documents.
</P>
<P>
   Independence police initially said that a man, who restaurant
employees said had been loitering outside, tried to shove the boy
from the Blazer before fleeing. But court documents state Christy
Robel ran outside, opened the Blazer's rear door and tried to grab
her son.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses told police the man slowed down, looked at the rear of
the vehicle in both the rear-view mirror and over his shoulder,
then sped off.
</P>
<P>
   The door had closed. And Jake was trapped, dangling outside from
the seat belt wrapped around his waist.
</P>
<P>
   Robel screamed for the thief to stop, but he sped off south on
Missouri 291, according to court documents.
</P>
<P>
   Ron and Kella Wells of Independence were driving along Missouri
291 when they saw the boy being dragged. Kella Wells called
Independence police.
</P>
<P>
   Other drivers also saw Jake and followed the Blazer onto
Interstate 70, then Noland Road, where the Wellses and brothers
Fred and Brad Byam cornered the Blazer. They tied the man's legs
until police arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County Prosecutor Bob Beaird called them heroes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people wouldn't have done it, but they did,'' he
said. ``The citizens involved are heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, Beaird learned that Davis should have been behind
bars.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was released from Carroll County Jail in Carrollton, Mo.,
after serving time for municipal charges in Independence.
</P>
<P>
   His release appears to be the result of miscommunication by
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   According to Carroll County Sheriff Joe Arnold, his office
received a fax from Independence police about 11 a.m. Tuesday
saying Davis had paid his $170 fine and should be released.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we get the word to turn him loose, we have to,'' Arnold
said. ``He's a free man.''
</P>
<P>
   But a state warrant had been issued Feb. 16 for Davis' arrest
for a probation violation.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Independence nor Carroll County checked to see whether
any outstanding warrants existed _ normally a standard procedure
when prisoners are about to be released.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, we didn't know there were outstanding warrants,''
Arnold said. ``If it's one of our prisoners, we check to see if
anyone else wants them before we let them go. The people (police
departments) we're housing them for, they tell us when to turn them
loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Independence Police Chief Gary George said his department checks
for outstanding warrants when prisoners are booked and when they
are released.
</P>
<P>
   But, George said, the warrant was issued after Davis had been
booked. And Davis wasn't an Independence prisoner when he was
released, George said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't release him,'' George said. ``He is their
prisoner....If he's in their jail, he's their prisoner.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jackson County prosecutor was reluctant to assign blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we would have preferred if he would have been
held,'' Beaird said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' criminal record spans some nine years and includes a 1991
conviction for robbery and stealing charges, and a 1999 conviction
for second-degree attempted robbery and resisting arrest after he
tried to steal a car.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Beaird said, Wyandotte County also issued a warrant
for Davis' arrest on drug possession charges.
</P>
<P>
   Back at their home Wednesday, the family of Jake Robel tried to
come to terms with the sudden emptiness his death left.
</P>
<P>
   Jake experienced severe complications at his birth in 1993 and
spent his first two or three months at Children's Mercy Hospital,
said Carol Robel, his grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first year was a real close one,'' she said. ``But after
that, he just blossomed. We have a very dedicated extended family
that came together during that crisis, and we're coming together
now. We're praying together and we're praying individually.''
</P>
<P>
   Jake was a kindergartner at Glendale Elementary School in
Independence.
</P>
<P>
   Three school counselors spent Wednesday visiting with students
and staff, helping them to cope with grief and anger, Principal
Galen Hoff said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are having to work through a lot of emotion here,'' Hoff
said. ``The children, they only know that Jake won't be here
anymore. But adults are dealing with this on a level children don't
yet understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Counselors later told administrators they, too, were affected by
Jake's death. Assistant Superintendent Patty Schumacher said the
death also disturbed district administrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one has just brought us to our knees,'' she wept.
</P>
<P>
   Jake's family also was ``struggling'' with their emotions toward
Davis, Carol Robel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to feel compassion in place of anger. It's just
very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   The man accused in her grandson's death was escorted into court
Wednesday morning while wearing a bulletproof vest over his red
sweatshirt and baggy black sweatpants. Large bruises stretched
across his forehead from the struggle Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Jake's family eyed Davis and sobbed.
</P>
<P>
   When Jackson County Circuit Judge Twila Rigby entered a
not-guilty plea and told Davis he would be held without bond,
family members said ``Yes!'' and applauded.
</P>
<P>
   Beaird met with Jake's family Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The allegations are hard for everyone to deal with,'' Beaird
said. ``It's pretty hard stuff to talk to the family and not be
affected.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused to stifle tears and cleared his throat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm supposed to be the prosecutor and not be affected by this.
But obviously I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Jake Robel is survived by his parents Christy and Greg Robel.
</P>
<P>
   Visitation will be today from 5 to 9 p.m. at Sheil Colonial
Chapel, 11924 47th St. in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral services will be at noon on Friday at St. Mark's
Catholic Church, 3736 Lee's Summit Road in Independence.
</P>
<P>
   Burial will follow at Mount Olivet Cemetery &AMP; Chapel Mausoleum,
where Jake's father is the groundskeeper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
