A6809 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-RUSSELL-STOVER-KAN &LR;      02-24 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSELL-STOVER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSEL STOVER TO CLOSE SOUTH CAROLINA PLANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Russell Stover Candies will close one of its plants because of
lower-than-expected candy sales.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City company said Wednesday that it would shut down
its Marion, S.C., plant, which has been making Russell Stover candy
for 30 years. The plant will close April 28, and its 836 employees
will face an uncertain future in an area that already has 12
percent unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad day in Marion,'' said the town's mayor, Bobby
Gerald.
</P>
<P>
   Robinn Weber, vice president of human resources for Russell
Stover, said the company's oldest plant was being closed because
the company can make more candy than it is selling. The sale of
boxed chocolates, its main product, has been less than hoped.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Stover, the country's largest boxed-chocolate maker,
does not disclose sales figures, but Forbes magazine recently
estimated its annual revenue to be $600 million.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Stover Candies began in Denver in 1923 with Russell and
Clara Stover making candies and dipping them in chocolate. In 1960
the company was sold to Louis Ward, who is credited with making it
a national firm. Ward died in 1996, and the company is now headed
by his sons, Tom and Scott.
</P>
<P>
   Today, most of the company's sales are assumed to still come
from the sale of boxed chocolates, with the Whitman's Sampler its
most popular product. But the company also has sought to diversify
its offerings. For example, it has begun to sell candy bars.
</P>
<P>
   Its boxed-chocolate business is facing more competition,
including giant Hershey Chocolate USA.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Stover candy will continue to be made at its plants in
Corsicana, Texas; Clarksville, Va.; Cookeville, Tenn.; Iola and
Abilene, Kan.; and Montrose, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   The South Carolina plant was one of three Russell Stover plants
with union workers. Weber said that had nothing to do with the
decision to close the plant.
</P>
<P>
   The South Carolina plant made only boxed chocolates. It also was
one of the company's most labor-intensive operations, with many
employees dipping pieces of fruit in chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   A representative of South Carolina Gov. Jim Hodges sought to
avert the closing by discussing financial incentives available to
companies doing business in the state. But Russell Stover said that
because the issue was one of producing too much candy, there were
no inducements that could keep it open.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald said Wednesday that the candy plant's fate was clear and
that it was time to market the plant to other businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're history,'' he said of Russell Stover's presence in
Marion.
</P>
<P>
   Marion has a population of 7,000, and its county has 36,000
residents. Russell Stover workers are expected to boost the
unemployment rate to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Weber said Russell Stover was cooperating with government
agencies to help workers find new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Taylor, business agent for the union that represents
about half the plant's workers, said they were paid an average of
$10 an hour _ good wages for the area.
</P>
<P>
   He said Russell Stover executives had agreed to discuss a
severance package for the workers. He said he hoped the
negotiations would be successful and a severance package would in
place when the plant closed in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a tough time, but I'm hoping we can get some
money in their pocket when it comes time for them to hit the
highway,'' Taylor said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
