<HEADER>
A6812 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-NICHOLS-FRAUD-KAN &LR;      02-24 1644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NICHOLS-FRAUD-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER NICHOLS CHAIRMAN, OTHERS FACE FEDERAL FRAUD CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN MARGOLIES  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former J.C. Nichols Co. Chairman Lynn L. McCarthy was charged
Wednesday in a 12-count federal indictment alleging he defrauded
the company of more than $150 million in cash and property. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also named in the indictment were Walter Janes, 65, Nichols'
former chief financial officer and treasurer, and Charles
Schleicher, 70, the company's one-time lawyer and a former director
of Nichols, developer of the Country Club Plaza. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy, 67, Janes and Schleicher were variously charged with
racketeering and racketeering conspiracy charges, mail fraud, wire
fraud, interstate transport of stolen funds and money laundering in
a series of transactions running from 1987 to 1995. The indictment
asks that they be made to forfeit to the government at least $15
million, allegedly the minimum losses caused by the three. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All three defendants, through their lawyers, denied the
allegations and vowed they would mount a vigorous defense. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The indictment, returned by a federal grand jury in Kansas City,
came after a four-year investigation by the FBI and the criminal
division of the Internal Revenue Service. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The probe was triggered by allegations of insider dealing that
surfaced after Allen &AMP; Co., a New York investment banking firm,
sued Nichols five years ago after Allen's unsuccessful attempt to
take over Nichols for $50 million. Many of the transactions in
question were reversed as part of a settlement of the civil
litigation in mid-1995. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy's attorney, Curtis Woods of Sonnenschein Nath &AMP;
Rosenthal, said he was ``perplexed'' by the charges, ``which were
resolved to everyone's satisfaction in civil litigation that was
mediated by a federal judge and approved by another federal judge
five years ago.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep in mind,'' Woods said, ``that the litigation involved the
reversal of all these transactions. ... So it's just very
perplexing to find ourselves five years later defending
transactions that, in some cases, date back 10 years. It doesn't
seem fair.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Schleicher's attorney, Jim Wyrsch of Wyrsch Hobbs Mirakian &AMP;
Lee, denounced the indictment as an attack on the legal profession
and said his client had ``always maintained the highest moral and
ethical standards.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because business transactions are complex does not mean
that they are illegal,'' Wyrsch said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Janes' attorney, Gerald Handley, said prosecutors were trying
``to criminalize conduct that's been settled already.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Lanza, a spokesman for the FBI, said the investigation was
not referred to the bureau, but was ``self-initiated'' after the
Allen civil litigation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on what we saw, we believed there was probably criminal
wrongdoing,'' Lanza said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy, a 37-year veteran of Nichols, was ousted as chairman,
president and chief executive officer of the company in May 1995.
As part of a shake-up triggered by the Allen litigation, Janes and
Schleicher also were relieved of their duties. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The turmoil at Nichols, long regarded as one of the pillars of
Kansas City's corporate community, led to its eventual purchase in
1998 by Highwoods Properties Inc. of Raleigh, N.C. All of the
transactions mentioned in the indictment occurred before the
Highwoods acquisition. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy was charged in all 12 counts of the indictment, Janes
in 10 counts and Schleicher in seven counts. The 41-page indictment
alleges eight specific acts of racketeering, all involving deals
said to have defrauded Nichols Co. The indictment charges that the
transactions were not approved by Nichols' board of directors or
its executive committee, or were approved on the basis of false or
incomplete information. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most of the transactions were uncovered during the Allen &AMP; Co.
litigation and later detailed in a May 1995 report produced on
behalf of Allen by Arthur Andersen &AMP; Co. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The racketeering acts alleged in the indictment: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -In 1992, McCarthy acquired control of two-thirds of Nichols'
stock without paying a dime. In exchange for assuming the debt of
Nichols' employee stock ownership trust, he was given 125,242
shares of J.C. Nichols stock. He never repaid the debt while
collecting millions of dollars in dividends. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -In September 1987, McCarthy, Janes and Schleicher deposited
nearly $1.6 million drawn on Nichols' account at Commerce Bank into
a personal account of McCarthy's at Country Club Bank. The funds
were then moved to another McCarthy account at First National Bank
of Shawnee Mission. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Beginning in May 1990, McCarthy and Janes used $4.74 million in
Nichols funds to pay for 6,474 shares of Nichols stock purchased by
McCarthy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Between January 1992 and July 1992, McCarthy, assisted by Janes
and Schleicher, swapped the 6,474 shares, valued at $6 million, and
a $2.7 million note for $5.9 million in Nichols-owned real estate
and $2.8 million in securities. Nichols allegedly wasn't told that
the shares were pledged to the Miller Nichols Living Trust and that
J.C. Nichols Co. would incur income tax expenses as a result of the
swap. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -From January 1994 to May 1994, Janes issued $65,500 in Nichols
checks to himself and used $46,904 to buy two Cadillacs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Between April 1994 and May 1995, Janes, with McCarthy's
knowledge, issued $1.13 million in Nichols checks to build and
operate Westport Brewing Co., a brewpub. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -On March 31, 1995, McCarthy deposited $508,000 in Nichols funds
into a personal bank account at Boatmen's Bank of Kansas in
Overland Park. Two months later, he transferred $370,000 to
Schleicher's law firm. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -On April 17, 1995, McCarthy, Janes and Schleicher wire
transferred $383,475 in Nichols funds to pay off a personal loan of
McCarthy's. The next day, the three wire transferred $1.12 million
to a McCarthy account. A check in that same amount, $1.12 million,
was presented to J.C. Nichols the same day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The indictment offers a stunning version of alleged
behind-the-scenes dealings by McCarthy, once one of Kansas City's
most influential business executives. As head of the company that
developed broad swathes of Kansas City, including the Plaza,
Mission Hills and the Brookside area, McCarthy enjoyed the
prestige, power and perks associated with one of Kansas City's
oldest and most-admired businesses. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The one-time Army paratrooper and University of Kansas football
star joined Nichols as an accountant in 1958, became treasurer in
1964 and a vice president in 1972. After ascending to the position
of executive vice president, he was named president in 1980 and
added the title of chief executive officer in 1984. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, the year he engineered a debt-heavy buyout of the
founding Nichols family, he succeeded Miller Nichols as chairman of
the company. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under McCarthy's leadership, Nichols Co. survived the real
estate bust of the late-1980s by borrowing heavily against the
company's previously debt-free properties _ ultimately including
the Plaza. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the company began to stagger under the burden of its buyout
and bank debt, McCarthy engineered the transaction that gave him
control of 65 percent of Nichols' stock. In return, a partnership
owned by McCarthy assumed $124.5 million in bank debt owed by J.C.
Nichols' employee stock ownership trust, which had been set up to
buy out the Nichols family. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy, however, never repaid the debt. Meanwhile, McCarthy
collected $3.76 million in dividends on the stock. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The deal went pretty much unnoticed _ though it was footnoted in
Nichols' 1993 annual report _ until late 1994, when Allen &AMP; Co.
sued Nichols after Nichols spurned its $50 million takeover
attempt. At the time, Allen, which had previously acted as a
financial adviser to Nichols, held a 6 percent stake in Nichols
through an affiliate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit set off a tangle of litigation during which many of
the deals between McCarthy and Nichols came to light. The
litigation ended in mid-1995, when the parties entered into a
so-called ``global settlement'' resolving most of the lawsuits in
one sweeping agreement. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As part of the settlement, McCarthy agreed to return the shares
he acquired from the trust and the land he acquired from Nichols. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, with the litigation simmering and Nichols' board
facing mounting pressure from shareholders, McCarthy and Janes were
ousted in a dramatic shakeup in May 1995. The board also dismissed
Schleicher's law firm, which had done work for McCarthy and
Nichols. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Arthur Andersen report commissioned by Allen &AMP; Co. estimated
Nichols' damages from nine separate insider deals at $71.8 million.
The report also alleged interest-free loans to top Nichols
officials, including $4.84 million advanced to McCarthy between
1992 and 1994. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney's office subpoenaed the Andersen report in
December 1995, marking the beginning of what turned out to be a
four-year probe involving testimony from numerous witnesses and a
tortuous paper trail. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very paper-intensive case,'' said Chris Whitley, a
spokesman for the U.S. attorney's office. ``Racketeering charges,
particularly ones that span the period of time we're talking about
here, aren't put together overnight.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The racketeering charges were brought under the Racketeer
Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act, which enables prosecutors
to charge patterns of criminal activity spanning long periods of
time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy, Janes and Schleicher face up to 20 years in prison on
the RICO and RICO conspiracy counts, 10 years on the interstate
transport and money laundering counts and five years on the mail
and wire fraud counts. They also face $250,000 or more in fines on
each of the 12 counts in the indictment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
