<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PULSIPHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PULSIPHER HOSPITALIZED AFTER COLLAPSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ The left-hander Bill Pulsipher, who is
vying to become the New York Mets' No.5 starter this season, was in
stable condition on Wednesday night at a Port St. Lucie hospital
after a respiratory distress incident at his home late on Wednesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Pulsipher's wife, Michelle, discovered him collapsed on the
floor of the bathroom at about 4 p.m. Pulsipher, 26, was
unconscious and was having difficulty breathing, and his wife
called 911.
</P>
<P>
   Pulsipher was taken by ambulance to the hospital, where a tube
was placed down his throat to assist with breathing because doctors
were not comfortable with his oxygen levels. As the evening went
on, Pulsipher's vital signs improved, and the tube was removed.
About 11 p.m., Pulsipher was breathing on his own and was expected
to leave the emergency room for a private room.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was sitting up,'' said Fred Hina, the Mets' head trainer.
``He had a Pepsi to drink; they'd taken all the tubes out of him.
The only thing left in him is an IV.''
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Steve Phillips said the cause of the collapse
was unknown. Phillips said Pulsipher will not resume workouts until
the club is ``comfortable with knowing what happened and why it
won't happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips added: ``They'll run the gamut of tests tomorrow.
They've done some tests already that have not shown anything. But
we have to be confident and at least get an understanding about
what happened before he takes the field again.''
</P>
<P>
   Pulsipher has spent all or part of seven of his eight
professional seasons with the Mets' organization, and Phillips said
the team was unaware of anything that might lead to an incident
like Wednesday's.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as we know, he has not had any incidents like this in
the past,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pulsipher threw live batting practice at about 1 p.m. on
Wednesday. His right leg was wrapped tightly after the workout, the
result of a cramp in his hamstring, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pulsipher chatted amiably afterward with reporters about his
chances of making the starting rotation, his efforts to develop a
changeup and his general preparedness for the season.
</P>
<P>
   He has been throwing since mid-December at the Port St. Lucie
Sports Complex. The Mets are auditioning four starters for the
fifth and final spot in the rotation, but club officials have
privately given Pulsipher the edge.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets reacquired him from the Milwaukee Brewers on Jan. 21
for infielder Luis Lopez, and when Pulsipher took the mound on
Wednesday, Phillips and manager Bobby Valentine moved from another
field to Pulsipher's, standing behind home plate and watching him
closely.
</P>
<P>
   Pulsipher is trying to rejoin a Mets rotation he has been out of
since 1995, when he went 5-7 with a 3.98 earned run average in 17
starts. At the time, Pulsipher, Jason Isringhausen and Paul Wilson
were expected to anchor the Mets' staff for the next decade. But
all three developed serious injuries, and Pulsipher was the first
to go down. He experienced soreness in his elbow that September,
and underwent surgery to repair a torn medial collateral ligament
the next April, missing all of the 1996 season.
</P>
<P>
   He pitched at four levels in 1997 attempting to come back, and
in 1998 he was traded to the Brewers, for whom he went 5-6 with a
5.98 era last year. After the elbow surgery, Pulsipher's problems
were compounded by panic attacks he suffered on the mound. He began
taking the antidepressant Prozac to combat the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this spring, Pulsipher said he had matured in several
ways since his rookie season. ``I was a 21-year-old kid when I
first made it to the major leagues,'' he said. ``That's young, and
if you don't change in the next five years and get more mature and
understand some of the things you did when you were younger are
silly, then you're going backward, you're not getting anywhere.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
