<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE THINGS WE DO FOR HEALTH
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ Today I start a new lifestyle; I hope it's not too
late.
<P>
   I'm going on a strict diet of chocolate, tobacco and red wine,
and I'm moving to a house next to the nearest nuclear power plant.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be easy making these changes, but a person can't be too
careful about his or her health.
</P>
<P>
   Red wine, of course, has been determined to be good for your
heart. Now scientific studies show that chocolate can help prevent
coronary problems, and tobacco has great promise in the prevention
and treatment of Alzheimer's and other bad stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Lunch today: bottle of chianti, a license-plate-size Mr. Goodbar
and a cigar. Why be moderate when it comes to safeguarding your
health?
</P>
<P>
   As for the relocation to the power plant neighborhood, you may
have seen a recent news story about a leak at a New York nuclear
plant that resulted in the release of radioactive steam over a
highly populated area.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the leak was small, barely radioactive and thus
posed no health threat.
</P>
<P>
   Reader Gar Smith has been checking out news stories on nuclear
leaks for 30 years and observes that  &UR; in every case, &LR;  officials
announce that the leak poses no risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thus,'' says Gar,  &UR; ``eau d'isotope  &LR; remains the only form of
pollution that poses no health problem.''
</P>
<P>
   RUBE GOLDBERG'S finest invention was our system of presidential
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   John McCain vaults into contention by winning his home state and
getting slaughtered by Republican voters in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   And of course it all started with McCain's great showing in New
Hampshire, wherever that is, and South Carolina, which is somewhere
below New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   In some states, independent votes count; in others, cross-party
votes count. In some states, they blindfold you at the polls and
you pin a donkey tail on a candidate, then they tabulate votes
according to the infield fly rule.
</P>
<P>
   I'VE GOT to admit, it's getting better, a little better all the
time. ...
</P>
<P>
   That's what they sing on that TV commercial for Philips
televisions, using the Beatles' song.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing we had great music in the '50s and '60s,
otherwise there would be thousands of TV ad writers begging for
spare change on street corners.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Tyler Hollingsworth points out that on those Phillips
commercials, they leave out the Beatles' next line, which is,
``Can't get no worse.''
</P>
<P>
   AND MICROSOFT, taking the high-brow road, has a TV commercial
for its Internet Explorer browser program. The music is the theme
of the ``Confutatis Maledictis'' from Mozart's Requiem, notes the
eagle-eared Tom Yarish.
</P>
<P>
   The on-screen caption is ``Where do you want to go today?'' And
in the background, the chorus sings, ``Confutatis maledictis,
flammis acribus addictis.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, Yarish points out, translates to, ``The damned and
accursed are convicted to the flames of hell.''
</P>
<P>
   So it's a southbound search engine.
</P>
<P>
   CONDEMNED TO Limbaugh Limbo are people like me who don't pledge
allegiance to radio god Rush Limbaugh.
</P>
<P>
   Actually it was cool to see so many Dittoheads knee-jerk, I mean
spring, to the defense of their leader after less-than-kind things
were said about him here.
</P>
<P>
   But I wonder about the female Rush-backers, since Rushbo
considers any woman who's not busy revarnishing her husband's
snooker table to be a ``Femi-Nazi.''
</P>
<P>
   ONE MORE from Gar Smith, who read the headline, ``Report: Tahoe
will soon turn green.''
</P>
<P>
   Gar wonders: ``In time for Earth Day?''
</P>
<P>
   RICK ROCKWELL and Darva Conger, I'd like you to meet Dennis
Rodman and Carmen Electra.
</P>
<P>
   Rick and Darva, two nice kids, and who knows where it all fell
apart. Maybe it was the first morning, when they awoke in the same
stateroom, looked at one another and screamed in terror.
</P>
<P>
   One report is that Rick tried to kiss Darva and she said, ``I
don't do that on the first marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   But the show was a ratings success, and next up for Fox is:
``Who Wants to Run for President on the GOP Ticket?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
