</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYMARRIAGE-CALIFORNIA_SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAY-MARRIAGE MEASURE PITS FATHER AGAINST SON
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By ELAINE HERSCHER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  David Knight, the gay son of the man behind the same-sex
marriage ban on California's ballot next month, broke a long
silence Wednesday to denounce the measure and talk about the pain
it has caused his family.
<P>
   ``I completely disagree with my father, and I don't think this
is right,'' he said about Proposition 22, sponsored by state Sen.
William ``Pete'' Knight. ``I think this story should get out to
help other people. It took me until I was 32 years old to stand up
and talk about who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Knight had declined press interviews since he wrote
an op-ed piece attacking his father's views, published in the Los
Angeles Times last fall. In that piece, he said his father was
pursuing a political agenda at the expense of gays, and their
relationship ended the day David came out to him. He described his
father's position as ``blind'' and ``uncaring.''
</P>
<P>
   Pete Knight responded that what has become a very public matter
between father and son should have remained private. Proposition 22
was designed to pre-empt same-sex marriages should they ever become
legal in other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could never get the point across to him that he's exactly
right. It is a private matter,'' David Knight said in a
teleconference with reporters set up by the No on Knight campaign.
``What he is attempting to do is single out a group that have
private, personal relationships. ... I wish he understood that, but
he doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Pete Knight, the measure's sponsor, issued a press release
Wednesday accusing its opponents of ``exploiting a private family
matter for political gain.'' It said he knew David had been under
pressure to make statements against his father and the ballot
measure.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative says marriage is valid only between a man and a
woman. Proponents say it simply protects the status quo. Opponents
say similar measures in other states have been used to undermine
domestic partner laws and other statutes that benefit gays and
their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every family has its problems, but I think my son knows in his
heart that Proposition 22 is about public policy and has nothing to
do with him and me,'' the elder Knight said.
</P>
<P>
   Describing his relationship with his father now as ``extremely
strained,'' the 38-year-old cabinetmaker said he supports same-sex
marriage. When he denounced his father's politics last year,
``there was anger there, and I wanted to put a face on it.'' But
that didn't alter his feelings for his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was I angry that he was in the forefront of this issue? Yes,''
he said. ``It's just anger, and it's just disagreement. I still
love my father.''
</P>
<P>
   David Knight said he has been with his partner, Joe, for six
years. They share a home in Baltimore. The elder Knight met Joe a
few years ago at Thanksgiving at the home of one of David's two
brothers, and the evening was tense.
</P>
<P>
   But father and son got along fine when David was in the Air
Force, when he followed in his father's footsteps and became a
fighter pilot and when he returned after flying missions in the
Gulf War, David said. It was only after he learned of David's
homosexuality that the two became estranged, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see my father as being pro-family in a very narrow sense.
He's pro-family as long as it's the norm,'' the younger Knight
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Knight says he has stayed away from the media to keep the
issue focused on marriage, not on him. The television ads for
Proposition 22 show images such as a family anniversary celebration
and position the measure as championing traditional marriage and
the right of Californians to decide how to define it.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The images) strike me as something I know my father would
approve of as a very positive and ethical campaign,'' the younger
Knight said. ``They're all wonderful images. But reality shows
images that are slightly altered from that, and they can be just as
beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Knight debunked the widely held belief among
opponents that his father is working out his issues with his son _
and a gay brother who died of AIDS _ at the ballot box.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a view of what he thinks marriage and family are.
He's doing what he really honestly believes,'' his son said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
