<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAMMYS-ANALYSIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE GRAMMY'S, IT'S A LATIN THING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It didn't take long Wednesday to tell which way the Grammy wind
was blowing.
</P>
<P>
   And for any record academy nominee in a major category whose
name was not Carlos Santana, the refrain was undoubtedly ``oy vey
como va.'' Front-runner Santana's sweep of the awards for his lush
``Supernatural'' album and its savvy hit single, ``Smooth,'' was
one of the few sure bets at the 42nd annual ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   It had to happen. The 52-year-old Mexico-born guitarist was long
overdue for academy recognition, even if it was sandwiched between
performances by teen faves Backstreet Boys and Kid Rock.
</P>
<P>
   But Santana's big night also spearheaded one of last year's
biggest trends _ the explosive success of Latin music and Latino
musicians. Among the highlights of the telecast from Staples Center
were sizzling performances by Marc Anthony, Ricky Martin, Poncho
Sanchez, Chucho Valdes and Ibrahim Ferrer of Cuba's Buena Vista
Social Club. Not to mention actress-singer Jennifer Lopez and her
eye-popping sliver of a dress, which kicked off the three-hour show
and made a convincing argument for open borders.
</P>
<P>
   Santana's ``Supernatural,'' though, was clearly the right album
at the right time. With its stylish multicultural sound that fused
rock-blues riffs to Latin rhythms and cameos from Rob Thomas, Dave
Matthews, Everclear, Eric Clapton, Lauryn Hill and others, the
album caught the Latin-pop wave, giving the veteran guitarist a
broad new audience in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I was conceived to his music,'' joked Grammy-winning
band leader Chris Perez, who is in his 20s. ``My parents were big
fans.''
</P>
<P>
   The Santana record and certain others were clearly deserving of
their trophies.
</P>
<P>
   There were few arguments backstage among the music press when,
for example, Beck's ``Mutations'' won best alternative music
performance or George Jones' ``Choices'' took the best male country
vocal performance trophy.
</P>
<P>
   It was equally heartening to see Ruben Blades' ambitious
``Tiempos'' awarded the best Latin pop performance nod, while the
great Cuban dance band Los Van Van's ``Llego ... Van Van: Van Van
Is Here'' got the best salsa performance vote.
</P>
<P>
   However, as usual, the music industry's annual schmooze fest had
little to do with much of the most exciting music created last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Those miniature gold-plated gramophones the academy gleefully
hands out each February ultimately end up on a very select number
of mantles.
</P>
<P>
   But that's old news. The Grammys, although the academy strongly
denies it, rewards sales figures first and foremost, just like its
rival, the American Music Awards. That's why a Mouseketeers chorus
line of Britney Spears, the Backstreet Boys and Christina Aguilera
turned up this year in the top categories.
</P>
<P>
   It was an attempt by the normally out-of-touch voting members to
mirror the ebbs and flows of the teen-dominated pop marketplace.
But our gang assuredly missed the boat when it comes to pop's other
driving force _ hip-hop.
</P>
<P>
   No examples of this highly influential genre were represented in
the night's key categories, a glaring omission that further tainted
Grammy's credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well. There's always next year. The academy recently
announced the formation of a Latin Grammy Awards to take place
Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised to learn of a separate rap academy at some
point in the future, probably years after hip-hop's relevance has
passed.
</P>
<P>
   It's the Grammy way. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
