<HEADER>
A6826 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-BUSH-CALIFORNIA-SFCHR     02-24 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH COMMITS TO L.A. DEBATE WITH MCCAIN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By JOHN WILDERMUTH 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ In his first trip to California since November,
Texas Gov. George W. Bush agreed Wednesday to debate his GOP rivals
next week in Los Angeles and pledged to spend much of the final
week before the March 7 primary campaigning in the state.
<P>
   ``I look forward to the Los Angeles Times debate (on March 2),
which I will accept today,'' Bush said while campaigning in
Southern California. ``I look forward to spending a lot of time
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Bloodied in Tuesday's Michigan primary, Bush is looking to
California for the knockout blow that will end Arizona Sen. John
McCain's surprisingly successful insurgent campaign for the
Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   And the campaign for the state's 162 Republican delegates is
likely to be a nasty one, if Bush's visit Wednesday was any
harbinger.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wasted no time in criticizing McCain's tactics in the
Michigan primary and suggested he was the real winner in that
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was amazed last night to hear that my opponent was reaching
out to Republicans,'' Bush said. ``That's an amazing admission to
make.''
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls in Michigan showed that much of McCain's support came
from Democrats and independents who were permitted to vote in the
Republican primary, a fact that Bush took pains to point out.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor said he lost ``the liberal Democratic vote''
to McCain in Michigan's all-comers primary, but said he
``overwhelmingly won the Republican vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also was angered at a telephone campaign in Michigan that
suggested he is anti-Catholic because of his appearance at Bob
Jones University in South Carolina, where leaders of the college
have called the Catholic church ``a satanic cult.''
</P>
<P>
   He told reporters the McCain campaign denied having anything to
do with the calls until ``after the polls closed, you'd put up your
notebooks and the cameras had been turned off.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said McCain ``claims to be riding his high horse, but takes
the low road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't accept that type of campaigning,'' he said. ``I don't
appreciate it one bit.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush may have put aside the ``compassionate conservative''
mantle for the down-and-dirty primaries in South Carolina and
Michigan, it was back for the California swing.
</P>
<P>
   His first stop Wednesday was at a downtown Los Angeles church
that has taken over an abandoned hospital to run a variety of
religious and social programs.
</P>
<P>
   While there, he visited with schoolchildren, listened to
concerns from people involved in nonprofit charitable organizations
and took a few questions before trying out his California-friendly,
kinder and gentler message.
</P>
<P>
   ``My reason for being here is I want Americans ... to understand
a vision where there are hundreds of soldiers in the army of
compassion, marching toward a goal,'' Bush said. The job of an
American president, he said, ``was to rally the armies of
compassion.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush stressed that America needs to support faith-based and
nonprofit groups that can do what government cannot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great false hope of the past is that government can save
people's lives,'' he said. ``It can hand out money, but it can't
fill the holes in people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   He also opposed a plan by McCain that would eliminate some of
the tax benefits of donating stock and property to charity, a move
that many charitable groups oppose.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan that (McCain) let out that will discourage charitable
giving is a bad plan,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush moved to shore up his Latino support in California by doing
a half-hour of questions and answers on the Spanish-language
Univision network.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Bush backed away from suggestions that
former Gov. Pete Wilson had hurt Republicans' relations with the
state's Latino voters by backing a variety of politically divisive
issues such as tougher immigration standards.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Pete is a friend,'' Bush said, ``we obviously have work
to do with Latino voters in California, and we will start that this
afternoon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
