<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-WINGS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS SHOCK RED WINGS WITH FOUR-GOAL THIRD PERIOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Blank stares, rounded shoulders and a few dropped jaws
littered Detroit's bench.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes hadn't expired in period No. 3, somebody named Aaron
Gavey had just scored the Stars' second goal in 45 seconds, and
what had until then been a swaggering Red Wings bunch instead was
staggering in shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they're not shocked that Aaron Gavey scored,'' Gavey
joked. ``Seriously, any time you score back-to-back goals, it
deflates a hockey team.''
</P>
<P>
   Deflates? The Red Wings fell flat on their face as the one-goal
lead they took into the period turned into a 5-2 loss at Joe Louis
Arena last night. The Stars have an NHL-best seven victories this
season when trailing after two periods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we collapsed,'' Red Wings defenseman Steve Duchesne
said. ``I'm not too sure exactly what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did the Stars, to be honest.
</P>
<P>
   Five goals is a couple of games worth of goals for them. They've
been hard-pressed to eclipse two for most games, much less four in
a period as they did in the third last night.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thornton scored at 1:11, sweeping in a rebound on a
Richard Matvichuk shot.
</P>
<P>
   Gavey scored at 1:56, taking a pretty cross-ice feed from Mike
Modano and whipping a shot past Wings goalie Chris Osgood.
</P>
<P>
   Modano scored at 13:43, directing a no-look pass by Jamie
Langenbrunner, on a play begun by Brenden Morrow, past Osgood.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Keane scored at 14:23, turning a Jamie Wright pass into
goal No. 5. ``Us? Five goals?'' Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor said
repeating that number. ``Pretty crazy, huh?''
</P>
<P>
   What's even crazier is who is involved on most of the goals, the
Morrows and Wrights and Gaveys.
</P>
<P>
   All of them began the season with the Stars' minor-league
affiliate, the Michigan K-Wings. Stars coach Ken Hitchcock noted
that it wasn't too long ago when a game like last night's would've
been too rich for the youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are playing with a lot of confidence,'' Hitchcock said.
``They are playing like they belong.''
</P>
<P>
   They've had to. The injuries that have plagued the Stars since
the second game of the season haven't gone away.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were missing two of their most consistent players, Guy
Carbonneau and Blake Sloan, last night. That's in addition to Conn
Smythe winner Joe Nieuwendyk, Selke Trophy winner Jere Lehtinen,
defenseman Shawn Chambers and forward Brian Skrudland.
</P>
<P>
   With all of the injuries, the Stars' fourth line consisted of a
defenseman playing in his first NHL game at wing (Brad Lukowich), a
player who has spent most of this season injured (Grant Marshall)
and a center who spent most of this season being bounced from
Kalamazoo to Dallas (Gavey).
</P>
<P>
   ``How is that different than any other game this season?'' Stars
forward Kirk Muller asked.
</P>
<P>
   Not much. The Stars just keep finding a way to win.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the season, the way found was defense. Last night,
it was offense. The end result is the same. Their victory coupled
with Phoenix's loss to Toronto gave the Stars a four-point lead in
the Pacific Division, which is big considering the first-round
series for the second-place finisher would likely begin in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it would scare the Stars, who have sent a message to
the rest of the league that they're not giving back the Stanley Cup
without a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can take it how they want to take it,'' Sydor said. ``We
have thought all along we'd keep on winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Things didn't look good after two periods. For the second
consecutive game, the Stars trailed 1-0 after one shot. Nashville
scored 26 seconds into Monday's game. Detroit's Slava Kozlov scored
1 minute, 15 seconds into last night's.
</P>
<P>
   Stars winger Brett Hull tied the game at the 13-minute mark,
only his third goal in 2000. The Stars were trailing after two
periods, though, thanks to a goal by Brendan Shanahan at 9:44 of
the second period.
</P>
<P>
   But then came Thornton, followed shortly by Gavey, and it was
all but over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boom,'' Modano said. ``We score four, and it's pretty much
over.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
