<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAMMYS-TV-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT QUITE A GRAMMY TV NIGHT TO REMEMBER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: note ITALICS below) 
 
 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Think of the Grammys as a Super Bowl halftime show, only without
a football game to justify it. It's spectacle for the sake of
spectacle, and it's gaudy bordering on obscene, but you just can't
take your eyes off it.
</P>
<P>
   The 42nd annual Grammy Awards ceremony, presented on CBS from
downtown's Staples Center, offered a nice, eclectic blend of
performances worth checking out. If only you didn't have to wade
through the tedium of the handing out of trophies and everyone
drearily thanking managers and groupies and catering services and
God to get to them.
</P>
<P>
   Will Smith opened the evening strutting around on a set that
looked like a carny midway from the movie ``Blade Runner.'' Smith
was a guy who clearly knew how to exploit the pageantry, but there
were also strong performances by artists who didn't need splashy
histrionics to make their point.
</P>
<P>
   One highlight was the Latin music medley, performed by Marc
Anthony, the ever-charismatic Ricky Martin and Cuban vocalist
Ibrahim Ferrer, who at 72 demonstrated gratifying energy as he
performed a brisk version of ``Candela.'' Another interesting
collaboration brought together Diana Krall, George Benson and
Erykah Badu.
</P>
<P>
   There were likewise some odd if not terribly inspired
juxtapositions among the presenters. Jamie Foxx, Busta Rhymes and
``Ally McBeal's'' Jane Krakowski, delivering the Best Female R&AMP;B
Vocal award. Andy Williams, Phil Collins and Macy Gray, announcing
Song of the Year. Michael Clarke Duncan, Moby and Shirley Manson
feting the Rap Duo or Group Performance.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these intros were amateurish, with presenters chuckling
or muttering to themselves _ do they not understand this is going
out over national TV? _ and almost all of them were awkward. Macy
Gray even apologized for her scripted banter.
</P>
<P>
   The Dixie Chicks offered up an ode to felonious female
self-empowerment. Kid Rock's segment offered a glimpse of a midget
grabbing his crotch. Faith Hill delivered a ballad perched atop
heels so precarious that she didn't dare take a step _ all she
could do was wobble her legs a bit. Grammy Legend winner Elton John
performed ``Philadelphia Freedom,'' but it would've been nice to
let him make an acceptance speech, too _ his probably would have
been the one colorful, memorable one of the bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Host Rosie O'Donnell opened with a monologue as flat as Bob
Dylan trying to hit a high C. She began with a bewildering joke
about having the ceremony either at the Staples Center or at a
Kinko's, then offered her witless admission, playing off Melissa
Etheridge's recent revelation that David Crosby was the father of
her child, that Rosie herself was one of Crosby's progeny _ and
that's funny (BEGIN ITALICS)why,(END ITALICS) exactly?
</P>
<P>
   She offered random but fatuous pokes at Whitney Houston, Sean
``Puffy'' Combs' and Diana Ross' recent run-ins with the law, or at
least folks wearing security uniforms at airports around the world.
Her comic batting average was lower than Michael Jordan's when he
played double-A ball.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, the television portion of the ceremony didn't convey what
a triumphant night it was for Carlos Santana. Of the three awards
he won before the TV audience _ of the record-tying eight in total
that he grabbed _ one was Best Song, which didn't even bring him on
stage. Most of his trophies were handed out before the broadcast,
so the Staples Center audience, if not the home viewers, probably
had already figured out he was going to sweep the evening. His
``Supernatural,'' which won album of the year, had virtually
everyone in the audience contributing to it.
</P>
<P>
   In general, it was a night where the veterans beat the young
artists: Sting and Whitney Houston both won with the same old same
old in categories otherwise dominated by fresher, more vibrant
talent _ the people who a decade or two from now, presumably, will
be receiving Grammys for warmed-over versions of the more vital
music they created this year. Wouldn't it be nice if, instead of
constantly playing catch-up, the Grammy folks actually gave the
trophies to those who deserved them in the first place?
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, nominees in major categories included the
likes of the Backstreet Boys, Britney Spears and Christina
Aguilera, performers whose fan base doesn't reach beyond puberty.
It takes an (BEGIN ITALICS)academy(END ITALICS) to honor this sort
of music? Why not just a fan club of teen-age girls? Choosing the
best among these folks is like choosing the smartest castaway among
Gilligan, the Skipper and Mrs. Howell.
</P>
<P>
   And hand the Grammy for best feigned expression of surprise to
Aguilera, who breathlessly declared, ``Oh my God, you guys. I
seriously don't have a speech prepared,'' before rattling off with
steely professional aplomb what may have been the longest laundry
list of thank yous of the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Of the pre-ceremony show, the less said the better. Ellen
DeGenerous, also riffing on Melissa Etheridge's strange bedfellows
with David Crosby, paraded around with a cup asking for donors. It
got exponentially less funny the more she milked the joke. Ricky
Martin didn't even appear to get the gag when she asked him, so she
changed gears and offered up the penetrating observation: ``You're
so lucky! Your life is amazing!''
</P>
<P>
   He, and we, had to agree. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
