<HEADLINE>
LAVIN NEEDS HELP, NOT A PINK SLIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The UCLA men's basketball team is on pace for its
worst regular season in 12 years and its worst conference season in
52 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' NCAA Tournament hopes are fading. They are not
competitive against the top teams in the conference. Their offense
is chaotic, their defense is flawed, their fundamentals are
atrocious and last week in Arizona they played without passion.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, coach Steve Lavin's future has replaced handicapped
parking as the hottest topic in Westwood.
</P>
<P>
   This is Lavin's fourth season since replacing Jim Harrick in
November '96 and the Bruins have gotten progressively worse. In
1997, Lavin's rookie year, they won 24 games and the Pac-10 title.
In 1998, they won 24 games and finished third in the Pac-10. In
1999, they won 22 games and again finished third. This season,
they're on pace to win 17 games and finish sixth or seventh.
</P>
<P>
   By conventional standards, the program has deteriorated. By UCLA
standards, it has crumbled. In the resulting rubble, three
questions have emerged:
</P>
<P>
   __ Can the Bruins afford to fire Lavin?
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be cheap, but yes.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Lavin received a six-year, $578,000-per-year
contract. It includes a rollover clause: For each year of the
contract, Lavin has the option to add a year, making it, in
essence, a 12-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin receives $153,000 in base salary, $35,000 for running
UCLA's summer camps, $195,000 for media promotional appearances,
and $195,000 in Adidas compensation.
</P>
<P>
   The buyout is front-loaded. According to records obtained by the
Daily News, UCLA would owe Lavin $1.190 million if he's fired after
this season. (That's the base salary for the remaining five years
of his contract, plus next year's summer camp, appearance and
apparel compensation.)
</P>
<P>
   If he's fired after next season, the Bruins would owe Lavin
$765,000, the base salary for his remaining five years.
</P>
<P>
   The difference ($425,000) is a paltry sum compared to the
school's $22 million deal with Adidas.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to fire him, the money isn't a problem,'' said a
source with close ties to several prominent donors.
</P>
<P>
   __ Should they fire Lavin?
</P>
<P>
   This is Lavin's first bad year _ !ital!see accompanying chart _
and nobody deserves to be fired after one bad year. Not teachers,
not electricians, not UCLA basketball coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin's critics point to lethargy, turnovers, bad shots and
sloppy defense as cause for termination. But the fundamentals
aren't any worse than they've been. UCLA's effort was inconsistent
in 1998 and it's inconsistent now. Its practices were inefficient
then and they're inefficient now. The offense was chaotic then and
it's chaotic now. The defense was unsound then and it's unsound
now. (If someone pump-fakes on a blacktop in the South Bronx, Dan
Gadzuric and Jerome Moiso leave their feet.)
</P>
<P>
   The difference is UCLA doesn't have Charles O'Bannon, Toby
Bailey, Kris Johnson, J.R. Henderson and Baron Davis to make plays
in the final minutes. Without them, close wins have become close
losses, close losses have become bad losses, and confidence has
eroded.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have been fundamentally unsound for years _ since
long before Lavin took command _ but they were always confident and
they had experienced playmakers. Now, they have none of the three.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain: The status quo won't cut it. The Bruins
either must make staff changes, dramatically improve their teaching
and discipline in practice or hire an adviser. Lavin, Michael
Holton, Jim Saia and Steve Spencer need help, and they need it now.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin's future should not be based on the final weeks. Even if
the Bruins regroup and make the NCAA Tournament _ they usually play
best when least expected _ the problems will remain.
</P>
<P>
   __ Will they fire Lavin?
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't comment on coaching situations during the season,''
athletic director Peter Dalis said.
</P>
<P>
   If Lavin commits an off-court transgression _ if he breaks the
law, violates NCAA rules, fails to enforce academic standards or
embarrasses the school _ he's in deep trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But Dalis and vice chancellor Peter Blackman don't believe one
bad season is cause for termination. If they didn't fire Harrick
after the Tulsa debacle in 1994, they probably aren't going to fire
Lavin.
</P>
<P>
   And they shouldn't. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
HOOPNOTES
</P>
<P>
   Daily News Staff Writer Jon Wilner is an Associated Press top-25
voter. Here are his top-10 teams for the week: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __1. Stanford (22-1) _ Showdown at Arizona is March 9. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __2. Duke (22-3) _ Blue Devils are younger than UCLA. Hmmm. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __3. Arizona (23-4) _ Can Wildcats hold No. 1 seed without Loren
Woods? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __4. Michigan State (20-6) _ Battling Arizona for final No. 1
seed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __5. Temple (20-4) _ If they shoot well, Owls are Final
Four-bound. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __6. Cincinnati (24-2) _ Bearcats played Southern Miss on
Wednesday night. &QL;
</P>
