r a BC-REPUBLICANS-CALIFORNI     02-24 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBLICANS-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA PRIMARY BATTLE TO DETERMINE RACE FOR GOP CANDIDATES
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW and CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROSEVILLE, Calif. _ Sketching vastly different images of the
Republican Party, Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Arizona Sen. John
McCain arrived in California Wednesday to begin a two-week battle
that is likely to determine the GOP presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Bush accused his rival of using Democrats to ``hijack'' the
nomination process, while McCain said he is trying build a
``governing coalition'' that could win in November.
</P>
<P>
   Staring at a campaign calendar that includes 18 GOP primaries or
caucuses between now and March 7, Bush and McCain mapped out
schedules that include extensive time in California, where by far
the largest share of delegates will be distributed.
</P>
<P>
   McCain _ who held a town hall meeting in this community 30 miles
north of Sacramento _ has the momentum after victories in Michigan
and Arizona on Tuesday. Insisting that the best GOP candidate is
the one who can appeal to swing voters, he urged Republicans to
embrace the Democrats and independents who have followed his call
for reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on in,'' McCain said in a message to fellow Republicans.
``Join us. Join us in this effort to be an inclusive party. Join us
in this effort to reach out.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But the forthcoming electoral terrain is not so friendly for
McCain. The sheer number of contest will put a premium on money and
organization _ where Bush holds a clear advantage. And it includes
primaries in several key states _ California and New York, most
noteably _ where Democratic and independent votes will not count
toward the allocation of Republican delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain has a difficult row to hoe as he tries to move his
campaign into the next phase,'' said GOP strategist Rich Galen. ``I
don't believe that anyone believes he can win the nomination
getting only 30 percent of the Republican vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 700 delegates who will be selected over the next two
weeks, more than half will be in states that do not allow Democrats
to vote in the primary. According to a count by the Bush camp, the
governor enjoys a 2-to-1 edge among the GOP voters in each of the
states so far.
</P>
<P>
   The math explains why McCain has added a new line to his stump
speech, telling audiences that ``I am a proud, conservative,
pro-life Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Though McCain's 17-year-voting record in Congress is staunchly
conservative, he has run an insurgent campaign that has been
critical of the Republican establishment, prompting taunts from the
Bush camp as he tried to flash his Republican credentials.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Reaching Out to Republicans
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it amazing that someone running for the president on
the Republican side is now all of sudden about to start out
reaching out to Republicans,'' Bush said Wednesday in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Though Bush began his campaign last year boasting of his ability
to attract moderates and swing voters, the Texas governor and his
aides have complained bitterly about the role of non-Republicans in
bolstering McCain's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you count up the Republican vote, I like my chances,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, Virginia and North Dakota all hold contests next
Tuesday, followed by 12 more states on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   The California primary is by far the most important and
delegate-rich contest. As in other states, the race has been marked
by what was once an overwhelming advantage for Bush being steadily
eroded by McCain.
</P>
<P>
   McCain plans to spend about half of the next two weeks in the
state, though late Wednesday he canceled two public appearances and
will have his wife Cindy appear on his behalf at a fund raiser
scheduled for Thursday in the Bay Area. A campaign aide said he
would return to his home in Arizona for the afternoon after a
morning visit to Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, after wavering for the past week, announced Wednesday he
would participate in a debate with McCain on March 2 in Los
Angeles, and his aides said he plans to spend about five days in
the state before the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (California) Republican leadership is squirming, because
they anointed George W. Bush,'' said Michael Genovese, political
science professor at Loyola Marymount University. ``They put all
their eggs in one basket, and now those eggs are cracking.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``they don't have a lot of faith in McCain, nor do they
trust him. He has a bit of an independent streak,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the delegate front, California provides a uniquely
complicated set of rules. Its mother lode of 162 delegates
represents 16 percent of the number needed to win the nomination.
Yet while the state's open primary rules allow registered voters to
cast ballots for any candidates, only the votes of registered
Republicans will count toward the distribution of the GOP
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   That opens the very real possibility that with the help of
Democrats and independents, McCain could win the popular vote,
while Bush captures all the delegates by winning the majority of
the Republican votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on a collision course if McCain wins the popular vote,''
said John Herrington, former chair of the California Republican
Party. Herrington suggested the possibility of a ``tremendous
uproar, and a floor fight at the convention.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Fleischman, executive director of the state Republican
Party, said there would be only one legal way for McCain supporters
to challenge the winner-take-all cache of delegates, if Bush is
favored by a majority of Republicans on March 7. McCain's campaign
would have to raise the issue at the Republican National
Convention, which is to be held in Philadelphia the first week of
August.
</P>
<P>
   ``The floor of the convention would have to vote on it, or the
credentials committee would have to recommend it ... to change
their rules to allow for the seating of the alternative
delegates,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Dissent Called Unlikely
</P>
<P>
   Because the winner-take-all rules of the California primary are
``written in stone'' for 2000 _ and won't change until 2004 _
Fleischman said such a move is ``politically unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he noted that ``all three (GOP candidates) have filed
affidavits that they have pledged to abide by the results of the
(current primary) process in California ... and have agreed to
forgo supporting any challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If any one of these candidates did decide to engage in a floor
fight,'' he said, ``it raises a question of character, and they
will have to answer the question'' as to why they've gone back on
their word. Bush retains a financial advantage, though it is not
nearly as large as it once was. After raising a record $70 million,
the Bush camp reported having $20 million on hand as of February 1.
That number is estimated by several accounts to have dwindled to
$12 million to $15 million. McCain has about $8 million at his
disposal, according to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The excitement generated by the race has led to record turnouts,
something that neutral Republicans are delighted by.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm pro baseball and this is a home run fight
between Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa,'' said Jim Nicholson, chairman
of the Republican National Committee. ``My attendance is up, my
turnstiles are ticking. I couldn't be happier.''
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle Political Writer John Wildermuth contributed to this
report from Los Angeles.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-00 0100EST &QL; 
