<DOCNO> NYT20000224.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6837 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-MCCAIN-PROFILE-SFCHRO     02-24 1443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-PROFILE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 REAL-LIFE MCCAIN WOOS WITH UNVARNISHED CHARM, STRAIGHT TALK  &HT;     By C.W. NEVIUS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arizona Sen. John McCain may be running the only presidential
campaign that needs a rim shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why am I running for president?'' he asks the crowd. ``Well,
my wife, Cindy, says it is because I sustained several severe blows
to the head in prison camp.''
</P>
<P>
   But seriously, folks ...
</P>
<P>
   When McCain pulls the microphone out of its stand and starts
roaming the stage, he resembles nothing more than vintage Johnny
Carson. It isn't just his sibilant delivery _ McCain's slushy S's
have already won him the political impressionists' vote _ but the
classic timing and easy rapport with the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've sold the screenplay to my book,'' he tells supporters
waving his best-seller at rallies. ``Sam Donaldson asked me who was
going to play me in the movie. I said I wanted Tom Cruise, but my
kids want Danny DeVito.''
</P>
<P>
   Badda-bing, badda-boom.
</P>
<P>
   McCain razzes his pals, zings reporters and often makes himself
the butt of the joke. And when he hits the punch line and flashes
that winning smile, a roomful of potential voters are beaming back.
He may be the first candidate ever to attempt to josh his way into
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder he's the sound bite of choice. Everyone complains
about cardboard candidates and sound-bite politics, and it seems to
be getting worse instead of better.
</P>
<P>
   A veteran reporter on the McCain bus recalls that during
Elizabeth Dole's short campaign, one of her staff members motioned
him over during an appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Dole would like to say hello to you,'' the reporter was
told. ``But you need to understand that it will be off the
record.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, reporters can't get rid of McCain. Step aboard his
famous bus, the ``Straight Talk Express'' _ ``We used to call it
the `B.S. Express,' '' McCain cracks _ and you'd better be ready to
banter.
</P>
<P>
   No one is immune from the hijinks, including his fellow POWs,
who turn out at his rallies and chuckle as their Navy buddy says,
``If there's an old, broken-down guy in the crowd, I was probably
in prison with them.'' The former fighter pilot isn't just a breath
of fresh air in American politics, he is a Corvette with the top
down. The hottest ticket in politics is a seat near the table in
the back of the Straight Talk, where network TV hotshots sit on the
floor for the honor of lobbing straight lines to the wittiest man
in the race.
</P>
<P>
   It's just that, well, when is enough is enough?
</P>
<P>
   When American voters look at McCain, you have to ask, do they
see a stand-up guy or a stand-up comic?
</P>
<P>
   If you listen to enough of his stump speeches, you get the
unmistakable impression that he feels this campaign is about the
man, not the message. McCain is counting on the force of his
personality to make him, the wisecracking guy you'd love to invite
to your house for a backyard barbecue, the man you want to send to
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has his tried and true big issue items _ campaign
finance reform, ``no food stamp army'' _ he admits it can look as
if he is rushing through the meat-and-potatoes policy, sometimes
plowing through his own applause lines, to get back to the funny
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys (staffers) complain all the time that I step on my
lines,'' McCain says. You can see how it happened. McCain likes to
talk about how he used to come out and deliver ``a 20-minute speech
and people were falling asleep.'' Then he hit on the town hall
meeting idea, using his quick wit and people skills. The result has
been a sensation.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, anything can happen out there, especially when
your candidate is willing to push the envelope. He'll do almost
anything if the mood strikes him. When he is given something at a
rally, from a sweatshirt to a garish NASCAR jacket with
checkered-flag sleeves, he puts it on immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The joke is that his staff is terrified someone will hand him a
pair of pants.
</P>
<P>
   His handlers finally had to tell him to quit asking the guy who
haunted his rallies in a land shark costume to come up onstage.
McCain did but only with the greatest of regret.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in New Hampshire, he recalls delightedly, he had
five different crusaders in animal outfits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I invited them all up onstage,'' he says. ``I said anybody in
a costume who came to my rally got to speak for 30 seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   That's McCain. He makes the call, off the cuff, and he sticks
with it.
</P>
<P>
   Some of it is great stuff. And sometimes _ like when a Florida
supporter said something in Spanish, and he replied,  &UR; ``Muchas &LR; 
 &UR; gracias.  &LR; Taco Bell. My Spanish is wonderful.'' _ it walks the line
of propriety.
</P>
<P>
   His comments recently calling his Vietnamese prison guards
``gooks'' is vintage. He not only said it, he went on and on, until
even some reporters on the bus were ready to move on.
</P>
<P>
   Strategist Mike Murphy sits nearby during his press conferences
to try to head off problems, but when McCain is on a roll, no force
of man or nature can stop him.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he ``gasped'' when he heard what his candidate said,
political director John Weaver smiled and said, ``I am so far
beyond gasping at this point. That's why I sit in the front of the
bus.''
</P>
<P>
   And when McCain thinks he is right, he isn't about to back down,
either. Told that radio talk shows in California were having a
field day with his remarks, McCain was unrepentant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fine with me ... ,'' he said. ``If I was on one of those talk
shows, the first thing I would ask any of those people is if they
have ever been to Vietnam. If one of my POW friends said, `John
McCain is bad, it's wrong,' it might give it some credence.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's handlers finally settled for saying that he would not
use the offensive word again, but they have to wonder when the next
brushfire will flare up.
</P>
<P>
   You know what they say: You can always tell an old fighter
pilot, but you can't tell him much. McCain got this far by shooting
from the hip, and he isn't going to change now.
</P>
<P>
   And until he got to South Carolina, it all seemed to be working.
Everyone _ kids, veterans, even Democrats _ was laughing along.
Every time he played one of his rallies and had the audience
roaring, he seemed sure that he had won over the voters.
</P>
<P>
   But Texas Gov. George W. Bush finally realized that McCain was a
rival to be taken seriously and hit McCain with attack ads. In a
typical gut decision, McCain took the high road, pulling his
negative advertising off the air. But the strategy didn't work;
McCain was solidly defeated and got knocked for throwing away his
chance at victory because he failed to respond. But he rallied with
wins in Michigan and his home state of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he's heading for California, where he knows now the hands-on
campaigning he did in New Hampshire and South Carolina isn't likely
to work. The question is: Can he convert that grinning, thumbs-up
appeal from high school gyms in New Hampshire and South Carolina to
the wide-open spaces of the Golden State?
</P>
<P>
   Things are changing for McCain, maybe faster than anyone
realizes. And his free-wheeling campaign, running on doughnuts,
diesel fuel and a plunge into the crowd, is going to have to change
too.
</P>
<P>
   He has resisted the idea of bringing in the Secret Service _ ``I
hate the thought of it,'' he says _ but even political novices are
taken aback by the way he faces flailing crowds with nothing more
than a grin and a single guard.
</P>
<P>
   When the Secret Service comes onboard, it will almost certainly
curtail the stage diving, and it may mean the end of the reporters
roundtable on the bus, too.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign began in a crowded race with a van and a couple of
writers. Now he travels with three buses, it is a two-man race, and
what would have been considered a respectable showing in South
Carolina three months ago is a bitter disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   There is also concern that McCain has run himself ragged getting
ready for the really tough work ahead. He said last week he was
trying to get by on ``three to four'' hours of sleep a night, and
that's incredibly draining, especially at age 63.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every big mistake made in politics is made when you are
tired,'' McCain said on the bus. ``I keep telling these guys
(staffers) that. I am up all the time. But this is a
once-in-a-lifetime opportunity. I have to be up.''
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, he will bear watching. He may catch fire,
implode or _ who knows? _ become the next president. With McCain,
anything can happen, and he's as eager to see what's next as anyone
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep waiting,'' he says, ``for the pie in the face.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
