<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6840 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-IMMIGRANT-SUPPORT-LAD     02-24 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRANT-SUPPORT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRO-IMMIGRANT GROUPS ANNOUNCE DRIVE FOR BENEFITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BILL HILLBURG 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Buoyed by a booming economy and backing from Big
Labor, pro-immigrant groups on Wednesday announced a drive to
increase access to federal welfare benefits for legal immigrants
and expressed support for amnesty for an estimated 5 million
undocumented aliens, 2.5 million of whom live in California.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Sharry, director of the Washington-based National
Immigration forum, called anti-immigrant sentiment ``an echo of the
recession of the 1990s'' and said that an array of advocate groups,
business and labor are primed to press Congress for changes in
immigration law.
</P>
<P>
   Sharry cited a Feb. 16 announcement by the executive council of
the AFL-CIO that backed immediate legalization for 500,000
Salvadorans, Guatemalans, Hondurans and Haitians, many of whom have
claimed status as political refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO also called for increased penalties for employers
who knowingly hire illegal aliens and more workplace protections
for legal immigrants, including the right to join or organize labor
unions.
</P>
<P>
   Sharry also referred to recent testimony to Congress by Federal
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, who credited immigrant workers,
especially professionals in high-tech industries, with playing a
vital role in the nation's ongoing economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-immigrant groups want Congress to repeal laws that
impose a five-year waiting period before new legal immigrants may
receive food stamps, Supplemental Security Income, Medicaid and
Temporary Assistance for Needy Families.
</P>
<P>
   They are further seeking the repeal of regulations, also enacted
by Congress in 1996, that bar illegal immigrants from using the
courts in deportation appeal cases, allow undocumented people to be
deported for crimes committed as long as 25 years ago and give the
Immigration and Natralization Service full jurisdiction over their
cases.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 law also allows the INS to hold illegal aliens without
bail for an undetermined period while awaiting hearings on their
status.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of undocumented people are currently being held at
sites nationwide, including an INS detention center adjacent to
Terminal Island Federal Prison in Los Angeles Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Muzaffar Chishti, an official of the Union of Neeedletrades,
Industrial and Textile Employees, called for a blanket amnesty for
all illegal aliens, saying such a move would ``reflect the reality
of today's labor market.''
</P>
<P>
   Chishti, citing INS estimates, put the number of illegal aliens
nationwide at 5 million, with half that total residing in
California. He also estimated that 75 percent of the new hires in
Southern California's low-wage labor market, including Los Angeles'
garment industry, are undocumented aliens.
</P>
<P>
   His views were echoed by John Gay, an official with the American
Hotel and Motel Association, and by Lowell Sachs, a spokesman for
Palo Alto- based Sun Microsystems, who said there was a critical
shortage of workers at both the low and high ends of the job
market.
</P>
<P>
   They both urged an increase in nation's annual 700,000-person
limit on legal immigration.That limit has been in place since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The high end of the labor market is already getting attention
from Congress. A bill introduced Feb. 9 by Sen. Orrin Hatch,
R-Utah, and backed by Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., would raise
the number of special work visas for high-tech professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Cecilia Munoz, vice president of policy for the National Council
of La Raza, a Latino civil rights group, expressed confidence that
growing electoral power will translate into meaningful reform of
immigration laws. She noted that, since 1992, the number of
registered Latino voters has increased 40 percent nationwide and 64
percent in California.
</P>
<P>
   That shift was news to state Sen. Richard Mountjoy, R-Monrovia,
author of Prop. 187. His ballot measure, which sought to block
illegal aliens from access to public education and social services,
was approved by California voters by a 60-40 margin in November,
1994. Prop. 187's major provisions were thrown out by the courts
and the measure was finally shelved in a 1999 arbitration arranged
by Gov. Gray Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is doing much better, but it still isn't right for
people to ilegally come to this coutry,'' Mountjoy said Wednesday.
``And illegal immigration only hurts those who come through
legally.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-00 0113EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
