<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6841 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-PRISON-RIOT-SFCHRON &LR;      02-24 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISON-RIOT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE INMATE SHOT DEAD, EIGHT OTHERS WOUNDED AS GUARDS BREAK
UP  CALIFORNIA PRISON RIOT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By BILL WALLACE, PAMELA J. PODGER and JAXON VAN DERBEKEN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRESCENT CITY, Del Norte County _ Guards fatally shot one inmate
and wounded eight others to break up a riot Wednesday in which more
than 200 Pelican Bay State Prison inmates were brawling and
stabbing each other with homemade knives, the state Department of
Corrections reported.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting involved convicts serving time in one of the higher
security housing units at a prison designed to incarcerate some of
the state's most incorrigible inmates. Most of the brawling
prisoners were black or Latino, and the confrontation appeared to
be racially motivated, corrections officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was black and Hispanic inmates fighting,'' said
Correctional Lt. Ben Grundy, a prison spokesman. ``We've had racial
incidents in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The disturbance was the most serious shooting incident at a
state prison since a new firearms policy was adopted last year that
strictly limits the circumstances under which correctional staff
members are allowed to open fire.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities could not say what caused the confrontation that
began about 9:30 a.m. in Facility B, a prison exercise yard that
serves four of the inmate housing areas at the 3,384-bed prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how this riot began or what precipitated the
incident,'' said Margot Bach, a spokeswoman for the California
Department of Corrections Wednesday afternoon. ``The most seriously
wounded inmates have been transported to a local hospital. ... We
can confirm that one of the inmates was pronounced dead at the
hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Other prison officials said that at least one of the inmates who
was wounded by gunfire was in critical condition. No prison staff
members were injured.
</P>
<P>
   Bach said gun-rail guards fired 24 rounds from their prison
issue Ruger Mini-14 rifles while attempting to quell the
disturbance.
</P>
<P>
   She said guards fired after inmates ignored repeated orders to
get down and after they did not respond to canisters of pepper
spray and tear gas.
</P>
<P>
   She said direct physical contact with inmates was not attempted
because of the number of people involved in the disturbance.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the gunfire and the firing of multiple canisters of tear
gas, it still took roughly 120 guards a half hour to bring the
situation under control.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the riot, the prison remained locked down, with
inmates confined to their cells and increased security throughout
the institution.
</P>
<P>
   Bach said a special ``deadly force'' investigative team from the
Department of Corrections has been dispatched to the prison, which
is situated 10 miles south of the Oregon border outside Crescent
City in remote Del Norte County.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Fama with the Prison Law Office, a San Rafael organization
that represents inmates, said the overcrowded conditions at Pelican
Bay ``probably had a lot to do with the riot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Problems between prisoners, including race-based problems, are
unfortunately a part of prison life. When you have too many
prisoners in a facility that wasn't designed for that amount, I
think it heightens the tensions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pelican Bay was supposed to house 2,280 inmates when it opened
in 1989. It currently is overcrowded by more than 1,000 prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Fama said the Department of Corrections must find ways to reduce
the prison population and find other ways of reducing violence
besides merely increasing the punishment of inmates.
</P>
<P>
   He said this is the first fatal shooting at Pelican Bay since
the 1995 ruling in a landmark federal civil rights case, Madrid vs.
Gomez, in which U.S. District Judge Thelton Henderson found the
prison's use of force and medical care unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is whether the use of lethal force under the
circumstances was justified. The second question is how CDC's
relatively new shooting-review process works,'' Fama said. ``The
federal judge found in 1995 that the shooting-review process was a
farce and a sham.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the union that represents California prison
guards did not respond to a phone request for comment on the latest
strife at Pelican Bay.
</P>
<P>
   California's prisons reported the most inmate deaths from
gunfire of any correctional system in the nation in the late 1980s
and early '90s. More than 39 inmates have been killed in prison
shootings since 1988, and the large number of shootings led to a
change in prison firearms policies that was adopted as a state
regulation late last year.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new rules, guards are allowed to fire at inmates only
to defend a prison employee from death or great bodily injury, to
prevent an escape or to stop a riot or arson.
</P>
<P>
   In an unrelated development, the U.S. attorney's office in San
Francisco announced Wednesday that two Pelican Bay correctional
officers, Edward Michael Powers and Jose Ramon Garcia, had been
indicted by a federal grand jury for conspiring to violate prison
inmates' civil rights by arranging for them to be attacked by other
inmates.
</P>
<P>
   The four-page indictment says that Powers and Garcia told
Pelican Bay prisoners that other inmates were child molesters, thus
making them targets for retaliatory attacks.
</P>
<P>
   On seven occasions, the two guards spread rumors about inmates
to encourage attacks on them, then put them together with other
inmates so that attacks could take place. In one instance, the
inmate who was attacked, Watson White, died from stab wounds he
received during the assault.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment says that on another occasion, Garcia and Powers
watched from a safe vantage point while an inmate assaulted one of
the prisoners they had set up.
</P>
<P>
   (This article was written and reported by Wallace in San
Francisco, Podger in Santa Rosa and Van Derbeken in Crescent City.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-00 0114EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
