<HEADER>
A6842 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-GRAMMYS-BACKSTAGE-LAD     02-24 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAMMYS-BACKSTAGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY ALL STOOD IN THE WIDE SHADOW OF SANTANA
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By HEATHER WOOD 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carlos Santana may have swept the Grammys on camera, but
backstage _ before the cameras were even turned on _ polka kings,
Sesame Street's Elmo, Disney's Tarzan and Erykah Badu's head-wrap
reigned.
</P>
<P>
   The little-known artists at the 42nd annual Grammy Awards, such
as Reggae's Burning Spear and Salsa's Los Van Van, turned on the
charm when they had their chance to shine in the dim lights of the
backstage press room.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the obvious fame of winners such as Tito Puente and
Emmylou Harris, Grammy winners grappled with comparisons to Carlos
Santana at nearly every turn. ``I'm just happy to be here,'' was
the most common declaration. ``We're happy for Carlos,'' everyone
said. ``He's so inspirational,'' the superficial ones said. Other
artists stood backstage with blank faces, as no one from the press
asked questions. We were waiting for Santana, you see. But by the
time Santana had won his fourth Grammy, it was obvious he wouldn't
be gracing us with his presence until the end _ he did, after all,
have four more awards to win.
</P>
<P>
   Ageless Latino artists resurfaced with renewed strength and
influence. Poncho Sanchez picked up his first Grammy after four
previous nominations. The Buena Vista Social Club, whose lead
singer turned 73 this month, showed how a life's work is worth more
than just a Grammy. Tito Puente not only wowed the Recording
Academy, but gave the best Jennifer Lopez impression since Cheri
Oteri's rear-enhanced spoof on ``Saturday Night Live.'' When the
five-time Grammy Award winner accepted the Best Traditional
Tropical Latin Performance award for ``Mambo Birdland,'' he met
with expected questions about the unstoppable Latin pop explosion
of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'm not Ricky Martin,'' he said as he did a little
dance. ``I'm not Marc Anthony,'' (he swayed his hips a little more
fiercely). ``And I'm sure not Jennifer Lopez.'' With that, Puente
turned around, slid his hands down his hips and showed off his
not-so-famous hind asset. And yes, Lopez show hers off in all its
glory.
</P>
<P>
   Even winners in the little-known categories recognized the
dominance of Latin sounds this year. Producer of the Year
(non-classical) Walter Afanasieff, who has produced albums for Marc
Anthony, Savage Garden, Barbara Streisand and Babyface, talked
about helping his Latin artists (including Anthony, Ricky Martin
and Jennifer Lopez) return to their roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me there's a little bit more emphasis on pop rather than
their roots, which are Latin. I'm hoping it will come back to the
Latin side, I'm hoping. You shouldn't lose your roots.''
</P>
<P>
   The Roots certainly know the meaning of, well, roots. The
hip-hop group took home a Grammy for Rap Duo Performance with
Erykah Badu. ``We're bringing musicianship back,'' said bassist
Leonard Hubbard. ``We're about the only signed instrumental hip-hop
band in the world and that needs to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Badu added her own appreciation of musicians past. ``This head
wrap is a symbol for people who have their own set of rules. I feel
I'm one of the midwives aiding in the rebirth of music.''
</P>
<P>
   Country music darlings the Dixie Chicks know the meaning of
roots, Nashville-style. The singers said they drew inspiration from
this year's country-song-like events of their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had two divorces and one marriage. It was very
inspirational,'' said lead singer Natalie Maines. ``I think we all
feel really lucky. This is our second album on a major label and to
have both of them acknowledged by the Grammys is unbelievable.''
The Chicks will kick off their first headlining tour in June.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Santana whose name was repeated over and over. Phil
Collins called him a dinosaur of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that he's still around is something, isn't it? It's
been what, 30 years?'' Sting was thankful to be spared competition
with the Grammy favorite. ``I'm just glad I wasn't in any
categories he was in.'' And B.B. King honored Santana's spirit.
``First of all, he is a great musician. And there isn't anybody in
show business who works harder than him. He's a fantastic man and a
friend, too.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-00 0114EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
