<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CIVIL-WAR-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BITTER MCCAIN-BUSH BATTLE REOPENS GOP'S OLD WOUNDS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors)   (This insightful 650-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``p''
political, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news
files.)  
  
 By ANDREW MARSHALL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The presidential primary race between George W.
Bush and John McCain has reopened all of the Republican Party's old
wounds and created a few new ones as the two contenders fight hand
to hand for the party's soul.
</P>
<P>
   The party establishment believed that this election would be
about transcending their differences, uniting on a candidate and
finding a new way to present the party as a national force.
</P>
<P>
   Instead it risks turning into open civil war over the legacy of
Ronald Reagan, the most successful Republican in modern history.
</P>
<P>
   There are many differences within the Republicans, as in most
parties. But the main divide is between the moralizing,
authoritarian wing, represented by the Christian right, and the
libertarian, free-enterprise wing.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had sought to reconcile the two with his call for
``compassionate conservativism.'' In the South Carolina race he
relied heavily on the religious right; McCain's campaign staff have
attacked the Christian Coalition, calling some of them bigots.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also made much of his appeal beyond the Republican Party to
Democrats and independents, which was a key aspect of winning the
Governorship of Texas. But it is McCain who has garnered the
independent vote.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Bush camp is attacking McCain for precisely the
advantage which originally it had hoped to make its own.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans accounted for just 47 percent of voters in
Michigan's Republican primary, the lowest since Georgia in 1984.
Then, Ronald Reagan was pulling conservative Democrats into his
camp and the turnout was regarded as a triumph; now, it is dividing
the party.
</P>
<P>
   There is a tension between those in the party who want it to be
a ``big tent,'' covering a broad coalition; and the proponents of
ideological purity.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had been in the former camp; now he finds himself
belaboring McCain for bringing new voters into the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   McCain increasingly uses the phrase ``Reagan Democrats,''
appealing to the memory of the constituency which the president
pulled together in 1980 and 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Then, predominantly right-wing Democrats were attracted by
Reagan's support of a strong defense and tax cuts, a union of
populism and patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   This was precisely the formula that Bush wanted to revive. But
so does McCain, with an appeal that seems to rest on his calls for
political reform and renewal _ a reminder of Reagan's call for
``morning in America.''
</P>
<P>
   `These things are part of an inclusive party, the party of
Abraham Lincoln and Teddy Roosevelt and Ronald Reagan. That's what
this is really about,'' said McCain. ``So I view this campaign as
sort of a seminal event for our party and this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Reagan, the Republicans have failed to find a credible
national leader and the party has squabbled over his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Newt Gingrich, the Congressional leader who won control of the
House of Representatives for the party, self-destructed after the
1998 elections; his leadership ended up by making the party look
partisan, ideological and bitter.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican hierarchy hoped that Bush was a figure behind
whom the whole party could line up; instead, the party is dividing,
angrily and publicly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rift clearly is not healable if McCain is the party's
candidate,'' Iowa Republican Party chairman Kayne Robinson told the
Washington Times.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that a Reaganesque campaign intended to win control
of Congress and the White House could end up by losing both.
</P>
<P>
   But there is another irony: These elections are also turning out
to be about the political legacy of another president _ Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   He took the Democrats to the right in an attempt to win back the
Reagan Democrats and resolidify the party's national base. John
McCain, at least, recognizes this.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't help but admire the job President Clinton did in
assembling a coalition _ moving to attract the great center in
political life,'' he has said. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 650-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
