<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGNOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
 
KINGS REACT TO McSORLEY ASSAULT 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta _ Boston defenseman Marty McSorley played 7
seasons with the Kings, but his old teammates are just as outraged
as the rest of the hockey world about Monday's vicious stick attack
on Vancouver's Donald Brashear.
</P>
<P>
   Luc Robitaille and Rob Blake were teammates of McSorley when the
Kings went to the Stanley Cup finals in 1993. Since the incident in
Vancouver that led to McSorley's suspension for the rest of the
season and playoffs, the two have been overwhelmed with so many
interview requests that they went to coach Andy Murray asking what
to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a good guy and helped this organization a lot, but what
can you say about what he did,'' said Robitaille, a teammate of
McSorley's for six years. ``It was so over the line there is no way
to condone it. I know he feels bad, but that is not enough. It was
awful and it is bad for hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   McSorley's 23-game suspension, which was handed down by the NHL
Wednesday afternoon, is the longest in league history. He also
would miss the postseason although the Bruins are 12th in the
Eastern Conference, six points from the eighth and final playoff
spot.
</P>
<P>
   Several Kings said the incident was not the most brutal they had
witnessed, but Canadian television ran around-the-clock coverage of
the story.
</P>
<P>
   The country's national sport has come under scrutiny the past
few years, experiencing financial problems due in part to a weak
dollar. There also is concern players are reared to be violent and
have been passed by the Europeans as skilled players.
</P>
<P>
   Kings coach Andy Murray said he hopes the McSorley incident will
not leave a lasting impression. In his own family, Murray's
15-year-old son Brady is recovering from a concussion at the family
home near Minneapolis. He hit the back of his head on the boards
after getting struck by a cross check in the back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a tough, physical game that is played with a lot of
emotion,'' Murray said. ``Those were virtues Marty McSorley brought
to this team. But players also have to show reason and there was
none of that in his case. There is absolutely no room for that in
our game.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Wednesday's game at the Saddledome, several Calgary
officials said they wished the league had mandated a specific
number of games for the suspension to set the precedent for future
infractions. There also is a chance McSorley could face criminal
charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the league can police the matter on its own,'' Murray
said. ``They've done a good job in the past and they know how
severe this incident is. This is not a part of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Quick whistles:The Kings flew after the game to Vancouver,
where they play Friday night against the Canucks. . . . With two
assists, Rob Blake tied Mark Hardy for the all-time Kings record
for a defenseman with 250. . . . Flames forward Valerei Bure
returned Tuesday from Los Angeles, where his wife, Candace, gave
birth to the couple's second child on Sunday. . . . Calgary's All-
Star defenseman Phil Housley did not play because of the flu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
