<SLUG> BC-POPE-FLAK-HOLYLAND-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE'S MIDEAST TOUR ALREADY SOURED BY CONTROVERSIES  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for Thurs., Feb. 24 _ first graf)   (This 475-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' general/religion news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By PHIL REEVES  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The Pope's Middle East tour, billed by the Vatican
as a personal spiritual journey to Christianity's roots, has
already been soured by religious rivalries and bare-knuckle
politicking, even before his arrival in Egypt Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The chief source of the 79-year-old pontiff's troubles lies
further along the Mediterranean coast in the Holy Land, and
especially Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Although he is not due to go to Israel and the Palestinian
Authority for nearly a month, the visit _ the first by a Pope since
1964 _ is already spawning almost daily controversies.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's environmentalists are up in arms. The rabbis are
uneasy. Ultra-Orthodox Jews are scandalized. And Ehud Olmert, the
mayor of Jerusalem, has already declared the trip to be marred by
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday it was the turn of the Israeli government to weigh in.
Last week its officials _ and also Mayor Olmert _ were annoyed by a
joint declaration issued by the Vatican and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat stating that Jerusalem should have a special
international status, and calling on Israel not to make any
unilateral decisions about its fate.
</P>
<P>
   As both the Jews and the Palestinians have competing claims to
create a capital in the city, this touched on an intensely raw
nerve.
</P>
<P>
   Now, according to news reports, the government is pressuring the
Palestinians to cancel a planned official welcoming ceremony for
John Paul II on the Temple Mount in Jerusalem's Old City, which was
seized by Israel in the 1967 Six-Day War.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials are worried that the Palestinians will seize
on the occasion to flourish symbols of their sovereignty in an
attempt to cause international embarrassment to the occupying
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli environmental lobby has also taken up the cudgels,
on a separate front.
</P>
<P>
   The Society for the Protection of Nature in Israel has
complained that dozens of bulldozers are ripping up a mountain
overlooking the Sea of Galilee by constructing a large parking lot,
and an amphitheatre in which the Pope will conduct mass for up to
100,000 pilgrims.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Israel's Environment Ministry said it was satisfied
that the site would be restored after the trip _ but the row is
unlikely to end there.
</P>
<P>
   Nor have Israel's large ultra-Orthodox community remained
silent. Notices have begun to appear on the walls of their
neighborhoods bewailing the ``sorrow that comes with the enemy at
the gate of Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   To this should be added wrangles over exactly where the Pope
should meet the chief rabbis; petitions demanding that he drop
plans for a service on the Jewish Sabbath; a land battle between
Muslims and Catholics over holy sites in Nazareth, and concerns
that the papal visit will unleash political unrest.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone agrees that the pontiff's expedition will be historic.
But this may be for the wrong reasons. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
