<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 01:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6855 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-HNS &LR;      02-24 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN CLAIMS FRONT-RUNNER STATUS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
and GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Despite a double loss and trailing in delegates,
George W. Bush declared Wednesday he will still win the Republican
presidential nomination through victories in state primary contests
that forbid crossover voting.
</P>
<P>
   John McCain beat Bush on Tuesday in his home state of Arizona
and in Michigan. His victory in the Northern industrial state came
largely on the strength of Democrats and independents who
participated in the open Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a U.S. senator, has now collected more delegates to the
nominating conventions than Bush and can claim the front-runner's
mantle. After Tuesday's wins, McCain has 96 delegates to Bush's 67.
A candidate must win 1,034 of the 2,066 delegates to capture the
Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Insisting that he is still a ``proud, conservative Reagan
Republican,'' McCain nonetheless wooed young, independent and
Democratic voters in Seattle and in Spokane to entice them to
participate in the state's Republican primary next Tuesday.
Virginia and North Dakota also hold open primaries that day, and
the three contests will award a total of 112 delegates.
</P>
<P>
   McCain urged voters to join his ``Straight Talk Express,''
saying it was time for all Americans who want to reform their
government to ``come aboard this train.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're leaving the station, my friends. It's remarkable, and I
can't tell you how happy I am,'' McCain told an overflow audience
at Gonzaga University in Spokane.
</P>
<P>
   While continuing to emphasize his own conservative Republican
credentials, McCain said his party had failed to reach out to
disaffected voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole campaign is about bringing you back into the
political system. ...We want them all ... because the party of
Abraham Lincoln is a party of inclusiveness,'' McCain said. ``I
think we aroused something in Michigan, and I hope we're arousing
it all across this country.''
</P>
<P>
   To sustain his campaign, McCain aides acknowledged that he will
have to attract more Republicans in the March 7 primaries,
especially in California, where Bush is still more popular among
mainstream GOP voters. McCain planned to spend Thursday campaigning
in California, and was scheduled to return to the state next week
to mount a final, intensive effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really are now focusing on Super Tuesday,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush continued to focus on Republican loyalist voters and
campaigned in Latino sections of Los Angeles. California's primary
is open to all voters, but its 162 delegates are only awarded based
on the registered Republicans who participate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to make sure I consolidate my Republican base,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush still appears to have an advantage over McCain in terms of
organization, financing and standing in national polls.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he won almost 70 percent of the Republican base vote
in Michigan. But slightly more than half the primary voters were
not Republicans, and they could return to their party in the
general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty soon we're going to start having these primaries where
those who want to come into our primary to hijack it are going to
have a difficult decision to make. Do they want to stay and support
Al Gore or Bill Bradley?'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Texas GOP officials lamented what they called the
``infiltration'' of Democratic candidates into their March 14
primary and the possibility that hordes of Democrats would vote
Republican to ``disrupt'' the GOP candidate selection process.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this new willingness on the part of Senator McCain to
join hands with those kinds of subversive efforts, who knows what
he might join forces with ... in the governor's home state,'' said
Texas Republican Chairwoman Susan Weddington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be prepared for it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign is counting on victories in closed primaries _
ones that award delegates based on votes cast only by registered
Republicans _ in Florida, New York and other states.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also will do well with superdelegates _ members of Congress
and other elected officials who have rallied behind Bush as the
establishment favorite and get a say at the nominating convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be some powerful states with big
delegations start to show up,'' Bush said. ``When we look back, we
are going to find my message is the winning message, is the reason
I'm going to be the nominee.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican consultant Charlie Black, an informal adviser to
Bush, said the Texas governor has been widening his margin over
McCain among traditional Republicans even in the contests that he
has lost. Bush won two-thirds of self-identified Republicans in
Michigan, according to exit polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the traditional kind of Republican race you run, he's been
increasingly successful,'' Black said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain political director John Weaver said their polls indicate
that Bush's relationship with Christian conservative leaders such
as Pat Robertson is beginning to turn off voters.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, he added, ``has tacked so hard to the right he's becoming
unelectable in November. ... I think a lot of Republicans _ not
just the Democrats and independents _ are beginning to figure that
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson is conducting his own telephone bank, urging
conservatives to vote for Bush and reminding them that McCain's
national chairman, former Sen. Warren Rudman, once said that
members of the Christian Coalition were ``vicious bigots.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said, ``I think it's disgraceful. I think it's conduct
Governor Bush should stop. ... He wants to win in the worst way and
I want to win in the best way.''
</P>
<P>
   Black said almost two-thirds of the delegates chosen in the next
two weeks will come from closed primaries where Bush should excel.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain's going to run out of time, but we're going to be
running up a majority of the delegates,'' Black said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he also plans to portray any state McCain decides to
skip as a state where McCain has lost because of his heavy national
news coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows who he is, and everybody knows who I am. So I
view all the primaries as being contested,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's problem may be that McCain is cutting him off from
new voters in states such as New Hampshire and Michigan. Even in
South Carolina, where McCain lost, the Arizona senator won a
majority of the votes cast by independents, Democrats and
first-time Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in a vice, and there's very little he can do to get out
of it,'' said University of Virginia political scientist Larry
Sabato.
</P>
<P>
   Sabato said if Bush pushes too hard to defeat McCain by
consolidating the base Republican vote he risks making himself
unacceptable to the independents in the general election. But
Sabato said if Bush does not consolidate conservatives, he risks
losses in the states with closed primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush can run the marathon and probably win the nomination, but
they'll have a very changed candidate,'' Sabato said. ``He's got a
foe who is giving him no quarter and may drain him of blood for the
fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Black said he believes Bush will right himself once he has the
nomination secure.
</P>
<P>
   ``A winner is a winner. Once Bush emerges as the winner, he'll
regain the aura of inevitability,'' Black said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
