<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT JUDGE HINTS AT BREAKUP AFTER `SECRET' GATES VISIT  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 250-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By DAVID USBORNE  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bill Gates, the founder and chairman of Microsoft,
met in secret last month with the judge overseeing settlement talks
with the U.S. government as part of an effort to resolve antitrust
charges against his company out of court, it was claimed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   News of the encounter came as the first phase of the legal
battle between Microsoft and the government at a drawn-out trial in
Washington nears a conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   A final day of hearings took place on Tuesday and the trial
judge, Thomas Penfield Jackson, should make his decision by the end
of April.
</P>
<P>
   Arguments on Tuesday, which focused on whether copyright law
might offer Microsoft some protection from antitrust regulations,
did not seem to go well for the software giant.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Jackson raised eyebrows by comparing the company to the
Standard Oil monopoly of John Rockefeller of the last century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Rockefeller had fee simple (absolute) control over his
oil,'' Judge Jackson told the lawyers of Microsoft. Referring to
the charges against Microsoft _ that it has similar control over
the software market and the browser sector and that it has abused
that position _ he added: ``I don't really see a distinction.''
</P>
<P>
   In a court action in 1910, Standard Oil was broken up into 30
companies.
</P>
<P>
   That Judge Jackson will uphold the government and the charges
against Microsoft is now considered inevitable. A subsequent ruling
on action against Microsoft would not be expected from the judge
until about November. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
