<HEADLINE>
YOU'RE NOT ALONE _ STRESSED MANAGERS HATE E-MAIL OVERLOAD, TOO  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 325-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``a''
domestic/general, ``l'' lifestyle and ``k'' commentary news
files.)  
  
 By CHERRY NORTON  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ E-mails have piled additional stress on Britain's
managers, who say that having to cope with their overloaded
``in-boxes'' is damaging their work performance and home lives.
</P>
<P>
   In a study of more than 800 managers, published Thursday by the
Institute of Management (IM), keeping up with e-mails has entered
the top 10 stresses of modern working life for the first time.
Nearly a quarter of the managers interviewed said it has caused
them stress in the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Previous research conducted by the IM showed that, in 1993,
``new technology'' was not a stressful subject for managers in
Britain, who were more concerned about office politics and
incompetent senior management.
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Hastings, head of policy at the IM, suggested that high
levels of stress now result from ``people having new technology
foisted on them by IT professionals with little training.''
</P>
<P>
   ``New technology may not be the panacea it once appeared,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   The research report, ``Taking the Strain,'' says the top 10
sources of pressure cited by managers include constant
interruptions, lack of support, poor senior management and time
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Most managers experienced a range of stress symptoms, including
excessive tiredness (81 percent) and loss of temper (71 percent).
</P>
<P>
   The most popular ways of coping with stress are physical
exercise, talking to friends, drinking alcohol and shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of the managers surveyed said they now handled
increased responsibilities as a result of the loss of key people
during company restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   The study showed that over four out of 10 managers are unhappy
with their workplace culture, 42 percent feel unable to cope with
their workloads and 40 percent struggle to meet goals and targets.
</P>
<P>
   Bullying is a further source of stress, with one in 10 saying
they have experienced bullying and intimidation on a regular
basis. &QL; 
