<P>
   &UR; For THURSDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Thursday, Feb. 24.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GAZA-POPULATION (Jabalya Refugee Camp, Gaza Strip) _ The
population explosion in the Gaza Strip appears to be unrivaled in
the world. Its 1.1 million residents are expected to triple by
2025. But for the young Palestinian government, with its
conservative, male-dominated Islamic society, it is a sensitive
issue. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic and
map have been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-U.S.-SPY (Paris) _ A report commissioned by the European
Parliament on the communications monitoring network called Echelon
says that Britain and the U.S. have used the network to gain
economic advantage, intercepting billions of commercial phone
calls, faxes and e-mails. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-ECHELON (Washington) _ What is Echelon? A primer. Plus
U.S. reaction to allegations from Europe that it is American
overreaching. By Elizabeth Bekcer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-JOURNAL-APOLOGY (Undated) _ The New England Journal of
Medicine, one of the world's top ranked scientific publications and
a leading critic of doctors' financial ties to industry, apologizes
to its readers for violating its own financial conflict-of-interest
policy in choosing experts to review drug therapies. By Lawrence K.
Altman.
</P>
<P>
   LIBRARY-INTERNET (Detroit) _ In what some voters in the
conservative western Michigan city of Holland saw as the
``Lexington-Concord of the fight against pornography on the
Internet,'' the the nation's first ballot measure to force a
library to install filters on its computers was soundly defeated.
Proponents of the measure outspent opponents 11 to 1, but opponents
in this tidy town in the heart of Michigan's Bible Belt feared an
assault on free speech. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-NY (New York) _ Sen. John McCain's victories in Michigan
and Arizona have set the stage for the first contested Republican
primary in New York state in 20 years. But McCain faces two
problems as he turns his attention East _ a contest closed to
non-Republican voters and yet again, a state electoral system
designed to favor the candidates favored by the Republican
establishment. By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-CALIF (Los Angeles) _ All eyes are now on California.
McCain's hope is that if there are Republicans anywhere who
remember what it was like to put together the Reagan coalition,
it's California Republicans. MCCain may now have enough money to be
relatively comeptitive here. There is a possibility that he could
win the California popular vote but not the vote for delegates,
restricted to registered Republicans. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Republicans in House and Senate
worry that McCain's anti-Congress campaign may ignite more
grassroots fury at incumbents that will hurt them in November. By
Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DINNERS _ The Clintons came to town determined to avoid
the social whirl of state dinners, and did not hold one for a year
and a half. Now they seem to pop up every week, including one
Wednesday night for King Juan Carlos I of Spain. Many nations are
now lobbying to schedule formal visits before Clinton leaves
office. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   DISCRIM-SECRETSERVICE _ Last year, after 16 years as an agent in
the insular fraternity of the Secret Service, Reginald G. Moore had
made it to one of the most prestigious posts in the agency as a
lead agent on President Clinton's protective detail, entrusted with
Clinton's life. Moore seemed to be poised to advance to the
agency's managerial ranks. But even though his written evaluation
for 1999 shows that he was among the most outstanding agents of his
rank, Moore, who is black, said he was denied a promotion and given
the task of training the white agent promoted ahead of him. When
Moore was reassigned to a counterfeiting squad in Dallas, he
decided to defy the Secret Service's traditional code of silence.
David Johnston
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHARITIES-TAXES (Undated) _ Imagine actually choosing to pay
taxes at a higher rate. That is what some foundations do. Now, a
little-noticed provision in the Clinton 2001 budget proposal aims
to simplify the tax, to allow foundations to focus on making grants
without regard to the tax impact of those decisions, according to a
Treasury official. But some charity advocates say the provision
will also eliminate the only incentive that now exists to encourage
more giving. By Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-INTERNET (Hong Kong) _ Marketplace Column: The fever
over Asian Internet stocks came close to delirium here Wednesday as
tens of thousands of Hong Kong residents besieged local banks to
buy shares in the stock offering of Tom.com, a 1-month-old
Chinese-language Internet service. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   HOTEL-AD-COLUMN _ With a record TV budget, Best Western
International has created an ad campaign that it hopes will raise
the profile of its brand as it battles higher-spending competitors
in the lodging business. By Jane L. Levere.
</P>
