<SLUG> BC-QANTAS-DEAD-DEER-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
68 DEER SUFFOCATE ON QANTAS PLANE  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 275-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 By KATHY MARKS  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ Qantas, the Australian airline which prides itself on
its squeaky-clean image, is under investigation after 68 deer were
found suffocated in cramped cages aboard ones of its planes.
</P>
<P>
   The deer were part of a herd of 114 animals that were being
transported from the eastern city of Brisbane to the Thai capital,
Bangkok. They were found dead during the Brisbane to Sydney leg of
the trip on Tuesday last week.
</P>
<P>
   The airline, which has never had a fatal accident, said
Wednesday that it had suspended all shipments of live deer pending
an inquiry into the incident.
</P>
<P>
   The deer were Rusas, a species introduced to Australia from Asia
more than a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   They were found squeezed into crowded cages and left
unmonitored. The surviving deer were seized and are being cared for
by the Royal Society for the Protection of Animals.
</P>
<P>
   Qantas is one of several parties that are being investigated
over the deaths. Raeleen Redford, the society's deputy chief
executive, said: ``They were subjected to high levels of stress
caused by overcrowding, and the results from the postmortem confirm
that the cause of death was trauma and suffocation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Society said it was appalled that anyone could consider
exporting such fragile animals in such a manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a very delicate, flimsy and flighty animal,'' Redford
said. ``Look at them and you basically see Bambi.''
</P>
<P>
   A Qantas spokesman said that the airline was assisting with the
inquiry. The airline regularly carries livestock in the pressurized
freight holds of Boeing 747 and 767 aircraft. It averages about
6,000 shipments a year, including domestic pets. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 275-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
