<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALAS-AFRICA-EDITORIAL-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SADLY, WE FIND IT TOO EASY TO FORGET ABOUT AFRICA  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Editorial)   (This provocative 450-word ``separate-buy'' editorial is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By THE EDITORIAL BOARD OF THE INDEPENDENT  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.N. Security Council has completed a ``month of Africa.''
Others, offering hostages to fortune, speak of ``the year of
Africa,'' even of an ``African century.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, however, the first weeks of the new millennium have
proved an almost unrelieved disaster for that benighted continent.
</P>
<P>
   In the Congo, a war that is Africa's equivalent of Europe's
Great War rages, involving six outside countries.
</P>
<P>
   In the Sudan (for 17 years now) and in Angola (for 25 years)
civil wars continue. Eritrea and Ethiopia are engaged in their own
bloody conflict, amid signs of new famine.
</P>
<P>
   Nine months after democracy returned to Nigeria, violence
between Christians and Muslims casts doubt on the future of one of
sub-Saharan Africa's potential regional superpowers.
</P>
<P>
   Misrule in Zimbabwe has wrecked another prospective African
showcase _ although this month's referendum defeat for Robert
Mugabe offers a glimmer of hope.
</P>
<P>
   The army has taken over in Ivory Coast, once star pupil among
France's former African colonies, while lawlessness continues in
Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe, but not only Zimbabwe, is suffering from an AIDS
epidemic without precedent.
</P>
<P>
   And if man does not oblige, then nature will.
</P>
<P>
   Take Mozambique, for instance, until now among Africa's few good
news stories, as it valiantly strove to put a ruinous 16-year civil
war behind it.
</P>
<P>
   Cricket followers will have noted the rains which played havoc
with the tourists' fixtures in South Africa and Zimbabwe. Those
rains, however, have brought calamity to Mozambique, leaving
hundreds of thousands homeless and at the mercy of malaria and
other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Wednesday launched a $13 million emergency appeal, and
the world's attention, briefly, will alight on a country most of
whose inhabitants live on pennies a day.
</P>
<P>
   A greater consolation, perhaps, for Mozambique is that, in
Africa, natural disasters such as drought and flood are less
enduring than tragedies made by man.
</P>
<P>
   The blame extends to everyone. Much obviously lies with Africa's
governments, often criminally negligent of the welfare of the
people they claim to rule.
</P>
<P>
   But we in the West are guilty, too, with our short attention
spans and our reliance on gestures such as debt-relief initiatives
and a promised ``war on AIDS.''
</P>
<P>
   More pertinently, the prices of export commodities on which
African countries depend are near historic lows, while
international aid in real terms is scarcely half what it was 30
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Of the world's 50 poorest countries, 31 are in Africa. Any
number of ``Africa years'' is unlikely to alter that dismal fact. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 450-word editorial is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
