<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASYLUMS-MEXICO-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LA VIDA `LOCO': MEXICAN MENTAL ASYLUMS `ABSOLUTELY SHOCKING'  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This graphic 850-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By JAN MCGIRK  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Mario's brow is bleeding again, since he keeps
knocking it against the cold cement wall.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro, whose arms are so atrophied that he cannot raise them to
swat away the flies clustering on his face, lies limp on a soiled
bed.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto's hands are bound as he is pulled down the corridor on a
leash, stumbling through puddles of urine.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Juanita is lashed by her ankle to the window frame
until it is time to be untied, stripped, dragged across a tile
floor, then hosed down with cold water.
</P>
<P>
   These are not their real names, but the daily degradations of
life in a Mexican asylum are all too real for 7,000 long-stay
mental patients across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The incidents are all documented. At the conclusion of a
three-year investigation into human-rights abuses in Mexico's
government mental institutions, Dr. Robert Okin, chief of
psychiatry at San Francisco General Hospital and co-author of a
newly released report, rated conditions ``among the worst we have
seen anyplace in the world. Absolutely shocking...subhuman.''
</P>
<P>
   An American team from Mental Disability Rights International, a
nongovernment organization working closely with Mexican rights
activists, inspected facilities with no forewarning.
</P>
<P>
   Although they witnessed some improvements since 1996, their
report charges that the Mexican government fails to enforce its own
mental health laws and that serious and pervasive violations of
international human-rights standards continue to be widespread,
particularly outside the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Patients can be placed inside a Mexican institution against
their will with little hope of ever leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Rosenthal, MDRI' s executive director, has toured a dozen
different countries since he founded this independent advocacy
group.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer says he was troubled by high-profile campaigns to
free a few political prisoners locked up in primitive asylums; he
wondered why no one else was outraged about the abysmal conditions
endured by the mental patients.
</P>
<P>
   Next month he will present the Mexico report in Washington to
the Inter-American Commission of Human Rights, part of the
Organization of American States.
</P>
<P>
   By drawing international attention to such dehumanizing
conditions, his independent advocacy group hopes to hasten reform.
The Mexican Health Ministry declined to comment on the findings.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by recent press coverage, Health Secretary Antonio
Gonzalez has inspected three of the most notorious psychiatric
hospitals, and admitted that he saw a ``lot of aspects to
improve.''
</P>
<P>
   Once they are labelled ``loco,'' Mexican mental patients without
private funds are isolated in public institutions referred to as
granjas, or funny farms.
</P>
<P>
   Detention can be arbitrary. Over two-thirds of the patients
actually are suffering from epilepsy or mental retardation, yet are
locked up in wards alongside the mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   Abandoned by families who are unable to care for them, the
majority get institutionalized for life simply because they have
nowhere else to go. Without stimulation or physical exercise, most
rapidly deteriorate inside the bare walls of the asylums and come
to resemble the other inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Understaffed institutions in remote areas can be dangerous, the
report concluded.
</P>
<P>
   At Ocaranza, in Hidalgo state, taking medication was judged a
health risk: to down pills with water out of a common bucket,
sharing the same cup between 50 patients, was bound to spread
infection.
</P>
<P>
   There is no access to soap before eating, despite the routine
filth of the hospital surroundings. Side-effects from psychotropic
medication often go untreated, and basic attention to open wounds
or bed sores is lacking.
</P>
<P>
   Physical restraint is frequently misused to prevent patients
from masturbating, instead of being resorted to only when their
actions can inflict harm.
</P>
<P>
   Even young children are trussed up in straight jackets or tied
with bed sheets to wheelchairs for prolonged periods.
</P>
<P>
   There are few activity programs or skills training to break the
monotony, no music, no artwork. At a facility near Guadalajara,
children are frequently left to rock or stroke themselves for
comfort.
</P>
<P>
   There is no attempt at behavior modification. Adolescents and
children lie for hours in soiled clothes, although the visiting
psychiatrists determined that 70 percent of them could be
toilet-trained with sufficient supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely are they even taken outdoors by harried staff, who prefer
to avoid exposing them to insect bites or sunburn.
</P>
<P>
   At Sayago Hospital, some 40 mental patients no longer can walk
because of prolonged inactivity, and now are confined to
wheelchairs. Bones are brittle and prone to fracture. There were
several deaths reported there after bronchitis broke out in the
wards.
</P>
<P>
   The MDRI team noted an acute shortage of blankets, towels, and
clothing, and even in cold weather, inmates walk around barely
clad. Many patients appear malnourished.
</P>
<P>
   The rights group urged that Mexico transform long-stay hospitals
into treatment centers. Launching a system of community residence
programs and halfway houses could enable many patients to lead
functional lives outside the granjas.
</P>
<P>
   The group warned that, unless the community provides support,
emptying institutions abruptly could create a mentally unstable
underclass among the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   To date, there are no government-funded group homes for mental
patients in all of Mexico. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 850-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-00 0145EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
