A6872 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-JUAN-GONZALEZ-RAN     02-24 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-JUAN-GONZALEZ-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS JUST HISTORY NOW FOR GONZALEZ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKELAND, Fla. _ Juan Gonzalez is busy.
</P>
<P>
   There are new teammates to meet, there's a mentor relationship
to start with young Juan Encarnacion, there are line drives to be
scattered to and beyond the fence of the practice field, there are
conditioning sprints to be run.
</P>
<P>
   He's much too busy for a stroll down memory lane.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't want to reminisce about the good times he had with
the Rangers, the Most Valuable Player awards, the three American
League West titles, the home run and runs-batted in- crowns, the
friends he made.
</P>
<P>
   He refuses to dwell on the bad times, when he was accused of
being a malingerer because he wouldn't play while hurt, the obscene
gesture at the official scorer who ruled an error on a wicked
liner, the charge that he cared more about his statistics than the
team.
</P>
<P>
   There's no time to lament his departure from Texas, it seems, or
to blast his former team for sending him packing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to say thank you to the Rangers organization for giving
me the opportunity by signing me to play professional baseball,''
Gonzalez said here yesterday. ``Thank you to the fans there. I had
some great memories in Texas. Two MVPs, All-Star Game, division
titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``But right now it's history. Now it's a new team, a new family,
a new city. It's a new time.''
</P>
<P>
   This new time sees Gonzalez with the familiar No. 19 on his back
and the familiar, powerful stroke. But it also sees him in a
strange uniform and in a strange place.
</P>
<P>
   A smiling, relaxed Gonzalez pulled on a Detroit Tigers uniform
for the first time yesterday, and went through his first
spring-training workout in a city other than Port Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   If being in a new uniform, in a new town, with a new team, seems
strange to Gonzalez, he disguises it well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball is the same,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers hope the baseball is the same. They packaged six
players, including some of their best young talent, to the Rangers
in exchange for Gonzalez, reliever Danny Patterson and backup
catcher Gregg Zaun because Gonzalez averaged .314 with 43 home runs
and 140 RBI the past four seasons, which included two American
League MVP awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave up some good young players, but that's what they are:
good young players,'' Tigers general manager Randy Smith said. ``We
got an established guy that, barring injuries, should be in
Cooperstown when he's done. I had zero hesitation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers made the trade because they were 12th in the 14-team
league with 747 runs scored last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we were missing last year, that big-name guy, that
go-to guy in the middle of our lineup,'' said third baseman Dean
Palmer, Gonzalez's Rangers teammate for eight seasons. ``When the
game's tight and you need a run, that's the guy you want up at the
plate. It's good. I just hope we can keep him for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the $140 million challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers general manager Doug Melvin traded Gonzalez because the
right fielder can be a free agent at the end of the season and the
club didn't want to pay the $15 million a year or so he would
command as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in shock when the Rangers traded me, but I understand,''
Gonzalez said. ``They didn't have the budget to pay me for the next
seven or eight years, so I understand perfectly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers are moving into a new, revenue-producing stadium this
season, so they can afford to keep him. They reportedly offered
$140 million over eight years, a figure that Smith refuses to
confirm or deny.
</P>
<P>
   But to Smith, the size of the contract isn't as important as the
necessity of getting Gonzalez signed to a long-term contract.
Otherwise, the Tigers paid a steep price to rent a player who can
make the team better but by himself isn't likely to carry it past
the Cleveland Indians in the AL Central.
</P>
<P>
   ``You make the deal with more than 2000 in mind,'' Smith said.
``You don't make the deal unless you think you can figure out a way
to make him stay. We're prepared to pay what those type of players
get on the open market. We want to create an environment where he's
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez isn't ready to commit to the Tigers beyond this season,
not necessarily because he thinks there might be greater riches on
the free agent market but because he wants to see if he'll like
living and playing in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he said. ``It's a big adjustment. It's too
early. I need more time.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't need more time, though, to get comfortable with his
new uniform and his new team. That's because despite what has
changed, his role remains the same: drive in the key runs that win
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows this is a better team this year,'' Gonzalez
said. ``I promise you this ballclub will win a lot more games this
year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
