<HEADER>
A6873 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-CAL-PRIMARY-LADN     02-24 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAL-PRIMARY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY LEE CONDON
</HEADLINE>
 
McCAIN COULD WIN IN CALIFORNIA, BUT STILL LOSE 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On March 7, both Sen. John McCain and Gov. George
Bush could claim victory in California _ one in the popular vote
``beauty contest,'' the other in the all-important delegate count.
</P>
<P>
   The way California's primary system is set up, a candidate can
be a winner and a loser at the same time. McCain could win
California the same way he won the Michigan primary _ with swing
votes from Democrats and independents _ and still lose the state.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the political parties in California, unlike those
in Michigan, only count votes cast by party members in awarding
delegates to the national conventions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will have a beauty contest in the overall vote,'' said
Marshall Riley, an active local Republican and member of the
executive committee of the California Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   On election night, election officials will announce two tallies
_ who won the party delegate selection vote and who won the popular
vote.
</P>
<P>
   So, McCain could win the overall vote, thanks to cross-over
votes from Democrats and independents, but still lose if most
California Republicans vote for the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   California has a winner-take-all primary. The candidate who gets
the Republican votes gets all the state's bounty of 162 delegates _
15 percent of the total needed to secure the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Republicans) will have to explain how someone can get a
plurality of popular votes in an election and get zero delegates,
at least from a public relations point of view,'' Riley said. ``I'd
have a hard time explaining it to a seventh- and eighth-grade civic
class.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Bill Jones, a Republican and a recently
converted McCain supporter, said he believes the parties should use
the results of the overall open primary rather than just counting
votes by their own party members.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parties can certainly write their own rules, but not
counting the votes of everyone who votes for their candidates is
not positive for the political process,'' said Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been pushing for a long time for them to use the results
of the blanket primary. I'm suggesting we're not sending the right
message if we're not welcoming the votes of Democrats and
independent voters. The parties have to go back to them for their
votes in November.''
</P>
<P>
   The McCain strategy has been to court independents and Democrats
to vote for him. The senator is trying to show that he has
cross-party support and will be able to beat the Democratic nominee
in November.
</P>
<P>
   But to party leaders, the name of the game in this contest is
securing delegates.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign sees nothing wrong with the system in place
now. ``We don't make the rules. We play by them,'' said Margita
Thompson, California communications coordinator for the Bush
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   California voters approved Proposition 198 in March 1996,
creating an open primary system. It allows Californians to vote for
any candidate they want in a primary, regardless of either the
voter or the candidate's party affiliation. Before the change,
independent voters were shut out of primary voting.
</P>
<P>
   But in June 1999, the state Legislature muted the effect of the
open primary, ordering Jones to prepare two separate tallies of the
primary election's votes.
</P>
<P>
   When voters cast their ballots, they will be coded so election
officials can pull non-Republican and non-Democratic voters out of
their respective primary tallies. If a Republican votes for Vice
President Al Gore, that vote will not be counted by Democratic
Party officials.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, a political science professor at Claremont
Graduate School, said if McCain wins in California, but loses to
Bush among Republicans, there will be discord about who should get
the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect there would be an awfully large fight within the
Republican Party,'' Jeffe said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Democratic and Republican officials have been fighting
Proposition198 since it passed, joining to sue to get it
overturned. The U.S. Supreme Court is slated to make a decision on
the constitutionality of the initiative this summer, said Bob
Mulholland of the California Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   While proponents of an open primary say having a separate tally
excludes independent voters, Mulholland said the national party
should be able to decide how it wants its delegates chosen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The votes from independents will be counted. But clearly if
they were concerned about voting for delegates, they could be
registered as Democrats. National party rules are a lot like
marriage _ you have to be committed,'' Mulholland said. ``Delegates
are the only thing that matters in California.''
</P>
</TEXT>
