<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-COLLEGE-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOYOLA MARYMOUNT CEREMONY CLOSES CHAPTER OF TRAGEDY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saturday, Loyola Marymount retired the jerseys of the late Hank
Gathers (No. 44) and his good friend Bo Kimble (No. 30).
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Loyola Marymount coach Charles Bradley announced his
resignation, effective at the end of a regular season that seems
destined to end without a single victory against an NCAA Division I
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Two events, linked but yet distant. As distant and as eerie and
as goose-bump-inducing as the events of what happened a decade ago.
In March 1990, Gathers, Kimble and Loyola Marymount provided
college basketball with a storyline that was both tragic and
uplifting.
</P>
<P>
   On March 4, 1990, the 23-year-old Gathers collapsed and died of
a heart ailment during a West Coast Conference tournament game at
Loyola Marymount. The WCC canceled the rest of the tournament.
Loyola Marymount, with a 23-5 record, went into the NCAA Tournament
without a player who a year earlier had become just the second
player to lead Division I in scoring and rebounding.
</P>
<P>
   Kimble, Gathers' best friend from their Philadelphia days, had
led the Lions in scoring during the 1989-90 season, succeeding his
teammate as the scoring champion. With coach Paul Westhead as
college basketball's resident Mad Scientist, Loyola Marymount's
frenetic style of play produced a Division I record 122.4 points
per game that season.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990 NCAA Tournament, Loyola Marymount inspired the
nation. In a first-round victory against New Mexico State, Kimble
honored his fallen comrade by shooting his first free throw
left-handed in a tribute to the left-handed Gathers. Kimble made
the shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that moment, I really didn't care if the ball went over the
backboard, to be quite honest,'' Kimble said. ``I was paying
tribute to Hank.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second round, the Lions dismantled defending champion
Michigan, 149-115, setting a tournament record for points scored.
Loyola Marymount's run ended when eventual champion UNLV defeated
Marymount, 131-101.
</P>
<P>
   All of those memories came flooding back Saturday at Gersten
Pavilion. The feel-good NCAA run of 1990 was recalled, but so was
the pain of a mother (Lucille Gathers) losing her son and a son
(Aaron Crump, now 16) losing his father. And the acrimony of a $33
million wrongful death lawsuit (eventually dropped) brought by
Gathers' family against the school, Westhead and team doctors.
</P>
<P>
   More reality hit Monday when Bradley resigned after just three
seasons. The Lions are 2-23 this season, with games remaining at
St. Mary's tonight and San Diego on Saturday, plus the WCC
tournament starting March 4. In nine seasons since 1990, Loyola
Marymount has not returned to the NCAA Tournament, has had three
winning seasons and a combined record of 91-159.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time passes,'' WCC commissioner Michael Gilleran said. ``Back
in 1990, it was both tragic and inspiring. There were so many
conflicting feelings. It was a tough time for us in the conference
office, but the people at the school went through even more.''
\Nrevhed:SPOTLIGHT
Huskies seek answers to poor play, not jokes
Before Connecticut's success of recent years, including last
season's national championship, the statewide joke was that you
couldn't spell Connecticut without N-I-T. That line is making the
rounds again.
</P>
<P>
   While it is unlikely that the Huskies will be left out of the
64-team NCAA field (the last defending champion to face that
embarrassment was Kansas in 1989), UConn is looking more and more
like UCan't. Monday night at Madison Square Garden, Connecticut
looked like a very average team in a 79-64 loss to St. John's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not playing like an NCAA Tournament team right now,''
junior point guard Khalid El-Amin said of the Huskies (18-8, 7-6 in
the Big East Conference).
</P>
<P>
   Of the past 10 national champions, none has been seeded lower
than No. 4. It's unlikely that the Huskies will maintain that
trend.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's problems are multiple. The Huskies are missing
go-to scorer Richard Hamilton and defensive stopper Ricky Moore
from last season. El-Amin and backcourt mate Albert Mouring have
struggled to bear the outside scoring burden (they were outscored
42-2 by the St. John's backcourt).
</P>
<P>
   ``Our backcourt play has been deteriorating over the last three
or four weeks,'' Connecticut coach Jim Calhoun said. ``But there
are a multitude of reasons. This team has some inconsistencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut has nonconference losses to Iowa and Michigan State.
Also, the Huskies have been swept in Big East play by Notre Dame
and St. John's, in addition to losing at Syracuse and at home to
Miami (Fla.).
</P>
<P>
   ``We've created this situation, nobody else has,'' Calhoun said.
``Right now, we are in a very difficult time. We want to get back
into the NCAA Tournament. Clearly, we have some work ahead of us.
\RSt. John's is\S trying to get a high seed in the tournament.
We're trying to make the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't get things together, our season is going to have a
very premature ending.''
\Nrevhed:FAST BREAKS \Nsubheds:NCAA Tournament update Mountain West
Conference commissioner Craig Thompson, chairman of the NCAA men's
tournament committee, discussed some of this year's issues during a
media teleconference yesterday. Thompson said that games in the
Western Athletic and Mountain West conference tournaments could
carry a bit more weight with the committee. Neither conference has
an automatic bid to this year's tournament. However, Thompson
believes that conference tournament games could mean more than
regular-season games when calculating at-large bids.
</P>
<P>
   This year's committee membership has been increased from nine to
10 and four of those members are new _ North Carolina Charlotte
athletic director Judy Rose, Iowa State athletic director Gene
Smith, North Carolina State athletic director Les Robinson and
Arizona athletic director Jim Livengood.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said the Ratings Percentage Index ``is probably the
most overrated tool that we use. People on the committee don't base
their selections solely on the RPI.''
\Nsubheds:Devilish in the desert Rob Evans, a former assistant
coach at Texas Tech and Oklahoma State, is stirring things up in
the Pacific-10 Conference. Evans is in his second season at Arizona
State after a successful six-year career at Mississippi. The Sun
Devils and their coach are making their presence felt.
</P>
<P>
   After Arizona State defeated Southern California on Saturday,
the players got into a postgame scuffle. And USC coach Henry Bibby
accused Arizona State of throwing elbows and ``undisciplined
play.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every coach in the country who knows me knows that I
run a disciplined program,'' Evans said. ``If I worried about what
one guy said about me, I'd be loony.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Arizona State travels to play at No. 4 Arizona. If the
Sun Devils continue their recent surge (five victories in their
past six games), consider the Arizona State-Arizona rivalry to be
at full boil.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Evans has been outspoken about Pac-10 issues such
as officiating, travel arrangements and a postseason tournament.
Stanford coach Mike Montgomery and Arizona coach Lute Olson and
their schools have been the leading opponents of a postseason
tournament. Evans believes the Pac-10 needs a postseason tourney.
Without naming names, he called nontourney advocates ``selfish.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a right to publicly disagree,'' said Olson, noting his
17 seasons at Arizona. Evans pointed out he has a right to an
opinion.
\Nsubheds:Layups Here is an exchange from this week's Atlantic 10
Conference coaches' teleconference. George Washington coach Tom
Penders was talking about the development of his young players.
``It's like a goat looking at a fence. If you make a big deal of
the fence, they're never going to jump over it,'' he said. St.
Joseph's coach Phil Martelli, who follows Penders on the call, had
this comment: ``When was the last time you saw a goat, Tom Penders?
Did you go down to Texas and become a cowboy?'' The ``New York
Daily News'' reported that the NCAA's investigation of St. John's
is focusing on the relationship between ``street agent'' Rob
Johnson and some of the school's players. That name should be
familiar to Texas A&AMP;M fans. Johnson's involvement with the Aggies
and former coach Kermit Davis put the school on probation in 1991.
Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski wore a yellow tie for his team's game at
North Carolina State. The fashion gesture was in honor of Georgia
Tech coach Bobby Cremins, who announced his end-of-the-season
resignation last week. ``What Mike Krzyzewski did, I'll always
remember,'' said Cremins, whose yellow tie has become a trademark.
``It's one of the nicest gestures anybody's ever done for me.''
Miami (Fla.), with a 73-71 victory last season and a 63-57 victory
Saturday, has become the first Big East Conference opponent to win
consecutive games against Connecticut at Gampel Pavilion.
\Nsubheds:By the numbers 6: Number of Big Ten Conference schools
with three or more consecutive conference championships. Michigan
State is in position to win its third consecutive Big Ten title.
101-50: The score in Stanford's victory against rival California
Saturday. It was the worst loss in Cal history, and it was
Stanford's largest victory margin against a Pacific-10 Conference
school. 23-0: Illinois' game-opening run Saturday against
Northwestern. The Wildcats were scoreless for the game's first
15:13. The final score: Illinois 63, Northwestern 30. 1986: The
last season Arizona State swept the Los Angeles schools (UCLA and
Southern California). 86.9: Percent of the team's minutes played by
Duke's top six players _ Chris Carrawell, Shane Battier, Nate
James, Jason Williams, Carlos Boozer and Mike Dunleavy Jr. Dunleavy
is out indefinitely with mononucleosis.
\Nrevhed:Inside the numbers Top-ranked Stanford leads Division I in
victory margin at 20.8 points per game. Margin of victory not only
can indicate a team's dominance, it often translates into NCAA
Tournament success. A look at where the teams with the largest
victory margins have fared in the past 10 NCAA tournaments: Year
Team Margin NCAA result 1999 Duke 24.7 Lost title game 1998 Duke
21.5 Lost regional final 1997 Kentucky 20.3 Lost title game 1996
Kentucky 22.1 Won title 1995 Kentucky 18.4 Lost regional final 1994
Arkansas 17.9 Won title 1993 North Carolina 17.8 Won title 1992
Indiana 17.6 Lost Final Four semifinal 1991 UNLV 26.7 Lost title
game 1990 Oklahoma 21.0 Lost second round
nn
</P>
