<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-FREE-AGENTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 
Cowboys work on free agents 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCKX 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Cowboys continue to work quietly toward
trying to sign a free-agent cornerback and bring in a No. 2
quarterback to replace Jason Garrett.
</P>
<P>
   They also are interested, if not growing anxious, in beginning
meaningful negotiations with their own top unrestricted free
agents, defensive tackle Alonzo Spellman and free safety George
Teague, since the team already has lost two defensive starters,
Randall Godfrey to Tennessee and Kavika Pittman to Denver. Garrett
defected to the New York Giants.
</P>
<P>
   When asked] about Spellman and Teague, Cowboys coach Dave Campo
said, ``I can promise you, we're on top of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Valley Ranch was a virtual ghost town late yesterday as Campo,
his assistants, along with members of the scouting department and
medical staff all made travel plans to Indianapolis for the NFL
Scouting Combine, which is today through Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The combine is a who's who of college players who are expected
to go in the first several rounds of the April 15-16 NFL draft. All
31 teams are involved in physical and psychological testing, using
their own coaches, scouts and medical staff to carefully evaluate
each candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have five selections, including only one pick
through the first three rounds because of trades made with Seattle
for receivers Joey Galloway (first-round picks in 2000 and 2001)
and James McKnight (third round in 2000). Forty-two picks will be
made before the Cowboys get a pick; they don't pick again until the
fourth round. \Ntagtop:Ray Buck, (817) 390-7096
\Ntagbottom:rbuck\Nstar-telegram.com
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
