</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-AUSTIN-RACETRACK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTIN RACETRACK CLEARS HURDLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Horse racing at a new racetrack in Austin, Texas, could start
next year after the Texas Racing Commission unanimously approved
plans for the Austin Jockey Club yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The track, which will be located near the new Austin-Bergstrom
Airport in southwest Austin, is projected to cost $14 million and
will be managed by the same company that operates Retama Park near
San Antonio. Retama general manager Bob Pollock said construction
on the AJC could begin in six months.
</P>
<P>
   The project must gain zoning approval from the city of Austin.
It's likely that the facility will handle wagering on races
simulcast from other locations next year before live racing begins
in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can get right after it as soon as the zoning is
final,'' Pollock said. ``This will be awfully good for Texas racing
as well as Austin.''
</P>
<P>
   The AJC received support from the Texas Thoroughbred Association
and the American Quarter Horse Association. The Texas Horsemen's
Partnership, which represents horse owners and trainers in Texas,
has pledged $2.5 million to help finance the track. Half of that
total will be repaid over a 10-year period.
</P>
<P>
   The commission ignored arguments from officials at Manor Downs,
which has been operating a quarter horse pari-mutuel racing season
outside of Austin since 1990. Howard Phillips, chief financial
officer at Manor, said Austin probably can't support two
racetracks.
</P>
<P>
   That has held true in other metropolitan areas. Bandera Downs
outside of San Antonio closed in 1995 after the opening of Retama.
And Trinity Meadows closed in '96 after Lone Star Park at Grand
Prairie started taking simulcast bets at the Post Time Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance at Manor Downs, located about 15 minutes outside of
Austin, has dropped from almost 40,000 in 1994 to 28,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   AJC officials pledged to the commission to operate a
quarter-horse season in addition to the 20-date thoroughbred season
they already have planned if Manor fails.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to existing tracks, AJC is small. Its $14 million
startup budget ranks below Lone Star ($105 million), Sam Houston
Race Park in Houston ($94 million) and Retama ($85 million). The
AJC is planning a 7-furlong dirt track with no turf course and will
be owned by Houston attorney Joe Archer, Humble real estate broker
Berry Madden and Retama Park chief executive officer Bryan Brown.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
