<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-INFIELD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS HOPEFUL INFIELD HOLES FILLED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Mike Lamb played at Double A last year.
Luis Alicea is 34, hit .201 at the major-league level last year and
hasn't been a regular in three years.
</P>
<P>
   But losing Todd Zeile and Mark McLemore to free agency has
forced the Rangers to take a chance on two players who weren't in
their plans going into the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Both are being asked to play regularly _ Alicea at second base
and Lamb at third _ for a team that expects not only to repeat as
American League West Division champions but contend for the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel confident with what we've done,'' Rangers general
manager Doug Melvin said. ``You can say it's a risk, but there's a
risk with a lot of major-league players. Luis hasn't played
regularly in over two years, but I think he's up to the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Mike Lamb, he's hit .300 everywhere he's went. Reid
Nichols \Rthe Rangers farm director\S kept saying, `I've seen a lot
of minor-league players, and this guy is going to be a player.' I
have enough confidence in our people to trust their judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Spring training will be the first test, and it's not certain
that both will be in the Opening Day lineup. That is especially
true with Lamb, who is trying to take over for Zeile at third. The
Rangers have Tom Evans, their Triple-A third baseman, in camp as a
safety net.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to do the job,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said.
``We'll make an evaluation; is he ready to play in the big leagues?
If not, is Evans the guy? If I don't like what I see, I may tell
Doug, `Hey, we need help.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But Mike Lamb is going to be given every chance. We'll be
patient. We'll work with him. I've only read about him. The next
six weeks we'll watch him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamb does have an impressive minor-league rsum. He hit .324 at
Double-A Tulsa last year with 98 runs scored, 51 doubles, five
triples, 21 home runs and 100 runs batted in. He also hit .343 in
the highly competitive Arizona Fall League, which further suggested
to the Rangers he was ready to jump past Triple A to the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take it as I have to win a job here,'' Lamb said. ``No
matter what people are saying, I still feel I've got to prove it to
myself and everybody else. I'm confident that I can compete at this
level.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were planning on Lamb playing at Triple A this year.
They were hoping Zeile could play third base for one more year,
then move to designated hitter. But when Zeile signed with the New
York Mets, the Rangers decided Lamb was a better risk than any of
the free agents available, including All-Stars Tony Fernandez and
Ed Sprague.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys who were out there weren't of the caliber where we
wanted to invest that kind of money,'' Melvin said. ``We feel we
have a guy who can step in and handle the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Alicea does have a major-league track record. He had two good
years as a regular, hitting .270 for the Boston Red Sox in 1995 and
.253 with 22 stolen bases for the Anaheim Angels in 1997. But after
being a superb backup for the Rangers in 1998 and hitting .274, he
slumped to .201 last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about that,'' Alicea said. ``I hurt my wrist
in spring training and waited until after the season to have
surgery. That was a big part of it. But the main thing is getting a
chance to play every day. It's difficult when you only get 100
at-bats to get into a good groove.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have safety nets at second base. Frank Catalanotto,
acquired from the Detroit Tigers in the Juan Gonzalez trade, is a
career .280 hitter with 34 doubles and 17 homers in 525 at-bats and
has played 69 games over the past three years at second base.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also want to look at Edwin Diaz, who was once one of
their top minor-league prospects. The Rangers lost him to the
Arizona Diamondbacks in the 1997 expansion draft, but he is back
with them on a minor-league contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he could play then, and I still think he can play,''
Oates said. ``He could be the best defensive second baseman in
camp.''
</P>
<P>
   But, like Lamb at third, second base is Alicea's job to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is an incumbent, it would have to be Luis,'' Oates
said. ``I don't expect him to play 140 games there, but I expect
Luis to get most of the playing time. How much will be determined
by how well he plays and how healthy he is.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
