<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TV-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS, FOX CLOSE TO TELEVISION AGREEMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ The Rangers are close to finalizing a
deal that would give Fox Network the TV rights for their games
televised locally.
</P>
<P>
   Club president Jim Lites said all 162 Rangers games will be
shown in the Fort Worth-Dallas area this season, with approximately
70 games on over-the-air stations and the rest on cable on Fox
Sports Net. The Rangers are awaiting final approval on the contract
from Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Lites declined to state the length of the deal but said it
involves a substantial increase in rights fees.
</P>
<P>
   The over-the-air games would be split between Fox stations
KDFW/Channel 4 and KDFI/Channel 27; KXTX/Channel 39, which is owned
by Rangers owner Tom Hicks; and KXAS/Channel 5, which has an
existing contract to broadcast up to five Rangers games. The
agreement gives Fox the right to decide which games it wants to
show on Channel 4 and Channel 27. Any games it doesn't want to show
will be telecast on Channel 39, Lites said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first year at least I would expect a bit of a bounce
around,'' Lites said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had 90 games shown over-the-air last year. Lites
said less games on the over-the-air stations make it easier for the
Rangers to attract advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball ratings are high right now, so the more games you
have, the harder it is for advertisers to keep up with the rating
points,'' Lites said. ``They only have so much money, and they have
to do business in Atlanta, Kansas City and other markets. We've
found that 70 games over-the-air and 90 games on cable works
best.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks sold the cable TV rights to his sports holdings, primarily
the Rangers and the Stars, to Fox Sports Net in the fall for what
sources said was a $300 million deal over 15 years, including $100
million upfront.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' contract with Channel 39 expires at the end of this
season. Lites said the Stars are also close to a deal that would
give Fox both their over-the-air and cable rights for at least 10
years. The NHL Board of Governors must approve the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' over-the-air rights are currently with Channel 39.
That deal expires at the end of this season. Lites said the new
arrangement would have 30-35 games over-the-air and the rest on
cable, similar to their current agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Lites said Hicks began looking to sell over-the-air rights once
he sold cable rights to Fox.
</P>
<P>
   This deal is ``what makes the most sense for us with our
resources,'' Lites said. ``It's economics.''
</P>
<P>
   Lites said Bill Jones and Tom Grieve will continue to serve as
the television broadcasters for all Rangers games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything we do, we'll pick the announcers and control the
broadcasters,'' Lites said. \Nsubheds:Dransfeldt starting over
Rangers management believes infielder Kelly Dransfeldt has the
defensive ability to be an everyday player in the major leagues.
But they're concerned about his hitting, which fell apart after he
was brought up to the major leagues May 1 last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get his stroke back,'' manager Johnny Oates said.
``We're going to spend a lot of time on his stroke. Rudy Jaramillo
\Rthe Rangers hitting coach\S is going to break it down and start
over again. He's got too many holes; his swing is too long.
Big-league pitchers were getting him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only thing keeping him from being a big-league
shortstop.''
</P>
<P>
   Dransfeldt was hitting .311 for Triple-A Oklahoma when he was
called up after Royce Clayton injured his shoulder. Dransfeldt hit
.189 in 16 games with the Rangers and, after being sent down May
21, he hit only .218 in his final 81 games with Oklahoma.
\Nsubheds:Briefly Rookie pitcher R.A. Dickey is sidelined with a
strained right hamstring. Juan Moreno, another minor-league
pitcher, also has stopped throwing because of soreness in his left
shoulder. The Rangers still have several key players unsigned,
including outfielders Gabe Kapler and Ruben Mateo, and reliever
Jeff Zimmerman. General manager Doug Melvin said he would like
everybody signed by the time exhibition games start March 3. First
baseman Rafael Palmeiro is expected today for the Rangers' first
full-squad workout. Catcher Ivan Rodriguez is expected tomorrow.
\Ntagtop:Staff writer Jennifer Floyd contributed to this report.
nn
</P>
