<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS REMAKING THEMSELVES INTO NEW BALLPARK'S IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ Remodeling like this hasn't been done since
RuPaul.
</P>
<P>
   Well before the Mariners moved into the Guilty Pleasure last
year, the bosses knew a fundamental makeover was inevitable because
of the differences between the old park and the new park.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment in spring training, figurative pallets loaded with
2x4s and drywall are everywhere, ready to implement the new design.
</P>
<P>
   Out with American League thunderball, in with National League
bittyball.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Kingdome, I used to tell my base coaches, `Don't run us
out of innings,''' said manager Lou Piniella, which meant avoiding
outs by trying to steal bases or stretch hits. ``Now, I tell 'em,
`Be aggressive. If they get thrown out, what the hell.'''
</P>
<P>
   Why not? The old style collapsed anyway. The Mariners, one-time
possessors of the game's most formidable offense, had in the second
half of 1999 the American League's worst team batting average,
.243. It wasn't all due to the bigger park.
</P>
<P>
   They traded hitters David Segui, Butch Huskey and Matt Mieske
for pitching, and saw Jay Buhner, Russ Davis, John Mabry and Carlos
Guillen go down with injuries while Ken Griffey Jr. was lamely
drifting out of town with a .255 second-half average.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but they still led all of baseball with 244 home runs. As
usual.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the home-run culture around the Mariners sucked in
just about everybody. From big guys to banjo hitters, all were
gorging on a diet of Kingdome grand salamis. Nobody in charge said
much of anything, because home runs put fans in the seats.
</P>
<P>
   But as Piniella said in reference to Griffey, Mark McGwire and
Sammy Sosa, baseball's most prolific home run hitters: ``Notice
where their teams finished? None were above. 500.''
</P>
<P>
   Even a guy like newcomer David Bell, a 175-pound second baseman
who hit 10 homers in 422 previous American League at-bats before
last season, went yard 21 times.
</P>
<P>
   But who needs dingers from a second baseman when the rest of the
lineup already is filled with Popeye arms? The Mariners needed base
runners.
</P>
<P>
   So he was often moved in the lineup from the last three spots,
where he hit .311, to the No. 2 spot. It didn't work. He hit .239.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked with David in Chicago once last season, after he had
a streak of about 75 at-bats with two walks,'' Piniella said. ``I
told him that had to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell, who hit just two home runs in the second half, owned up to
the fact that the home-run virus was virulent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every part of the game can be contagious,'' he said. ``That's
why it's so important to develop chemistry, because negative things
can be contagious too. For whatever reason, good hitting, pitching
and fielding can all be contagious.''
</P>
<P>
   Good pitching must become epidemic, based on the half-season
consequences of hitting in the new park.
</P>
<P>
   In last season's 42 games, the park had the highest strikeout
factor and the lowest batting average factor in the American League
(Mariners and opponents), according to STATS, Inc.
</P>
<P>
   It was also lowest in hits, doubles and triples, although
curiously it was second-highest in home runs.
</P>
<P>
   While a half-season is not enough for final conclusions,
particularly without performances in April, May and June, it's
apparent the new yard is seriously imbalanced in favor of pitching.
In other words, thanks for the memories, Griffey and Alex
Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the imbalance has been addressed by repainting and
reconfiguring the hitting background beyond center field.
Complaints were numerous from all teams that day-game pitches could
not be tracked because of glare.
</P>
<P>
   Still, now that San Francisco's Candlestick Park is gone from
baseball, the GP probably trails only Denver's Coors Field, where
the mile-high altitude warps the game, and the Ballpark at
Arlington (heat and wind), as the yard most vulnerable most of the
time to environmental conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's spring of steady dampness and heavy, southwesterly air
usually gives way to the brightest, most humidity-free summers in
North America, along with a northerly breeze. Because it is
baseball's most northern outdoor park, the sun will appear at the
widest spread of angles throughout a season.
</P>
<P>
   The retractable roof means some conditions can be manipulated a
little to suit a game situation as well as fan comfort. But there's
no manipulating the fact that a cold, breezy, damp yard is hard on
hitters.
</P>
<P>
   So the Mariners have assembled a pitching-dominant roster that
includes more line-drive hitters, and supplied it with a fresh set
of instructions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want them to hit balls on the ground and down the lines,''
Piniella said. ``We're going to bunt more, raise our on-base
percentage, run the bases hard and hit behind the runners.
</P>
<P>
   ``And no more home run contests in batting practice.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first spring-training media chat Tuesday, Rodriguez
captured the Mariners conversion with a remark from his first
drills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't bunted in seven years,'' he said. ``That should tell
you how that ballpark plays.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Mariners head north in a month, the salami
breath will be gone. Identification will be possible only through
fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
