<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS RESPOND TO MOTIVATIONAL TALK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY _ Hell, fire and Andy Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Add them up, and the Los Angeles Kings' 7-2 victory against the
Calgary Flames on Wednesday was a sermon that took off only after
the team's first-year coach got mad.
</P>
<P>
   All season, Murray has showered his players with positive
thoughts and little sayings attempting to keep the team upbeat. But
after two losses and a two-goal deficit in the first 10 minutes
against Calgary, Murray called timeout. He started naming names.
</P>
<P>
   Misbegotten Kings like Aki Berg and Donald Audette responded
with goals. Struggling Jere Karalahti and Jason Blake did, too.
</P>
<P>
   Then the big guys, Luc Robitaille, Ziggy Palffy and Rob Blake
moved in to finish off a string of seven consecutive goals,
including five in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake, this was Murray's handiwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he called the timeout, we knew there were two ways we
could go,'' said Robitaille, whose power-play goal was his 10th in
1 32nd this season and 549th of his career. ``Andy put the season
on the line. He made us desperate. We played like there was no
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   For Berg, that was important. He came back Monday in Edmonton
after getting benched for two games and played worse. And with 6:01
gone in the first period Wednesday, Berg allowed Jarome Iginla to
skate by and score Calgary's first goal.
</P>
<P>
   Murray had ripped Berg after the morning workout, saying, ``He
was so bad (vs. Edmonton) I couldn't bench him or I might have lost
him forever.''
</P>
<P>
   With 7:43 gone in the second period, the Kings finally got the
message.
</P>
<P>
   Audette, who also added two assists, scored his first goal since
Dec. 14 when he took a pass from Glen Murray in front and beat
Flames' goaltender Fred Brathwaite.
</P>
<P>
   Less than five minutes later, Berg atoned for Calgary's first
goal by tying the game after passes by Dan Bylsma and Len Barrie,
two more forgotten Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That meant so much to me,'' Berg said. ``It just gave me so
much confidence. The last few days haven't been easy, but I knew if
head up good things would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   His teammates noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could just see how up he looked after scoring the goal,''
defenseman Mattias Norstrom said. ``Everyone felt good for Aki.
Most of us have been there. He really played well.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost lost in Berg's performance was Audette's effort. Even
before he missed six weeks with a badly sprained left ankle, he was
slumping. Audette had 10 goals in the team's first 25 games, but
since then had scored only once.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned, Audette played on the third line instead of
his customary spot on the second unit. He went to Murray on Tuesday
and said he'd like to be a scorer again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I can do,'' Audette said. ``I asked for a chance,
and I did the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Audette's second line finished with five points. Overall, the
Kings rattled Brathwaite with 48 shots, including 36 in the final
two periods.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were so many good signs, but I really thought the play
of the second line made a big difference tonight,'' Robitaille
said. ``They were forechecking like crazy the whole game. And
Donald just adds another dimension to them.''
</P>
<P>
   When Murray went to the whip in the first period, he also knew
the Flames were playing without defensemen Phil Housley (flu) and
Cale Hulse (ankle).
</P>
<P>
   ``That left them with just four defensemen,'' Murray said.
``That is a hard position to be in. We knew if we kept dumping the
puck in, good things would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray was especially happy for Berg, who is still just 22. But
he also was pleased for the team, which moves on to Vancouver for
Friday's game with the Canucks. So pleased, he canceled today's
practice. No speeches are planned either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told them we had 50 minutes left and how we played
could determine our season,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
