<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLE DOWN THE STRETCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC is shorthanded because of injuries, but the
Trojans believe their recent five-game losing streak is due more to
sluggish second-half starts.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans have led the past three games at halftime but
quickly lost the advantage in the opening minutes of the second
half against UCLA, Arizona and Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think we're losing games in the first five minutes of
the second half,'' forward Brian Scalabrine said. ``I think the
Arizona and Arizona State games were decided in those first five
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason?
</P>
<P>
   Forward David Bluthenthal believes the Trojans stop running
their offense and begin to force outside shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we talk about every time, that we need to continue
to move the ball around. Not just come down and have Brandon
(Granville) and Brian spot up and shoot,'' Bluthenthal said. ``When
we run our offense and move the ball around, we make more shots
than when it's just one pass and then take a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Perimeter breakdown: It's been almost a month since the
Trojans won a game, ironically against tonight's opponent, Oregon
State. USC made a Pacific-10 Conference record 20 of 29 3-point
attempts in its 82-69 victory over the Beavers.
</P>
<P>
   In the five games since that victory, the Trojans have made only
33 percent of their 3-point shots (32 for 96).
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a false sense of security,'' Bluthenthal said of the
Oregon State game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to shoot 20 for 29 again (against Oregon
State),'' Scalabrine added. ``But as long as we do things right,
especially on defense, we should win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Tournament hopes: The Trojans (13-11, 6-6) need to win five
of their remaining six games to earn an NCAA Tournament bid, but
Bluthenthal is hopeful that even if the Trojans win four games,
they will receive consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win four of six, I think it's possible to make the
tournament,'' Bluthenthal said. ``Especially if Sam (Clancy) comes
back from his injury and we can blow those last two teams out
(against the Washington schools). Then we're 10-8 in the conference
and we have some momentum. Hopefully, the committee will see
that.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, USC coach Henry Bibby refuses to discuss the number of
victories the Trojans need over the final three weeks of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has an answer for us and everyone has calculated
it,'' Bibby said. ``We're trying to play out the six games the best
we can. We just have to come focused knowing there is no
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Stat leader: USC guard Jeff Trepagnier is the only player in
the Pac-10 who ranks in the top 10 in five different statistical
categories. Trepagnier is first in steals (3.4), fifth in scoring
(15.7), sixth in blocks (1.4), eighth in rebounding (7.0) and ninth
in field-goal percentage (.487).
</P>
<P>
   __ Record pace: Bluthenthal is close to setting a school record
for most rebounds in conference play (10.3), which would surpass
the mark held by Cliff Robinson (9.8) in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   __ Last word: USC players were split on whether next year's
first meeting with Arizona State would be highly anticipated
because of the postgame brawl that marred last week's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys are fired up for next year,'' Bluthenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   But Scalabrine disagreed, saying, ``I'm not circling Arizona
State on my calendar. That was just a physical game. Nothing
more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
