<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS TRY HATCHER FOR CAREW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Mickey Hatcher is the Angels' new hitting coach,
replacing seven-time batting champion and Hall of Famer Rod Carew,
who was let go after last season after serving as the club's
hitting coach since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But Hatcher, a .280 career hitter in 12 major-league seasons,
won't try to rewrite the book on hitting. His job, he says, is to
help instill confidence and support the hitters any way he can.
</P>
<P>
   He has his work cut out for him, considering he is coming in not
knowing the hitters and taking on the task of improving an offense
that ranked last in the American League in batting average (.256)
and runs scored (711) in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened to this team last year had nothing to do with
Rod Carew,'' Hatcher said. ``It had to do with injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher won't tinker with anybody's swing. Reviewing videotape
as Carew did so much won't be such a big part of Hatcher's coaching
method.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a hitting coach, my personal philosophy is they know
themselves as hitters as much as anybody,'' he said. ``They got to
the big leagues for a reason. I'm coming in to work with them. I
want to know their program, what they like to do to prepare. As a
player, I didn't want anybody messing with my mechanics. I'll ask
them, `What did Rod do? Do you want to keep that program?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher believes it's possible to have paralysis by analysis.
Too much staring at the video machine can do as much harm as good.
Darin Erstad, for example, works and studies as hard as anybody.
And he struggled all last season, finishing with a .253 average and
13 homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to simplify things,'' Hatcher said. ``If you have
mechanics on your mind when you're up there, you forget `See the
ball, hit the ball.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher, however, wants his hitters to work hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here for them,'' he said. ``If they want to put in extra
work every day, hitting soft toss or hitting off a tee, we'll do
it. (Manager) Mike Scioscia's philosophy is that the coaches are
the first ones here and the last ones to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Erstad absent: The Angels conducted their first full- squad
workout Wednesday, minus one.
</P>
<P>
   Darin Erstad did not participate in batting practice or outfield
drills because of an inflammed bursa sac in his left shoulder. He
had an MRI on the shoulder Feb. 15, and the results were normal.
But during his physical on Tuesday, team physician Dr. Lewis Yocum
injected the bursa sac with cortisone.
</P>
<P>
   Angels spokesman Tim Mead said it's possible Erstad will work
out today, but he'll likely take another day off before getting
back on the field.
</P>
<P>
   __ Greene update: There were times in the past two or three
years that it seemed certain Todd Greene's catching career was
over. Twice he had surgery on his right shoulder, but he says his
shoulder is fine now.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the first offseason in three years that I didn't have
surgery on my shoulder,'' Greene said. ``It's a lot better. It's
healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene was supposed to work his way into the catching rotation
last season, but he was injured in a collision at the plate and
didn't catch again. Greene, though, says the injury was whiplash,
not his shoulder. And he said he was ready to catch late in the
season, but manager Terry Collins said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were 20 games out,'' Greene said. ``He said there was no
reason to risk it.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia said Greene figures to work his way into the catching
rotation, but they will take things slowly with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a major concern,'' Scioscia said. ``It's important we
make sure Todd's healthy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
