<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS TIE CANUCKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ It was American League baseball at its best on
Wednesday night at The Pond. The pitching wasn't very good and the
ball seemed to be juiced.
</P>
<P>
   Actually it was an NHL game, of sorts, between the Anaheim
Mighty Ducks and Vancouver Canucks. The goalies _ Dominic Roussel
for the Ducks and Felix Potvin _ looked as if they were trying to
stop hand grenades most of the night and as a result the game
turned into offensive shootout in a 4-4 tie before 12,682.
</P>
<P>
   Each shot had a sense of drama, especially in the first two
periods, when the Ducks and Canucks combined for eight goals in the
first 36 minutes of play.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks outscored the Canucks 3-1 on the power play _ getting
goals from Oleg Tverdovsky, Teemu Selanne and Steve Rucchin. But
Vancouver outscored Anaheim 3-1 at even strength.
</P>
<P>
   After falling behind 2-0 in the first half of the first period,
the Canucks came roaring back on a power play goal by Mark Messier
and even strength goals by Darby Hendrickson and Markus Naslund to
take a 3-2 lead early in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Rucchin tied the game, 3-3, with the Ducks' season-high third
power play goal of the game at 3:04, but Anaheim would have rally
one more time just to get to the dressing room tied, 4-4.
</P>
<P>
   Brad May knocked the puck away from Tverdovsky in the Anaheim
zone and Matt Cooke pounced on it and easily beat Roussel on the
short side at 9:34. The Ducks, who outshot the Canucks 16-7 in the
period, got the goal back with the help on bad rebound left by
Potvin.
</P>
<P>
   After taking shot from a steep angle, Ladislav Kohn chased down
the loose puck and tucked a backhander past the Vancouver goalie at
15:43.
</P>
<P>
   Potvin certainly wasn't brilliant, but he did come up with three
big saves in the the second period. He stopped Jeff Nielsen on a
shorthanded less than two minutes before Vancouver's fourth goal.
He also stopped Rucchin and Selanne from point-blank range.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Roussel was fighting each and ever shot. In addition
to the four goals he allowed, the Anaheim backup nearly allowed
Trent Klatt's 70-foot floater to beat him.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the third period that Roussel came up big for
the Ducks, stopping a breakway by Naslund.
</P>
<P>
   With Anaheim's recent history of blowing leads, power play goals
by Tverdovsky at 1:03 and Selanne at 8:36 had the Ducks feeling fat
and sassy _ and the Canucks jumped on them.
</P>
<P>
   And as usual it was poor penalty killing and goaltending that
turned the momentum in favor of Vancouver. Roussel, starting his
second consecutive game in place of Guy Hebert, couldn't handle a
rebound off a deflection and Mark Messier scored at 11:34 to cut
the lead to one.
</P>
<P>
   It was ninth straight game that the Ducks had allowed a power
play goal.
</P>
<P>
   Ranked 27th in the league in penalty killing, Anaheim did manage
to kill off a penalty to Marty McInnis, but rookie Vitaly
Vishnevski was rocked by May freeing the puck for Cooke. The
Vancouver center quickly got it to Darby Hendrickson in the slot
and he snapped a shot past Roussel at 14:58 to tie the game, 2-2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-00 0224EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
