<P>
   &UR; POPE'S MIDEAST TOUR ALREADY SOURED BY CONTROVERSIES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The Pope's Middle East tour, billed by the Vatican
as a personal spiritual journey to Christianity's roots, has
already been soured by religious rivalries and bare-knuckle
politicking, even before his arrival in Egypt Thursday. Although he
is not due to go to Israel and the Palestinian Authority for nearly
a month, the visit _ the first by a Pope since 1964 _ is already
spawning almost daily controversies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY for Thurs., Feb. 24 _ first graf) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Phil Reeves, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Wed., Feb. 23) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (475 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-POPE-FLAK-HOLYLAND-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BITTER MCCAIN-BUSH BATTLE REOPENS GOP'S OLD WOUNDS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The presidential primary race between George W.
Bush and John McCain has reopened all of the Republican Party's old
wounds and created a few new ones as the two contenders fight hand
to hand for the party's soul _ and the legacy of Ronald Reagan, the
most successful Republican in modern history. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Marshall, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Wed., Feb. 23) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (650 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-GOP-CIVIL-WAR-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MICROSOFT JUDGE HINTS AT BREAKUP AFTER `SECRET' GATES VISIT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bill Gates, the founder and chairman of Microsoft,
met in secret last month with the judge overseeing settlement talks
with the U.S. government as part of an effort to resolve antitrust
charges against his company out of court, it was revealed
Wednesday. Judge Jackson raised eyebrows by comparing the company
to the Standard Oil monopoly of John Rockefeller of the last
century. In a court action in 1910, Standard Oil was broken up into
30 companies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By David Usborne, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Wed., Feb. 23) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (250 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-MICROSOFT-BREAKUP?-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LA VIDA `LOCO': MEXICAN MENTAL ASYLUMS `ABSOLUTELY SHOCKING' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Pedro, whose arms are so atrophied that he cannot
raise them to swat away the flies clustering on his face, lies limp
on a soiled bed. As usual, Juanita is lashed by her ankle to the
window frame until it is time to be untied, stripped, dragged
across a tile floor, then hosed down with cold water.
</P>
<P>
   These are not their real names, but the daily degradations of
life in a Mexican asylum are all too real for 7,000 long-stay
mental patients across the country. A newly released report rated
conditions ``among the worst we have seen anyplace in the world.
Absolutely shocking...subhuman.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Jan McGirk, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Wed., Feb. 23) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (850 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-ASYLUMS-MEXICO-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; YOU'RE NOT ALONE _ STRESSED MANAGERS HATE E-MAIL OVERLOAD,
TOO &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ E-mails have piled additional stress on Britain's
managers, who say that having to cope with their overloaded
``in-boxes'' is damaging their work performance and home lives. In
a study published Thursday, keeping up with e-mails has entered the
top 10 stresses of modern working life for the first time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Cherry Norton, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Wed., Feb. 23) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (325 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-EMAIL-STRESS-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 68 DEER SUFFOCATE ON QANTAS PLANE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ Qantas, the Australian airline which prides itself on
its squeaky-clean image, is under investigation after 68 deer were
found suffocated in cramped cages aboard ones of its planes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Kathy Marks, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Wed., Feb. 23) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (275 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-QANTAS-DEAD-DEER-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SADLY, WE FIND IT TOO EASY TO FORGET ABOUT AFRICA &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Security Council has completed a ``month of Africa.''
Others, offering hostages to fortune, speak of ``the year of
Africa,'' even of an ``African century.'' So far, however, the
first weeks of the new millennium have proved an almost unrelieved
disaster for that benighted continent.
</P>
<P>
   Of the world's 50 poorest countries, 31 are in Africa. Any
number of ``Africa years'' is unlikely to alter that dismal fact. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Editorial) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By The Editorial Board of The Independent, London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Wed., Feb. 23) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (450 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-ALAS-AFRICA-EDITORIAL-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INDIA'S HIGH-TECH BOOM IS GREAT SUCCESS STORY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ The Indian high-tech boom is one of the great
under-publicized stories of the world economy. Last year, Indian
software exports were nearly $3 billion _ ten times the level of
four years earlier. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Hamish McRae, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Wed., Feb. 23) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (475 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-INDIA-HITECH-BOOM-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ISRAELI POLITICAL FOES WAGE INTERNET WAR &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Sticks, stones _ and, for that matter, bullets and
bombs _ can break your bones. Could this be why two sworn political
enemies in Israel shifted their battle to cyberspace? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Phil Reeves, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Wed., Feb. 23) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (300 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-CYBERWAR-ISRAEL-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
