<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 09:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6984 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-RELIGION-ELECTION-NYT     02-24 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-ELECTION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RELIGIOUS RIGHT MAY BE A GENUINE VOTING BLOC AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Last autumn the evangelical magazine ``Christianity Today''
posed the cover-story question: ``Is the Religious Right
Finished?''
 &HT;    In the wake of the South Carolina Republican primary, the answer
should be: ``Not quite yet.''
 &HT;    In South Carolina, Christian conservatives backed Gov. George W.Bush by 3 to 1. Factoring them out of the vote, Bush would have
lost. Without the religious right, South Carolina would have gone
for Sen. John McCain.
 &HT;    Following the primary, Rep. Lindsey Graham (R-S.C.) contended
that McCain had been politically victimized by 19 days of hate
mail, intimating that such attacks had been orchestrated by
operatives at least loosely associated with religious right gurus
Ralph Reed and Pat Robertson.
 &HT;    As a result of the vicious campaign, former candidate Gary Bauer
backed McCain and Graham characterized the attacks as ``lies.''
 &HT;    Bush courted Christian conservatives by visiting _ and not
criticizing _ the racist and fundamentalist Bob Jones University
and moving far to the right on social issues. In a CNN debate, Bush
pointedly mentioned the support of the Log Cabin Republicans, the
gay Republican interest group, for McCain.
 &HT;    To those with theological ears to hear, Bush's remark was
code-language to Christian conservatives meaning: ``Vote for me
unless you want a bunch of immoral sodomites running the country.''
 &HT;    They heard. Nearly 100,000 of them stampeded to the polls and
voted against McCain.
 &HT;    This strategy seems to have caught the mainstream media
off-guard. Until South Carolina, religion had not seemed an issue
in the presidential race. Early on, all the candidates professed
Christian faith. All shaped their views to fit a conservative
Christian agenda. A couple_ notably Alan Keyes and Bauer _ had long
associations with the religious right.
 &HT;    With so much piety, the religious right vote was thought to be
evenly divided between candidates and unlikely to sway the race.
 &HT;    Not, of course, with Ralph Reed as master religion strategist.
 &HT;    Although it pains me to say it, Reed is a genius. The former
director of the Christian Coalition is an adviser to Bush. In the
September 1999 issue of ``Christianity Today,'' Reed claimed that
Christian conservatives ``are the largest single voting bloc in the
electorate _ 24 percent of all those who walked into a voting booth
in 1998. That is larger than the union vote, the feminist vote, the
gay vote, or any other single constituency organized around an
issues agenda.''
 &HT;    There has been, however, a problem with this voting bloc. With
the exception of the 1994 mid-term elections, they have not voted
as a bloc since the end of the Reagan presidency.
 &HT;    Since 1988, Republicans have tried to mobilize religious right
voters around a number of different candidates and issues. With few
attractive national candidates, political strategists attempted to
organize Christian conservatives around abortion. Hard-core
religious right types have insisted on a pro-life position, but
among more moderate Christian voters abortion proved a dead-end.
 &HT;    Despite dazzling media success in the last decade, the religious
right has been a rudderless ship_ more a potential voting bloc than
a solid one.
 &HT;    Enter Ralph Reed. Reed understands that the religious right will
never have real power until it is unified around a single candidate
and can propel that candidate _ in service to their agenda _ to the
White House. The nicely pious George W. Bush just does not match
Ronald Reagan's charismatic charm.
 &HT;    But there is an issue to mobilize the troops: the threat of gay
rights.
 &HT;    If Reed and Robertson can make Bush into the anti-homosexual
candidate, they could successfully capitalize on homophobic anxiety
in Christian circles. With most of the nation's major Protestant
denominations meeting this summer to deal with divisive problems
related to homosexuality, the issue will be at a fever pitch
leading into the fall elections. Religious right activists should
be able to enlist more moderate Christian voters around this cause.
With homosexuality the issue _ an issue that seems more ``clear
cut'' to most religious voters than abortion _ the religious right
may be a genuine voting bloc this year.
 &HT;    Gay rights may have been a throwaway debate line in South
Carolina. If it successfully mobilizes the nation's ``largest
voting bloc'' in upcoming primaries, it will become a centerpiece
issue by November.
 &HT;    No, the religious right is not finished. At least it is not
finished as a powerful political interest lobby. But _ if there was
ever any doubt _ it is finished as a ``religious'' entity. After
all, faithful Christians follow the Ten Commandments: ``You shall
not bear false witness against your neighbor.''
 &HT;    Yes, those are the same commandments the religious right is
lobbying for lawmakers to hang on schoolroom walls. Perhaps Reed
and Robertson should read them first.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.2000 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass writes a religion column for the Santa
Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious studies
at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is ``Standing
Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th Century
America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
