<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 10:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6992 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV27-C     02-24 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: THE RESURRECTION OF POLITICAL PUNDITRY
 &HT;    Moving in (k) commentary and (p) political categories for
release Sunday, Feb. 27.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Most folks who have followed the 2000 presidential
race must be getting pretty tired by now of seeing the contenders
roar back to life after being declared political dead ducks.
</P>
<P>
   But you can be rest assured that this born-again stuff on the
road to the White House is not really happening.
</P>
<P>
   It arises simply as a vision in the eyes of pundits who can see
no farther than the next round of primaries. And it is fueled by
news producers and editors in the mistaken belief that viewers,
listeners and readers would ditch them if they failed to come up
with fresh angles.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, you can be further assured that these fake
political funerals and resurrections will be buried for good well
before Easter Sunday, which in this election year will, for
certain, occur on April 23.
</P>
<P>
   Every four years, a unitary Republican and Democratic Party
springs to life, if only for a week or so, for the purpose of
nominating their presidential and vice presidential candidates.
Since the current system insures that most of the convention
delegates will be chosen by April 23, the phony guessing game will
be over by then.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, that will merely serve as a signal for the pundit
class to start up the next guessing game: Who will win in November?
Even before the inauguration, you can bet that speculation will
arise on whether the president-elect will be dumped in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Someday, perhaps, a sophisticated computer program, brimming
with artificial intelligence, will sift through the data and tell
us conclusively what these intermittent zigs and zags mean. Until
then, here's a stab at it:
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who will win in November?
</P>
<P>
   A: Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did you arrive at that answer?
</P>
<P>
   A: In a contest that weighs personality more heavily than
issues, a nice guy beats a stiff klutz even if Mr. Nice comes
across as a bit of a lightweight and even if the klutz has most of
the issues nailed down cold.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who's the klutz, Al Gore or Bill Bradley?
</P>
<P>
   A: Gore. Bradley isn't going anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why's that?
</P>
<P>
   A: Bradley's in a vicious cycle: His poor polls beget nasty
coverage or outright neglect, which begets anemic fund-raising,
which begets fewer TV ads, which begets even worse polls. In the
end, a campaign just goes down the drain.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So that's why you need a virtuous circle to win, right?
</P>
<P>
   A: You got it. Sen. John McCain is in one now, but it won't last
long.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why's that?
</P>
<P>
   A: Because when we tote up the Bush delegate count in late
March, after the Republican voters in California, Texas, New York,
Ohio and Florida have had their say, McCain will be toast.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What will those numbers reveal?
</P>
<P>
   A: They'll show that Bush has a majority of delegates he needs
to get nominated for the presidency by the Republican National
Convention in Philadelphia on Aug. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there any way you could be wrong about this?
</P>
<P>
   A: Real pundits are always right, even when their clips fail
them.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
