<DOCNO> NYT20000224.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 10:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7003 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN27-COX     02-24 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: A world of trouble for candidate Gore
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   While most of the nation's political attention has been fixed on
the clang and clatter of the Republican knights jousting for their
party's presidential nomination, Vice President Al Gore has been
quietly working himself into a bit of a jam.
</P>
<P>
   Not over the Democratic nomination. That is now pretty much a
sure thing for Gore, barring fey Bill Bradley being taken over by
go-getter aliens.
</P>
<P>
   The sinkhole that is widening in Gore's path to the White House
is the issue of international trade, particularly the pending
proposal to admit China to the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration bargained hard with China last year
to secure conditions that make Chinese membership markedly
favorable for American commercial interests, especially agriculture
and manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   But as a consistent free-trader, Clinton is more at odds with
congressional Democrats, financially beholden to the AFL-CIO, a foe
of world trade, than with congressional Republicans. The bind is
particularly tight for Gore, who needs union money to field a
credible general-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gore emerged from private meetings with AFL-CIO leaders recently
to say he seconds Clinton's policy, but others at the sessions got
the impression he would back moves to attach conditions that labor
wants _ titularly for overseas environmental and work-force
protections but actually meant to queer the deal and exempt U.S.
workers from international competition.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting confusion has left Gore looking rattled and
indistinct and, at least for the moment, has stranded congressional
Democrats who are unwilling to buck the AFL-CIO unless Gore
provides them with political cover.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the House Republican leadership, for once actually
playing politics instead of finding novel ways to commit political
suicide, has adopted an agenda that backs Chinese WTO membership,
calls for opening U.S. markets to Africa and the Caribbean and
supports American leadership in international trade organizations.
</P>
<P>
   In that, the Republicans are harkening as much to their
big-business sugar daddies as the Democrats are to their labor big
spenders, but the GOP is right on the merits of the issue. The
United States overwhelming benefits more than it suffers from
expanding trade.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP leadership has warned, however, that the legislation
needed to animate free-trade policies won't pass without a strong
Democratic muster. Translation: Republicans will hold back enough
GOP votes so that Democrats very visibly will have to anger the
AFL-CIO or will have to kowtow publicly to its protectionism,
either a political liability to the party.
</P>
<P>
   All the noise in the Republican primaries is a boon of sorts to
Gore, letting him flounder around little noticed as he tries to
figure out how to have the issue both ways. But push will come to
shove in Congress within weeks.
</P>
<P>
   We'll get a hint then about whether Gore the candidate is
credibly evolving toward Gore the president.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
