<DOCNO> NYT20000224.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 10:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7007 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN27-CO     02-24 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: A rotten Strawberry
 &HT;    (For release Sunday, Feb. 27, 2000. Moving in Sports and
Commentary categories.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I don't know what possessed me to keep a file on baseball player
Darryl Strawberry; I rarely write about sports figures. Call it
intuition. The troubled (and troubling) athlete is back in the news
_ not for what he did on the field but what happened off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Strawberry failed still another drug test. It's his
fifth failure, now challenging the major-league record of pitcher
Steve Howe, another chronic druggie who was given seven chances by
major-league baseball to redeem himself. Those are six chances more
than alleged gambler Pete Rose was given.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Strawberry is a fortunate man. He beat cancer, didn't
he? He also survived a bunch of drug test failures, and arrests
ranging from soliciting a prostitute, to failure to pay child
support, to assault on his ex-wife. He lost a paternity suit, as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry even tried to get away with cheating the U.S.
government of a half-million dollars in unreported earnings. While
the IRS caught up with him, and he paid a $300,000 fine, Strawberry
got off easy. Instead of the usual prison term, Strawberry was
placed on six months' home confinement. But, the judge added, it's
OK to go play baseball at home and away while serving his
home-confinement term.
</P>
<P>
   Is this man lucky or what?
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe he's not so lucky. He's a sick man and I'm not just
referring to the colon cancer he overcame. Substance abuse is a
sickness. Only the strongest of minds can overcome it. And
Strawberry isn't one of those. He has had enough chances, and
failed, to be judged an incorrigible.
</P>
<P>
   A player of his immense talent _ and unfulfilled promise _ has
been given every opportunity. He not only has flubbed them but he
also can be considered a threat to the integrity of the sport.
That's the terminology Major League Baseball uses to justify
keeping the great Pete Rose from its liturgy. His return, baseball
claims, would harm the integrity of the game.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not certain what is left of baseball's ``integrity.'' Is
John Rocker a part of that integrity? Darryl Strawberry? The dozens
of substance-abuse cases among its players? The player strikes? The
dollar-based constant shuttling between teams? The mass firing of
the umpires?
</P>
<P>
   Are Cal Ripken Jr. and Darryl Strawberry really in the same
profession?
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry is a brutal abuser of whatever positive image there
remains of baseball. If I was making millions of dollars a year for
playing a game, I'd be delighted to pay my taxes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, after another bout with cocaine _ and a 60-day
suspension _ Strawberry visited a children's hospital in Tampa and
said one of his priorities was to work with kids and to warn them
about the traps of drugs and alcohol. ``This is something more
special than hitting a baseball or hitting a home run,'' he said,
obviously lying to himself _ and to the kids.
</P>
<P>
   Just a year ago, Strawberry became a spokesman for the National
Council on Alcoholic and Drug Dependence. He said he was optimistic
about his future. He was right, if only for a short _ but glorious
_ period, when the New York Yankees brought him back onto the
major-league scene after a 120-day suspension. He batted .327 in
what remained of last year's regular season, then went on to play
in the 1999 World Series, batting .333 there.
</P>
<P>
   Life was sweet again. The cancer was gone, the fans loved him,
his talent was obvious, he was playing for likely the greatest
baseball team of all time. Why then a test of positive for cocaine
just prior to the start of spring training?
</P>
<P>
   You'll have to ask Strawberry. He is his own worst enemy. He is
his own sickness.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
