<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7032 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-MINORITY-BUSH25-COX     02-24 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINORITY-BUSH25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush works to mend ties with minority voters
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Eight months after launching a campaign he hoped
would attract minority voters to the Republican Party in droves,
George W. Bush on Tuesday felt compelled to make it clear that he
is opposed to bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me make it crystal clear to folks here and across America:
``I reject bigotry. I reject prejudice. I repudiate
anti-Catholicism. I reject the politics of those who try to pit one
group of Americans against another,'' Bush said as his defeat in
Tuesday's Michigan primary became apparent.
</P>
<P>
   The self-styled ``compassionate conservative'' surely hoped that
by now his dedication to diversity _ an integral part of his Texas
image and one of the qualities that made him such an attractive
presidential candidate to the Republican establishment _ would be
unquestioned. Unfortunately for him, it isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's appearance two weeks ago at Bob Jones University, a
fundamentalist school that bans interracial dating and is
anti-Catholic, may have alienated a substantial number of minority
voters and moderates. Speaking at the school could have contributed
to Bush's Michigan defeat, observers there said, and the Bob Jones
issue likely will persist as a problem for him in upcoming
primaries and in the general election, if he wins the GOP
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The actions he took in South Carolina just remind
African-Americans that the Republican Party has been on this course
since Reagan's days,'' said Hanes Walton, a political scientist at
the University of Michigan who studies race in politics. ``You
can't make inroads when your rhetoric appears to be simply
rhetoric, period.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor often talks about bringing minorities, who
traditionally vote Democratic, into the GOP fold. Republican Party
leaders were impressed that Bush got 49 percent of the Hispanic
vote and 27 percent of the African-American vote in his 1998
re-election bid. In contrast, only 21 percent of Texas Hispanics
and 12 percent of blacks voted for GOP candidate Bob Dole in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   They were thrilled when he spoke Spanish on the stump and touted
the rising test scores of minority students in Texas during his
tenure. In contrast to recent GOP presidential candidates, Bush
frequently campaigns in minority areas, and surrounds himself with
African-Americans and Hispanics during media-friendly events. Such
gestures are designed to send a message of inclusiveness not only
to minorities, but to swing voters who have been repelled by what
they see as the intolerance of the Republican right.
</P>
<P>
   But after his lopsided defeat to Republican rival John McCain in
the New Hampshire primary, Bush came into South Carolina desperate
for a victory. Speaking at Bob Jones a day after that stunning
rebuke, Bush played up his pro-life credentials and made it clear
that reaching out to the religious right would be a critical part
of his South Carolina strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy worked. The national media and the Democrats
slammed Bush for appearing at Bob Jones, but he won South
Carolina's GOP primary in large part because he got two-thirds of
the religious conservative vote. Without it, he would have lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``When asked about interracial dating, I didn't hesitate to say,
'Of course I don't accept their policy.' But I didn't go to accept
their policy. I wanted them to accept my policy. That's why I went
to give the speech,'' Bush said earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also notes that the school has been a frequent stop for
politicians, including Ronald Reagan and South Carolina's
Democratic governor.
</P>
<P>
   But what is smart politics in a South Carolina GOP contest
doesn't necessarily play well in the rest of the country. In
Michigan, which has a large Catholic population, McCain made sure
to remind voters of Bush's Bob Jones appearance. McCain wasn't
invited to speak at the school, but he said if had been he would
have used the opportunity to criticize its policies.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't clear how many voters in the Michigan primary, more
than half of whom were independents and Democrats, were influenced
by the Bob Jones issue. More than 1.3 million people voted in
Michigan, up from 524,161 in 1996. Bill Ballenger, who publishes a
respected newsletter on Michigan politics, said he doubts it was a
major factor.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Bush's African-American and Hispanic supporters said
this week that while they were troubled by Bush's speech at Bob
Jones, they don't doubt the governor's dedication to racial and
religious tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably would have advised him not to go there, being
Catholic myself. However, I don't see that as an anti-Catholic
stand by a long shot,'' said Miguel Berrios, a probation and parole
manager for the Michigan Department of Corrections who organized
Bush's Hispanic supporters in the western part of that state.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were an endorsement, I would be livid. But it's not an
endorsement of that philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   But state Rep. LaMar Lemmons of Detroit, who urged Democrats to
vote for McCain to punish Bush ally Gov. John Engler for
eliminating Detroit's elected school board and its separate
criminal courts, said the Bob Jones issue boosted his efforts.
Lemmons said he got many phone calls from Catholics outside Detroit
who wanted to help his cause because of Bush's Bob Jones
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started off as being an African-American-based group, but
as Bush did things in South Carolina we expanded throughout the
state,'' Lemmons said. ``It had a mobilizing effect.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Bush campaign clearly was worried about being associated
with the anti-Catholic views of Bob Jones' leaders. On the day of
the primary, it sent out nine news releases with statements from
nine Republican governors, all of whom denounced the McCain
campaign for making phone calls to voters emphasizing the school's
anti-Catholic stance and noting that Bush had remained silent on
the issue while speaking there.
</P>
<P>
   The issue also may resonate in upcoming primaries in diverse,
moderate states such as New York and California. U.S. Rep. Peter
King (R-New York), who had endorsed Bush, switched to McCain as a
result of the Bob Jones speech. King is Catholic and represents a
heavily Catholic district.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, meanwhile, are salivating at the prospect of
bringing up Bob Jones in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is horrified by this kind of hatred. Why isn't George
Bush? A real leader challenges hatred and ignorance head on,
instead of tacitly endorsing it,'' Democratic National Committee
spokeswoman Jenny Backus said after Bush was grilled on the issue
on NBC's ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   Many conservatives worry that Bush has handed the Democrats a
potent weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Arch-conservative talk radio host G. Gordon Liddy called Bush's
visit ``a very dumb move'' because many of the Reagan Democrats
that Bush hopes to attract are Catholic. And New York City Mayor
Rudy Giuliani, a Bush ally, said Bush should have boycotted the
university, or at least spoken out against its policies when he was
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he made a mistake by doing it,'' Giuliani said. ``If
you're going to go there and they have this history, then if you
make that decision to do it then probably you should take on the
issue in some respect.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
