<HEADER>
A7033 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-BORDERS-COLUMN25-COX     02-24 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Handshaking, baby-kissing season is in full swing
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ The political season has arrived in full
force, happily filling the newspaper with political ads (hey, I'm a
capitalist). Political signs have sprouted like fire ant mounds
after a rain, and candidates are making the rounds of pie suppers
and political forums. Suddenly politicians are showing up
everywhere more than two people are gathered, from ribbon cuttings
to Rotary Club meetings.
</P>
<P>
   This is as it should be. You get elected by talking to as many
people as you can and persuading them to vote for you. And in a
small town, it's easy enough to talk to someone running for office
and get some sense of whether this is someone who can do the job.
</P>
<P>
   For us in the newspaper business, election season is both
exhilarating and exhausting. It's akin to Christmas. There's a lot
of pre-holiday hoopla, but by the time the big day gets here,
you're ready for it to be over so you can take down the decorations
and get on with day-to-day life.
</P>
<P>
   We make endorsements at this newspaper, which means we have an
obligation to interview all the candidates in the contested races.
We conduct the interviews one-on-one sometimes, and other times we
ask all the candidates in a particular race to come in at the same
time for a mini-forum. Again, it's often fascinating but often
exhausting to talk to that many candidates and try to keep straight
who's running for what and why.
</P>
<P>
   Why do we make endorsements? It's simple. I believe a newspaper
has an obligation to take stands on local issues that affect our
readers. We do that all the time. What local issue has more effect
on our readers than who we elect to office? These are the folks,
after all, who make many of the major decisions that affect our
lives: how much we pay in taxes, what type of law enforcement we
have, how our schools are run and how justice is dispensed.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean we have any lock on wisdom. Far from it. I've
been involved in endorsing candidates in local races for 18 years
now, and there's a long list of folks who got the newspapers'
endorsement and ultimately turned out to be a poor fit for the job.
All we can do, and usually there are three to five people involved
in the decision-making process, is listen to the candidates, look
at the record, and decide who we think would be best at the job.
</P>
<P>
   Does getting the newspaper's endorsement help someone get
elected? I don't have a clue and don't care. We're not handicapping
a horse race. There have been several times where we've endorsed
someone who had no chance of winning and, sure enough, lost
handily. If I had a dollar for everyone who has told me they decide
who to vote for by picking the folks we don't endorse, I could
probably pay a semester's college tuition for one of my rug rats.
That's fine. We're not telling anyone how to vote, and despite what
the conspiracy theorists think, we don't have a political agenda.
All I care about is electing someone who's honest, competent and
willing to work with others. On the local level, I could give a fig
if that person is a Republican or Democrat. It simply doesn't
matter.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of conspiracy theorists, I have to laugh when folks
think that because we devoted 2 inches more space to one candidate
than another, or someone's picture ran three columns wide, while
another was only two columns wide, that it's all part of grand plan
to elect someone we're backing. My stock answer: We're lucky to get
a newspaper out every day. We don't have the time or the
intelligence to run a conspiracy. What we do try to do is give
everyone an even shake, treat political events the same, and give
readers enough information to make an informed decision. All that
occurs separate and apart from how we decide who to endorse on the
editorial page.
</P>
<P>
   I do have one pet peeve that in interviews automatically serves
as a strike against someone running for office. Countless times,
I've heard a candidate for a position say that he hasn't looked at
the budget yet, but plans to study it just as soon as he gets in
office. To me, this is the equivalent of someone wanting to be an
airline pilot and saying he's planning on reading the flight manual
right after takeoff. Virtually everything done in government is
public record, from budgets to meeting minutes, correspondence and
everything else. Someone running for county commission, for
example, who hasn't even bothered to start attending commission
meetings is either supremely confident or arrogant. If you are
running for office, do your homework.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I feel better getting that off my chest. All complaining
aside, I still admire anyone who's willing to stick his or her neck
out and run for office. Thank goodness being an editor isn't an
elected position. Some days I'm not sure I could make the runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
