<HEADER>
A7034 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GARCIA-COLUMN25-COX     02-24 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas Independence Day celebrates state's mosaic
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ From the outset, Jay Johnson's vision for a
March 2 celebration was more than just honoring a day. His idea was
to honor what Texas has become in the 164 years since it broke from
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   You may recall that Johnson, who owns an Austin construction
firm, took note last year that March 2, Texas Independence Day,
would often come and go with little notice. Enlisting the aid of a
small circle of friends that included Sen. Gonzalo Barrientos
(D-Austin), Johnson put together an organization called Celebrate
Texas. That group helped plan a parade down Congress Avenue and a
noon shindig on the Capitol grounds.
</P>
<P>
   It was a white-knuckle flight because the idea had to take form
in a short period of time. February 1999 was a test of Johnson's
considerable energy.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the planning, however, Johnson stressed that the
holiday belonged to all Texans and worked hard to ensure that the
celebration was a true mosaic of the Lone Star State's many
different cultures.
</P>
<P>
   While that sounds good, pulling together a Texas celebration was
somewhat ticklish, given the darker side of the state's history.
Johnson, a native Austinite, was driven to the point of obsession
to reach out, to ensure that the celebration was one that reflected
the state today.
</P>
<P>
   African-Americans are painfully aware of the state's
segregationist past and its impact on their lives today. To be
frank, there has always been some ambivalence in the Hispanic
community about March 2. Horror stories about past and present
discriminatory treatment of Texans of Mexican ancestry are
plentiful and vivid. There are some of us who know history well
enough to look askance at some of the characters of the 1836
revolution but also recognize that the government of Mexico at the
time was no treat either. Mexico then was run by a megalomaniacal
militarist who shredded the constitution of 1824 and who was not
highly regarded by Mexicans then or now.
</P>
<P>
   But the topper is this: It is our state, too. Tejanos are an
integral part of the state's past and future. Our muscle _
yesterday and today _ built the state, and our intellects help
shape its future.
</P>
<P>
   That's why this year as last, the parade and celebration at the
Capitol will once again be a picture of the state today. Johnson
picked ``Together we're Texas'' as both slogan and theme for the
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's celebration reflected the slogan and the only
difference this year is one of scale. The event has grown. Music
for the Capitol celebration ranges from conjunto to gospel to jazz
to western swing.
</P>
<P>
   This year's parade has drawn 67 units so far and counting. It
will be one of the biggest parades in the city's history. Military
bands, high school bands, floats, riders on horseback including
Buffalo soldiers, charros and cowpokes of all shades have signed
on. Those on the ground will be joined by an airborne contingent of
50 aircraft _ everything from vintage airplanes operated by the
Confederate Air Force to helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was a tired but happy camper last week as he surveyed
the interest and the enthusiasm of celebration participants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a monster parade,'' Johnson said ``and the
ones in the parade are so excited (to be participating) that
they'll be dancing up Congress Avenue.''
</P>
<P>
   The event aims to communicate ``present day values, about what's
good about being Texan.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, Johnson mused, there will be a day of permanent
reconciliation for Texans, but for now, he said, he'll settle for
March 2 ``as a day we can all be proud of, because together, we're
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Garcia, a member of the board of Celebrate Texas, is the
editorial page editor of the Austin American-Statesman. You may
contact him at agarcia(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
