<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No shortage of holy figures to dictate truth to us, if allowed
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Though a bad week for holy men in the Middle East,
it was a promising one in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Reformers took over Iran's parliament, intent on new liberties
and less unquestioned authority for people in beards.
</P>
<P>
   Should the effort succeed, it would further deplete the ranks of
the world's pure church-states, which include Afghanistan, Saudi
Arabia, the Vatican Republic and Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   With Oklahoma in the wings.
</P>
<P>
   Attempting to rush to the intellectually barren plain recently
claimed by the Kansas state school board, Oklahoma's state textbook
committee voted to reject five biology books.
</P>
<P>
   As with the Kansas board, which dropped evolution from its state
curriculum guidelines, the Oklahoma committee purged the textbooks
for promoting evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing some of the comments of the committee, it is
instructive to observe that though the influence of an ayatollah is
on the wane in Tehran, it is on the upswing in Oklahoma City in the
person of state school board member Laura Dobson. Granted, though
under the Islamic model a female ayatollah is akin to a Brahma bull
giving milk, Dobson appears hot for the title.
</P>
<P>
   When it was pointed out that assorted items she complained about
in textbooks pertained to national standards on which all students
are quizzed, she said, ``Our national science standards are
invalid. The national science standards are not scientific.''
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear exactly what level of expertise Dobson has to make
such a statement. Maybe she's a Ph.D.'s Ph.D. More likely, she
doesn't believe what she doesn't want to believe, and that will be
that. It's her right. Is it her authority? An ayatollah's job is to
enforce faith as fact, and faith as orthodoxy.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, TV audience: Who wants to be an ayatollah?
</P>
<P>
   By now, those of us who understand the essential nature of the
state staying out of spiritual matters must acknowledge that some
people don't get it, won't get it, and won't give up.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the most learned Steve Forbes, running for president
until just recently. Not long ago in an Iowa classroom, Forbes
defended the notion of posting the Ten Commandments on school
walls, saying it's essentially an advertisement of who we are _ a
Christian nation, run by Christians.
</P>
<P>
   ``In schools, you should have an understanding of from whence we
came, and it starts with the Ten Commandments,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you went to a country that has the Muslim religion ... you
might expect to see the Koran there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Koran is not the basis of this civilization,'' said
Forbes, speaking of the American brand. ``The Ten Commandments
are.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a news flash.
</P>
<P>
   The First Amendment seems to pronounce the establishment of
religion off-limits. This guy running for president assumes the
First Amendment says, ``Congress shall adopt and enforce
Christianity. And those who resist shall burn in Hades.''
</P>
<P>
   In Colorado, a bill to require the posting of the Ten
Commandments in public schools was pulled from the table after
passage by a state Senate committee.
</P>
<P>
   It's an interesting concept, posting commands for students that
include ``honor the Sabbath'' (what, no pro football games?) and
``you shall have no Gods before me.''
</P>
<P>
   The question some students will ask is, ``Who is this `me' guy?
_ The principal? The football coach? The governor? Or some old lady
on the school board?''
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured, in a church-state, with laws which end all
uncertainty, which expel science when it conflicts with certainty,
and with torches and burning stakes to enforce the certainty, we
will be at no loss for holy people to light them.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
