<HEADER>
A7037 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NYFASHION-BACKSTAGE25     02-24 0367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYFASHION-BACKSTAGE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: EMBARGOED for Sunday, Feb. 27
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Backstage `dressers' help models quick-change for runway shows
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By the time I'd finished talking with the backstage
dressers at the recent New York runway shows, I was thinking of
signing up myself. It looked like fun.
</P>
<P>
   These are folks who have normal day jobs but take time off for
Fashion Week because they love fashion and get a kick out of
working the shows. One dresser said she worked in the hair
department for the Broadway production of ``The Lion King.''
Another was a caterer.
</P>
<P>
   I was mistaken for a dresser one afternoon when I showed up at
the backstage check-in entrance wearing a black sweater and slacks
_ the dresser uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before a show begins, dressers are standing by racks of
clothing, making certain everything is in place. Each is assigned
to a specific model and must be familiar with the outfits and
accessories that model will wear. Often there's a Polaroid shot of
models in each outfit to consult. They get paid more, apparently,
if they also steam-press the clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Dressers often wear aprons filled with items they might need:
lint brush, shoe horn, safety pins, towelettes for removing marks
from a garment, sandpaper to scrape new-shoe soles so the models
don't slip.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Ashley, a nutrition consultant in New York, told me
working the shows is an exciting change of pace. ``I pick up
clients this way, too,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Out front, the models _ calm and collected _ saunter down the
runway. But the instant they're out of the audience's sight, they
fly to their dresser and scurry to get ready for their next
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, everything runs smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once for a Chanel show, one of my models lost her shoe on the
runway and was really upset about it,'' Ashley said. ``I told her
that she hadn't fallen and that she should just go back out there
as if nothing had happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoes, she added, are always either too big or too small. ``We
pack them with tissue if they're big,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-00 1059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000224.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7038 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NYFASHION-PRODUCER25-     02-24 1839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYFASHION-PRODUCER25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio woman takes on New York fashion world's bright lights, big
runways
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ She shuffles the cards as proficiently as a Las Vegas
dealer, and the stakes can be just as high.
</P>
<P>
   But you won't see spades or clubs on the stiff white cards
Deborah Hughes holds as she races up and down the aisles of the
Bryant Park tent, stopping only long enough to place or switch
cards on chair seats as she goes.
</P>
<P>
   The deck she holds is a ``who's who'' of the fashion world, and
Hughes' expertise lies in knowing who goes where: editors from
Vogue and Harper's Bazaar, writers from The New York Times and The
Washington Post, executives from Bergdorf-Goodman and Saks Fifth
Avenue, celebrities who come to support their favorite designers. A
faux pas can be disastrous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like seating people for a dinner party,'' she explains.
``It's very time-consuming.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, 42, a former model and public-relations director for
designer Carolina Herrera, is a pro.
</P>
<P>
   The job is called ``front of house,'' and it's just one of the
demanding assignments the Dayton, Ohio, native regularly performs
as head of her own New York public relations firm. At the recent
``7th on Sixth'' Fashion Week of runway shows and parties, keeping
up with Hughes is like trying to catch a bird in flight. She and
her staff have major responsibilities for six events over one week,
including a New York City Opera Thrift Shop benefit, two magazine
launches and three runway shows.
</P>
<P>
   Most all-encompassing is the Douglas Hannant fashion show, for
which Hughes is producer. She oversees it all: models, hair and
makeup teams, control-room technicians, interviews, invitations and
seating.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before show time she's already on the run: racing between
last-minute conferences with lighting and sound specialists,
supervising the frenzy of photographers and television camera crews
flooding the small backstage area, where rows of models are being
made up and coiffed.
</P>
<P>
   Designer Hannant, calm under the circumstances, says he and
Hughes have been friends for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deborah is a three-dimensional person; she knows everything
about fashion, but there's nothing `surface' about her,'' says
Hannant. ``In fashion, there's not a lot of real people.''
</P>
<P>
   THE CONTROLLED CHAOS OF A
</P>
<P>
   RUNWAY SHOW
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in her uniform of snug black leather pants, jean jacket
and boots, Hughes kisses and hugs everyone who arrives backstage,
shepherding each to interviews with Hannant or with New York's most
renowned make-up artists or hair stylists, who are working on
models.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you want a blackout before the finale?'' asks lighting
designer Gordon Link, who is playing with the red lights on the
runway when Hughes climbs into the control booth. ``What would you
like to see?''
</P>
<P>
   When Apollo 440's ``Stop the Rock'' comes through the sound
system full blast at rehearsal, Hughes throws her arm into the air
and begins to dance. ``I'm getting excited!'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put Cosmo Girl next to Cosmopolitan, was that OK?'' asks a
staffer.
</P>
<P>
   As show time nears, she checks her watch. ``Four models aren't
here yet!'' she says. Because models rush from show to show during
Fashion Week, many arrive in the nick of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``First looks,'' Hughes shouts above the din when all are
accounted for, meaning it's time for models to don their first
outfits. If they dress too early, clothes will wrinkle.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes signals her staff to let photographers take up positions
at the end of the runway. After rearranging and checking a giant
paper seating chart, the audience is let in.
</P>
<P>
   When everyone is seated, Hughes does a ``front row sweep'' to
see who's missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd wait for the editor of Women's Wear Daily, or The New
York Times, or a celebrity,'' she says. ``The magazine people can
always come to the showroom afterwards.''
</P>
<P>
   Lights dim and the show gets under way, with Hughes on a headset
in the control room, directing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go, go, go!'' she shrieks to Anton, her backstage staffer who
is sending each model onto the runway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Energy, energy, tell them to put a hole in the runway! Is
Jackie, ready? Octavia, go!,'' Hughes screams. ``Who's lining those
girls up? They're in the wrong order!''
</P>
<P>
   But out front, the industry's most professional models parade
down the runway in Hannant's elegant fashions, calm and
self-assured.
</P>
<P>
   `SORRY, YOU'RE NOT ON THE LIST'
</P>
<P>
   As the week progresses, Hughes also supervises ``front of
house'' arrangements for designers Marc Bauer and Jill Stuart and
juggles backstage interviews for another of her accounts, the
Internet site ibeauty.com. Among those who show up backstage are
rapper Lil' Kim, fashion commentator Elsa Klensch, singer Toni
Braxton and TV host Star Jones.
</P>
<P>
   One of Hughes' toughest assignments is saying ``no.''
</P>
<P>
   Backstage at the Jill Stuart show, she turns away a photographer
who won't stop hassling her. In the lobby of 30 Rockefeller Plaza
on Tuesday night, hordes attempt to get into the Visionaire
magazine party in the 65th floor Rainbow Room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four hundred are invited and 1,000 will try to come,'' Hughes
says. ``It's the hottest party in New York this week.''
</P>
<P>
   One woman says she's left her invitation in Paris. Another
claims she's related to the Renoir family. Someone else says he's
there to represent a boss who can't make it.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes isn't swayed. ``Sorry, you're not on the list,'' she says
firmly, checking her big black notebook.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs, the party is swinging: There's a drag queen DJ and
four scantily clad, greased-up men dancing on giant boxes,
champagne is flowing and hundreds of fashion folks milling about _
all dressed to the hilt and hoping to attract the attention of
photographers and video crews.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, cigarette in hand, paces among them all, keeping a
watchful eye out for anyone who isn't wearing the denim armband
that guarantees admission to those who belong. This day won't end
for her until after 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the frenetic week, Hughes gets a chance to sit
down for a chat over lunch.
</P>
<P>
   She traces her interest in beauty and fashion back to the age of
3, when she stayed with her aunt, Pearl Fry, while her mother
worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``My aunt had a beauty shop called Pearl's, and I always helped
her after my nap,'' she recalls. ``I'd sweep up the hair.''
</P>
<P>
   At 13, when Hughes was ``skinny and tall and all legs,'' she
signed up at Fashion 70, a local modeling school. She was also on
Rike's department store's Teen Board.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a model-of-the-year contest in New York at the
Waldorf Hotel and I entered it,'' she says. ``You were supposed to
be 16, and I won it the night before my 16th birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   YOU CAN TAKE THE GIRL OUT OF DAYTON...
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a crown and fur coat, Hughes won $1,000 and a
slew of modeling offers. Accompanying her to the Waldorf was
classmate Gwen Scott. The two have remained best friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our lives are totally different, but there isn't anything we
wouldn't do for one another,'' says Scott, a. realtor. She visits
Hughes regularly _ most often during Fashion Week or for Hughes'
birthday in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get to live in her world when I'm there and she gets to live
in my world when she comes to Dayton,'' Scott says.
</P>
<P>
   After winning the modeling contest, Hughes moved to New York,
living with her agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went home to Dayton every Friday and took my laundry,'' she
remembers. ``Everyone was nice in New York, but I was so naive and
trusting. A man on the street would tell me he lost his money and
I'd listen and believe him ... until I saw the same man telling
someone else the same story the next day!''
</P>
<P>
   At 18, Hughes moved to Europe, modeling and living in
Switzerland, Italy, Germany, France and England.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most important part of my life,'' she says. ``I
learned so much and met such interesting people.''
</P>
<P>
   When she decided to stop modeling and move back to the United
States, she applied for a job with Carolina Herrera, a Venezuelan
designer who was launching her own line of fashions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my God, oh my God!'' exclaims Hughes when asked how Herrera
influenced her life. ``I learned so much from her, she is so
wonderful, and she was a huge influence on me and the nicest
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes began as a receptionist (''I made less in a week than I
had in an hour as a model''), then was promoted to director of
advertising and public relations, traveling throughout the world
with Herrera.
</P>
<P>
   Among the celebrities who ordered the designer's elegant
clothing was Jacquelyn Kennedy Onassis.
</P>
<P>
   ``She used to call me `Legs' because my legs are so long,''
Hughes says. ``She was very soft-spoken, always smiling, and we did
a lot of her clothes and Caroline's wedding dress.''
</P>
<P>
   When she felt it was time to move on, Hughes joined an old
friend, Kevin Krier, whose firm produces many New York fashion
events.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, she started her own public-relations firm. Deborah
Hughes Inc. began in Hughes' apartment, has since moved to a
spacious New York loft and now employs five full-time staffers,
more during busy times such as Fashion Week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never seems like a risk when I'm doing it,'' says Hughes,
who says she never sets goals, describes herself as very impatient,
and says she lives ``by the seat of her pants.''
</P>
<P>
   She says she knows instinctively when the time is right to make
a change.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents have always supported my decisions,'' she says.
``I'm very lucky because my family gives me courage, strength and
support. My parents brought me up to believe I shouldn't be
dependent on someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   AWAY FROM THE FRENZY OF FASHION
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, she's dating another Daytonian but prefers not to
give his name. The two met at a party in New York. When the
gentleman said he was from Dayton, Hughes thought he was putting
her on.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, then what high school did you go to?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meadowdale,'' he responded, naming her alma mater.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, so what were the colors?'' she demanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black and gold!'' he said without hesitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, sing the school song!'' said Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   He burst into: ``Meadowdale, oh Meadowdale, our hearts belong to
you...''
</P>
<P>
   They've been going together ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things I like most about myself are things that came from
Dayton,'' she says. ``I'm fair and honest and compassionate towards
people. I try to help people who need help. And I'm always there
for my friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Though she's intimately involved with the fashion and beauty
industries, Hughes is able to step back from it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are very addicted to fashion,'' she says, ``I
don't know exactly why ... but I'm glad they are.''
</P>
<P>
   But Deborah Hughes labels herself ``the worst shopper in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you the last time I bought something,'' she says.
``I'm happy in my jeans and T-shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
