<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7039 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-LOVESUPREME25-C     02-24 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-LOVESUPREME25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Profiles of black couples at odds with media image
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On movie screens, black men often communicate with
violence. On television, black women rarely have anything good to
say about their men. With the occasional exception _ the recent
black ensemble comedy ``Best Man'' at theaters; the Huxtables on TV
_ the happily married black man and woman are seldom reflected in
popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   First-time authors TaRessa and Calvin Stovall hope to change
that with their new book, ``A Love Supreme'' (Warner Books,
$23.95).
</P>
<P>
   Experienced in getting the word out _ Calvin, 46, is a longtime
journalist; TaRessa, 45, was media coordinator for the Children's
Defense Fund in Washington _ they networked and chatted up their
book idea all over the country. From the dozens of responses, they
selected 20 couples for candid snapshots. They are men and women
who love each other in many ways: in long-distance romances,
through prison walls or in spite of the walls they had built up
internally because of bad previous relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like a proud papa,'' remarks Calvin. ``I feel like,
through these stories, we're offering the kind of inspiration and
information and hope people need to combat the overwhelmingly
negative portrayals in the media.''
</P>
<P>
   Which may seem strange coming from the managing editor of the
Courier-Post newspaper in Cherry Hill, N.J., who worked at The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution in the early 1990s. But not in light
of the NAACP's recent battle with national television networks
about poor minority representation this past year. And just this
past month, Essence magazine dedicated a cover story to the lack of
black men in lead movie roles.
</P>
<P>
   Media images aside, declares Atlanta author and playwright Pearl
Cleage, the real lives that black Americans lead are enough to make
efforts such as ``A Love Supreme'' necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relationships between black men and black women are almost
always terrible,'' says Cleage, who with husband Zaron W. Burnett
Jr. is one of three Atlanta couples profiled in the book. ``And I
qualify that by saying that a lot of our relationships are fraught
with lies. And disappointment. And a lot of abuse between people
who say they love each other. And oftentimes we're in such dire
circumstances as these that we forget what a vision of people in
love looks like. ... This (book) adds to the body of work that does
demonstrate the possibility of love.''
</P>
<P>
   And tot, ``A Love Supreme'' is a specific example of
something too few black men know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black men believe the more women you have, the greater lover
you are,'' says Burnett, director of the Just Us Theater Company in
southwest Atlanta. ``Page after page of this book prove that if you
can really make one person truly understand and love you, then you
have achieved great love.''
</P>
<P>
   And that comes across to any reader, notes Johnetta B. Cole,
former president of Spelman College. ``My only concern about this
book is that someone might misunderstand, and assume that this book
lifts above all other love stories the love story of black women
and men,'' says Cole, who is featured in ``A Love Supreme'' with
husband Arthur J. Robinson Jr., whom she's known since childhood.
``I deeply believe that all people have the capacity to truly love.
So I would like to see this book in the hands of every conceivable
combination _ racially, by class, by sexual orientation, by
physical ability and disability and by age. This is quite an
offering.''
</P>
<P>
   And clearly one that has affected its authors.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether writing ``the book'' about black love added
any pressure to their own relationship, TaRessa Stovall replies
playfully, ``We have no excuses now. No backing out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No way,'' Calvin adds.
</P>
<P>
   A love indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
