<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7040 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-MILNER25-COX     02-24 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MILNER25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Book entitled `Name Dropping' not about what you think
 &HT;    By Jay Milner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I mention the fact that John Kenneth Galbraith, the noted
Harvard-based economist and author, brought me a Coke one time
during my stay at Harvard some years back as Journalist in
Residence, it's what you call ``name dropping.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the name of Galbraith's new book, ``Name Dropping''
(Houghton Mifflin). Unlike most of his other books _ they number in
the 20s _ this new one isn't about economics or politics, not
specifically anyway. The subtitle om FDR On'' and it's a
chatty book about the famous people the Harvard economics professor
emeritus has been involved with professionally and personally
through the years. As the jacket blurb states, ``Drawing on a
lifetime of access to many of the greatest public figures,
Galbraith creates a rich and uniquely personal history of the
century _ a century he helped shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides President Franklin D. Roosevelt, before World War II and
during, Galbraith includes chapters on Eleanor Roosevelt, Harry
Truman, Adlai Stevenson, John F. Kennedy, Jacqueline Kennedy and
other members of that remarkable family, India's Jawaharlal Nehru,
L.B.J., and others.
</P>
<P>
   In his opening chapter, ``On Name Dropping,'' Galbraith points
out that ``Books, like those who write them, have an unplanned life
of their own. The very act of writing has a controlling role. When
I started this book, I intended to describe the political
personality _ the personal and public traits that, as I saw them,
allowed the great leaders of our century influence or dominate the
political scene. There are still elements of this intention in the
pages that follow. But it faded as a central purpose. ``Instead, as
the work proceeded, there was more interest for the author, as I
trust there will be for the reader, in how great political figures
appeared to their contemporaries, of whom I was one. What did I
recall of personal encounters or public association with Franklin
Roosevelt, Eleanor, the Kennedys, Nehru and others? ...''
</P>
<P>
   He continues: ``Reminiscence and anecdote, as they tell of one's
meetings wit the great or the prominent, are an established form of
self-enhancement. They make known that one was there. This is not
my purpose; my aim is to inform and, perhaps, on occasion, to
entertain. The risk, nontheless, exists that critics who are less
than tolerant may sugest that I am indulging in name-dropping.
Hence the title of the book and that of this chapter. Nothing so
disarms a prosecutor as a prior confession of guilt.''
</P>
<P>
   The late columnist Murray Kempton once told me that he and
others regarded Adlai Stevenson as ``the government in exile.''
Galbraith seems to be one of those. He points out Stevenson's
weakness as a candidate as ``his most frequent and to many his most
endering political statement, often repeated, as 'I want to talk
sense to the American people.' Holding them to be intelligent, he
held that they were to be informed, not persuaded, and certainly
not by mindless rhetoric. Being intelligent and knowledgeable about
the issues, they would listen carefully, come to the right
conclusions and vote for him. Again, the reaction was different as
between Stevenson's immediate following and the public at large.
... All this shaped the form and content of the Stevenson
campaigns. With them I was closely inolved more so than in the case
of any other candidate, John F. Kennedy not excepted. The error of
our course I came only gradually (and reluctantly) to see.''
</P>
<P>
   And Galbraith expalins this error: ``After the 1952 campaign
Stevenson's speeches, much admired, were published in book form. He
sent me a copy. I was well represented therein, and I put it on a
shelf with my other writing. Looking at my contribution in later
years, I sensed the fatal flaw: I had written seeking the approval
of the candidate, his campaign acolytes and myself, not that of the
larger public, the electorate as a whole. So had the other
writers.''
</P>
<P>
   It's no longer a mystery why Stevenson lost twice. But it would
be refreshing if some of that fatal flaw rubbed off on today's
candidates, of both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Milner writes for Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
