<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7041 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-SCANDALMONGER25     02-24 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SCANDALMONGER25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sex, lies and a quill pen
 &HT;    By Tom Blackburn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Sex scandals involving politicians are
as old as the Republic. In the first big one, in 1797, Treasury
Secretary Alexander Hamilton confessed to adultery to squelch
rumors that he stole public money. The second, in 1803, was the
charge that President Thomas Jefferson had children with one of his
slaves.
</P>
<P>
   The reputations of Jefferson and Hamilton survived. The
journalist who blew open both scandals was a Scotsman, James
Thomson Callender. His reputation didn't make it. History writes
him off as an acerbic scandalmonger who died drunk.
</P>
<P>
   History may write him off, but William Safire, the New York
Times columnist who delights in being contrarian, writes him back
into events in this novel with footnotes. Seeing as one columnist
is writing about another, Safire is sympathetic.
</P>
<P>
   The result may not be great fiction, but it's great fun. It
shows the Founding Fathers with their pants down: Jefferson schemes
like a Tammany boss with James Madison and James Monroe. Aaron
Burr, who really was a Tammany boss, looks out for himself.
Hamilton plots legal strategy for a libel case he is defending, and
the clerk of the House, John Beckley, is the original Deep Throat.
</P>
<P>
   The story encompasses the origins of the political party system
in America and the laying down of modern libel law. President John
Adams had signed the Alien and Sedition Laws, the former to deport
Callender and the latter to imprison him if the alien law didn't
work.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson objected to them both, until he became the target.
Then he unleashed state libel laws against the critics. In those
days, truth was no defense in a libel case.
</P>
<P>
   But worms turn. ``Even miserable miscreants like Callender,
(Hamilton) was forced to admit, served a public purpose in checking
a too-popular government's power.'' Safire himself couldn't have
admitted it better.
</P>
<P>
   Safire is smitten with one of Hamilton's favorite words:
contumelious. At one point, Hamilton uses it and a friend advises
him to pick a substitute more familiar to people. He picks
slanderous. It means something like ``deliberately humiliating.''
As a word maven, Safire wants it to make a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   How much of history according to Safire is true? Not all, but
more than you might at first think.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the dialogue is straight from the speakers' letters,
duly footnoted. In one of the best scenes, Burr intervenes to
prevent a duel between Monroe and Hamilton. There's a delicious
irony there, since later Burr would kill Hamilton in a duel. The
intervention didn't happen, but the footnote shows how it nearly
did.
</P>
<P>
   Safire's life of Maria Reynolds is more fully fleshed than
history allows. Mrs. Reynolds came on stage as alleged bait used by
her extortionist husband to catch Hamilton. In his pamphlet
defending himself, Hamilton blamed an affair with her for payments
he couldn't deny making to her husband. The suspicion was _
Callender had it, and Safire lets it hang _ that Hamilton and
Reynolds were dipping into the public till together.
</P>
<P>
   In history, Mrs. Reynolds disappears. But not in
``Scandalmonger.'' Safire posits an earlier affair between her and
Burr. Burr did, in fact, handle her divorce from Reynolds for no
fee. Safire brings her back to befriend Callender in his last years
and get direct evidence for him that Jefferson had once ``offered
love'' to the wife of Jefferson's best friend.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few things in ``Scandalmonger'' that didn't happen
(and the footnotes tell you what they are) but nothing that
couldn't have happened. The novel will be most fun to readers who
know a bit about the period because Safire, unconstrained by
documentary evidence in a work of fiction, is free to print the
contumelious rumors.
</P>
<P>
   But even if all one knows is what can be gleaned from the book,
the reader will be no more misled than visitors whose knowledge is
confined to the monuments and memorials.
</P>
<P>
   A great political novel? Not when compared to Robert Penn
Warren's ``All The King's Men.'' But ``Scandalmonger'' is much more
than just fun and games.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
