<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7043 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS25-COX     02-24 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A distressing look inside American medicine
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Doctors tend to write alike: Beautifully
observed, descriptive, but absent emotion. They take it all in, but
they keep a clinical distance. The odd thing is that they do this
even when recollecting their experiences in print.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Blood of Strangers'' is a seriously good book by an
emergency-room doctor named Frank Huyler. He works in Albuquerque,
but I'm sure his stories could derive from any metropolitan area of
America.
</P>
<P>
   The detachment works in Huyler's case because he's chosen to
narrate his book in brief, aphoristic, and for the most part
unrelated segments of five to seven pages apiece; he always cuts
away before he has to make some sort of emotional connection.
</P>
<P>
   Huyler is strongest when narrating the way things go subtly
awry. He respects the mystery of life just as much as he does the
mystery of death.
</P>
<P>
   There are no explanations here, just events and people, some of
them astonishing _ a superb female brain surgeon who would do a
couple of lines of coke every morning. When she'd had a really bad
day, she'd buy a live chicken, take it home and cut its throat with
a straight razor. (Relax. She washed out after a drug test lit up
like a fireworks display.)
</P>
<P>
   There's a short piece about suicides that's worthy of Lewis
Thomas, particularly a haunting suicide note Huyler came across:
``I'm driving,'' a woman wrote. ``Somewhere there will be a
train.''
</P>
<P>
   There is the woman who refuses to take her blood-thinner because
she believes in the Lord more than she does in medicine. She
quickly throws a clot and dies. At the autopsy, Huyler watches the
pathologist remove a clot the size of a thumb. The attending
physician bows his head and says the Lord's Prayer while the
pathologist shifts uncomfortably.
</P>
<P>
   I love his tale of a 26-year-old cowboy with pneumonia, renal
and respiratory failure, as well as other things indicating an
early demise. The comatose patient, Johnson by name, became a
teeter-totter over which two doctors exercised completely different
methodologies. One was rabidly proactive, demanding a full court
press to save Johnson's life, while the other was content to keep
the patient comfortable and out of pain.
</P>
<P>
   Huyler gets rotated out of the ICU. Six months later, he's
walking down the hallway when he passes a man reading a paper while
waiting for an appointment. It's Johnson, looking hale and hearty.
Did he live because of the proactive doctor's efforts, or in spite
of them? Huyler has no idea.
</P>
<P>
   There is three-in-the-morning desolation here, real-world
wisdom:
</P>
<P>
   ``After a while, you come to rely, more than anything else, on
first sight. You walk into the room and you think, sick or not
sick. Not sick goes home as fast as possible. Sick you watch. You
draw blood, you order X-rays, you give them fluids. You are careful
because a little bell went off when you walked into the room and
saw them.''
</P>
<P>
   Huyler writes about a particularly pleasant patient who
specialized in killing convenience-store clerks. He was
unremittingly grateful every day of his hospitalization, even as
the cops kept watch outside the door so he couldn't get away and
kill somebody else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was glad, even as weak as he was, that he meant me no harm,
that I was not ... alone in the store and unready.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each day I helped him get better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Blood of Strangers'' takes you deep into the world of
medicine most patients can sense but would rather not confront _
fallible people, rotten odds, inferior protoplasm and exhausted
doctors trying to keep people alive when there's no reason they
should be.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
