<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 11:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7044 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-JEFFERSON25-CO     02-24 2401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-JEFFERSON25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A tour fit for a president
 &HT;    By Jan Tuckwood
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _
</P>
<P>
   ``He who fears no truth fears no lie.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Thomas Jefferson
</P>
<P>
   Well said, Mr. President, but how do we tell our kids the truth
about Sally Hemings?
</P>
<P>
   This is our quandary as we wait outside Monticello, home of our
third president, one of the smartest men who ever lived and, as it
turns out, one of the most fascinating, in that National Enquirer
sort of way.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson had at least one child and probably six with his slave
Sally,and now, even the people who run Monticello admit it.
</P>
<P>
   No shame, just facts. The rumor that's been bubbling for 200
years has been confirmed, and as every leader since Henry VIII
knows, nothing intrigues the masses like dirty laundry.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, CBS aired its miniseries on Jefferson and Hemings'
38-year relationship, ``Sally Hemings: An American Scandal.'' Last
month, the Monticello Foundation published its exhaustive report on
their affair, and since then, Monticello's publicity staff has been
deluged with demands from film crews worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Jefferson's one hot president.
</P>
<P>
   When my family visited Monticello last summer, there were
titters among folks waiting in line to see Jefferson's majestic
home: Hmmm, wonder how they'll handle the Hemings affair?
</P>
<P>
   I decided to take Jefferson's advice and go with the truth. The
DNA doesn't lie, I tell my three daughters, ages 17, 12 and 9.
Jefferson wrote ``all men are created equal,'' but he owned slaves,
and he had children with one of his slaves. That slave, Sally, was
the beautiful, pale-brown half-sister of Jefferson's dead wife,
Martha _ they had the same father.
</P>
<P>
   Sordid as it may sound, that's the truth.
</P>
<P>
   The girls, too young to grasp the hypocrisy, seemed impressed.
Wow, he did all that and invented the swivel chair, too!
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson's human foibles made him more real to them.
</P>
<P>
   Before we were done, our Meet the Presidents Tour of
Charlottesville, Va., and Washington, D.C., hit the grandest,
grittiest and goriest spots to help bring Jefferson and his friends
alive for the kids.
</P>
<P>
   Did you know that pieces of President Lincoln's skull are on
display in Washington?
</P>
<P>
   We discovered that, too.
</P>
<P>
   MEET THE PRESIDENTS TOUR
</P>
<P>
   Washington came first, but Jefferson makes a more lasting
impression.
</P>
<P>
   That's what my children decided after our Meet the Presidents
Tour of Washington, D.C., and Charlottesville, Va., last summer.
Our goal: Put some flesh and blood on the founding fathers by
seeing how they lived and how they died.
</P>
<P>
   Before this trip, my kids' knowledge of George and Thomas was as
flimsy as an old dollar bill. Jefferson was basically just that guy
on the nickel.
</P>
<P>
   Did they know that he was 6-feet-2 and bony with uncommonly long
limbs and hands?
</P>
<P>
   Or that his handwriting was so precise that he could record a
whole day's activities on a palm-size ivory tablet?
</P>
<P>
   Or that he soaked his big feet in cold water every morning for
60 years and believed this kept him healthy?
</P>
<P>
   Did they know that he had a long affair with one of his slaves?
</P>
<P>
   No, they had no idea until we visited Monticello, Jefferson's
home outside Charlottesville.
</P>
<P>
   Kids usually find homes of dead presidents boring. Sorry,
George, but mine found Mount Vernon underwhelming. They even
dismissed the White House as ``a bunch of colorful rooms with old
paintings.''
</P>
<P>
   But they liked Jefferson's gadgets, and they became fascinated
with his graveyard.
</P>
<P>
   Tip for parents: Graveyards give kids the creeps and therefore
hold them in thrall.
</P>
<P>
   We visited Monticello in August, when it was very hot and very
crowded. After taking a shuttle bus from the welcome station up to
Jefferson's ``little mountain,'' we were told to return in an hour
for our guided tour of the mansion.
</P>
<P>
   We had plenty of time to wander the grounds, and we wisely chose
to walk along Mulberry Row, where the slaves lived, down a
half-mile path to the family graveyard.
</P>
<P>
   My children, ages 17, 12 and 9, studied every gravestone they
could read through the massive iron gates.
</P>
<P>
   There was Martha Jefferson Randolph's dead baby. And Dabney
Carr, Jefferson's boyhood friend, who had made Jefferson promise to
bury him under their favorite oak tree. And Jefferson's own
obelisk-shaped stone, inscribed according to his instructions:
``Here was buried Thomas Jefferson, Author of the Declaration of
American Independence, Of the Statute of Virginia for Religious
Freedom, and Father of the University of Virginia.''
</P>
<P>
   There were newer graves, too, one just six months old. This is
where Jeffersons still come to be buried, and now, this cemetery is
the focus of controversy: Shouldn't Sally Hemings' descendants be
buried here, too?
</P>
<P>
   Hemings, the slave whose long-time affair with Jefferson
produced at least one child and probably six, is portrayed in
modern movies as gorgeous and pale, and, based on what historians
know, that's probably correct.
</P>
<P>
   Monticello slave Isaac Jefferson once recalled Sally as ``mighty
near white ... very handsome, long straight hair down her back.''
Jefferson's grandson Thomas Jefferson Randolph described her as
``light colored and decidedly good looking.''
</P>
<P>
   Sally's four children who survived to adulthood, three boys and
a girl, had an indisputable resemblance to Jefferson and passed
into white society. But what's more, the DNA of her youngest son,
Eston, matches the DNA of other Jefferson males. And a thorough
study of Jefferson's whereabouts during the conception of the
children adds to the case.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson was at Monticello when all six of Sally's children
were conceived. Given how much Jefferson traveled, the chance is
just 1 percent that his presence was a coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it was love or lust, rape or romance, no one knows,
and it's unlikely that anyone will ever know,'' said Daniel Jordan,
president of the Thomas Jefferson Memorial Foundation, which runs
Monticello, when the foundation's report concluding that Jefferson
fathered the Hemings children was released Jan. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of glossing over the bumps in Jefferson's character,
Monticello's guardians took Jefferson's words to heart: ``Follow
truth wherever it may lead.''
</P>
<P>
   This frankness makes Monticello more than your typical rich
man's mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Traditions of slave life are celebrated alongside the triumphs
of Jefferson's presidency, and by showing visitors the whole
picture, politically correct or not, the history lesson sticks.
</P>
<P>
   Reverence puts kids to sleep, but quirkiness delights them.
</P>
<P>
   And Thomas Jefferson was one quirky fellow.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE MONTICELLO: HOME OF A GREAT MIND
</P>
<P>
   Tip for all who visit Monticello: Prepare to feel like a stupid,
lazy underachiever.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to Mr. Jefferson, you are, you most certainly are.
</P>
<P>
   As one of my children commented, ``People sure got a lot done
before they had TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Jefferson got this much done, kids. That was a guy who used
both sides of his brain.
</P>
<P>
   Monticello, which Jefferson began building in 1769 when he was
26, is full of his inventions, and all of his creative tinkering
served a useful purpose.
</P>
<P>
   He was particularly fond of things that turned, such as swivel
chairs, revolving bookstands that could hold several books at once,
and closets with moving prongs to hold coats and shirts.
</P>
<P>
   These gizmos, plus Jefferson's space-saving devices _ his own
bed was tucked into an alcove to save space and all the staircases
in the house are narrow for the same reason _ gave us good reason
to poke our heads into every nook of Monticello.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson designed a Great Clock for the entrance hall that uses
a system of weights and chains to tell the time and day, from
Sunday near the ceiling on down through the week. Trouble was,
Jefferson ran out of room for the whole week, so he cut a hole in
the floor and put Saturday in the basement.
</P>
<P>
   Time was of the essence to Jefferson, who rose with the sun
every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Determine never to be idle,'' he wrote to his daughter Martha
in 1787. ``No person will have occasion to complain of the want of
time who never loses any. It is wonderful how much may be done if
we are always doing.''
</P>
<P>
   We spent several hours doing Monticello, inspecting the gardens,
the slaves' dwellings, the stables and the wine cellar.
</P>
<P>
   The kids pronounced it ``about a hundred times neater than Mount
Vernon,'' and let's face it: Washington was the father of our
country, but Jefferson, scandal and all, was a more interesting
man.
</P>
<P>
   MONTPELIER AND ASH LAWN-HIGHLAND: THE PRESIDENTS NEXT DOOR
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson loved the company of James Madison, our fourth
president, even though most people found ``the great little
Madison'' rather serious and colorless.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why somber Madison chose such a cheerful shade of
yellow for his lifelong home, Montpelier.
</P>
<P>
   Montpelier is off Route 20 in Orange, Va., about 30 minutes
north of Monticello. It attracts fewer tourists than the 2,000 that
flock to Monticello every summer day, but it's every bit as
beautiful, if not as quirky.
</P>
<P>
   With its stunning view of the Blue Ridge Mountains, Montpelier's
``a squirrel's jump from heaven,'' as Madison liked to say. Madison
was a little man (5-foot-2 according to his enemies and 5-foot-6
according to himself) with a big mind. He was 36 when he wrote the
U.S. Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   My kids were on mansion overload when we drove by Montpelier,
and a real tour of the place would have prompted a family mutiny.
Same with Ash Lawn-Highland, home of our fifth president and
Jefferson pal, James Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   No offense, James, but Ash Lawn-Highland looks more like
Monticello's country cousin than a mansion. It's a 535-acre estate
with the atmosphere of a working plantation, including cattle,
sheep and peacocks in the yard.
</P>
<P>
   The real character among this circle of friends was Dolley
Madison, who was the first presidential partner to be called the
first lady. She also was first to serve ice cream at the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   BARBOURSVILLE RUINS: THE GHOST HOUSE OF A GOVERNOR
</P>
<P>
   We did stop by the home of another Jefferson friend, James
Barbour, governor of Virginia from 1812 to 1814.
</P>
<P>
   Barbour's home is believed to be the only building designed by
Thomas Jefferson in Orange County, Va., but visitors today get just
a glimpse of the mansion's former grandeur: Since Christmas Day
1884, it's been a burnt-out shell of a home, a ghost house with
crumbling walls and mysterious memories.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Barboursville Ruins is a historic landmark set amid
830 acres of rolling hills that's now home to a premiere vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   We tasted some of the Barboursville wines, picked up a nice
bottle of Pinot Grigot and then toured the ruins. The kids spent an
hour wandering through the rooms of the destroyed house, which
reminded us of Twelve Oaks after the Civil War in ``Gone With the
Wind.''
</P>
<P>
   On summer nights, the genteel Southern accents of Barbour's time
are replaced by the British lilt of the bard. Shakespeare's
comedies are performed under the stars at the ruins.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, Mr. Jefferson and the ``society of our taste'' that he
formed with Madison, Monroe and Barbour would approve.
</P>
<P>
   They shared a love of the arts, but they loved their Virginia
countryside and their new country even more.
</P>
<P>
   As Jefferson wrote in 1824: ``Our revolution ... presented us an
album on which we were free to write what we pleased. We had no
occasion ... to investigate the laws and institutions of the
semi-barbarous ancestry. We appealed to those of nature, and found
them engraved on our hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   DID YOU KNOW. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Mount Vernon, George Washington's home on the Potomac River
and a short drive outside Washington, D.C., is the nation's most
visited historic home, with more than 1 million guests a year.
(Elvis Presley's Graceland in Memphis, Tenn., attracts about
750,000.) To learn more about Mount Vernon, see
www.mountvernon.org. If you go in the summer, get there early.
Admission: $9 for adults, $4.50 for children 6 to 11.
</P>
<P>
   _ The neatest thing inside Mount Vernon is Washington's bed,
where he died of quinsy (a really bad infection of the tonsils) in
1799 after getting several bleedings from his doctors.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Derringer pistol that John Wilkes Booth used to kill
President Lincoln is on display at the Ford's Theatre Museum in
Washington, D.C. So are Lincoln's clothes from that night and the
ropes used to hang the conspirators.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lincoln's blood-stained pillow can be seen at the Peterson
House, across the street from Ford's Theatre. To learn more about
Ford's Theatre and Lincoln's death, see www.nps.gov/foth/.
</P>
<P>
   _ A fragment of Lincoln's skull and the bullet that killed him
are on display at the Walter Reed Army Medical Museum in
Washington, D.C. So are pieces of vertebrae from John Wilkes Booth.
The museum, at Elder and Georgia Avenue NW, is open 10 to 5 daily.
Phone: (202) 782-2200.
</P>
<P>
   _ President Lincoln's 1865 assassination was not the only
tragedy at Ford's Theatre. In 1893, all three floors of the theater
collapsed, killing 22 federal workers. The restored theater opened
in 1968. Admission is free, but call ahead because the working
theater is closed during show performances.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Before you visit Monticello, stop by the Monticello Visitor's
Center nearby. A video on Jefferson's life is shown throughout the
day, and a large free exhibit of Jefferson's belongings (clothes,
glasses, papers) provides a personal look at the man. The excellent
Monticello web site (www.monticello.org) features the new detailed
report on the Jefferson-Hemings affair and a complete Jefferson
history. Admission to Monticello is $11 for adults, $6 for children
6 to 11, and includes a 30-minute guided tour of the home.
</P>
<P>
   _ University of Virginia, designed by Jefferson, is in downtown
Charlottesville and worth a tour.
</P>
<P>
   _ Take the scenic Route 20 south from Orange, Va., to
Charlottesville to see Montpelier and the Barboursville Ruins.
Check out their websites at www.montpelier.org and
barboursvillewine.com. A self-guided tour of the ruins is free.
Wine tastings are $3 per person including a souvenir glass.
Admission to Montpelier is $7.50 for adults and $3.50 for children
6 to 11.
</P>
