<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ Until he was touched by an Oprah, North Carolina
native Robert Morgan was happy to sell 10,000 copies of his novels.
So far, ``Gap Creek'' has sold more than 600,000 since the author's
apperance on Winfrey's book club. Not bad for a high-school dropout
who grew up in a family who didn't own a car or a TV set and who
didn't see his first movie until he was 17. In other news,
Amazon.com has combined with PEN to launch another book award for
short-story writing with a $10,000 prize. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 21.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-KIDS _ Roundup of the latest children's books. (Bookman,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-LOVESUPREME _ Former Atlantans TaRessa and Calvin
Stovall's first book, ``A Love Supreme,'' is about a love barely
acknowledged in the media: that between married black men and
women. We talk to the authors, playwright Pearl Cleage and former
Spelman College president Johnnetta B. Cole - who are featured with
their husbands in the book _ as well as Atlanta couples at the
local signing about the need for such an effort. Not just for black
people's benefit, but the general public's consideration.
(SoMurray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-MILNER _ Jay Milner's review of Kenneth Galbraith's ``Name
Dropping'' (Houghton Mifflin). (Milner, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MILNER-COLUMN _ When I mention that John Kenneth Galbraith, the
noted Harvard-based economist and author, brought me a Coke one
time during my stay at Harvard some years back as Journalist in
Residence, it's what you call ``name dropping.'' That's the name of
Galbraith's new book, ``Name Dropping'' (Houghton Mifflin). Unlike
most of his other books _ they number in the 20s _ this new
Galbraith book isn't about economics or politics, not specifically
anyway. The subtitle is ``From FDR On'' and it's a chatty book
about the famous people the Harvard economics professor emeritus
has been involved with professionally and personally through the
years. As the jacket blurb states, ``Drawing on a lifetime of
access to many of the greatest public figures, Galbraith creates a
rich and uniquely personal history of the century _ a century he
helped shape.'' (Milner, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-SCANDALMONGER _ The reputations of former Presidents
Jefferson and Hamilton survived. The journalist who blew open both
scandals was a Scotsman, James Thomson Callender. His reputation
didn't make it. History writes him off as an acerbic scandalmonger
who died drunk. History may write him off, but William Safire, the
New York Times columnist who delights in being contrarian, writes
him back into events in this novel with footnotes. Seeing as one
columnist is writing about another, Safire is sympathetic.
(Blackburn, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   EYMAN-ON-BOOKS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Doctors tend to write
alike: Beautifully observed, descriptive, but absent emotion. They
take it all in, but they keep a clinical distance. The odd thing is
that they do this even when recollecting their experiences in
print. ``The Blood of Strangers'' is a seriously good book by an
emergency-room doctor named Frank Huyler. He works in Albuquerque,
but I'm sure his stories could derive from any metropolitan area of
America. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet Books page for the current week.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS 0222 -- Author John Updike has put together an
ambitious and clever prequel to Shakespeare's `Hamlet.'' (Hulbert,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes a 2-column color
illustration of Updike and a 6-pica color photo of book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: PAY IT FORWARD -- In ``Pay it Forward,'' author Catherine
Ryan Hyde wonders what would happen if you tried to change the
world -- and did. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post) Art includes a 6-pica
color photo of book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SKUBE ON BOOKS -- Gadflies get around and no one
circulates like Stanley Fish, the former chairman of Duke
University's literary department. (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes 6-pica color photo of book
jacket and a 1-column color mug of columnist.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BIOGRAPHY -- Author Jane Fletcher Geniesse follows the
footsteps of intrepid traveler Freya Stark in ``Passionate Nomad.''
(Browning, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: NONFICTION -- A biography of Jon Vickers hits the low as
well as the high notes. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: PUBLISHING NOTES: A new book unmasks the science of where
we live, who we are and what we buy. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post)
