   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   DADS _ Why visiting day is different at Moore Haven
Correctional. Like father, like son. That old saying holds for kids
whose dads go to prison. But a new program aims to keep the next
generation out of jail. (Belkin, Palm Beach Post). 45.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-JEFFERSON _ How to introduce your kids to Thomas
Jefferson. With discussion of Monticello, Barboursiville Ruins,
Montpelier and Ash Lawn-Highland. (Tuckwood, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: IF YOU GO BOX
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet Travel page for the current week.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL 0222: SOMETHING FOR EVERYONE -- South Africa is a
diverse nation offering some wonderful amenities for tourists.
Here, two travel agents offer tips on making the most of South
Africa. (Hamilton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes one
4-column color photo of downtown Cape Town, a 2-column photo of
monkeys playing in a park, a 2-column photo of a sunset near Cape
Point and a 18-pica photo of a street vendor near Soweto.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: PLANTATION INN -- Florida's Plantation Inn is a model of
casual elegance. (Park, Palm Beach Post) Art includes a 1-column
color photo of the inn.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS -- The Danish Design Center has moved into a
new home. (N.Y. Times News Service.)
</P>
<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   MILAN-FASHION _ A. Scott Walton reports from Fashion Week in
Milan. (Walton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   NYFASHION-BACKSTAGE _ By the time I'd finished talking with the
backstage dressers at the recent New York runway shows, I was
thinking of signing up myself. It looked like fun. Hours before a
show begins, dressers are standing by racks of clothing, making
certain everything is in place. (Moss, Dayton Daily News). MOVED
EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, Feb. 27.
</P>
<P>
   NYFASHION-PRODUCER _ She shuffles the cards as proficiently as a
Las Vegas dealer and the stakes can be just as high. You won't see
spades or clubs on the stiff white cards Deborah Hughes holds as
she races up and down the aisles of a Bryant Park tent, stopping
only long enough to place or switch cards on chair seats as she
goes. The deck she holds is a ``who's who'' of the fashion world
and Hughes' expertise lies in knowing who should sit where: editors
from Vogue and Harper's Bazaar, writers from The New York Times and
The Washington Post, executives from Bergdorf-Goodman and Saks
Fifth Avenue, celebrities who come to support their favorite
designers. A faux pas can be disastrous. Hughes, 42, a former model
and public relations director for designer Carolina Herrera, is a
pro. (Moss, Dayton Daily News).50. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, Feb. 27.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   ANGIE-ANPARO _ A conversation with Angie Anparo, who is one of
the artists on hot producer Matt Serletic's new Melisma label.
(Mlongino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   TRACE-ADKINS _ Short piece on funny, good-looking, country
singer Trace Adkins, who is making some waves. (MLongino, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   AMANPOUR-IRAN _ CNN's Christiane Amanpour returns to her native
Iran in a documentary, ``Revolutionary Journey,'' and examines the
changing politics as well as the remnants of her own life there,
which she left 21 years ago. Grade: A. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   TV-KINGDOM _ Review of ``The 10th Kingdom,'' NBC's hugely
ambitious and wondrously imaginative new 10-hour miniseries,
beginning Sunday. ``Kingdom'' re-imagines all of the classic fairy
tales, but in a modern context, with humor, suspense, special
effects and plenty of Freudian meat. Truly worth watching. Grade:
A-. (Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 22.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE NEWS AND REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   MICHAEL-DOUGLAS _ Q and A with Michael Douglas about his new
movie ``The Wonder Boys,'' directed by Curtis Hanson (``L.A.
Confidential''). The Oscar-winning actor talks about making the
comedy movie, his new-found affection for Atlanta (he recently
visited The Carter Center here in his work for the U.N.) and about
his engagement to Catherine Zeta-Jones (plus, he reveals the
pick-up line he used on her when they first met). (BLongino,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   FRANKENHEIMER _ Interview with director John Frankenheimer
(``Ronin,'' ``The Manchurian Candidate'') who helmed ``Reindeer
Games'' for Miramax. He's also directed several TNT movies.
(BLongino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 31.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-REINDEER _ Movie review: ``Reindeer Games'' with Ben
Affleck. (Murray, Atanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-BIGTEASE _ Movie review: ``The Big Tease,'' a lightweight
comedy about a hairdresser going to the olympics of hairstyling.
Grade: C. (Ringel, Atanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-WONDERBOYS _ Movie review: ``The Wonder Boys,'' from
director Curtis Hanson (``L.A. Confidential''). Grade: B.
(StMurray, Atanta Journal-Constitution). 21.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-DIGITAL _ PARK CITY, Utah _ On the surface, Chuck Collins
doesn't appear to be a movie industry mover and shaker. But
Collins, 44, is on a mission from Kennesaw to remake Hollywood.
It's one day before the start of the Sundance Film Festival, Robert
Redford's annual celebration of independent movies, which ended
Jan. 30, and Collins has traveled the nearly 2,000 miles here from
Atlanta to represent Cobb County's Digital Projection Inc. As DPI's
national market development manager, Collins is overseeing the
installation of roughly $1 million in cutting-edge projection
equipment that Sundance ultimately used to screen about 17 of its
112 films. The demonstration's ultimate impact portends to the
coming digital visual age in Hollywood. We report on Hollywood's
pending change to digital visuals, the controversy among filmmakers
and how the switch may alter what's shown at your local movieplex.
(BLongino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 45. WITH PHOTO and
LAYOUTS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, Feb. 27.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS _ Mini reviews of all currently playing
movies. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-WONDERBOYS _ Movie review of the ``Wonder Boys.'' The
Wonder Boys are actually Wunderkinds, which a German-English
dictionary translates as ``infant prodigies.'' Infant is perfect,
for, in different ways, these guys are a couple of pipsqueaks. They
can't even dispose of a dead dog. Three stars. (Schwan, Palm Beach
Post). 15.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MRDEATH _ A review of ``Mr. Death.'' 3 stars. Eccentric
documentarian Errol Morris (``The Thin Blue Line'') studies one
Fred Leuchter, an execution-device designer who, not satisfied with
success in that cheerful field, took up a second career as a
Holocaust-denial ``expert.'' (Garcia, Austin American-Statesman).
18.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-REINDEER _ A review of ``Reindeer Games.'' 2 stars. A
former criminal wants to start a new life, but they just keep
pulling him back in. Ben Affleck, Gary Sinise and Charlize Theron
star. (Garcia, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-SIMPATICO _ A review of ``Simpatico.'' 3 stars. Racetrack
scheme goes awry when romantic betrayal intrudes. Nick Nolte, Jeff
Bridges, Sharon Stone star in this adaptation of the Sam Shepard
play. (Macor, Austin American-Statesman). 13.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-REARWINDOW _ A look at the restored ``Rear Window,''
Hitchcock's supreme paean to the voyeuristic soul of the movie
experience. James Stewart and Grace Kelly were at their finest in
this masterful 1954 thriller. (Macor, Austin American-Statesman).
20. MOVED
</P>
