<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 11:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7060 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     02-24 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Thursday, Feb. 24, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Friday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-RIOT (Crescent City, Calif.) _ Inmates at Pelican Bay
State Prison, involved in the bloodiest riot in the prison's
10-year history, had been in a lock-down for most of the last six
months because of a similar incident in August. They had been
allowed back in the prison's exercise yard in large numbers for
just a week when Wednesday's violence broke out. It ended in a hail
of gunfire, as guards shot one inmate to death and injured 12
others. By PETER HARTLAUB and ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-PROFILE (Crescent city, Calif.) _ It doesn't have the
name recognition of Leavenworth, Sing Sing or any other
high-profile hellhole for the nation's convicts. But despite its
brief history, Pelican Bay has a reputation in law enforcement
circles as one of the worst maximum security lockups in the United
States. By SCOTT WINOKUR.
</P>
<P>
   DAVIDIANS-RAID (San Antonio) _ For the first time, a Branch
Davidian survivor of the Feb. 28, 1993, shootout at the Davidian
compound near Waco, Texas, has admitted that he fired at two of the
four U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms agents who were
killed during the battle. By DICK J. REAVIS.
</P>
<P>
   AREA-CODES (San Francisco) _ Faced with imminent, rapidly
changing area codes, the California legislature is considering
legislation that would assign separate new area codes to wireless
phones, pagers and data lines. The bill would require the state's
Public Utilities Commission to adopt a technology-specific area
code overlay and determine how to implement it. By VANESSA HUA.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PARENTING-SKILLS (Undated) _ Dr. T. Berry Brazelton raised his
kids some 50 years ago, when moms stayed at home, guns at school
were unheard of and parents didn't have to compete with 200
television stations for their kids' attention. Despite the
challenges of being a parent today, the child development
specialist says working prents don't need is to feel guilty about
leaving their children in the care of others, ``We're just stuck
with it,'' he said of child care. ``We're stuck with making it
work.'' By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-LUNCHES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Veggie burgers and soy milk are
edging closer to school lunchrooms. It is not shifting student
tastes but soy industry lobbying and a sustained push by activists
that are putting pressure on school menus. The U.S. Department of
Agriculture is preparing regulations that will make it easier for
schools to be reimbursed for soy burgers or similar foods. By RICK
KARLIN.
</P>
<P>
   WIGS-KIDS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Bonnie Molitor's most striking
feature used to be her hair _ a two-foot long shining blond curtain
she frequently flicked back over her shoulders with a gesture as
natural and unconscious as breathing. She had been growing it since
she was four-years-old, submitting to only the tiniest of trims at
the hairdressers. But this week she had nearly a foot of her hair
lopped off and donated to a nonprofit organization called Locks of
Love, which donates custom-made wigs to children who suffer from
alopecia areata. By ELIZABETH BENJAMIN.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-MARRIAGE (San Francisco) _ David Knight thinks his father,
Republican state Sen. Pete Knight, is wrong about gay marriage,
wrong about gay rights. But he agrees with his dad about one thing:
``The big issue is, he feels (my homosexuality is) a private
matter. I could never get the point across that he's exactly
right,`` David Knight said Wednesday in only his second public
statement in opposition to Proposition 22, the anti-gay-marriage
initiative his father sponsored on California's March 7 ballot. By
CAROL NESS.
</P>
<P>
   LAURA-SCHLESSINGER (San Francisco) _ The Horizons Foundation has
launched a national campaign to get conservative radio personality
Laura Schlessinger, known as Dr. Laura to her adoring audience of
20 million, to tone down her attacks on gays and lesbians. By CAROL
NESS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   UPS-INTERNET (San Francisco) _ United Parcel Service Chairman
and CEO Jim Kelly sees a pot of gold at the end of the Internet
rainbow. And it's painted brown. ``In a world where dot-com fever
has created over 50,000 new millionaires in the Bay Area alone, UPS
believes that the biggest riches still to be found will be in the
physical world of fulfilling digital transactions,`` said Kelly. By
ALAN T. SARACEVIC.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Chicago Alderman Edward Burke
wants to require that businesses selling cigarettes post graphic
photos of diseased lungs, hearts and mouths near checkout counters.
What do you think kids will do with diseased-organ photos that are
meant to shock them? My guess is they'll be reproducing the
pictures on T-shirts before the year is up. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
</TEXT>
