<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ANTI-TOBACCO IDEA GOES UP IN SMOKE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Like Chicago Alderman Edward Burke, I have been
a long-time foe of tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Decades before dozens of the tobacco industry's dirtiest secret
memos were leaked to the public, even years before the U.S. Surgeon
General began to warn the public about the health hazards of
smoking, I knew cigarettes were seriously nasty.
</P>
<P>
   As a child in a house of smokers, a teen-ager cruising around in
smoke-filled cars, an adult jazz fan peering through thick blue
haze to groove on Mose, McCoy or Monk, I'd have done darn-near
anything to make people stop smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why I think I understand where Alderman Burke is coming
from.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, he announced that he would introduce an ordinance in
the Windy City, requiring businesses that sell cigarettes to post
graphic photos of diseased lungs, hearts and mouths near check-out
counters or cash registers.
</P>
<P>
   Said Burke: ``The public has become jaded by written warnings
alone and needs to be further informed about the health risks
associated with the use of tobacco products. The use of photographs
may be the most powerful tool at our disposal to get the message
across.''
</P>
<P>
   Now I will grant the alderman that much of the public has indeed
become jaded by written warnings about cigarettes. All it takes is
a trip to the movies to see that much of the public is way past
jaded. Cigarette smoking is in the throes of a reverse chic
revival.
</P>
<P>
   After a fairly smoke-free 10 or 15 years, heroes and heroines,
not just bad-guy losers, again smoke on screen. And they act as
though they really, really enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   It is not surprising that young people _ that segment of the
population most susceptible to media images _ are also smoking in
higher numbers than we've seen in years.
</P>
<P>
   While the smoking population of the U.S. has been stuck at about
25 percent for the last decade, almost one-third of teens took up
smoking in the '90s. This is about 3,000 new young victims every
day.
</P>
<P>
   I will wager that almost none of these kids is smoking because
she or he needs to be further informed about the health risks
associated with the use of tobacco products.
</P>
<P>
   One 14-year-old I know, who started sneaking cigarettes with her
adolescent pals about a year ago, used to come home from grade
school and harangue her cigarette-addicted mother with statistics
on lung cancer, heart disease and the negative health effects of
second-hand smoke.
</P>
<P>
   From what ``the experts'' can tell, kids begin smoking today for
many of the reasons kids always engage in stupid behavior:
rebellion against authority, boredom, peer pressure and the
pathetic belief that they are immune to the dangers of such things
as speeding cars, alcohol, drugs, unprotected sex and tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   With nicotine, however, kids are soon in the same swamp of
addiction as their adult counterparts. Worse. Last year, a study at
the University of California at San Francisco revealed that the
earlier people begin to smoke, the more severe _ and irreversible _
is the damage to their lungs. Even if they manage to quit.
</P>
<P>
   In a nationwide survey, 70 percent of adult smokers said they
wanted to break their habit. Sounds like these folks don't need
additional information either; they already know that what they're
doing is killing them.
</P>
<P>
   Will publicly posted gross-out photos of cancerous lungs, mouths
and hearts that look like ``Alien II'' help them get the nicotine
monkey off their back? Maybe. But don't expect large numbers. Most
hard-core cigarette addicts have tried a variety of stop-smoking
programs and tricks. They seem to need the kind of intensive help
we give heroin and cocaine addicts, which may include temporary
drug mitigation therapy with medications like Prozac.
</P>
<P>
   As for kids: You hear their music, you see their grunge
clothing, you watch their smart-ass, cynical cartoon shows like
``South Park.''
</P>
<P>
   What do you think they'll do with diseased-organ photos that are
meant to shock them? My guess is they'll be reproducing the
pictures on T-shirts before the year is up.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, people like me, who have spent our lives trying
to escape the disgusting effects of cigarette smoking, won't be
able to walk into a mom-and-pop or the corner bar without getting
visually assaulted by the very demon we thought we had on the run.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, Alderman Burke. Your idea is close, but no cigar.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
