<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARENTING-SKILLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     EXPERT SAYS PARENTS SHOULDN'T FEEL GUILTY ABOUT CHILD CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SYLVIA WOOD  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. T. Berry Brazelton raised his kids some 50 years ago, when
moms stayed at home, guns at school were unheard of and parents
didn't have to compete with 200 television stations for their
children's attention.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just nostalgia to say today's world for children and
parents is more complex, from the Columbine High School massacre to
the shortage of quality child care and family time.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder families are stressed, Brazelton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing parents need to hear are solutions,'' said
Brazelton, the well-known pediatrician and guru of parenting with a
syndicated column, radio show and more than 28 books to his name,
including ``Touchpoints'' and ``What Every Parent Knows.''
</P>
<P>
   What working parents don't need is to feel even more guilty
about leaving their children in the care of others, said Brazelton,
a child development specialist and professor emeritus of pediatrics
at Harvard Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just stuck with it,'' he said of child care. ``We're
stuck with making it work.''
</P>
<P>
   An advocate of improving child care, Brazelton encourages
parents to ask a lot of questions and pay attention to the number
of children per provider. For infants, there should be no more than
four babies to one employee. With toddlers, he caps the ratio at
5-to-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look to see if it's safe, feels good and whether your
caregiver really likes children,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brazelton said one of the most common pitfalls for working
parents often comes at the end of the day, when they try to step
back into their role as moms and dads after a long, tiring day at
the office.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than rush into the evening chores, he encourages parents
to spend time reconnecting with their children. ``Sit down with all
of them in your lap, talk, rock, sing and get close to them
again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also advises parents not to let their feelings of guilt about
being away from their children make them avoid asking them to pitch
in and help with the chores, from setting the table to helping
prepare dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's absolutely critical for families to depend on
each other,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On television, Brazelton believes parents have to set stricter
limits, or risk losing their child's attention to the barrage of
violence and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents just have to take control and say this is an area
where you don't have any choices. You can watch an hour of TV a
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Since stress is inevitable, Brazelton is convinced that the best
thing parents can do is learn how to manage it and help their
children do the same by laying a good foundation in the first three
years of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is an answer to any of the stresses in life, it's
that we want to give our kids self-esteem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   An octogenarian, Brazelton still travels around the country
giving speeches while teaching at Children's Hospital in Boston,
where he founded the Touchpoints Project, an outreach program to
train professionals how to better serve families of infants and
toddlers.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, some of his positions on certain developmental
milestones in children's lives, including the best age for toilet
training, have sparked controversy. He recently raised eyebrows
after asking the Procter &AMP; Gamble Co., the makers of Pampers, to
manufacture a larger diaper to accommodate older children not yet
ready to use the potty.
</P>
<P>
   But most pediatricians agree with his child-directed approach,
whether it's toilet training or feeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a kid in diapers at kindergarten,'' said Dr.
James Saperstone, a pediatrician with Capital Care Pediatrics
Guilderland, N.Y. ``It's when they show readiness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
