<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV24-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT GOOD CAN COME FROM THIS? 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Thursday Feb. 24  
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I met a loving couple the other day. The two women have been
together for many years and live in a nice house with a garden and
well-behaved dogs and cats. You would never suspect they were bent
on destroying the time-honored institution of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   They actually pass as nice neighbors and contributing members of
society. Of course, they live in sin, but that's what 50 percent of
Californians would have them do rather than support their right to
marry.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 22, or the Knight Initiative, which Californians
will vote on March 7, is a baffling piece of wannabe law. It would
add language to the California Family Code that only marriage
between a man and a woman is valid or recognized in California.
Even though same-sex marriage is already not legal in the state,
supporters seek the measure as a down-the-road guarantee to keep it
from being imported.
</P>
<P>
   They insist that Prop. 22 is not intended to discriminate
against gay people.
</P>
<P>
   How can that not be? Such a law would take the state several
steps backward at the same time California has taken two giant
steps forward. We started out the new century being more
open-minded than the last century, with a new law establishing a
statewide domestic partnership registry so that gay state employees
can get insurance benefits for their partners. Another new law
outlaws discrimination against gay students and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   So, how do you explain a retro law that would punish the same
group of people you've already decided to treat fairly? Do
Californians believe in equal rights or not?
</P>
<P>
   What good could come from Prop. 22? Basically it would prevent
two women or two men from getting married in another state where it
might someday be legal for gay people to marry and then coming to
California and expecting that marriage to be honored. Help me here.
Why would that bother anybody? I understand being stopped at the
California line to make sure you're not bringing gypsy moths in on
your melons from Arizona but how could honeymooning Jim and John
put the state in peril?
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Prop. 22 say their motives have nothing to do with
discrimination but with state sovereignty. They don't want gay
Californians sneaking off to Vermont, or any other state that might
eventually allow such unions, and then coming back to Petaluma and
_ doing what, flaunting their legality?
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the measure say, of course, it's about
discrimination. They say to pass this law would poison the air and
encourage uglier laws and create more separation between the gay
world and the straight world.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say we need Prop. 22 to underscore the belief that
children are best raised in an environment where they have a mother
and a father.
</P>
<P>
   How about two mothers and two fathers? I know several of this
family mix in which the surrogate father and his male partner are
helping to raise the child of the lesbian mother and her partner.
</P>
<P>
   How about we vote in language that children are best raised in
an environment that fosters love? Prop. 22 does not foster love.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say we need this law to protect marriage, but how
does keeping one kind of couple from marrying threaten another kind
of couple's marriage? Since when did my blissful state depend on
another's?
</P>
<P>
   If marriage-protectors are really serious about pushing measures
that would improve the health of married life, they could work on
shortening the work week, raising the minimum wage, creating good
child care centers where people work.
</P>
<P>
   They could demand affordable housing, longer vacations, better
birth control and work to eliminate stress, alcoholism and domestic
violence.
</P>
<P>
   They could urge couples to turn off the TV one night a week and
talk to each other.
</P>
<P>
   I got that last idea from the two women I just met. We were all
talking about when couples work long hours it's almost necessary to
make a date with each other in order to have any romance. They said
they turn off the TV, make a nice dinner, rent a movie, and then,
they laughed, `We fall asleep.' '' Isn't that something? And we
heteros thought that gay people had sex all the time. The troubling
report about Prop. 22 is that, according to public opinion polls,
half of Californians believe it's a good idea. Forty one percent
are opposed to it, and the rest are still undecided. This means
Prop. 22, which has twice as much money behind it as the other
side, has a good chance of passing.
</P>
<P>
   I still don't get it.
</P>
<P>
   At first blush it sounded like a busybody law and a spiteful
move toward one group of people. At last blush, it still does.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
