<SLUG> BC-UPS-INTERNET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     UPS CHIEF SEES AN `E' IN COMPANY'S FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALAN T. SARACEVIC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The head of United Parcel Service told two
business groups that he sees a pot of gold at the end of the
Internet rainbow. And it is painted brown.
</P>
<P>
   `` UPS believes that the biggest riches still to be found will
be in the physical world of fulfilling digital transactions,'' Jim
Kelly, the chairman and chief executive of the shipping company,
told the Commonwealth Club of San Francisco and the Oakland Chamber
of Commerce on Wednesday. ``In other words, where the rubber meets
the code _ digital code _ is where the money's at.''
</P>
<P>
   Most electronic commerce companies have found the last mile of
their business models the most daunting. Getting products from
click to brick has proved difficult.
</P>
<P>
   And many have turned to UPS, and its competitor Federal Express,
as their fulfillment divisions. UPS believes it is poised to take
full advantage of that opportunity, using the Internet as a
springboard into new territories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Commerce, in a nutshell, has always been about the transfer of
goods, information and funds,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said his 92-year-old company, which sold shares to the
public for the first time last year, can do more for electronic
commerce than deliver products. Through its UPS Capital division,
the executive told the business leaders that his company ``can lend
you money to grow. Finance your inventory. Even buy your accounts
receivable outright.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly sees this outshoot of UPS's core business as a critical
service for small companies trying to get a toehold in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   To help the process along, UPS recently formed another wholly
owned subsidiary, UPS e-Ventures. The company is designed to
identify and bring to market companies that will serve the needs of
businesses that operate on the Internet, Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Another subsidiary will be UPS e-Logistics, which will offer a
package of services _ from warehousing to order fulfillment to
customer service _ for small and medium-size companies that sell
their products on the Internet. UPS already offers such services to
its larger customers through UPS Worldwide Logistics.
</P>
<P>
   UPS used money from its initial public stock sale to help
finance these ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Although the company's stock enjoyed a healthy first-day pop in
November, it was treated to a cold dose of Internet economics in
late January. After reporting that its fourth-quarter profit grew
37 percent, the stock fell 8.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts attributed the decline to traders who were disappointed
that UPS did not get a bigger boost from holiday sales shipments by
Internet retailers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-00 1230EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000224.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 12:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7105 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-WIGS-KIDS-HNS &LR;      02-24 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIGS-KIDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SIXTH-GRADER LOSES HER PONYTAIL FOR A CAUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (ATTN: Fla.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ELIZABETH BENJAMIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY. N.Y. _ Bonnie Molitor's most striking feature used to be
her hair _ a two-foot long shining blond curtain she frequently
flicked back over her shoulders with a gesture as natural and
unconscious as breathing.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie's hair was the longest in her sixth-grade class at Albany
School 19. She had been growing it since she was four-years-old,
submitting to only the tiniest of trims at the hairdressers.
``Please Mom, one inch, not two,'' she would plead.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, Bonnie faced a stylist's scissors without fear.
The 11-year-old voluntarily had nearly a foot of her hair lopped
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just like helping people,'' said Bonnie, who will send her
ponytail to a nonprofit organization called Locks of Love, which
donates custom-made wigs to children who suffer from alopecia
areata.
</P>
<P>
   This mysterious condition causes hair on the head, and sometimes
the entire body, to fall out. Doctors are unsure exactly what
causes the disease, for which there is no cure.
</P>
<P>
   Locks of Love, based in Palm Springs, Fla., was founded in 1997
by Peggy Knight, who suffered from alopecia areata as a child and
keenly remembered the shame and embarrassment of growing up without
hair. The organization has given away more than 185 custom-made
wigs that retail for about $3,500.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult for children to find wigs that fit properly,
Locks of Love Executive Director Jennifer Cox said. The Locks of
Love wigs feature a silicone cap that creates a vacuum seal around
the head and prevents the wig from slipping.
</P>
<P>
   It takes about a dozen ponytails like Bonnie's to make a single
wig, each of which has more than 150,000 hairs.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie got the idea to donate her hair while watching
television. She saw a show about a group of teens who gave their
hair away to cancer patients. But Bonnie kept quiet at first about
her motivation when she asked her mother, Debra Weinlein, 42, for
permission to get a haircut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her to wait, because it was such a drastic thing, and I
wanted to make sure she really wanted to do it,'' Weinlein said.
``But then when she told me why. I thought it was wonderful and
immediately said yes.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Weinlein took her daughter to the Scissors III &AMP; Co.
Salon where owner Christine Murray showed Bonnie to a chair. The
cut took all of half an hour _ the bulk of it done in several swift
clips as Murray cut off Bonnie's 12-inch ponytail.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie held the silky tail and stroked it as Murray shaped her
remaining shoulder-length locks. The sixth-grader did not cry for
her lost glory, but she admitted the new, more sophisticated style
would take some getting used to.
</P>
<P>
   `'I've got a new child,'' Weinlein mused. ``I can't believe how
much older she looks.''
</P>
<P>
   Extra-long hair runs in Bonnie's family. Her great-grandmother,
Esther Bailey, had auburn hair that hung to the tops of her thighs.
She cut it when she gave birth to twins, one of which was
Weinlein's father.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey's hair is likely packed away somewhere in the attic,
basement or drawer at one of her eight children's homes, Weinlein
said. She hopes to find it in time to send it to Locks of Love
along with Bonnie's ponytail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame how many people get their hair cut and don't know
that someone else needs it,'' Weinlein said. ``Once it hits the
floor, though, it's useless.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
