<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-GERALDINE-FERRARO-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHOLIC-BASHING IS BACK IN STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Campaign
Countdown commentary column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Campaign
Countdown, a rotating campaign-commentary column written by former
Democratic vice-presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro and by
MSNBC host Laura Ingraham.) 
 By GERALDINE FERRARO  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    I had a hard time watching Pat Robertson on CNN Saturday night,
gloating over George W. Bush's win in South Carolina.
 &HT;    The Christian Coalition was energized, he proclaimed. They had
worked their heads _ he would never say ``butts'' _ off to get out
the vote. They had made thousands of phone calls. They had sent out
tens of thousands of pieces of direct mail. They had made a
difference.
 &HT;    When a reporter suggested that the Christian Coalition had
delivered South Carolina for Bush, Robertson was happy to agree.
But he went even further _ it had actually elected the next
president of the United States, he said.
 &HT;    Hold on now. To quote that great American philosopher, Yogi
Berra, ``It ain't over 'til it's over.'' And Americans who believe
in religious tolerance _ especially those of the Catholic faith _
have a lot to think about after South Carolina.
 &HT;    No doubt about it, Bush's visit to Bob Jones University was a
smart political move _ in the short term. It may have involved
pandering to an institution built in the image of a founder who
reportedly believed that Catholicism is a satanic cult, that the
pope is the Antichrist and that the Catholic Eucharist is
comparable to cannibalism, but it's worth it if the university has
thousands of volunteers ready to help get out the vote.
 &HT;    And he didn't have much to lose _ Catholic-bashing doesn't upset
too many people in South Carolina. As for the wider world, if
Catholic-bashing doesn't seem to hurt museum curators or members of
Congress, why should it harm a presidential candidates?
 &HT;    Back in November, New York's Brooklyn Museum opened
``Sensation,'' an exhibition that featured a rendition of the
Madonna by an African artist which used elephant dung and
porn-magazine clippings among its elements.
 &HT;    It stirred up a controversy, of course, but the museum
administration had known it would _ the same thing had happened
when it was first shown in London. But the directors of an
outer-borough museum that had long struggled to attract visitors
knew that controversy would bring attention, and with the attention
would come long lines of paying customers. As indeed they did.
 &HT;    Canny marketing, to be sure, and if a few Catholics saw the
piece as an insult to them and to their religion, well, that was
the price of success.
 &HT;    I didn't see the exhibit, but as a Catholic I was nonetheless
offended by it. As a believer in civil liberties, I agree with the
show's defenders that its freedom of expression is protected by the
First Amendment _ but, as a Catholic, I will never go to the
Brooklyn Museum again.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, in January Catholic-bashing reared its ugly head in
Washington.
 &HT;    It's been more than a century since the office of chaplain of
the House of Representatives was created, and this year was the
first time a Roman Catholic priest was recommended for the post.
The House Republicans can't find a heartbeat when it comes to
enacting virtually any significant piece of legislation, but the
nomination of a Catholic chaplain woke them up in a hurry.
 &HT;    With the speed of lightning, the Republicans rejected the
nomination, installing a Protestant minister instead. Neither
Speaker Dennis Hastert (R.-Ill.) nor Majority Leader Dick Armey
(R.-Texas) offered any explanation for their actions. And, as you'd
expect, they were surprised at the angry reaction from House
Catholics of both parties.
 &HT;    Since 1960 Catholic politicians, fearful of upsetting the
church/state balance forged by John F. Kennedy, the first Catholic
elected president, have avoided speaking up for themselves. But the
rejection of a Catholic chaplain, apparently for no reason other
than his Catholicism, struck many as a return to the rampant
intolerance of the 19th century, and drew a vociferous response
from many Catholics in the House.
 &HT;    And now Catholic-bashing may actually have helped a candidate
win his party's presidential nomination.
 &HT;    Sen. John McCain may have lost the South Carolina primary
because he refused to pander to the anti-Catholic forces that
dominate that state's Republican Party. McCain declared that he
would have refused to appear at Bob Jones University because of its
teachings against racial intermarriage and Roman Catholicism.
 &HT;    And, as Robertson was so happy to point out, McCain lost by a
beefy 12 points.
 &HT;    But McCain knows something that neither Robertson nor Bush has
figured out: The Democrats who turned out in droves to support
Ronald Reagan in 1980 and again in 1984 were hard-working,
blue-collar Catholics.
 &HT;    McCain realizes that those Catholics are the most conservative
members of the Democratic Party, and that they have more loyalty to
their issues than to political labels. His whole campaign has been
built on reaching out to independents and Democrats.
 &HT;    In short, he wants the Reagan Democrats back. He believes that
the only way for the Republicans to win is as a party of inclusion,
not one of exclusion. And he's right.
 &HT;    After the Michigan polls closed on Tuesday night, Pat Robertson
was back on television, but this time he was a different man, still
defiant but more cautious. It seemed to be sinking in that the same
ploy that had helped win South Carolina had angered Michigan
Catholics who, three days later, went to the polls and helped
McCain to a razor-thin win.
 &HT;    After his humiliating defeat in New Hampshire, Bush had proven
himself willing to compromise principle to win. He would have known
better if he'd read a 1996 book by former Sen. Warren Rudman
(R.-N.H.). In it, Rudman wrote that the Republican Party will
discredit itself if it allies itself too closely with the Christian
Coalition.
 &HT;    It already has.
 c.2000 Geraldine A. Ferraro  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Geraldine Ferraro was the Democratic vice-presidential
candidate in 1984. A former member of Congress, she is a political
analyst for Fox News and president of G&AMP;L Strategies in New York
and Arlington, Va., a corporate consultancy on workplace and
diversity issues.)
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Campaign
Countdown, a rotating campaign-commentary column written by former
Democratic vice-presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro and by
MSNBC host Laura Ingraham.)
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _ _  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
