<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7132 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e BC-TREK-JAMES-WONG-DIREC     02-24 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREK-JAMES-WONG-DIRECTS-FINAL-DESTINATION-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAMES WONG'S `FINAL' ANSWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of director
James Wong on the set of ``Final Destination.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    James Wong scares the hell out of people.
 &HT;    Since the early 1990s, Wong and his partner, Glen Morgan, have
creeped out millions of television viewers by writing, producing
and/or directing episodes of ``The X-Files,'' ``Millennium'' and
``The Others.'' He also whisked viewers to the cosmos with the
short-lived sci-fi series ``Space: Above and Beyond.''
 &HT;    What's with Wong and his affinity for the genre?
 &HT;    ``I love the adrenaline,'' he says. ``I've also always looked at
the sci-fi fans as a smarter audience. You can never sneak stuff by
them, because they are so into the stories, so into the genre.
 &HT;    ``They are avid and careful watchers,'' he says, ``more so than
the general public, I think. Creating shows for people who really
care is cool.''
 &HT;    On March 17 Wong and Morgan will expand their horizons with the
arrival of their first feature, ``Final Destination.'' A
supernatural thriller, ``Final Destination'' was co-written by
Morgan and Wong, co-produced by Morgan and directed by Wong.
 &HT;    The film stars Devon Sawa as Alex, a student who experiences a
vision of the plane he has just boarded being blown to smithereens.
Sure enough, moments after he and several classmates hurriedly
disembark, the plane blows up.
 &HT;    Later, those who left the plane start dying gruesome deaths. Is
Alex causing the mayhem, or could it be something even more
mysterious?
 &HT;    ``This movie is very exciting and a lot of fun,'' Wong says by
telephone from his Los Angeles production office. ``But, to be
honest, an audience that's not into this adrenaline-rush kind of a
movie, or that doesn't like violence at all, might find it an
ordeal to go through.
 &HT;    ``It's not violence directed from one person to another,'' he
adds, ``but it's a supernatural force _ death, actually _ that is
hunting down our characters. So there is that very suspenseful,
scary, intense experience. If you're into that, then you're going
to like this movie. It's an in-your-face ride.''
 &HT;    The biggest difference between directing a movie and a
television-series episode, Wong says, is the time-crunch factor.
Filmmaking allow more time to prep, to perfect scenes on the set
and to fix mistakes during the editing and audience-testing
processes.
 &HT;    To make ``Final Destination'' genuinely cinematic and effective
on the big screen, Wong turned to production designer John Willet,
among others.
 &HT;    ``What we've done, after our main character has cheated death,
is skew all of our sets,'' Wong says. ``The perspectives change
subtly. Even sets we'd seen before change a little bit _ Alex's
bathroom, for example, looks different the second time you see it.
 &HT;    ``There's an uneasiness that is created by the set design, then
also by the angles, editing, music and everything else,'' he says.
``There's a layer of uneasiness that permeates the whole movie.''
 &HT;    Wong infused similar uneasiness into ``X-Files'' and
``Millennium,'' of course. He and Morgan spent several seasons with
Chris Carter on ``X-Files,'' writing several memorable episodes.
Wong earned an Emmy nomination for directing ``Musings of a
Cigarette-Smoking Man.''
 &HT;    Many ``X''-philes feel that the show has suffered since the
duo's departure, but Wong downplays any chance of their taking an
encore.
 &HT;    ``I think that show has passed me by,'' Wong says. ``It's in its
seventh season, and I've not worked on it since the fourth.''
 &HT;    However ...
 &HT;    ``If Chris called and said, `Hey, do you want to do something?'
and Glen and I were available,'' Wong says, ``I'd definitely do
something.''
 &HT;    Wong and Morgan also oversaw the controversial second year of
``Millennium,'' which centered more on the Millennium Group's
mythology than on the case assignments of Frank Black (Lance
Henriksen). Some fans _ as well as Henriksen himself _ felt that
Wong and Morgan had broken something that needed no fixing.
 &HT;    Wong says that he ``stands by'' the Morgan/Wong era of
``Millennium,'' but otherwise declines comment.
 &HT;    Then there's ``Space: Above and Beyond,'' a sci-fi adventure
that seemingly refuses to die. Fans of the series, which ran from
1995 to 1996, gather with the show's stars and creators at an
annual ``Space'' convention, publish a ``Space'' newsletter and
lobby Fox and the Sci-Fi Channel to fund fresh episodes or at least
a two-hour television-movie finale.
 &HT;    ``I don't know what it is about `Space,''' Wong says. ``I guess
it just touched a chord. A lot of people loved those ideals about
the military, those ideals about what real courage is and what
you'd do for the person next to you.
 &HT;    ``People want to think we'd all have those qualities if we were
put under the crucible of war,'' he adds. ``I'm surprised people
still talk about it, and gratified they appreciated the work.
 &HT;    ``Actually, I'd love to do a `Space' movie,'' Wong concludes.
``I would do it in a heartbeat.'' 
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
