<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FUNGUS IS AMONG US: RIGHT IN THE LIVING ROOM! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's show and tell time.
</P>
<P>
   Show and tell is usually reserved for the early grades of school
(the handyman never did have any), but this time two readers showed
some humdingers to the handyman. What's more, they wanted to know
what they could do about them.
</P>
<P>
   A mushroom in the living room.
</P>
<P>
   That is the bombshell that Andrea Martin of North Easton, Mass.
dropped in the handyman's lap. It was literally in the living room,
growing between the slider and the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The 'shroom began growing one day in September and continued
that day and a night, wrote Martin. She finally broke it off and
nothing more grew, until another came up this month.
</P>
<P>
   So, what to do about it?
</P>
<P>
   That's easily said, not done. You have to eliminate all
moisture; because mold _ and mushrooms _ will grow on almost any
moist surface, indoors or out.
</P>
<P>
   An immediate solution is to treat the area with a solution of
one part household bleach and three parts water. This will kill the
mold and might keep it from coming back, but if the moisture is not
eliminated, the problem will continue.
</P>
<P>
   To eliminate the dampness, aim a heat lamp or floor heater at
the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The original water was probably caused by a leak; one source is
the slider itself. Make sure you keep open the little drain holes
that keep water flowing out of the grooves in the slider.
</P>
<P>
   Another leak source is the space under the slider, outside,
especially if there is not a full step down from threshold to
patio. If there is not a full step (7 1/2 inches) down from the
slider, it will always be a problem. Sometimes caulking joints in
the seams of the facia board will help.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Martin said the water is overflowing the gutter,
running behind the gutter, down the wall and the face of the
sliders, until it gets under the inside floor.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, the gutter or the drip edge (the edge of the roof)
should be adjusted so that water dripping over the edge will drip
into the center of the gutter. Little else will correct this
problem.
</P>
<P>
   So, good luck, Andrea Martin. With some of that luck, and
perseverance, you can solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cracking and breaking bricks
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another show and tell for the handyman was from Charles Merhib
of Wellesley, Mass., who submitted pictures of his brick steps and
wondered why cracks appeared in the mortar joints and in the
bricks, and why some bricks actually broke off at their ends.
</P>
<P>
   As Merhib wrote, some years back a mason skimcoated the sides of
his 1949 concrete steps, and mortared brick on the treads and
flagstone on the landing.
</P>
<P>
   In a few years, the mason was gone and the bricks began cracking
along the top through both brick and mortar, said Merhib. Cracks
also developed where the bricks overlap the risers, and there were
cracks in places where there was no apparent stress. The ends of
some bricks broke off where they overlap the riser.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another mason said we need waterstruck brick, but those were
too misshapen to use. I even made concrete bricks to duplicate
bricks, but they did not hold up well either,'' Merhib said.
</P>
<P>
   Why all the cracks and what can be done about them? We thought
about simply laying bluestone slabs on the brick, or better yet,
taking off the brick and putting on a bluestone tread, Merhib said.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the mason did everything right; except maybe putting
the bricks on their wide side on the treads instead of on their
narrow sides.
</P>
<P>
   What has happened, simply is this: Ordinary stress (movement of
the entire cast concrete steps) will cause cracks in the mortar. If
these cracks are allowed to remain, water gets into them, and in
winter it freezes, expanding the cracks and breaking bricks.
</P>
<P>
   The cracks across the front of the bricks and the breaks where
they overhang the riser are caused by stress; people step on the
end of the brick, pressing down where the brick overhangs the
riser; repeated stepping will crack and break the brick.
</P>
<P>
   Why bother with an overhang? It's good because it looks good and
allows toe room for people climbing the steps. It makes climbing
steps more comfortable. The fact that the bricks were laid on their
wide side aggravates the problem; bricks laid on their narrow sides
will resist cracking and breaking longer.
</P>
<P>
   The same thing happened to the handyman's steps, which had hard
brick
</P>
<P>
   properly mortared, but no brick is immune to stresses.
</P>
<P>
   The handyman's answer was to replace some of the bricks and keep
repointing (chipping out of old mortar and putting in new) where
and when needed. It is a matter of maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   But Merhib's idea of putting a bluestone slab on each step is
excellent. Take off the brick and use it in a patio or somewhere,
and mortar in a bluestone slab. Actually, they make bluestone
treads that will work very well and should fit those cast concrete
steps perfectly, allowing a slight overhang.
</P>
<P>
   That's it, Andrea Martin and Charles Merhib. There is plenty of
work, but I see nothing but success if you persevere. Then show and
tell again, triumphantly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
