<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7143 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-WOMEN-ICE-ART-BOS &LR;      02-24 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-ICE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 COLD THRILLS BRING WOMEN TO THE MOUNTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE DANIEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; NORTH CONWAY, N.H. _ Ina Steinhilber arrives at International
Mountain Climbing School on a recent Friday evening looking every
bit the Newbury Street gallery manager she is.
</P>
<P>
   Under her full-length faux fur coat, she wears a black
turtleneck, long black skirt, and black boots. Her dark hair is
pulled back tightly, and she carries a black leather bag over her
shoulder. Her smiles seem nervous, and she looks relieved to learn
_ as do the other three women here for a weekend ice climbing
course _ that none has tried the sport before.
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday morning, Steinhilber, 28, the same woman who eyed the
climbing wall in her gym for 18 months before giving it a try, is
clinging to a 30-foot-tall slab of ice, a footlong ice tool in each
hand, the sharp picks carefully slung above her head into the
frozen wall, attired this time in layers of polypropylene,
Gore-Tex, and fleece. She has a helmet on her head and chemical
foot-warming packs in her plastic boots. The front teeth of the
crampons attached to the bottoms of those boots stick into the ice
like industrial-strength darts to support her weight, and from down
below classmate Diane Murphy is yelling, ``Way to go, Ina.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Herskovitz, 33, who owns a public relations firm, is
watching too, saying ``Look how graceful she is'' and then joking
``Why did we let her go first?'' Murphy, 36, who left a job as a
computer consultant to teach snowboarding in Maine, laughs with
her. When Steinhilber guides her pick into a pock in the ice, the
women on the ground murmur, ``Oh yeah, that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   The instructors, Peg Immel, 56, of Lincoln, Mass., and Michelle
Jenkins, 37, of Jackson, N.H., are also tracking Steinhilber's
progress from the ground. ``You won't be able to see your feet over
that bulge,'' Immel shouts. ``Take small steps, get your crampons
straight in, and then stand up straight.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a long way from the climbing wall in Steinhilber's gym
and the one-day rock climbing workshop she did last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Finally Steinhilber reaches the top and, ice picks in hand,
smiles to her classmates below. This time the smile is real.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never in a million years thought I'd like it as much as I
did,'' she says. ``I never even thought I could do it. There's a
great combination of fear, excitement, and then the thrill when you
actually reach the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Immel remembers that feeling, and reliving it is one reason she
teaches new rock and ice climbers. Immel, who owns Zuma Tex-Mex
Cafe in Boston's Fanueil Hall with her husband, Stephen, has been
offering these Women's Weekend Ice Climbing Retreats since last
winter. The retreat part comes in the two-night stay at Cranmore
Mt. Lodge, meals, a hot tub _ and a massage.
</P>
<P>
   Both days' climbs this weekend take place at a partly sunny spot
called Walk in the Woods, which is more like a very steep climb in
the woods, in the Frankenstein Cliffs area of the White Mountains,
a half-hour drive from North Conway.
</P>
<P>
   The women head into the backcountry early to stake out their
piece of ice in this popular climbing region. They trudge single
file, backpacks laden with clothing, food, hot drinks, water,
ropes, carabiners, harnesses, and other equipment. The crunch of
sparkling snow underfoot muffles their voices as they pass
surrounding cliffs dotted with the bright red or yellow specks of
other climbers moving slowly up the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Like rock climbing, ice climbing is gaining followers, though
more slowly. About 90 percent of the 50,000-plus, overwhelmingly
male readership of Climbing magazine participates in rock climbing,
while only 27 percent climbs ice, says editor and publisher Duane
Raleigh. ``The anecdotal evidence is that more women are out ice
climbing, and certainly over the past five years the sport has
grown,'' says Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ice climbing,'' he adds, ``is more brutish, more like
construction work.''
</P>
<P>
   What women may lack in brute strength, says Immel, they
compensate for with flexibility, balance, and technique. ``I used
to say that the difference between the two is that rock climbing is
like ballet and ice climbing is like building a garage,'' she says.
``But the better you get, the more delicate it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Immel, a small, nimble woman, certainly moves delicately as she
scales a cliff to secure some ropes, her blond curls barely visible
under her helmet, her movements a quieter point and place than the
noisy hacks and kicks of her novice charges.
</P>
<P>
   Climbing, of course, is only part of the sport. There are the
added obstacles of staying warm, enduring a strenuous hike to the
climb location while toting heavy gear, and maintaining and
organizing an array of equipment. Potential dangers include
frostbite, sticking oneself with pick or crampons, falling chunks
and collapsing walls of ice, and avalanches.
</P>
<P>
   One climber in the group, 31-year-old Julie Walko of Arlington,
Va., left after a single day on the ice, saying, ``It's too cold.''
Sunday's afternoon temperature climbs 20 degrees higher than
Saturday's 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difficulties are part of the fun,'' says instructor
Jenkins, who always brings a thermos of spicy hot tea to share with
the climbers. ``Yes, about 75 percent of it is just hard work, but
the other 25 percent makes it all worthwhile.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginners learn to climb by top rope, meaning a rope is secured
at the top of the cliff. A belay, a friction-based pulley system
that can hold thousands of pounds, connects the rope from the
climbers' harnesses to the belayer, the person on the ground
controlling the give. If a climber slips, she either won't fall at
all or will fall only a few inches as the rope stretches. More
advanced climbs involve climbers' working together, fixing the
ropes bit by bit, which means more room for error.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, after finishing the weekend course, says she's ready for
more. ``It's a really cool sport,'' she says. ``I think it's the
being really intensely focused on it. You're just so in it.''
</P>
<P>
   The route down the mountain is a quick and easy glissade (an
intentional slide on their backsides), using the ice tool for
rudder and brake, followed by the slow drive out of North Conway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so frustrated that I was stuck in traffic because I was
so excited to tell someone about the weekend,'' says Steinhilber.
``So I took out the (school's) brochure. I think I might take a
three-day mountaineering course.''
</P>
</TEXT>
