<HEADER>
A7146 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-MCMANUS-LANDRY-FAITH-     02-24 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCMANUS-LANDRY-FAITH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOM LANDRY WAS A MAN OF GOD AND FOOTBALL -- IN THAT ORDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Religion Commentary)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Mike McManus is a syndicated columnist whose ``Ethics &AMP;
Religion'' appears in almost 100 newspapers)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By MIKE McMANUS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    When I read of the death of Tom Landry, 75, the legendary coach
of the Dallas Cowboys, my mind went back to 1983 when I had the
privilege to interview him just before a championship game.
 &HT;    To the millions of Americans who watched him on TV, Landry
always seemed in control of the situation. Dressed impeccably, with
a tie and fedora hat, he was always extraordinarily calm. His face
seemed absolutely emotionless.
 &HT;    Why? ''My players had to believe I was in control,'' Landry was
quoted as saying. ''It would hurt them to see me losing it.''
 &HT;    But often he was not invincible. For the three years that
preceded my interview with him, the Cowboys lost the championship
game needed to get into the Super Bowl. For these reasons, his
attitudes on winning and losing were particularly interesting.
 &HT;    He gave God credit for victories, but never gave Him credit for
losses!
 &HT;    ''I believe my talent comes from the Lord, and whatever success
I've had is because of my belief in God,'' he told me. ''I believe
He has a plan for my life, and uses my influence to further His
kingdom. But God doesn't take sides in football games.''
 &HT;    How then, does God work?
 &HT;    ''I rely on Him to give me concentration and to be prepared to
do as well as I can,'' Landry said. For example, he said, in the
middle of a game, ''something will come to mind and I'll make a
decision to call a play. I don't know where the idea comes from _
whether God placed it in my mind or not. But I know He prepares us
to meet the trials of life.''
 &HT;    According to Rev. Leighton Farrell, his pastor at the time, when
people asked Landry if he prayed for victory, he replied, ''My
prayer is not to win, but that every person might play to the best
of his ability and that there be no major injuries.''
 &HT;    The day before I spoke with Landry, Philadelphia's head coach,
Dick Vermeil, who had led the Eagles from mediocrity to the Super
Bowl a couple of years earlier, resigned although he had years left
on his contract. ''I am emotionally burned out,'' Vermeil said
after a losing season.
 &HT;    Asked about that, Landry said, ''If you put your whole priority
on winning football games, you can be burned out when you lose.''
 &HT;    Before he committed his life to Christ in 1958, winning football
games WAS Landry's highest priority. During a Bible study in the
off-season at his home, he decided to transform his nominal
church-going Christianity, ''where God got lost in the shuffle,''
to a point where Christ would be the No. 1 priority in his life.
 &HT;    He said, ''I did not have a flash on the road to Damascus'' (a
dramatic conversion, like St. Paul). And the impact was gradual.
But in reading the Bible daily for 15 to 20 minutes, he developed a
new way of looking at people, his family and at winning and losing.
 &HT;    He was no longer as excited by either victory or defeat, and
began exuding a calm confidence that inspired others.
 &HT;    And he created an atmosphere in which players could grow
spiritually as well as physically. First, he invited players and
their wives to join a tea/Bible study. And a chapel service was
organized before every game.
 &HT;    The approach worked. Former star quarterback Roger Staubach
testified at his funeral, ''He was our rock, our hope, our
inspiration. He was our coach. Probably there were some players
that didn't love him, but all respected him. He was committed to us
and you don't find that type of commitment in life very often.''
 &HT;    His son, Tom Landry, Jr., told the congregation filled with Pro
Football Hall of Famers and Super Bowl champions, ''Tom Landry was
everything the world believed him to be. He was a man of virtue, of
high moral character, a man whose talents and hard work propelled
him to the top of his profession. Tom Landry never strayed from his
ideals. He remains a consistent shining example to all of us.''
 &HT;    Shortly after I interviewed Landry, the team lost the
championship to the Washington Redskins, led at the time by Coach
Joe Gibbs, another committed Christian. After the victory, every
Redskin fell on his knees on national TV and recited the Lord's
Prayer, led by Gibbs.
 &HT;    A day later, I called Landry and asked him if he had prayed for
victory. He laughed and replied, ''There's nothing wrong with
praying for victory, but God might get divided if there are
Christians on both sides.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.2000 Mike McManus
