<HEADLINE>
WHY IS FOX SPOILING ALL OUR FUN? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why is Fox TV canceling ``Who Wants to Marry a
Multimillionaire?'' Surely not for reasons of taste. Certainly not
because of poor ratings.
</P>
<P>
   The decision must have something to do with the specter of a
monster lawsuit by the bride, and possibly one by the bridegroom,
too. (Although what could Rick Rockwell sue the network for?
Defamation of character? With a character like his?) The other 49
contestants might have a case too, a class action suit. Given
everything that's come to light about Rockwell, weren't they lured
onto the program under false pretenses? (I see a new Fox show
shaping up: ``Who Wants to Sue for Millions?'')
</P>
<P>
   The promise of more ``WWTMAM?'' was high on my list of Reasons
to Go On Living, a list that seems shorter every day. So I'm
disappointed. And yes, I know I should be ashamed of myself, but it
was so wonderfully tawdry. I want more, and I'm sure I'm not alone.
Never underestimate the appeal of really, really terrible TV.
(Could that be another new Fox show? ``Really, Really Terrible
TV''? Or have they done that one already?)
</P>
<P>
   `WWTMAM?'' made my week, although I suppose it's only fair to
admit it was a bad week. The big night found me all but immobilized
with back pain, switching back and forth between the finals of the
Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show and ``WWTMAM?'' It goes without
saying that the dog show was infinitely more civilized than the
human show. Dazed as I was by pain, there were moments when the two
seemed to blend into one. I kept waiting for ``WWTMAM?'' host Jay
Thomas to pull back the contestants' lips to examine their teeth.
Was it my imagination, or did the chosen bride, Darva (``I did it
for a lark'') Conger, resemble a whippet? The bridegroom? A pit
bull, definitely. And not a well-trained, well-groomed example of
the breed. Down, boy. Heel! Some dogs will do anything for
attention.
</P>
<P>
   I loved it, every cheap, degrading minute of it. So what is
there to love about 50 young women offering to commit instant
televised matrimony with a rich man they've never met? It's a
perfect comment on our national obsession with money, an obsession
that's reached the point of total lunacy. ``WWTMAM?'' could have
been satire. Too bad it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   It's ``reality'' programming, a genre Fox TV pioneered. Given
revelations about Rockwell's past _ the restraining order, the
financial fudging _ I wouldn't be surprised to see him someday on
another Fox ``reality'' show, ``America's Most Wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   What does ``WWTMAM?'' have to do with reality? What's real about
marrying somebody you've known for 30 seconds? That's pretty
un-real, even in Las Vegas, where you can get married faster than
you can get good seats for Siegfried &AMP; Roy. Not that I have
anything against getting married in Vegas. I've done it myself.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not climbing up on a high horse with all those people
condemning ``WWTMAM?'' and intoning about the sanctity of marriage.
Marriage is sacred for some; for others it's a financial
opportunity. That's always been true, and it always will be. On
``WWTMAM?'' we saw how far some women were willing to go for the
promise of money. It was sick. It was appalling. It was also
enthralling, hilarious, and even instructive.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they could save the show by changing the title to include
certain warnings: ``Who Wants to Marry an Alleged Multimillionaire
Who May be a Maniac?'' or ``Who Wants to Marry and Quickly Divorce
a Self-Described Multimillionaire and Win Cash and a Host of
Valuable Prizes?'' Or maybe just ``Love For Sale, Anyone?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
