<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7157 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-     02-24 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERHAPS THE INTERNET ISN'T AS LONELY AS FEARED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two days ago, a shocking study out of Stanford University
concluded that the Internet is creating a nation of lonely people,
wired Eleanor Rigbys who spend less time at such socially
productive activities as watching television (gasp!) and shopping
in stores. According to the breathless report, a staggering
minority _ yes, minority _ of Internet users attend fewer social
events and spend less time with family and friends. And even e-mail
threatens to destroy the social fabric and pull people apart. The
scientific evidence? ``You can't share a coffee or a beer with
somebody on e-mail or give them a hug,'' said Norman Nie, co-author
of the report and director of Stanford's Institute for the
Quantitative Study of Society.
</P>
<P>
   The geniuses at Stanford contend that technology is turning us
into hug-deprived misanthropes. Their research, however, conflicts
with a recent study of our own. Instead of looking at Internet
loners, we interviewed Internet lovers, would-be Romeos who go
online looking for a lifelong squeeze. And the results are
astounding: Of all the men who conduct online advertising campaigns
for a wife, some 50 percent end up in the arms of a lovely lady
named Amy. Sigh. E-mail brings them together.
</P>
<P>
   Money, it turns out, can buy you love online _ as long as you
make the right offer.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit A: Rod Barnett, a.k.a. Mr. www.10K4aWife.com. Last year,
this St. Louis businessman launched a Web site offering a $10,000
reward to the person who introduces him to his future wife. ``No,
there is nothing wrong with me,'' he writes on the site, ``and I
can assure you that I am not desperate.'' Not lacking in
confidence, he goes on to describe his ideal mate: a Barbie-esque
brunette with humanitarian interests, compassion, and other
qualities that come in handy in the Miss America pageant. His
motto: ``Fate is what happens when you fail to take charge.'' Theme
song: That syrupy thing from ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit B: Ed Ryder, a.k.a. Mr. www.searchingforher.com. Last
month, this Pennsylvania native put up a Web site offering a reward
of at least $25,000 for a spouse. The catch: He linked the prize to
the stock of of Sedona Corp., an Internet start-up in Limerick, Pa.
``I want to make it known that I am not desperate, I am not lonely,
I am merely unfulfilled,'' he says. A three-time graduate of Dale
Carnegie confidence-building courses who is currently in between
opportunities in ``the lawn care business,'' he describes himself
as ``the type of person who stops traffic to save a turtle.'' He
also outlines his entire life story: He was the last kid picked for
kickball, got bullied in junior high, and once had a harrowing
incident involving a G.I. Joe action figure and a bathroom. (Trust
me, that's more than you need to know.)
</P>
<P>
   So, is the Internet an alienating medium that turns would-be
lovers into loners? It's quite the opposite, Barnett, 36, says.
``It's ideal for niche marketing,'' he explains. ``You have to say,
`I like to snowboard in my underwear' if that's who you are.' ''
Precisely.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Barnett announced on the site that he is ``seeing
a very wonderful lady named Amy exclusively.'' She's a stewardess
from Dallas who is said to resemble the actress Denise Richards.
``I want people to realize that they were wrong if they said this
was crazy,'' Barnett said from his St. Louis office. ``They were
wrong. Look what I got.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ryder, 34, has another story. Since launching his site, he
has been inundated with requests from the media but hasn't exactly
been flooded with potential dates. The site is attracting a fair
amount of traffic. But Ryder confesses that most of the visitors
are coming from a pornography site that is listing his Web address
in its joke section. ``I feel like a schmuck,'' he says. ``People
are laughing at me. I'm taking my embarrassment threshold to new
levels.'' If it doesn't work out, he figures he'll try an
introduction service in Russia. Seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Ryder put all his stock in the Internet appeal _ both literally
and figuratively. ``The campaign is a failure,'' he says.
``Something must be wrong.'' Maybe it's the reward. He bought a
chunk of stock in Sedona, which hasn't exactly made him a killing.
It was trading on the NASDAQ at $3 3/4 a share last week; if the
stock stays flat, the reward remains $25,000. But if it goes up to
$25 a share, the award becomes $50,000; if it hits $50, the reward
jumps to $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   What do the folks at the Securities and Exchange Commission
think of this offer? ``We don't do family law,'' says spokesman
John Heine. ``But a good wife is priceless.''
</P>
<P>
   The offer could be subject to federal and state security
regulations, says Northeastern University law professor Hope Lewis,
since it links another interest to the performance of a stock. But
it's unlikely anyone would ever investigate this bizarre offer,
Lewis adds.
</P>
<P>
   As for the folks at Sedona, they would like to keep a cool
distance from Ryder. ``He just happens to be a shareholder, and we
don't want to meddle in this guy's personal dreams,'' says Mike
Mulshine, Sedona's director of investor relations. ``But God,
what's a guy to do to meet a nice girl? It's so hard for young
people to meet these days.''
</P>
<P>
   If you believe the Stanford report, maybe that's because they're
spending too much time online. But according to our exhaustive
study, some half of the aspiring grooms who offer rewards online
end up happily ever after. Why is the other half so unsuccessful?
Our theory: He's only accepting handwritten letters delivered via
snail mail. Barnett was perfectly happy to accept e-mail
solicitations (and as he says, ``Look what I got.'') So ignore the
hysteria over hug-free e-mail. The Stanford researchers don't have
a clue: They went looking for loners in all the wrong places.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send e-mail to p(long dash)hartigan(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
