<HEADER>
A7159 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-SINDEN2-BO     02-24 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-SINDEN2-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINDEN, TEAM AGREE WITH SUSPENSION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Corrects Sinden's whereabouts when the decision to suspend waas
made by the NHL.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta _ Bruins president and general manager Harry
Sinden said the team supports the NHL's decision to suspend
defenseman Marty McSorley for the remainder of the regular season
and the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Sinden was on his way to New York when the leage decided on the
supplementary discipline of the Monday night incident in Vancouver
involving McSorley and Donald Brashear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever suspension the league handed out, the Bruins and
myself were prepared to accept as the fair one and the right one,''
said Sinden. ``The disciplinary procedure of the NHL is something a
person like myself and (Edmonton GM) Glen Sather have had a hand in
putting into place. We think it's a very good one, and we think
it's administered by very competent people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team in no way finds this excusable and does not condone
these kinds of actions from any player and never has. We've
witnessed over the years a number of them both as victims and as
the guilty party in some instances and never have condoned any of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   McSorley's future in Boston remains a question mark. He is
signed through the year and will become an unrestricted free agent
July 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marty and I are going to talk,'' said Sinden. ``Any answer I
make to that right now is something that would be construed, if I
said yes or no, one way or another, and it shouldn't be because
Marty and I are going to sit down and talk. I will say this: he's a
Bruin, he's part of our family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't find this type of action excusable. On the other
hand, we will lend our support now that he's been punished and
supplementary discipline has been handed down. We will lend our
support to Marty as a Bruin and as a member of our team and do what
we can to help him from this day forward. I'm not quite sure what
that will entail.''
</P>
<P>
   What it might entail, Sinden said, is an effort to show that
this was an act that was out of character for McSorley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, he's very remorseful at this point,'' said Sinden,
who spoke with McSorley Wednesday. ``He feels ashamed. He's full of
shame. He's under a great deal of stress right now. He's shaken by
the whole thing. If we can help show that this wasn't him, this act
was not Marty. I know we only had him on the team for a short
period of time, but I talked to a number of people about Marty
McSorley before I signed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got some wonderful opinions about him. I've talked to some
people in the last couple of days who know him much better than I
do, and they all confirmed to me that this was out of character for
him. He's been 17 years in the league; he's been a policeman for
every team he's been with. It's a role that's acceptable to the
fans, by the league, by each team. He's found himself in trouble
from time to time, but I think over 17 years, he's done very, very
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden has been answering questions all year about the
controversies surrounding his club. There were the holdouts, the
injuries, the coaching controversy, the Joe Murphy debacle, and now
this.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been the worst year, I'll tell you that,'' said Sinden.
``It hasn't been pleasant. This is just another thing on top of it
all. It's something we're trying to get straightened out now.
Frankly, that's a bigger concern, the way this team plays, than
anything for me at the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   All of McSorley's teammates, for the most part, believed that
McSorley was going to be banished for the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people assumed that's what it was going to
be,'' said goalie Byron Dafoe, who is in Boston awaiting word on
the extent of his knee injury. ``Obviously it's a pretty hefty
suspension, the most ever. I feel bad for Marty because I think
genuinely deep down he really didn't mean to do what he did. Hockey
is a reaction, spontanaeity type of sport, and I think he showed
true remorse in his statements right after. I think the suspension
is severe and probably fair. I feel bad for Marty because he's
really not that type of person.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe said the incident was painful for everybody, and he said
he thought there was some bad luck involved as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everything went wrong in the way that it unfolded for
Marty,'' said Dafoe. ``He could've maybe caught his cheek and not
his temple, if Brashear had fallen on his side or forward and
hadn't landed on his head. Everything went the wrong way for Marty
there. It made it look that much worse and thus the punishment has
to be that much worse. Thank God it caught his helmet and not
directly on his temple because there could've been some severe
damage.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe and Anson Carter, who were injured in Monday night's game,
both underwent MRIs Wednesday. Dafoe's right knee is injured, while
Carter has a shoulder problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
