<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7160 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-DRUGS-$ADV26-C     02-24 1701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DRUGS-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DESPITE GAINS IN DRUG WAR, MEXICO UNDER PRESSURE TO CATCH THE
COUNTRY'S MOST NOTORIOUS DRUG KINGPINS
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Feb. 26 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIJUANA, Mexico _ One rumor puts the Arellano Felix brothers in
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Supposedly they dress as handsomely as Versace models and blend
in among stars thanks to the millions they make as Mexico's most
successful drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   But other reports, especially from U.S. law enforcement agents,
say several of the six brothers are probably in this industrial
border city, where they are believed to enjoy the protection of
police that are too afraid, too bought off or too incompetent to
capture them.
</P>
<P>
   As Washington prepares for its annual anti-drug
``certification'' ritual next month, Mexico's continuing failure to
catch the Arellano brothers or other top fugitive drug kingpins is
likely to surface as a sore point.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday(March 1), the White House will release a list of
countries the Clinton administration believes should be
``certified'' as reliable drug-fighting partners of the United
States. Those rejected by the White House or by Congress, which
reviews the list, face trade sanctions or the loss of U.S. economic
aid.
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, Mexico _ whose booming exports have made it
the second largest U.S. trading partner _ is cooperating better
than ever in the past with U.S. officials and has upped its
seizures of drugs in the last year. It will probably be certified.
But Mexico's ``unwillingness or its inability'' to capture major
traffickers remains a serious shortcoming and a poor reflection on
its police forces, said one U.S. official familiar with Mexican law
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mexican police are one of the worst if not the worst
police force in Latin America,'' said the frustrated U.S. official,
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   White House anti-drug czar Gen. Barry McCaffrey, who generally
believes Mexico is committed to the drug war, also said ``the
single most overwhelming threat coming out of the drug
organizations is corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want a central demonstration of the problem,'' he said
in a recent interview in Mexico City, ``it's in Tijuana.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To what extent are state police and local police in Tijuana
able to confront those huge criminal organizations? The answer is
pretty pathetic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Constantine, who last year retired as director of the
U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration, has often publicly hammered
Mexico, claiming that authorities here have continually blown
opportunities to arrest the Arellanos and other kingpins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really disagree with these criticisms,'' said Eduardo
Ibarrola, the Mexican Deputy Attorney General for International
Affairs. As for corruption, he said, ``we are working really hard
at cleaning house.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the Arellanos appear to have vanished, Ibarrola
argued, shows that the traffickers fear the heat has been turned up
against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some years ago the Arellanos were openly living and traveling
everywhere, and they were not really hiding,'' Ibarrola said. ``As
a result of (our) investigations, they are running ... Now they are
really scared that we are going to arrest them, one way or another,
sooner or later.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arellano family, which inherited its smuggling ring from a
second cousin who was arrested in 1989, has been linked to scores
of killings of police, prosecutors and others in this area. One of
the brothers, Francisco, has been imprisoned in connection with the
1993 killing of the Roman Catholic cardinal of Guadalajara. The
cardinal died in a hail of bullets at an airport in an attack
reportedly intended for rival traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Arellano, the brother who allegedly runs the gang's
execution squads, has been on the FBI's 10-Most-Wanted list since
1997. A U.S. federal indictment awaits him and other members of the
gang in Southern California _ if only Mexican police could catch
them.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an increase in drug seizures by Mexican authorities last
year and a program to train a new federal anti-drug force, between
55 and 60 percent of the cocaine that enters the United States is
still shipped through Tijuana and other border cities in Mexico.
Much of the marijuana, heroin and methamphetamine smuggled into the
United States are of Mexican origin.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico allocated more than $500 million of its own money last
year for eradication of poppy and marijuana fields, and
interdiction of drugs. Yet, U.S. officials generally say they've
seen no significant drop in the quantities of narcotics smuggled
via the Southwest border.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called overwhelming the border,'' said San Diego U.S.
Customs Service chief investigator Ed Logan, describing
traffickers' strategy. For every seizure customs agents make,
perhaps a dozen make it across.
</P>
<P>
   Last week(Feb. 18), agents detained a well-dressed Mexican
couple who were driving a new sport-utility vehicle into San Diego
from Tijuana that was packed with an estimated $1 million worth of
cocaine hidden in a false compartment.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, the group with the greatest success at interdiction
last year was the Mexican Navy, which seized more than 25 tons of
cocaine from ships sailing from South America up to the Mexican
Pacific coast. The Navy's seizures accounted for more than 67
percent of all the cocaine intercepted last year in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has ``an adolescent pre-occupation with nationalism''
that makes its law enforcement authorities sensitive about the
appearance that Americans are telling them what to do, a U.S.
official also said. But over the last year, Mexico's willingness to
share information has ``markedly improved,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, however, Mexico suffered an embarrassing setback in
image when it failed to arrest a state governor after implicating
him in drug trafficking. Mario Villanueva, the former governor of
Quintana Roo state, vanished just days before he was going to be
arrested. He allegedly used his office and state police to assist a
cocaine cartel based in Cancun and the northern border city of
Juarez.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptical Mexicans viewed Villanueva's escape as a sign
government agents were bribed or told to let him go. McCaffrey and
some other U.S. officials are more charitable. They say they either
don't know what happened or believe Mexican authorities honestly
couldn't keep tabs on Villanueva's private airplane.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico's Baja California state, where Tijuana is located,
numerous state and federal police have long been suspected of
consorting with the Arellanos. In 1997, a former state attorney
general was suspected of assisting in the execution of a
Tijuana-based federal police commander. At least a dozen
prosecutors have died in assassinations since the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy State Attorney General Guadalupe Olga Jimenez said
Tijuana is currently in the throes of a major turf war over drug
trafficking that's resulted in at least 64 violent gangland-style
killings since January.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't know if the war is directly linked to the Arellano
family; investigating organized crime and smuggling is the
responsibility of Mexico's federal police, she said. But the
federal police, she said, haven't asked her to turn over any of the
64 drug-related homicides she's investigating.
</P>
<P>
   Jimenez admitted corruption still haunts the state police. Last
year, 70 out of about 400 officers were fired for corruption or
other offenses. She said training has improved, however, along with
safeguards to prevent her officers from committing crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my officers are armed with guns that are inventoried,''
she said. ``If one of those arms is used in a homicide we will know
it was committed by someone in this office.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico is pinning much of its strategy against traffickers in
Tijuana and other border cities on a new 1,500-strong anti-drug
squad under the auspices of the federal Attorney General's office.
About 11,000 newly constituted Federal Preventive Police officers
are also assigned to fight organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey praised Mexico for adopting a system of vetting for
the special squads, but he said the groups are still ``anemic.''
</P>
<P>
   The recruits are very young and receive only about a month's
special training. When you're starting a police force, he said, it
takes 5 to 15 years before people are skilled enough to even
qualify as sergeants.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you need to do is mentor them,'' said U.S. Customs
Commissioner Ed Kelly, a former New York police commissioner who
directed police reform in Haiti. ``You're not going to change
people with a one-month training course.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly was in San Diego recently observing his agents make
seizures of drugs coming across the Mexican border.
</P>
<P>
   In San Diego, U.S. DEA agents are training members of Mexico's
special squads stationed in Baja California. And both sides are
engaging in daily bilateral discussions about how to catch
traffickers, according to law enforcement sources familiar with the
situation here.
</P>
<P>
   But an atmosphere of distrust still prevails. As one U.S.
official on the border put it, ``We have the experience to know
whom we can work with and whom we should stay away from.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't do our job without (the Mexican police),'' the
official, who also spoke on condition of anonymity, added. ``It is
frustrating at times. The work is not always good. But what's our
other option?''
</P>
<P>
   Jesus Blancornelas, a Tijuana newspaper editor who the Arellanos
nearly killed in an alleged assassination attempt two years ago,
doesn't think much of the new federal police yet. Blancornelas,
editor of Zeta, is known for his coverage of trafficking and
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no investigations going on,'' Blancornelas alleged.
``The only thing going on is they stop cars and check for drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two choices for the police,'' he added. ``You take
good money from the traffickers, much more than you get as a cop.
Or you simply leave the traffickers alone so you stay out of
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
