<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7161 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-BRITAIN-MUMBOYS-$ADV2     02-24 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-MUMBOYS-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MUMMY MAKES THEM DO IT: MORE BRITISH MEN STAYING, ENJOYING
COMFORTS OF HOME
 &HT;    (900&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With chart information attached at end of story.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Feb. 26 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.2000 Special to the Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ To many, Cary Grant was the embodiment of the British
male. Even with that accent, he always betrayed a roughness beneath
his suavity. It's hard to imagine him _ or the likes of Agent 007 _
living at home with mum.
</P>
<P>
   But it appears that's what Britain has become: a nation of
Mummy's Boys.
</P>
<P>
   A new Social Trends report, compiled by Britain's Office of
National Statistics, reveals that one in three British men between
the ages of 20 and 35 still live at home with their parents. And
more than half of those between the ages of 20 and 24 do so.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, not even one-fourth of all British males aged
20 to 35 still enjoyed the cushy life at their parent's place.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, according to the U.S. Census Bureau, 15 percent
of American men aged 25 to 34 still live at home, while 59 percent
of men aged 18 to 24 do so.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers here blame the British phenomenon on a number of
factors.
</P>
<P>
   For one, British adults are waiting longer to tie the knot: Over
the last 10 years, the average age at which men get married has
climbed from 26 to nearly 30; for women it has gone from 24 to
nearly 27.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, a growing number of British adults are forced
to remain at home, having been made economic refugees by low-paying
entry-level jobs and the skyrocketing costs of housing.
</P>
<P>
   The average price of a house in London, for example, now tops
$244,000.
</P>
<P>
   Still, though, the trend doesn't seem to extend to females here.
According to the study, twice as many men as women stayed at home.
Only one in six women are still with their parents by the time they
reach 35.
</P>
<P>
   This begs the question: Is something beyond financial
constraints tying men to the parental hearth?
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it appears to be mummy herself.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Heffernan, for example, admits he's a mummy's boy, but
he's far from ashamed. What's more, the 27-year-old part-time
telemarketer has no immediate plans to leave his parent's spacious
home in suburban London.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Mummy) gets me up in the morning, she makes all my dinners,
she runs the bath, makes my bed usually, irons all my clothes,
washes my clothes,'' he said. ``She loves it. It wouldn't be the
same if I wasn't here. She wouldn't know what to do with herself.''
</P>
<P>
   The only downside? Keeping girlfriends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be difficult if you go out to a club and meet girls.
I've brought a couple of girls back before and had to kick them out
early in the morning, and usually it doesn't go over too well,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Heffernan does hope to save money while at home so that _
eventually _ he can buy his own house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if I move out at 35, I've hopefully got 40 years left to
live on my own,'' he reasoned.
</P>
<P>
   In general, researchers say that girls usually enjoy less
freedom than boys while living at home, and so are more anxious to
fly the coop, even if they aren't ready to marry. Two-thirds of
women rent before buying, but only one-third of men do.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, these researchers say women mature at a faster
pace than young men. Many women in their twenties are at their best
and already can be startlingly self-confident. Men, though, may not
really begin to grow up until they reach about 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young women in Britain are becoming more financially
independent, and just more independent in general,'' said Carol
Summerfield, a co-editor of the Social Trends report. ``And young
women are the ones who are more likely to move out of their old
homes and in with an older partner.''
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists are also keen to point out that there's less
pressure on British males these days to be macho.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years ago, the heroes of the day were Clint Eastwood
and (Sean Connery's) James Bond, who would never have been seen
running home to mum for a cup of tea,'' said Dr. Mick Cooper, a
psychologist at Brighton University. ``Now there is no shame
attached to being at home.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the prospect of a child living their adult years in
the comfort of their old home makes some parents shudder with fear.
But many are overjoyed at the thought of keeping their offspring at
Chez Mum and Dad.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Kenny, a columnist for The Daily Telegraph, said this
return to the nest should be viewed as a positive signal of the end
of the generation wars.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in their twenties and thirties now get along a lot
better with people in their forties, fifties and sixties,'' said
Kenny, whose own sons, in their twenties, still live at home.
</P>
<P>
   She said it's wonderfully useful to have her sons around to do
things like deconstruct ``The Simpsons'' or help research something
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, Sue Arnold, mother of three young boys, said
she can't imagine her sons living with her at 30.
</P>
<P>
   She said there should be a distinct winding down of comforts in
all homes _ no more ironing, no more sticky toffee pudding and,
above all else, regular rent payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``That should flush the little darlings out,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Britain, of course, isn't the only country to have witnessed a
rise in the number of adults remaining in their parent's homes.
</P>
<P>
   In Canada, the number of adults still living with parents has
grown considerably over the past 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   And, in some countries, it has always been considered normal for
men to stay at home. In Italy, nearly half of all men live at home
until they marry. But this is a place in which men who do not live
at home generally call their mothers, on average, three times a
week, married or not.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it may be some time before such an arrangement becomes
socially acceptable in the United States, where living at home is
often synonymous with wimpishness.
</P>
<P>
   Just consider last year's hit by the Atlanta-based female
singing trio TLC, which even coined a new term for unsuitable
suitors who still live at home with their mothers _ scrubs.
</P>
<P>
   --------------------------------------------------------------------
----
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE'S STAY-AT-HOME ADULTS
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Europe, the number of young adults who choose to
remain at home with their parents has been growing for years.
</P>
<P>
   Percentage of young people age 25-29 living at home with parents
in 1987 versus 1997:
</P>
<P>
   Belgium....................19 percent, 24 percent
</P>
<P>
   Greece.......................39 percent, 49 percent
</P>
<P>
   Spain..........................49 percent, 59 percent
</P>
<P>
   Italy............................39 percent, 56 percent
</P>
<P>
   Portugal....................39 percent, 49 percent
</P>
<P>
   France........................14 percent, 17 percent
</P>
<P>
   United Kingdom......15 percent, 17 percent
</P>
<P>
   Source: Eurostat, the Statistical Office for the European
Communities.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
