<SLUG> BC-TV-GRAMMYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL SHINY SURFACES, LITTLE SUBSTANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite all the flash, the ``42nd Annual Grammy Awards'' was an
undistinguished, unemotional three-hour telecast, with a small
handful of highlights. It ended up looking too much like all the
other televised music awards shows _ and there are very many of
them these days. Regardless of the Santana sweep, wins by Sting,
and a tribute to Elton John, the CBS show was crammed with
predictable new-guard glitz and numbingly oversized production
numbers. Santana may have been the biggest winner since Michael
Jackson in 1984, but his presence on the telecast was strangely
minimal.
</P>
<P>
   Rosie O'Donnell, host for the second year in a row, didn't help
matters. Her opening monologue was flat, second-rate standup, and
she appeared to be going through the motions all evening. About the
53-year-old Cher, she quipped, ``I don't want to say she's old, but
she's calling everybody Sonny.'' Thud. About Sean ``Puffy'' Combs,
recently arrested for weapon possession, she joked that he plans to
star on Broadway in ``Puffy Get Your Gun.'' Thud. And her faux
medley of Diana Ross songs included ``Touch Me in the Airport.''
Splat. At one point, she said, ``I could go on all night. Don't
make me.'' As if we had a choice.
</P>
<P>
   With a few exceptions, the song performances were big and
electrified with an excess of blinking lights and geometric
choreography. Ricky Martin _ or, as O'Donnell dubbed him, ``Ricky
shake-your-bon-bon Martin'' _ shook his bon-bon with special
fervor, proving once and for all that he does have bionic hips.
Martin was out to raise the bar on himself, after he captured
America's eye at last year's Grammy ceremony with a blazing version
of ``Livin' La Vida Loca.'' His performance of ``Maria'' was fiery,
literally, beginning with a giant shadow of the singer and ending,
amid a Cirque de Soleil-like stage ensemble inside a ring of real
fire. What will he do next year? Hard to believe it has been only
12 months since Martin, now music media wallpaper, hit the big
time.
</P>
<P>
   Britney Spears, another performer who needs to take a publicity
break, sang a medley that took her from some kind of massive
butterfly-like plumage to a stage filled with funkified robots.
Don't ask. It was as elaborate as it was forgettable. Kid Rock
burst into ``Bawitdaba'' and then took the energy higher with Grand
Funk Railroad's ``An American Band.'' The lights twirled
ferociously, but not as ferociously as they had during Will Smith's
fog-swamped show-opening number. Home viewers may have been
reaching for their sunglasses. While the Dixie Chicks avoided
pumped-up stage tricks to sing about domestic abuse in ``Goodbye
Earl,'' they showed bad taste by pumping the video for the song to
the TV audience.
</P>
<P>
   The better moments of the night included Chucho Valdez and
Ibrahim Ferrer, who came before Martin in a Latin ``jukebox'' set,
and the pairing of Elton John and the Backstreet Boys for a
high-energy ``Philadelphia Freedom.'' Alas, John, who was
introduced by Billy Joel, never got the chance to share his
feelings about the honor, robbing the night of one of its few
possible emotional moments.
</P>
<P>
   The telecast's costuming highlight came very early on. You could
hear the collective jaw hit the floor when Jennifer Lopez came out
to present an award with David Duchovny. As if to show she is
unrepentant about her involvement in the gun incident with Puff
Daddy, Lopez wore a sheer aqua dress with cleavage that plunged at
least six inches south of her belly button. What O'Donnell wryly
called ``a classy little understated number'' looked like a
politely wrapped gift ripped very wide open.
</P>
<P>
   The night's giant kid award went not to Kid Rock, but to Macy
Gray, the newly hot R&AMP;B singer. Gray, wearing a bright blue
longcoat with fur shoulders and wrists, towered above everyone she
stood beside, including Phil Collins and Andy Williams, with whom
she presented the Song of the Year prize. In her little-girl voice,
Gray stumbled over her script, and you have to wonder what she
might have said if she'd won for one of her two nominations. Gray
lost the best new artist slot to Christina Aguilera, she of the
most excellent posture, who was a bright vision of silver and blond
in a tight Versace dress that conjured thoughts of a human disco
ball. ``Oh my God, you guys,'' she gushed. ``I seriously do not
have a speech prepared whatsoever. I'm shaking right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The preshow festivities were unnervingly uneventful. On a garish
red carpet, which was greenhoused in plastic against rain, Ellen
DeGeneres worked hard to create a sense of buzz, hamming it up like
Carol Burnett, girl reporter.
</P>
<P>
   She mopped the carpet clean when the coverage started. She
putted a golfball into the waiting open mouth of Moby, who laid his
golf-ball-shaped head on the ground. She brought out a life-size
poster of Ricky Martin, then asked the unerringly modest sensation
to stand beside himself. And she eagerly approached handsome pop
stars like Sting, Martin, Clint Black, and Marc Anthony with an
empty cup, noting, ``Melissa scored with David Crosby. You never
know who I'm gonna meet here.'' And _ Joan Rivers take note _
DeGeneres, who hosted the Grammys twice in recent years, was
knowledgeable enough to ask questions without any inadvertent
insults.
</P>
<P>
   She was appropriately deadpan in the face of Aguilera and,
later, Spears, who arrived in a poufy white wrap that was perfectly
Zsa Zsa-esque.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
