<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW MUCH POWER DO WE NEED? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They say it's impossible to have too much computing power, but
sometimes I wonder.
</P>
<P>
   At the office, I use an Apple iMac and a Pentium II; at home, an
AMD K6-III and a couple of old Intel Pentiums running Linux. I
can't recall the last time I needed more horsepower than these
machines provide. That's partly because I spend so much time on the
Internet, where the sheer speed of the computer makes little
difference.
</P>
<P>
   So despite a healthy gadget-freak lust for more potent hardware,
I can't help wondering what on earth I'd do with a one-gigahertz
computer. They'll be hitting store shelves by autumn for as little
as $2,000. Their muscular Intel and AMD chips will put my
400-megahertz home machine to shame. Yet this won't mean much to
the average consumer running workaday software.
</P>
<P>
   You can already buy a one-gig machine today for $2,500, complete
with a handy built-in refrigerator to keep the processor chip from
melting. KryoTech Inc.'s Super-G machine links its small
refrigeration unit to a cooling interface bolted onto an AMD Athlon
processor. By dropping the chip temperature to minus-40 degrees,
Super-G dramatically boosts the chip's speed without roasting it.
</P>
<P>
   The trick is to achieve such speed at room temperature. Intel
and AMD are doing it partly by making the ultra-tiny transistors on
each chip out of copper, instead of the traditional chipmaker's
friend, aluminum. Copper is harder to work with, but makes a much
better electrical conductor.
</P>
<P>
   Another gimmick involves making everything on the chip smaller.
The previous generation of processors contained circuits no bigger
than a quarter of a micron. That's already 400 times thinner than
the average hair. By making the circuits a wee bit smaller _ .18
micron _ you get more circuits on board, so the chip can do more
work. At the same time, the chip becomes physically smaller, and
that reduced size also makes it run faster _ the electrons pulsing
through the chip don't have to travel as far.
</P>
<P>
   So you switch to copper and shrink the circuits and get your
chip up to one-gigahertz speed. And then you go and spoil it all by
plugging in the same old memory chips. The processor can only work
as fast as it can scoop up information from the memory. As
processors get faster, memory hasn't been keeping pace.
</P>
<P>
   The ``bus'' that carries data between the processor and the
memory runs at 100 million cycles a second on most recent
computers, with some going up to 133 megahertz. Memory makers are
working on designs that'll boost that considerably.
</P>
<P>
   Late this year, Intel is rolling out a chip codenamed
Willamette, which will start at one gigahertz with a later bump to
1.5 gigahertz. This chip will be designed to work with a new kind
of memory chip called Rambus, which can serve up data to the chip
at 400 million cycles per second. The result, in theory, should be
dramatically faster performance.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's slower Pentium III chips can also use Rambus, and it's
starting to appear in a few systems. But the stuff costs several
times more than traditional memory chips and requires a new type of
motherboard to boot. So you'll mainly find it on network server
computers rather than home desktops.
</P>
<P>
   We haven't even mentioned the forthcoming Intel Itanium
processor, but you'll never try this one at home. It's got a
fundamentally different design from the Pentium series and is
mainly intended to compete against Sun Microsystems Inc.'s
UltraSPARC line of high-end corporate systems.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the forthcoming Pentiums and Athlons will offer power far
beyond what's needed to run today's most common computer tasks. But
that's only because we've come to expect so little of our
computers.
</P>
<P>
   We still have to train them to do accurate speech recognition,
and even then, computers often don't get it right. They still don't
let us do broadcast-grade video over the Internet, or 3-D graphics
that are truly lifelike. We've grown tolerant of such limitations,
because our hardware runs fast enough to make our mediocre software
look good.
</P>
<P>
   The still-faster hardware due out this year will no doubt
inspire the creation of better, more innovative software,
eventually. Until then, what good is a gigahertz?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(You can contact Hiawatha Bray at bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
