<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN IT COMES TO HOGS, IT'S ALMOST ALL HARLEY CLONES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's cold, it's windy, and indoors at Rockingham Park in Salem,
N.H., the milling masses are dreaming of spring and being outside
in a warm wind. Snow covers the racetrack, and horseflesh has given
way to the iron horse.
</P>
<P>
   I wander the exhibits at the New England Motorcycle Expo and ask
myself, ``Can't anybody come up with something original?''
</P>
<P>
   I'm a denizen of motorcycle shows. I know that at least half of
what I see will be booths selling helmets, cotton skullcaps, flamed
clothing, leather hats, chaps, gloves, jackets, and hundreds of
varieties of T-shirts. It makes me wonder if they really own a bike
or just the shirt.
</P>
<P>
   I know that no belly is too big, no pair of leather pants too
tight. I watch the line at Heidi Jo's Beef Jerky stand and note
that passing tough-guy bikers are too shy to make eye contact with
Jennifer Lavoie, Playboy Playmate, who lounges in a leopard-skin
bikini.
</P>
<P>
   But today, for that first time, I blaspheme: Who will have an
original thought?
</P>
<P>
   I've only ridden Harleys (and one 1958 Triumph), but I've never
been a Harley snob who looks down on those who ride other (read
Japanese) motorcycles. Ride what you can afford, has been my motto.
Even in the Harley community there is a disgusting prejudice
against those who ride new Harleys (they almost always start, they
don't drip oil) on the part of those who ride old Harleys
(sometimes they start, they do drip oil). Never mind that if Harley
hadn't manufactured, and new riders hadn't stepped forward to buy,
the new Harley, there would be no Harley-Davidson today.
</P>
<P>
   So I see Harley, even as it evolves, sticking to its original
thought, improving on it, doing what a good company should.
</P>
<P>
   Then I wander through the Honda exhibit and note they've got the
motorcycle market covered: their own traditional high-r.p.m.
rockets; a nice lineup of four-wheelers; and, what's this? a
Valkyre _ pure rip-off of the classic Indian, and the Shadow _ pure
rip-off of the Harley.
</P>
<P>
   Beside them, Triumphs sit looking for identity: dirt bike?
cruiser? throwback to the old days? They're trying it all.
</P>
<P>
   And here are the Vulcans _ Nomad and Drifter _ fat-fendered and
looking all-Indian.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps as upsetting as any of them is the Kawasaki W650 (W
standing for We stole the idea): It's a Triumph clone, right down
to the rubber knee grips on the gas tank, the long, flat seat, the
winged flanges where exhaust meets cylinder.
</P>
<P>
   Can't somebody have an original thought?
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, I wasn't appalled by the insurgence of
knockoff motorcycles. Back then, I wrote, ``There's a new thunder
on the roads of motorcycling and it's being spit from the exhausts
of thousands of bikes manufactured every year that look just like
customized Harleys, may even have Harley engines and other
components in them, and are fueling an industry that is growing
rapidly in the Harley's shadow.''
</P>
<P>
   They called them clones, hybrids, and ``special construction''
motorcycles, and they arose because ``The Motor Company,'' as
Harley is known, created a demand that it could not supply. It was
fueled by the image of Harley riders as tough hombres on the road
to freedom who love being In The Wind, as a popular motorcycle
magazine is named, escaping the strictures of reaching middle age.
</P>
<P>
   Harley was moving from around 30,000 bikes sold each year in the
early 1980s, to reaching for 200,000 annual sales. Clones did not
seem like such a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   So we got clones from companies named Big Dog, California
Motorcycle Co., Castle Motorcycles, Confederate Motorcycles,
Illusion, American Eagle, American Image, Surgical Steeds, Titan,
Victory, and Iron Horse.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't know the trend would spread to established
manufacturers and original design would disappear.
</P>
<P>
   So as I wandered the Expo, I wondered how this happened even as
the market has become more diverse than ever. It used to be almost
strictly a guy thing _ women rode on the back of motorcycles. Now,
nearly 20 percent of new bike purchasers are women. At the Expo,
the guy wearing the T-shirt that read, ``When In Doubt . . . Knock
'Em Out'' stood in glaring contrast to the women bikers promoting
Alli's Rally 2000, for the Allison Burke Fund for The Floating
Hospital/New England Medical Center. Or Women on Wheels pushing
their 7th Annual Rally for Breast Cancer on June 4.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers have an emerging, diverse (aging boomers looking
to hang onto their youth, women, young riders looking for high-tech
thrills) market, yet they're going retro, ripping off ideas from
others. Keep doing it, they'll ride the wave into oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   Some are fine: Indian is trying to make a legitimate comeback.
So is Excelsior-Henderson with its Super X, though its V-Twin,
85-cubic-inch engine and its look smell like a Harley.
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to see somebody show up at one of these shows sticking
to their guns (BMW wasn't represented, and I suspect they would fit
this latter notion).
</P>
<P>
   Stick to their guns the way it looks like Ducati is doing. At
Eastern Cycles' exhibit, the Ducati sat looking low, explosive, and
distinctive. From the new models right back to the 250-cubic-inch
vintage Ducati of Johnny ``Holeshot'' Strehpfer.
</P>
<P>
   So I wandered on, pausing to admire Tony Deluca's 1962 Harley
XLCH Sportster, admire its classic tank and tiny solo seat.
</P>
<P>
   But then I ran smack into the Suzuki Intruder (Harley) and
Yamaha Road Star (Harley Dresser) and I was overwhelmed by the
thought once again: Won't somebody please have an original thought?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
