</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (f and s coding)  
 MIT SPORTS LAB SEEKS INNOVATION THROUGH R&AMP;D  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ The pitchers and catchers have reported to
Major League Baseball's spring training, and it is almost time for
one of longest-running issues in professional sports to be argued
all over again.
</P>
<P>
   When is a strike really a strike? When is a ball a ball?
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a problem for someone at MIT.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want to make too big a deal out of it, because I
know the phone's going to start ringing off of the hook _
especially with calls from the umpires' union,'' said Kim B. Blair,
director of MIT's new Laboratory for Sports Innovation. ``But the
technology for automatic strike zone detection, we think, is there.
We think we can do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there a market for it? Are the players going to like it?
Would the owners like it? That's what we need to find out,'' Blair
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Laboratory for Sports Innovation strives to be for the
sports industry what MIT's Lincoln Laboratory has been to the
energy and defense industries, what the Laboratory for Computer
Science is to high technology and the Media Lab is to television
and newspapers _ a center for the research and development of new
designs and concepts.
</P>
<P>
   The sports lab's goal is to cater to the $4.7 billion sporting
goods industry, to media companies that spend billions of dollars
annually to broadcast sports, and to fans who simply want to attend
some games.
</P>
<P>
   Among the new designs and concepts developed by the lab recently
are a new softball that can be hit just as far as an old one, but
that hurts less when it strikes a player, and a cyclist's training
system that provides a rider with real-time data to correct
aerodynamic positioning.
</P>
<P>
   The potential for research and design seems limitless. A gel
that's rubbed on the hands could obviate the need for rock and
mountain climbers to build up calluses. New designs could improve
shoes, rackets, bats, and other equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not a lot of R&AMP;D that goes on in the business,
generally,'' said Bob McGee, editor of Sporting Goods Intelligence,
an industry newsletter. ``Amid all of the concern about logistics
and meeting price points and that kind of stuff, it's one of the
areas that's being cut first, especially if you are not one of the
big players in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   And, observers say, even the big players often buy up smaller,
innovative companies or pay outsiders for their new product
designs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rawlings is the manufacturer of the radar ball, a baseball
that cannot be hit, but says how fast it is going when it strikes
the catcher's mitt,'' said Michael May, spokesman for the Sporting
Goods Manufacturers Association. ``It is based on computer chip
technology, and the design won the Product of the Year award at a
show in 1989. Rawlings manufacturers it, but it bought the design
from an an inventor somewhere in the Dakotas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like this program at MIT would fit right into what
is a normal pattern in the industry,'' May said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Massachusetts Institute of Technology has long
participated in research on sports and in the development of sports
products. Testing the impact of the new press box and 600 Club on
the production of home runs at Fenway Park several years ago and
developing sweet spots and power zones for more than 2,000
commercial tennis rackets are just two of many examples.
</P>
<P>
   But Blair and others at MIT saw a need to bring all of the work
under one roof, especially in light of the consolidation of the
aeronautics industry after the Cold War. ``With peace breaking out
everywhere, in aerospace there was some concern about, gee, what
else is this department going to do?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like a number of engineers and designers, Blair, who specialized
in aeronautics at Purdue University, turned to sports.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the Laboratory for Sports Innovation, which was
established in August, is to build up a budget of $2 million to $3
million over the next three years to finance the research and
development, with much of the money coming from companies that will
turn to MIT for its expertise.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first such sports development project at any US
university, Blair said. It competes internationally with only the
University of Sheffield and Cambridge University in Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, students who have begun to sign up for courses at the
lab are presented with an intriguing educational experience, Blair
said. Part of the attraction is that in the aeronautics and
aerospace industries, for example, product and concept development
often take two decades and the labor of hundreds if not thousands
of engineers, he said. In the sports industry, designs can be
completed in a year or two by someone working alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports involves relatively familiar products and easily
grasped concepts,'' Blair said. ``Students are familiar with a
shoe, a climbing harness, a tennis racket. It's something they can
get their hands on. They understand how it works and how it feels,
and that is a big leg up in learning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
