<HEADER>
A7170 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      02-24 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CULT ICON IS DRIVEN TO PROVIDE MAINSTREAM COMFORT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In one of my favorite Bill Mauldin cartoons from World War II, a
Jeep is sprawled in the mud, a front wheel snapped flat like a
broken leg. A GI, head turned away and hand over his eyes, reaches
back and puts a pistol to the Jeep's hood, his heart aching as he
puts a trusted companion out of misery. I expect to see a tear
trickle from a headlight.
</P>
<P>
   Born of war's necessity, evolved into a symbol of rugged fun,
the classic Jeep is a true American icon. It was developed after
the Army asked American companies to come up with a simple rig:
front- and rear-drive axles, a two-speed tranny, narrow track,
short wheelbase, and folding windshield.
</P>
<P>
   Bantam delivered first, with the BRC, called the Blitz Buggy.
Ford followed with the Pygmy and Willys-Overland with the Quad.
From these came the Jeep we know today: tough motor, rectangular
and angular body, flat profile, stamped grille.
</P>
<P>
   It is a look that endures right down into the 2000 Wrangler
Sahara. It's still got the exterior hood latches, the up-and-over
lip at the rocker panels, the jailbars grille. Jeep has even
returned to round headlights after dabbling with rectangular.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, it's far more comfortable _ wide, firm seats with high
backs _ than in the past. But it also retains a rugged feel with
padded rollbars, seats covered to shed water like good rain gear, a
vertical dash that appears a bulwark of security (and houses
standard dual airbags), and that familiar view through a flat
windshield over the classic rectangular hood.
</P>
<P>
   The controls are simple and convenient, mostly set in a
rectangular box at center dash. There's a hefty use of plastic on
dash and controls but it's used well and doesn't feel cheap or
lightweight. Storage is minimal in the doors, but ample in a big,
deep center console and secure in Velcro-flap pockets on the backs
of the front seats.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-'90s, Jeep knew it had to update in the wake of a
slew of competitors who were taking enthusiasts off road in greater
comfort. It is one thing to be a cult icon, another to be outdated.
Perhaps the best change was eliminating leaf springs and replacing
them with coils to supplement shocks.
</P>
<P>
   ABS is an option and my advice there is: Opt.
</P>
<P>
   The Sahara I drove came with an 4.0-liter, inline-6 engine with
cast iron block and cast iron head. It had plenty of power for
highway cruising at 70 and higher and off road in snow seemed to
draw from a bottomless pit of torque. Pushed hard off road and
driven at commuter speeds, however, it got only about 15 miles per
gallon.
</P>
<P>
   On the highway the engine was a bit loud and there was a steady
wind noise from just above the windshield. Its agility moving in
and out of traffic was OK, but it's not meant for weaving like that
anyway. On rough roads, its short wheelbase let it hop, skip, and
jump a bit (still classic Jeep). Off road, it doesn't so much bull
its way through challenging terrain so much as scratch and claw.
</P>
<P>
   The three-speed automatic was prone to abrupt shifts that I did
not like and made me wish I had a test model with the five-speed
manual.
</P>
<P>
   But, hey, idiosyncracies are what make the Jeep the Jeep, and if
you love it, you live with them.
</P>
<P>
   Nice touches
</P>
<P>
   --The toggle switch control that distributes sound to four
speakers, front to rear, side to side.
</P>
<P>
   --The heater. Heats up fast. Heats up hot. Great on those
sunrise fetch-the-newspaper runs.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyances
</P>
<P>
   --A disconcerting blind spot in the driver's outside mirror.
</P>
<P>
   --The parking brake, which was a pain to get completely off.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Base price: $14,430 &QL; 
Price as tested: $20,345 &QL; 
Horsepower 181 /Torque: 181/222 lb .-ft. &QL; 
Wheelbase/Overall length: 93.4 inches/152.0 inches &QL; 
Width/Height: 66.7 inches/69.4inches &QL; 
Curb weight: 3257 lbs. &QL; 
Seating: 4 passengers &QL; 
SOURCE: Manufacturer &QL;
</P>
