<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7174 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-GAY-MARRIAGE-HNS &LR;      02-24 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-MARRIAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HOMOSEXUAL SON TAKES ON FATHER'S ANTI-GAY INITIATIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (ATTN: Calif., Md.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CAROL NESS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ David Knight thinks his father, state Sen. Pete
Knight, is wrong about gay marriage, wrong about gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   But he agrees with his dad about one thing: ``The big issue is,
he feels (my homosexuality is) a private matter. I could never get
the point across that he's exactly right,'' David Knight said in
his second public statement in opposition to Proposition 22.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative, which will appear on the March 7 ballot, was
sponsored by Knight, a Republican from Palmdale, and seeks to
affirm that California will not recognize marriages between
same-sex couples.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a private matter, and what he's attempting to do is
single out a group that has private, personal relationships. I wish
he understood that, but he doesn't,'' David Knight said Wednesday
in a telephone interview from Baltimore, where he lives with his
partner of six years, Joe Lazarro.
</P>
<P>
   Knight, 38, is a reluctant campaigner for gay rights. But he is
angry at his father for shutting him out since David told him he
was gay four years ago, and for pushing to reinforce California
laws against same-sex marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Knight, 70, tried three times to get the state Legislature
to pass an anti-gay-marriage bill before going directly to the
voters.
</P>
<P>
   David Knight's tone was softer than in the column he wrote last
year for the Los Angeles Times. In the column, he called his
father's initiative a ``blind, uncaring, uninformed, knee-jerk
reaction to a subject about which he knows nothing but which serves
his political career.''
</P>
<P>
   David Knight had followed in his father's footsteps in the
military, flew F-16s like his dad and basked in his father's pride
until the day in 1996 when he came out as gay. Then, everything
changed.
</P>
<P>
   He has seen his father only once since then, he said. Their
relationship is ``extremely strained and it hasn't been the same
since.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his father has no concept of his life as a Baltimore
furniture maker and domestic partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We renovated a house, we both work every day. It's pretty
boring, actually,'' he said. ``We have a very good life with a lot
of very good dear friends and it's very nice.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Knight said he has resisted past efforts to get him
involved in lobbying his father over gay rights issues. He decided
to speak out against Proposition 22 because ``I feel very strongly
about it. I am for same-sex marriage. ... I wanted to put a face on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he disagreed with the premise of one of the No on Knight
campaign's two new television ads, which says Pete Knight sponsored
Proposition 22 because he ``may not like the idea that his son is
gay.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the basis is, he's got a view of what he thinks
marriage and family and what's being taught in school should be,''
David Knight said. ``He's doing what he really honestly believes,
and I believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   David Knight strongly disagrees with those beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was I angry with it? Yes. Was I angry he decided to be in the
forefront of this issue? Yes. But that's my father's belief. ... I
still love my father.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Knight responded with a fiery statement to the No on
Knight ad. ``They should be ashamed for exploiting a private family
matter for political gain,'' the senator said.
</P>
<P>
   While Pete Knight accused the opposition of pressuring his son
to speak up, David Knight said he wanted to. Like his father, he
said it is because the issue is so important.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely awkward'' to have his family name at the center
of the battle, David Knight said. And it has deepened strains in
the family, he said, asking reporters not to contact his two
brothers and their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``And yet it's comforting to know I'm helping in something I
believe in very strongly,'' he said. ``I think it's extraordinarily
pivotal. California is the most populous state in the country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
