<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7176 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-VICTIM-SPEAKS-BOS &LR;      02-24 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VICTIM-SPEAKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOOTING VICTIM TRIES TO REPAIR A SHATTERED LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Seven months after her longtime boyfriend allegedly
shot her in the face and executed her two best friends while they
dressed for their second day of college, Shunae Allen says she
still loves him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't still have love for him now, that would mean I
never loved him,'' she explained. ``But I hate what he did to me,
to himself and to two of my friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in her aunt's home, Allen, 19, talked for the first time
of trying to refashion a shattered life even as she struggles with
the emotions she has for a man who still calls her from his jail
cell _ and the guilt she feels about her two lost friends, Monique
Brown and Patrice Lassiter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask myself all the time _ why me?'' said Allen. ``I wish we
were all here together or we left here together. Why am I left here
to go through all this alone?''
</P>
<P>
   In August, 21-year-old Jason Pierce allegedly shot the childhood
friends in their suburban Atlanta townhouse not far from Morris
Brown University, a black college where Pierce was a junior.
Pierce, who until then seemed to have left the street life behind,
disappeared, prompting a manhunt up and down the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Police finally caught up with him a week later, bringing him
into custody after a wild chase through nearby Brookline and a
shootout near the Mall at Chestnut Hill. Another man in the car
with him, Sean Taylor, has eluded police and is still at large.
</P>
<P>
   Now, said Allen, her life has turned eerily quiet. The families
of her two dead friends refuse to talk to her. She spends most days
at home. When she wants to be by herself, she hops a bus. But even
riding the bus, she said, she gets curious stares.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to be the first to say hello,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Once a month, the still-beautiful teenager with long braids,
visits the doctor, so he can check her progress. The bullet holes
on her high cheekbones have healed to look like two small
blemishes. Her jaw has healed so well that there is no outward sign
that the bullet shattered it.
</P>
<P>
   Allen said she has not given up her dream of going to college to
study computer programming. She hopes to enroll at the University
of Massachusetts sometime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I still want to go to school outside of the state, but not
Atlanta _ that gives me the creeps.''
</P>
<P>
   Late at night, when the house settles around her, she sits in
front of a computer, writing about her life, trying to find some
reason for the tragic turn of events.
</P>
<P>
   She has also spent ``a lot'' of time on the phone to Pierce, who
she plans to testify against in Atlanta. Pierce must first face a
trial here, to answer for the chase and shootout. Then in Atlanta
he faces murder charges and possibly the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   During the first phone calls, Allen recalls sobbing and begging
Pierce to tell her why he would do something so violent to the
people he cared so much about.
</P>
<P>
   ``He remained silent,'' she said. ``He has never admitted that
he actually did it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She has continued to press him for answers, but Pierce always
evades her, asking her about her aunts, her parents, and her many
cousins, she said. At the end of each conversation, Pierce tells
her to be strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to know where was his mind when he did this,''
she said. ``How could you be so stupid when you had so much going
for you?''
</P>
<P>
   Allen recalls first meeting Pierce, her boyfriend of six years,
at the Boys and Girls Club in in Boston's Roxbury neighborhood. She
was in sixth grade and hanging out with her best friend, Monique
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Pierce began showing up at her basketball
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would call my name and hide, silly stuff like that,''
recalled Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, she was wary of Pierce because she knew he hung out
in the streets and had been in trouble with the law. They dated
through English High School, where the three girls and Pierce all
went to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he began changing. He became a role model to me and to the
children in my family. Everybody wanted to go to college like
Jason,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her last fond memory of him was the night before the shooting,
when the four friends went to see ``In Too Deep,'' a movie based on
a Boston undercover officer and a drug kingpin.
</P>
<P>
   After the shooting, Allen's other friends visited her, but
seemed uncomfortable, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to be normal again, but I know things will never
be the same.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she still has nightmares and recurring dreams about her
friend Brown. She still remembers watching the police chase after
Pierce on the television, her mouth open, ``wanting to talk to
him.'' She has every intention of going to his trials _ here, and
in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the house, she keeps pictures of her friends, and a
picture of Pierce is tucked under the rim of her bedroom mirror.
</P>
<P>
   But Allen says she won't allow the tragedy to stop her from
enjoying life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to move on,'' she said. ``I still try to party and go
to clubs. I try to appreciate life a lot more. In the past I didn't
take it too seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen said what hurts her most is that the parents of Lassiter
and Brown won't speak to her.
</P>
<P>
   She called the parents, who she has known most of her life, and
one of them confronted her about false rumors that she was going to
marry Pierce. She said one of the mothers asked her why she lived
and the other girls died.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said if I had a choice to live or die I would be gone,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Allen recalled one of the most peaceful moments after the
tragedy. Her worried family members kept a close eye on her but she
was able to slip away from the house and take a bus to the Boston
Public Library.
</P>
<P>
   With her legs folded, Allen sat on the concrete steps watching
the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the young woman, wearing black shades that covered a
bruised eye and hid her from the public, said she walked into a
nearby church and stood in the back, watching the wedding of a
stranger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so beautiful,'' she said. ``All I wanted was a little
peace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-00 1343EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000224.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7177 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-OIL-GAS-CRISIS-SCARE-     02-24 2319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-GAS-CRISIS-SCARE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 A WORLD of CHEAP OIL  
 &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 310-798-0970; fax, By AMY MYERS JAFFE AND ROBERT A. MANNING  
 c.2000 Foreign Affairs Magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Oil prices have been flirting recently with $25 to $30 per
barrel, the highest in a decade _ levels almost reminiscent of the
oil shocks of the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   And the yo-yo prices have been accompanied by hysteria about
dwindling supplies and potentially dangerous transfers of wealth,
from nation to nation.
</P>
<P>
   But the energy problem looming in the early 21st century is
neither skyrocketing prices nor shortages. Instead, the danger is
precisely the opposite. Long-term trends point to a prolonged oil
surplus and low oil prices over the next two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, this scenario of plenty could destabilize
oil-producing states, especially those in the ellipse stretching
from the Persian Gulf to Russia. And although the U.S. economy
would by and large benefit, the backfire of low oil prices could
imperil U.S. interests.
</P>
<P>
   Both the popular and the elite media _ from Parade magazine
asking ``Could It Happen Again?'' to Scientific American, no less,
proclaiming ``The End of Cheap Oil'' _ are peppered with forecasts
of gloom and doom about energy security.
</P>
<P>
   But this ``sky-is-falling'' school of oil forecasting has been
systematically wrong for more than a generation. In its dramatic
1972 ``Limits to Growth'' report, the group of prominent experts
known as the Club of Rome wrote that only 550 billion barrels of
oil were left and these would run out by 1990.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the world consumed 600 billion barrels of oil between
1970 and 1990, and there are today more than a trillion barrels of
proven reserves. This figure is likely to continue rising even as
global consumption exceeds the current 73 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   The scarcity forecasters _ in some cases, the same people who
predicted in the 1970s that oil would cost $100 per barrel by 2000
_ are not only still wrong, they also have it exactly backward. The
world's problem is not scarcity but glut.
</P>
<P>
   This is true despite the recent Saudi-engineered production
cutbacks by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
(OPEC), which boosted oil prices off their $8-per-barrel lows.
Seasoned oil-market watchers knew this fragile deal among oil
producers could dissipate quickly. Indeed by late February the
Saudis were signaling to the markets their support for a production
rise, which would trigger a price fall.
</P>
<P>
   As OPEC knows, other oil producers around the globe are enjoying
new finds and announcing new plans to expand capacity. The oil
supply potential in Iraq, Russia, Africa and elsewhere belies the
Cassandra-like predictions that the world will soon deplete its oil
assets.
</P>
<P>
   So too, the prophecies of dried-up wells obscure the far more
likely prospect: a sustained oil glut and long-term low oil prices,
which will have very different _ and largely unconsidered _
political and strategic consequences.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 dalliance with $8 barrels hinted at the possibilities,
with the economic meltdown in Russia and a forced succession in
wealthy Brunei.
</P>
<P>
   The Arab states of the oil-rich Persian Gulf, non-OPEC producers
and consumers are simply not prepared for a new geopolitics of
energy. Neither, frankly, is Washington. The political
reverberations of a sustained oil glut should not be
underestimated.
</P>
<P>
   Several important regimes _ in the Persian Gulf states, Russia,
the former Soviet republics and such key Latin American countries
as Venezuela, Mexico and Colombia _ count on healthy oil revenues
for calming restless populations, assuaging social tensions and, in
some cases, significant nation building.
</P>
<P>
   Without the salve of rising oil revenues, many of these lands
can expect to see heightened political instability, social unrest
or even civil wars, which could be grimly reminiscent of the recent
Balkan slaughters.
</P>
<P>
   Without healthy oil revenues to buy off restive populations, the
leaders of various repressive gulf regimes will be left with only
repression to silence foes and quell public discontent, which could
fuel even more violent opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Radicalized local populations could also threaten the Middle
East peace process. Disgruntled gulf states might be tempted to
placate Islamist movements by funding the terrorists of Hamas, for
instance.
</P>
<P>
   The 1991 Persian Gulf war demonstrated the West's capacity to
defend important oil regions from traditional external threats like
the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait. But America's painful experiences
with revolutionary Iran in the late 1970s and the Balkans in the
1990s are grim reminders of how hard it can be to cope with
internal instability.
</P>
<P>
   The new dynamics of the global oil market have profound
implications for U.S. national security policy. Washington had
better gird itself.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong-headed predictions of scarcity are as old as the oil trade
itself. In 1885 the U.S. Geological Survey predicted ``little or no
chance of oil in California.'' In 1914 the U.S. Bureau of Mines
forecast only a 10-year supply of oil in the United States, and the
list goes on.
</P>
<P>
   The latest scarcity theorists are exemplified by one of the
world's most prominent petroleum geologists, Colin Campbell. He has
argued in many industry, policy and scientific journals that
growing global consumption of oil, driven by the emergence of a
modern, industrialized Asia-Pacific, is dramatically raising
demand.
</P>
<P>
   This rise, he warns, will collide with a slowdown in new oil
discoveries, leading to another energy crisis. By 2003, global
production will peak and the oil age will start to end.
</P>
<P>
   Why then have average oil prices NOT risen much in nearly a
generation?
</P>
<P>
   One reason is profound changes in the oil and gas markets.
Another is a profound high-tech revolution. Many analysts expected
that non-OPEC oil production would be short-lived. But they missed
the technological advances _ including computer-assisted,
three-dimensional imaging that lets geologists ``see'' underground
oil pockets _ that slashed the costs of developing hard-to-tap
reserves and improved the chances for new discoveries.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, better platform designs and drilling methods have also
let companies recover more of the oil they find. These
technological gains have dramatically lowered the cost of finding
and producing oil and natural gas and given energy consumers ample,
inexpensive supplies just at the time that earlier forecasts had
predicted a shortage.
</P>
<P>
   They have extended the life of existing wells and allowed the
oil industry to double the amount of oil recovered _ in many cases
from about 20 percent to 30 percent to between 50 percent and 60
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The average U.S. costs for finding oil fell from about $15 per
barrel in the 1980s to just $5 per barrel in 1998. Drillers are
four times as successful at finding natural gas and six times as
successful at finding oil as they were before the 1973 oil crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Now that finding and producing oil is cheaper and easier, more
and more countries are getting into the act.
</P>
<P>
   Ample, accessible new reserves will soon come on-line in the
waters off the Gulf of Mexico, eastern Canada and western Africa,
as well as onshore in central Africa, South America and frontier
areas in the former Soviet Union and the far reaches of the Arctic.
</P>
<P>
   Increased oil production in Venezuela, Colombia, Canada, Brazil
and the U.S. South has begun crowding more-distant Persian Gulf oil
out of the U.S. market. When growing oil imports from the Atlantic
basin (the North Sea and West Africa) are added in, the divide
widens.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming decade, the United States will increasingly rely
on oil from within the Western hemisphere and the Atlantic basin.
In the new, more efficient global oil market, most sellers strive
to sell their oil to the closest buyer to maximize revenues. It is
East Asia's dependence on Middle Eastern oil that is rising
substantially, not America's.
</P>
<P>
   There are other reasons to expect that the oil glut will NOT dry
up. All the major auto manufacturers have made large investments in
post-internal-combustion cars and have new prototypes of ``hybrid''
cars (that is, cars that run on both gas and electricity) and
fuel-cell cars to be mass-marketed by 2005-15, if not sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota and Honda are already marketing hybrid models in the
United States that get 80 miles per gallon, and experts say that by
2015 these post-combustion cars will make up at least 20 percent of
new vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Trends in the Middle East also bode well for lower oil prices,
particularly as U.S.-led sanctions against Iran, Iraq and Libya
begin to erode. Iraq, with 110 billion barrels in proven reserves,
has been held back from tapping them by U.N. sanctions since it
invaded Kuwait a decade ago. If sanctions are eased _ after, say,
Saddam Hussein is toppled, or the Desert Storm coalition collapses
completely _ one can expect to see Iraq's production rates double
within five to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   In the oil-rich gulf, Iran and Kuwait are also working to reopen
their oil sectors to foreign investors, hoping to boost their
capacity to pump out oil, their political clout and their national
security.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Arabia is following suit, both to protect its regional
prominence and to stimulate its economy. The Royal Dutch/Shell
Group recently announced an $800 million investment in offshore
Iranian oil fields, which could further add to the glut.
</P>
<P>
   If Kuwait, Iran and Iraq get their way, and if non-OPEC
production grows at only two-thirds the rate it did between 1985
and 1995, oil markets could be even more oversupplied than in 1998
_ the year prices collapsed to $8 per barrel.
</P>
<P>
   To consume all the oil that will probably be pumped out over the
next 10 years, world oil demand would need to grow by more than 3
percent per year, instead of the 1.8 percent annual growth rate
between 1980 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   If the days when the gulf was America's lifeline are fading,
then similarly, no Caspian oil will feed U.S. markets; rather, it
will flow to Europe and possibly to Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The politics of defending America's global oil supply will
probably complicate as the world's oil habits change. As U.S.
imports from the Persian Gulf diminish, the expensive U.S. military
role of ``guardian of the gulf'' will become increasingly
vulnerable to citizens at home calling for more burden-sharing.
</P>
<P>
   Will Congress and the U.S. public continue to agree to spend
blood and treasure to protect the Persian Gulf region while such
allies _ and recipients of the region's fossil fuels _ as the
European Union and Japan play virtually no military role there?
Such questions have colored the debate about expanding NATO's
post-Cold War role beyond Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Then too, China's rising hunger for oil imports means that it
will depend more on the same energy resources and sea
transportation lanes shared by the United States, Japan and other
industrialized countries. China, which conceives of itself as an
emerging great power, however, probably will not be comfortable
relying on the U.S. Navy to defend the sea lanes through which its
own Persian Gulf oil lifeline will have to be strung.
</P>
<P>
   If China thinks it is more vulnerable in energy, it could become
more assertive, particularly if U.S.-Chinese relations turn
adversarial. But if generous supplies of oil at moderate prices
persist, energy issues might actually provide a good opportunity
for cooperation between China, its neighbors and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The lessons of the past century should have taught us that
politics, not geology, has ruled our oil-supply fate. Politics and
diplomacy brought the price of oil from $8 per barrel to $23 last
year. The internal politics of the Persian Gulf have repeatedly
disrupted U.S. oil supplies in the past and could do so again in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   As U.S. dependence on Middle East oil wanes and Asian reliance
on it grows, a new set of issues will arise: rivalries between
Asian countries for oil supplies and complex problems about sharing
the burden for keeping the gulf's oil flowing freely.
</P>
<P>
   Properly assessing America's strategic situation in a world of
cheap oil _ in hopes of ensuring a more reliable oil supply _
should not be limited exclusively to military assistance but should
be linked to political and social institution-building and
diversified economic development.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, such reforms will better insulate the shakier countries
from the internal turbulence caused by volatile oil revenues.
Supply would be more secure, and the citizens of oil-producing
nations would gain more from the natural wealth their countries
control.
</P>
<P>
   Both producers and consumers thereby win _ regardless of how
high or low oil prices eventually wind up.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Amy Myers Jaffe, former senior economist for Petroleum
Intelligence Weekly, directs the Energy Research Program at the
James A. Baker III Institute for Public Policy at Rice University.
Robert A. Manning is senior fellow and director of Asian studies at
the Council on Foreign Relations and author of the forthcoming
``The Asian Energy Factor Revisited.'') &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
