<HEADER>
A7191 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-SEXUAL-REVOLUTION-NYT     02-24 2622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEXUAL-REVOLUTION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SECOND SEXUAL REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 310-996-0075; fax,
310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By JACK HITT  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    It was only two years ago that Bob Dole went on ``The Larry King
Show'' to discuss his prostate-cancer operation.
 &HT;    During a commercial break, so the story goes, King leaned over
to ask his old friend, confidentially, how he was dealing with the
operation's grimmest side effect, impotence.
 &HT;    Dole cheerfully informed the talk-show host that there was a new
drug, Viagra, and miraculously, it had cured the problem. King
asked Dole if he would discuss it on the air, and Dole said sure,
why not?
 &HT;    The world was about to become a very different place. Viagra
would cycle through the expected paces of pop-culture acceptance
with stunning speed.
 &HT;    Leno and Letterman got an entire summer's worth of monologues
off the subject. And the newspapers regularly pumped out clowning
(and possibly true) stories about the drug. For example, there was
Frank Bernardo, 70, who left his wife, declaring, ``It's time for
me to be a stud again.'' There was also Gen. Sani Abacha of
Nigeria, who died in the midst of a Viagra-fueled encounter with
two women in his magisterial bed.
 &HT;    But the jokes are over. Viagra's sales topped $1 billion in the
first year and Pfizer is now the second-largest drug company in the
world. The drug's use has leveled off, but consider the level:
Nearly 200,000 prescriptions are filled each week, and 17 million
Americans have used the drug.
 &HT;    Viagra has been embraced by the well off (4 percent of the total
population of Palm Beach County has a prescription), but not only
by the well off. Not long ago, Wal-Mart and Kmart had a Viagra war
that drove the per-pill price down from $10 to $7.80.
 &HT;    At this moment, there are at least a dozen new Viagra-like
medicines and devices currently in clinical trials.
 &HT;    Many of these drugs are for men, but this time around, there are
just as many for women _ specifically, for a new phylum of illness,
female sexual dysfunction, which will soon cycle through the same
paces as ``erectile dysfunction,'' setting the word ``frigidity''
alongside ``impotence'' in our dictionary of merry old archaisms.
 &HT;    ``Our knowledge of sexual health is in revolutionary mode,''
says Dr. Irwin Goldstein, a Boston University urologist and pioneer
in the field.
 &HT;    With $1 billion in sales for Viagra, the research pressure is
intense, yielding paper titles like ``The Ejaculatory Behavior in
Sexually Sluggish Male Rats. ...'' Scientists, doctors and
pharmaceutical companies are racing to discover newer and better
drugs.
 &HT;    Who doubts they will improve the lives of those who suffer from
the newly discovered sexual disorders now showing up in the medical
journals? But these drugs will also have, some say, an
''enhancing'' effect on normally functioning people.
 &HT;    More important, the temptation for anyone to obtain these drugs
will be more easily satisfied than ever before because the family
of pharmaceuticals inspired by Viagra is entering the market at a
time when medicine is decentralizing, slipping the reins long held
by doctors.
 &HT;    For most of the 20th century, any sexual complaint was treated
on the psychiatric couch, not in the lab. Only comparatively
recently has impotence been understood to be an organic disease _
potentially identifiable and treatable with medicine.
 &HT;    The change is part of a cultural shift that dates back to the
birth-control pill, when mostly young people were liberated to
experiment with sex fearlessly outside of marriage. Many moral
conservatives continue to condemn the era for unleashing the
Pandoran epidemics of teen-age pregnancy, sexually transmitted
disease and moral decline.
 &HT;    But this telling of the story ignores a more subtle and
significant shift.
 &HT;    Average folks _ young and old, liberal and conservative _ began
to accept that sex was not a biblical imperative whose sole aim is
procreation, but a lively part of good health _ something to be
enjoyed, like great food and laughter, well into old age. This is
the revolution that Dole has joined at the barricades.
 &HT;    The distinction is not just medical; it's metaphysical.
Psychological problems carry with them the full freight of personal
responsibility. But a physical problem seems more like a cosmic
error, something unrelated to a person's actions.
 &HT;    It's no flaw in your manhood or womanhood if your sexual organs
don't work. It's a ``disorder'' _ and by being labeled as one, it
becomes something detached from your own true self and easier for a
patient to emotionally confront and for a doctor to treat.
 &HT;    Indeed, now that Dole has made the world safe for sexual-health
research, new hypotheses and fresh ideas seem commonplace in this
growing new field.
 &HT;    And many of the cutting-edge discoveries are occurring for
women. Last year, the Journal of the American Medical Association
published a study reporting that 43 percent of women experience
some kind of sexual dysfunction.
 &HT;    Recently, the Network for Excellence in Women's Sexual Health
was organized to help doctors and health care professionals who
want to enter this area of practice. Tests and experiments are
being conducted in university labs and corporate R-and-D facilities
all over the country.
 &HT;    The cumulative lesson of much of this research is leading to two
categories of treatments _ hormone therapy, which restores desire,
and various drugs, which amplify the sensation of arousal.
 &HT;    Many companies are researching hormone medicines. Solvay already
markets one called Estratest. Organon is in trials with a treatment
called tibolone, which is believed to increase desire. Dr. Glenn
Braunstein, an endocrinologist at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center in
Los Angeles, is working on a ``testosterone patch'' under grants
from the marketing giant Procter &AMP; Gamble.
 &HT;    But the real gold rush is occurring in the other field of
research _ creating a drug to increase blood flow to the genitals.
The researchers want something simple _ a tablet or perhaps even
better, a quick-acting cream that is stabilized at room temperature
so that women can carry it in a purse like lipstick or men can just
toss it into a shaving kit.
 &HT;    The competition is furious among small firms, each with a
blood-flow drug _ some for men, some for women _ that's anywhere
from one to five years from getting to market. Herewith a sampling,
complete with active ingredients:
 &HT;    -- Vivus: prostaglandin E-1 cream.
 &HT;    -- MacroChem: a gel, using a version of prostaglandin E-1 called
Topiglan.
 &HT;    -- NexMed: alprostadil, a variant of prostaglandin E-1 cream.
 &HT;    -- Tap Pharmaceuticals: an apomorphine treatment formulated into
a small tablet placed under the tongue.
 &HT;    -- Pentech Pharmaceutical: ditto.
 &HT;    -- Zonagen: phentolamine, in tablets and suppositories.
 &HT;    -- Pfizer: Viagra for women (sildenafil).
 &HT;    -- Palatin Technologies: a peptide molecule derivative called
PT-14; in the earliest test stages.
 &HT;    -- ICOS Corp.: a tablet code-named IC351. (That's all they would
reveal.) Bill Gates, who may be telling us something, owns almost
13 percent of the company.
 &HT;    I wanted to compile a complete list of every sex drug currently
in trials. But it became an endless pursuit, the research being so
frenetic and the line between legitimate and illegitimate being so
confusing.
 &HT;    Obviously, once hard science ratified the actual existence of a
drug like Viagra, the very reality of it was a wake-up call to
America's snake-oil salesmen. Infomercials have shifted from
vegetable slicers and wrinkle tonics to ``natural'' aphrodisiacs.
There is scarcely a tree left standing in the rain forest whose
bark hasn't been stripped and tested for the alternative-health
industry.
 &HT;    The Internet is teeming with unsolicited ads for products with
vaguely homonymic names, though none of them come close to Pfizer's
allegedly unintended melding of ``vital'' and ``Niagara'' to
generate the best product name since Coke.
 &HT;    Some long-touted aphrodisiacs are now being tested too. A
derivative of chili peppers is in legitimate trials. Does this
count as a drug?
 &HT;    NitroMed, a company based in Massachusetts, is working on a
mixture of an old passion powder called yohimbe (stripped from the
inner bark of the Corynanthe yohimbe tree in tropical West Africa)
combined with an amino acid called L-Arginine to see if the two can
work effectively as a vasodilator _ that is, a chemical that
increases blood flow.
 &HT;    Then there are the nondrug inventions. A company called
UroMetrics is working on a vacuum device, fitted with a small cup
the size of a thimble, and intended to draw blood directly to the
clitoris. It might be easy to dismiss this as a sex toy, except
that it's also in trials for FDA approval, and UroMetrics intends
to distribute it only as a medical device via prescription.
 &HT;    The pace of change inside this small research world also means
that almost no one is stopping to reflect on the implications of
the drugs that are marching _ and there really is no stopping them
now _ toward the marketplace.
 &HT;    It would be nice if all medical breakthroughs were just to treat
the kind of complaints outlined by doctors. But welcome to the
world of 21st-century consumer needs; there's ``medicine'' for the
most curious things. With couples holding down two jobs and the
enraged pace of modern life, who doubts that a drug-enhanced
four-minute sexual encounter among harried day traders could become
the norm?
 &HT;    The whole idea of a long slow evening won't necessarily
disappear. It'll just go the way of sitting on the porch, the 3
o'clock dinner and the literary novel _ something experienced over
the holidays or on vacation.
 &HT;    ``I find it simply incredible this whole thing is happening,''
said Leonore Tiefer, a psychologist at the New York University
School of Medicine and pretty much the only critic of all this
research I could find. ``There is no such thing as 'female sexual
dysfunction,''' she added. ``It's a social construction invented to
benefit the drug companies.''
 &HT;    Tiefer believes that a kind of ``magical thinking'' infects the
way most of us imagine our sexuality. That it can always be better,
and that we resist the natural changes that define the arc of a
well-lived life: ``That's where this disorder comes in and says,
'If there is a change' _ and invariably there is a change in life _
'then change is bad.' Ah, a problem! So we invent a universal
model, a normative view of sex. If you don't get wet for X period
of seconds from Y pressure of stimulation, then you have a
problem.''
 &HT;    Tiefer was evasive when I asked her about the existence of real
medical conditions being cured by these new drugs. She believes the
medicalization of sex gives people an out _ a way to avoid the root
cause of their sexual problems.
 &HT;    ``I don't see many women depressed about the blood flow to the
genitalia. They are depressed about many other things about sex,
but not that. This research should be done, of course, but with a
few dollars, by a few people, in a few places. But it should not be
this Boeing of sex research.''
 &HT;    Not surprisingly, many researchers dismiss Tiefer's ideas as
rear-guard propaganda to protect the sex concession that therapists
have held for so long. Fears that the medical establishment will
big-foot the psychologists' business is not an imaginary concern
these days.
 &HT;    The central theme of Peter Kramer's now-classic book,
``Listening to Prozac,'' is the observation that, in the treatment
of depression, drug therapy has driven talk therapy right out of
business.
 &HT;    Beyond the idea of making sex into a very goal-oriented act,
where Viagra and its progeny are truly revolutionary is in putting
something mysterious and uncontrollable under our control. These
drugs suddenly enable us to ``control'' our own sexual health,
pushing the idea of sexuality far beyond the lab or the couch.
Tiefer's ideas seem to presume that these medical inventions will
stay under the strict control of doctors, that the old rules of the
medical-industrial complex still apply.
 &HT;    But the Golden Age of the AMA is over. The appearance of Viagra
has taken place at a time when medicine itself is in the process of
decentralizing and allowing market forces to guide many decisions.
 &HT;    Increasingly, patients are told to take charge of their own
health care; politicians debate a ``patient's bill of rights.''
HMOs themselves are built on the idea that individuals will decide
the general direction of their own care. Doctors are increasingly
called health-care ``providers'' as drugs are now marketed directly
to patients.
 &HT;    Viagra was one of the first new drugs introduced to the world
alongside the slogan: ``Ask your doctor about. ...''
 &HT;    In this loosey-goosey environment, Viagra has already slipped
into the recreational underground _ far beyond the reach of both
psychologists and doctors. Of course, the authorities have tried to
crack down on the practice of selling pharmaceuticals online. And
in December, President Clinton called on the FDA to take measures
to stop the practice.
 &HT;    But controlling the Web is futile, as I discovered one day last
winter when I typed ``Viagra and aphrodisiac'' into a search engine
and was offered hundreds of choices. The Web sites sound like
jokes: ``drugman.com'' and ``mywebdr.com'' and ``viagraguys.com.''
 &HT;    I opted to get my fix from a Web site called ``kwikmed.com.''
 &HT;    After I signed on _ I waited while this message scrolled by:
``Brought to you by Tide Detergent'' _ I was instructed to fill out
an on-line medical interview.
 &HT;    I was asked obvious questions, like ``Are you taking any heart
medication?'' I told the truth and said no. I was asked only a
couple of private questions, but I admitted to no dysfunction
whatsoever.
 &HT;    Only one question was devoted to ascertaining my ``problem.'' So
I wrote: ``Life is not as good as it should be'' _ a philosophical
statement I have pretty much always lived by. When I clicked the
box marked Send, I instantaneously received a message back saying
my doctor had ``approved me for Viagra,'' unless of course my
credit card didn't clear.
 &HT;    The next morning, at the crack of the workday, barely 12 hours
after I had clicked the send button, the FedEx guy appeared with an
envelope that rattled when he handed it to me. In a brown bottle
were 10 of the famous blue diamond-shaped pills. The crooked label
looked as if it had been produced on an Officemax printer. My
doctor was someone named ``A. Guzman.''
 &HT;    As we permit more and more market forces to take command of the
health-care industry, it shouldn't surprise anyone that the new
drug dealer will not be found in the shadows, offering sinsemilla
under his breath. He's already sitting right on our desks, his
cursor winking at us.
 &HT;     c.2000 Jack Hitt  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Jack Hitt is a contributing writer for The New York Times
Magazine.) &LR;
</P>
