<HEADER>
A7195 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-IRAQ-OPPOSITION-SADDA     02-24 2425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-OPPOSITION-SADDAM-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ANTI-SADDAM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 310-996-0075; fax,
310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By JANINE di GIOVANNI  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    Ahmed Chalabi, a Shiite Muslim from a prominent Baghdad family,
is by turns haughty and brooding, princely and strangely
preoccupied.
 &HT;    In the cold weather, he goes about London in a goatskin robe,
which he likes to flick grandly behind him, and Gore-Tex hiking
boots. But while he may look like some tribal elder who wandered
down from the hills (in trendy shoes), he holds a Ph.D. in
mathematics from the University of Chicago and is fluent in several
languages.
 &HT;    He is also the closest thing either the Clinton administration
or its Republican opponents have to a strategy for replacing the
failed policy of containing Saddam Hussein.
 &HT;    Chalabi, 55, is the head of the Iraqi National Congress (INC),
the once and, for now, future guiding body of the Iraqi opposition
to Saddam Hussein.
 &HT;    Pushed aside as leader early last year, Chalabi managed to
reclaim his position at a general assembly of the INC in New York
this fall.
 &HT;    And that, it bears mentioning, was no easy task. The 300-plus
delegates who met at a Manhattan hotel had arrived from Britain,
Lebanon, Syria, Turkey, Iraq, Jordan, Saudi Arabia, Iran, Turkey
and Canada. And they shared little but a history of backstabbing
and mistrust.
 &HT;    In truth, they gathered only to prove to their American patrons
that they were still collectively committed to overthrowing the
only person they loathe more than one another _ the devil in
Baghdad.
 &HT;    In flowing robes and cheap shiny suits, the delegates
distributed ``Free Iraq'' T-shirts and squabbled. They argued
throughout the weekend _ over the buffet dinner, over mint tea and
over the fax machine spewing out messages from across the world.
 &HT;    Yet somehow, by dawn on Monday morning, they managed to conclude
the general assembly by electing a new seven-man leadership, and
with a minimal amount of blood on the floor.
 &HT;    But not before Chalabi had walked out several times in disgust.
 &HT;    ``It was not a pretty sight,'' one delegate said. ``They threw
shoes at each other. I couldn't believe it. They took off their
shoes and threw them at each other.''
 &HT;    Yes, they threw shoes because they are desperate. With
Washington acting as midwife, the organization is now under serious
pressure to get results.
 &HT;    Saddam is now exercising virtual veto power on U.N. weapons
inspectors and, with an impending U.S. presidential election, the
Democrats are anxious to have something, anything, they can
plausibly hold up as a pro-active Iraq policy.
 &HT;    At the same time, the Republicans, eager to pre-empt the
Democrats, are claiming it was their idea to back the INC and that
they had to push the Clinton administration into getting behind it.
 &HT;    With both U.S. political parties competing to patronize the INC,
it would seem to be well positioned to make good on the promise of
fomenting an Iraqi revolution. But it doesn't seem any closer now
to that goal than it did eight years ago, when it was formed in the
wake of the Persian Gulf war.
 &HT;    Although Congress appropriated $97 million to bankroll the seven
main Iraqi opposition groups, the money has remained in Washington
as the groups have jockeyed for power. That struggle seems to be in
abeyance.
 &HT;    The INC still has one major problem, however. It hasn't figured
out a way to outsmart the Iraqi dictator. ``Saddam kills anyone he
doesn't trust,'' says one observer. ``He squashes opposition like a
bug.''
 &HT;    In its short and painful life the Iraqi National Congress has
done little to inspire confidence that it could ever serve as the
linchpin for American policy. Only now can it be said to be coming
of age, and at that, very slowly. The formal seven-man presidency
includes representatives of all the major factions. Chalabi was
given no official title, but he is acknowledged to be acting in a
presiding role.
 &HT;    It is a perplexing group. Each faction appears to have its own
agenda. The Kurds, for instance, have the issue of nationalism; the
monarchists want to see a royal return; the Islamic groups are
paralyzed by infighting. Yet all now protest their undying
solidarity.
 &HT;    ``All Iraqi opposition groups are united on the need to get rid
of Saddam,'' Chalabi insists. ``We all want the same thing. A
democratic Iraq.''
 &HT;    Adds Sharif Ali Bin al-Hussein, the 43-year-old leader of the
Constitutional Monarchy Party: ``We have a common goal and a common
strategy. It's not about power, it's about unity of Iraqi
opposition.''
 &HT;    This was echoed (cautiously) by the Kurdish leader Jalal
Talabani and the others.
 &HT;    ``What is important now,'' one delegate said heatedly, ``is
getting rid of Saddam. Together.''
 &HT;    Chalabi is insistent that this time the opposition will get it
right. ``Look, we don't want to get a bunch of guns and go blazing
into the sunshine,'' Chalabi said. ``We are going to work with
careful steps to prepare with the U.S. so that our forces are
ready.''
 &HT;    For veteran INC-watchers, ``blazing into the sunshine'' is a
not-so-veiled reference to the group's Waterloo _ the 1996 debacle
in Erbil, a town in northern Iraq that served as its base of
operations before it was leveled by Saddam's tanks.
 &HT;    For the INC, Erbil is a gaping, deep wound that just won't heal.
 &HT;    ``You ask why we don't have an army, why we aren't preparing
actively?'' asks Aras Habib, the organization's operations chief.
``We had an army. We had a good army. We had weapons. We were
fighters. It was destroyed in Erbil.''
 -0- 
 &HT;    The Iraqi National Congress was born in 1992, in the wake of the
Persian Gulf war, with Chalabi as its democratically elected
president. Its operatives lobbied diplomats, opened a human-rights
office and developed military, political and intelligence
operations, largely operating out of Erbil.
 &HT;    What they did not do is establish a financial infrastructure or
a real plan to overthrow Saddam. Vagueness has always been the
Iraqi opposition's downfall. The closest thing to a plan was
Chalabi's ``enclave'' or ``three city'' strategy.
 &HT;    ``I always refused to subscribe to the American policy of
containment,'' he says. ``My strategy was to construct an enclave
and to unite all the opposition groups, including the Kurds, to
form an alliance.''
 &HT;    Chalabi's plan was to capture Kirkuk and Mosul, the leading
cities in the north of Iraq, and Basra, the main southern city, and
slowly squeeze the life out of Saddam's regime.
 &HT;    ``He believed that the Iraqis themselves have the willingness to
rise up against Saddam,'' says Zaab Sethna, an INC adviser who sees
Chalabi more as a visionary than as a naif. ``But this could only
be done if the INC built up its strength in the north and the south
by luring defectors and acquiring arms.''
 &HT;    Whether ultimately feasible or not, the plan had two major and,
as it turned out, fatal flaws. First, it demanded the cooperation
of the two main Kurdish factions _ the Kurdish Democratic Party
(KDP) and the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK) _ which had a long
history of bloody feuds.
 &HT;    ``To think one could unite the Kurds under one anti-Saddam
banner when they had historically been incapable of uniting
themselves was overly optimistic,'' says Patrick Bishop, a
Paris-based Middle East specialist. ``Over the years, the main
Kurdish groups have shown themselves capable of getting in bed with
the devil if they felt it suited their interest.''
 &HT;    Second, the plan assumed the full cooperation of the CIA, which
had been trying for years to oust Saddam. But the agency didn't buy
into Chalabi's strategy, insisting that the dictator would succumb
only to a coup.
 &HT;    However, Chalabi, believing the regime would topple under
sustained pressure and counting on American support, went ahead
with plans to attack Kirkuk and Mosul. By the summer of 1996, he
says, he had a CIA-trained army of more than 1,000 and a highly
effective intelligence operation.
 &HT;    But on the night of Aug. 31, 1996, Chalabi's plans were blasted
into the thin desert air.
 &HT;    ``I was sitting in a meeting at the American Embassy in London
between the PUK and the KDP,'' he says, ``when Saddam's tanks crept
up on the outskirts of Erbil.'' A bitter tone creeps into his
voice. ``We waited for air support, but it never arrived.''
 &HT;    ``Apparently, it was gruesome,'' Sethna recalls. ``Fighters were
calling from the satellite phones. They could see the tanks in the
distance, and they kept calling and calling for help but no one
came.''
 &HT;    Saddam had been invited in by Massoud Barzani, the Kurdish
Democratic Party leader, who saw a way to eliminate both the Iraqi
National Congress and the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan in one
treacherous move.
 &HT;    The CIA, fearing another debacle like the Bay of Pigs, refused
to help. Hundreds of INC men were executed, and thousands more fled
to Turkey.
 &HT;    Chalabi's critics had long scoffed at the idea that the INC
could ever seriously challenge Saddam's Republican Guard, 80,000
strong, and his superior weaponry. They also dismissed his claims
about his intelligence network and disparaged him as a leader.
 &HT;    But the debate was moot by the morning of Sept. 1, when, for all
practical purposes, the Iraqi National Congress ceased to exist.
 &HT;    By now, having temporarily shelved the three-city plan, the INC,
newly invigorated, has a more modest goal: simply to get off the
ground by setting up bank accounts, re-establishing contacts in
Iraq.
 &HT;    Mostly, says Daniel Byman, a Middle East expert at the Rand
Corp., they are waiting, waiting ``for a lucky break so they can
fill in the gap. I honestly don't think they know what that is.
Maybe Saddam will take a lucky bullet. Maybe there will be a change
in government and they will step in. That seems to be their plan.''
 &HT;    For his part, Saddam is widely believed to have taken advantage
of a year free of U.N. weapons inspectors to resume development of
chemical, nuclear and biological weapons.
 &HT;    While he is not directly threatened by outside forces, other
than the occasional bombing raid by allied warplanes, he is said to
be paranoid about internal threats. In November, according to
intelligence reports, he called in his military commanders for
consultations in small groups _ an indication of growing suspicion.
 &HT;    Whether he was concerned about the INC or some other, undetected
threat is debatable.
 &HT;    ``There are signs,'' says one academic analyst. ``Saddam was
very nervous about the New York meeting.'' But there are also signs
that he hardly noticed it.
 &HT;    ``If he was worried, the Iraqi press wouldn't be writing about
it in their newspapers,'' another analyst says. ``They are
certainly not writing about what is happening in the south. Now
that would be damaging to Saddam.''
 &HT;    One thing has emerged from New York: The INC has been granted a
last opportunity to grow up and become a serious player.
 &HT;    ``The October summit was like crossing the Rubicon,'' admits one
State Department official, who said he had more faith in the
opposition than ever before.
 &HT;    There is also the growing congressional support, particularly
among Republicans looking to highlight the failed Clinton policy.
But how seriously does Washington really take Chalabi and his
organization?
 &HT;    ``The INC has a lot of support because Congress is full of a lot
of posturing idiots who couldn't find Iraq on the map and don't
know anything about foreign policy,'' says one critic. ``They just
know something has to change.''
 &HT;    But Byman points out that the INC has taken two major steps in
the last year.
 &HT;    ``One is their change in leadership, which remedies some of
their problems,'' he says. ``The other is that they've moved away
from past grandiose schemes like marching on Baghdad to addressing
basic organizational steps that they avoided for too long.''
 &HT;    However, Byman still has his doubts about the fundamental
differences within the coalition. ``They all agree that Saddam
should go,'' he frets, ``but what else they agree on, I'm not
sure.''
 &HT;    The Clinton administration is equally unsure about Chalabi, both
for his personality quirks and for his history. For a time last
year, it even seemed as if the White House would rather see Saddam
in Baghdad than Chalabi.
 &HT;    ``They were down on Ahmed because of Jordan,'' says one
Washington observer. (In 1989, Chalabi was indicted for embezzling
millions from a Jordanian bank he founded in the 1970s. He was
eventually convicted in absentia.)
 &HT;    Another blow came in 1998 when Gen. Anthony Zinni, commander of
the American forces in the Persian Gulf, bluntly told Congress that
the opposition groups ``have little, if any, viability.''
 &HT;    But the skepticism has quieted down, whether for cynical
reasons, a growing sense of respect for the INC or plain
desperation.
 &HT;    ``The Saddam regime has got to go,'' says one senior State
Department official. ``We crossed that bridge last year. But what
is different now is the opposition. Their recriminations have
subsided. They're watching each other, watching Washington. They're
more sober.''
 &HT;    Exactly how Chalabi and his men are going to pull off a stunt
like getting rid of Saddam Hussein, when the international forces
during the gulf war could not, remains to be seen. For now, the
Iraqi National Congress appears to be starting with basic
organizational issues that should have been addressed a decade ago.
 &HT;    ``They're asking how broad a coalition they can get, and how
they can share resources and leadership,'' Byman says. ``It has
been a good year because they are sitting down and talking, but
that's the first step in 100 and they still have 99 to go.''
 &HT;     c.2000 Janine di Giovanni  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Janine di Giovanni is a correspondent with The Times of
London.) &LR;
</P>
