<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATTERNED TILE WAS INSTALLED THE `WRONG' WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. When I had 12- by 12-inch ceramic tile installed, I think the
tiler goofed. The tiles have a distinct marbleized pattern running
across them, and they should have been placed alternately, with the
pattern of one tile running at right angles to that of the next.
The tiler did not do that, so the pattern runs from side to side,
parallel with the pattern on the next row of tiles. It looks weird.
Can anything be done?
</P>
<P>
   STEVES HOBBS, Westford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Sure, something can be done. Take up all the tiles and lay
new ones, since most of the old ones will break when they are pried
off. If the tiler does that for nothing, OK _ but it's unlikely
that he will. You could ask for a refund, but his response may be
that there is nothing wrong with the way the tiles were laid. I
don't think there's a hard-and-fast rule as to how they must be
laid. Therefore, your best bet is to live with the weird-looking
tiles. You might get used to them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have to store a refrigerator for six months. Is there any
particular way to store it? Should I cover it? Will it be OK in a
basement?
</P>
<P>
   A.L., Wakefield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If you have to store it in a basement, keep the door open and
throw a plastic tarp over it, but do not tie it at the bottom; let
air circulate around in it. Better yet, remove the door if it is of
the type that cannot be opened from the inside. If you store it in
any place other than a basement or unheated garage, simply keep the
door open, or remove it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a brown stain on my gray granite countertop. I can't
feel anything on the surface, but it certainly shows, and I can't
get it off. I have tried everything available. I think the stain is
from oil. Any brilliant ideas?
</P>
<P>
   FRUSTATED STAIN-SCRUBBER
</P>
<P>
   A. To treat an oily stain, your best bet is to absorb it. And to
do that, sprinkle baking soda on it, liberally, and let it sit
there for an hour or more, then sweep it up and throw it away.
Repeat as necessary. If that doesn't work, you can try washing the
stain with a strong solution of baking soda and water. Do not use
Soft Scrub on granite; it may turn it white, according to the
manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Other granite cleaners that might work are TileLab's StoneWash,
Stain Remover, and Stone &AMP; Tile Stripper, sold at Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a large walk-in closet off my master bedroom. It's
great for storage, but has developed a lot of moisture on the walls
and the window (a vinyl replacement window), and there is mold
growing on both walls and window. The room is unheated and has
three outside walls. How can I fix the closet so I can store
clothes in it without fear of moisture or mold?
</P>
<P>
   PETER VISELLI, Salem, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. For starters, open the closet door to let heated house air
circulate inside, and open the window to let the water vapor
escape. The replacement window might have made the room much
tighter than it was, so that water vapor builds up in the closet
and condenses on cool surfaces. You don't have to keep the window
open all the time; opening it a bit for a few minutes twice a day
should be enough to reduce the water vapor. Add heat: A few
100-watt bulbs will help some, as long as they are kept away from
clothing. Or, use an electric heater, again being careful to keep
it away from clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the quick fixes. A permanent fix is to insulate the
three exterior walls. This will help some, even though the closet
is unheated, because the walls will be warmer and water vapor will
be less likely to condense on them. Put a louvered door on the
closet for automatic air circulation.
</P>
<P>
   To get rid of the mold, wash it with a solution of 1 part
household bleach and 3 parts water. Keep this solution away from
the clothes, and wear skin and eye protection. An alternative to
the bleach solution is a detergent called Era; it contains oxygen
bleach, which is milder and safer than household bleach.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Many of the nailheads in my plasterboard wall are showing,
and some are popping a bit. How can I correct this unsightly
problem.
</P>
<P>
   M.S., Westborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Sometimes, nails will pop after the wooden studs dry out and
the nails lose their grip. Sometimes, the nails were not indented
deeply enough before joint compound covered them. For free-standing
nails that are not in joints, drive them deeper into the
plasterboard and give them a final whack with a hammer, making a
dimple that you can fill with joint compound. Apply the compound
once, smooth off, and let dry. Appy a second coat and let dry;
apply a third coat and let dry, then sand smooth. If some of the
popped nails do not seem to be holding, pull them out and subsitute
a drywall screw.
</P>
<P>
   If the nailheads are showing in a taped joint, the tape and
joint compund in the joint must be removed, nails countersunk, and
new compound and tape applied. The rule for compounding three times
still applies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail him
at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
