<HEADER>
A7205 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS &LR;      02-24 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE NIGHT MAKES RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ It was Homer, of course, who told the story
of the fall of Troy. But in the pantheon of Red Sox legends, two
epic homers on one October night will forever be remembered as the
rise of Troy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys still going to get on me about not hitting in the
playoffs?'' Troy O'Leary said Wednesday morning, knowing that he
had already authored the answer to his question last autumn in
Cleveland when he hit a grand slam and three-run home run in the
fifth and deciding game of the American League Division Series at
Jacobs Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``You remember the defining moments of your own career,'' said
fellow outfielder Trot Nixon, ``but if you're there, you never
forget the defining moments of someone else's career, either. That
was unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Twice O'Leary came to the the plate following an intentional
walk to Nomar Garciaparra. Each time, he hit the first pitch into
the seats. His grand slam off Indians starter Charles Nagy in the
third inning, and the three-run home run he hit off reliever Paul
Shuey to break a 8-8 tie in the seventh, take their place with
Carlton Fisk's World Series pole-bopper and Dave Henderson's
Anaheim shocker as the Sox' most dramatic postseason home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Only the six innings of no-hit relief by a hurting Pedro
Martinez in Boston's 12-8 win could compete with the drama of
O'Leary's night. ``We sent a description of that game to Ripley,''
manager Jimy Williams would say afterward, ``and he rejected it.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary, however, kept it. `I've got the damn tape,'' O'Leary
said Wednesday on the first day of workouts for the full Sox squad.
``(Jim) Thome going deep twice for them, and (Travis) Fryman
hitting one, and (Robbie) Alomar making plays for them, and Pedro
coming out of the bullpen. You can't ask for a better game.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary's home run totals have increased the last three seasons,
from 15 to 23 to 28. The same is true of his extra-base hits (51 to
67 to 68) and RBIs (80 to 83 to 103).
</P>
<P>
   He led the Sox last season in home runs, hit .346 against
lefthanded pitchers, and led American League left fielders in
slugging percentage (.495). By all measures, including a noticeable
uptick in his defensive skills, it was the best season of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Leary entered the ALDS carrying the stigma of his 1-for-16
performance against Cleveland in 1998. And even as the Sox were
putting up record numbers against the Indians, including a 23-7
beating in Boston in Game 4, O'Leary's bat had been quiet. He did
not have an extra-base hit or RBI entering the deciding game.
</P>
<P>
   And you ask why Indians manager Mike Hargrove twice elected to
pass Garciaparra intentionally? ``We had been handling O'Leary,''
Hargrove said afterward, ``up until tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   When Nagy walked Garciaparra to load the bases in the third
inning, O'Leary said he went to the plate with this thought: ``I
told myself, `This is what it's all about. Let's see what you're
made of.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The second time, O'Leary said, he dispensed with the philosophy.
``When they walked him again,'' he said, ``it was a tie ballgame. I
didn't care what I did. I just wanted to get the ball up in the
air. I got lucky, man. I was pretty happy about it.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary said the game was about more than defining one player.
``I think the way we came back from being down two games in a
five-game series told not just about myself but the team,'' he
said. ``People doubted us all year, but Dan (Duquette) did a great
job of bringing people in here. We already knew about Pedro and
Nomar, but Dan brought in other people who knew their jobs and
played well together.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is like a second family, the kind of family you want
to be in. Nobody bitches about anything. Hopefully, we'll still
have _ What's that word? _ the same camaraderie.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary, who spent the offseason working out in Arizona, said
that even after last season's success, both he and the Sox will
face their share of skeptics. ``People are still going to doubt
us,'' he said, ``because we don't have many big-name players. Pedro
and Nomar are our only big names, and we build around them. But we
know in our heads and minds that we can play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt better about myself in the offseason, but now I'm
thinking about what I'm going to do this year. The home runs? Sure,
they were the best thing I've ever done, no doubt. But who knows
what's going to happen this year?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
