Sunday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee or Tim
Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Friday:
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARIES-TURNOUT (Washington) _ At a time when election experts
bemoan low turnout in recent elections, the candidacy of Sen. John
McCain has driven up the numbers of voters taking part in
primaries. Much like Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura, McCain is
drawing voters who otherwise might not cast ballots. Will such
voters' interest last into the general election? Yes, some experts
say, if McCain manages to stay in the race. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Just who is Warren Rudman? When he
was a U.S. senator, he was much admired for common sense, integrity
and fair-mindedness. But then he became Sen. John McCain's campaign
co-chairman and a target of the religious right, which is out to
defeat McCain any way it can. Pat Robertson of the Christian
Coalition calls Rudman a bigot, an outrageously wild charge based
on nothing more than Robertson's fury that McCain is doing so well.
By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-REFORM (Washington) _ Sen. John McCain's presidential
campaign has put new energy into efforts to reform the campaign
finance laws. McCain got his zeal for reform as the result of the
``Keating Five'' savings and loan scandal 10 years ago, an event
that he says changed his life. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
