<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REINDEERGAMES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEO-NOIR WITH TWISTS: SCREENWRITER CRAFTS ELMORE LEONARD-LIKE CRIME
DRAMA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The tongue-in-cheek crime drama ``Reindeer Games'' was
originally supposed to open in December, but any movie that opens
with a bloody, lifeless Santa Claus lying in the snow isn't gonna
do much for your holiday spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Soon enough, Ben Affleck's voice comes onto the soundtrack,
ready to tell the tale of how Santa got into such a state. We
discover that Affleck is a car thief named Rudy whose story begins
during the last days of a prison stretch. Although the current
``Boiler Room'' proves that Affleck can be convincing when he shows
a devious side, at first glance he still looks miscast here. But
his boy-next-door passivity is put to good use in this twist-laden,
irony-heavy guilty pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   During his incarceration, Rudy becomes best buds with cellmate
Nick (James Frain), who develops a pen-pal relationship with an
apple-cheeked woman named Ashley (Charlize Theron). Nick's plans to
meet Ashley after his release are quashed when he's stabbed in a
prison fight, so Rudy decides to take his place. Turns out to be a
good move _ initially, at least: Ashley is beautiful, ready and
willing, as Affleck and Theron demonstrate during a
clothes-ripping, furniture-jarring motel-room love scene, and
Affleck appears to be following his buddy Matt Damon into the
assumed-identity territory of ``The Talented Mr. Ripley.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``Reindeer Games'' has less lofty ambitions than that
complex drama. It has its own complexity, though, which becomes
clearer when Rudy/Nick meets up with Ashley's no-good brother
Gabriel (Gary Sinise), who wants Nick's help in a casino robbery.
Too bad for Rudy that he's just pretending to be Nick, because
Gabriel isn't taking no for an answer.
</P>
<P>
   You could call ``Reindeer Games'' the Elmore Leonard movie that
Leonard never got around to writing. Standing in for him is hot
young screenwriter Ehren Kruger (''Arlington Road,'' ``Scream 3''),
who puts all the Leonardesque elements in place: Criminal tries to
go straight, gets mixed up with wrong woman, finds himself working
with dumber criminal and colorful sidekicks in a complicated heist
plot.
</P>
<P>
   Kruger doesn't yet have Leonard's ear for dialogue, but he does
have a knack for twists. How much you enjoy ``Reindeer Games''
depends on how willing you are to fall for the twists, which become
increasingly silly.
</P>
<P>
   But neo-noir fans are also likely to get the biggest kick out of
the movie, thanks to Affleck's winking performance as a guy who
would rather be anywhere than with the people he's become messed up
with and thanks to Frankenheimer's renewed confidence with action
movies. The director, who turned 70 this month, probably will never
regain the form he showed in the '60s with movies like ``The
Manchurian Candidate'' and ``Seconds,'' but ``Games'' is evidence
that he can still make entertaining throwaways.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Reindeer Games''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: John Frankenheimer
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Ben Affleck, Charlize Theron, Gary Sinise
</P>
<P>
   Length: 92 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ profanity, violence, nudity and sexual situations
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
