A7224 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-WONDERBOYS-TEX     02-24 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-WONDERBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WRITE STUFF: DOUGLAS, MAGUIRE MAKE YOU BELIEVE PEN IS MIGHTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the first frames unspool of Curtis Hanson's delightful new
film ``Wonder Boys'' (his follow-up to the Oscar-winning ``L.A.
Confidential''), the picture envelops you like an engaging novel
savored slowly in front of a crackling fire on a snowy afternoon.
It's fitting praise, especially for a film that largely concerns
itself with the art of writing, but the simile rings true
throughout.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Douglas, who has built a career on playing thoroughly
disreputable characters _ be they greedy investors, adulterous
husbands or bored millionaires _ taps into new territory here ... a
character you can like.
</P>
<P>
   Not that college writing professor Grady Tripp (Douglas) is
perfect. Far from it. He drinks too much, gets high too often,
neglects his wife, and to top it off, he's having an affair with
the school's chancellor (Frances McDormand), who just happens to be
married to Grady's immediate boss.
</P>
<P>
   But Grady is certainly one of Douglas' most human portrayals _
an unshaven, terminally disheveled, soft-spoken genius, the kind of
teacher we all dreamed of befriending in college, but whose
challenging courses threatened to cut too deeply into our social
lives.
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder wannabe-writers Katie Holmes (''Dawson's Creek'')
and Tobey Maguire (''The Cider House Rules'') circle his warm glow
like a pair of overeager moths.
</P>
<P>
   But Maguire has a light of his own _ he's a morose loner whose
gloomy personality and penchant for lying betrays his talent as a
gifted writer. He and Douglas are the wonder boys of the title.
One, a promising writer lurking in the shadow of his own secrets;
the other, a great writer trapped in the shadow of his own
brilliant first novel. It will take the two of them, surviving a
wild weekend of misunderstandings and mistakes, to find their way
back into the light.
</P>
<P>
   Like any story well told, ``Wonder Boys'' fills its periphery
with wonderful characters _ Robert Downey Jr. as Grady's sexually
charged gay editor, Rip Torn as a self-important celebrity author,
Holmes as the seductive but wise student, McDormand as a the real
love of Grady's life and Maguire as the wide-eyed Wunderkind. But
Douglas alone emerges from the film with a performance that's
nothing short of a wonder. You won't want it to end.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Wonder Boys''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Curtis Hanson
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Michael Douglas, Frances McDormand, Tobey Maguire
</P>
<P>
   Length: 118 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ profanity, violence, adult subject matter and drug
use
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is a film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
