<HEADER>
A7239 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-JUDYBERLIN-TEX     02-24 0349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-JUDYBERLIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BABYLON'S' FIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine a Long Island-set ``Magnolia'' directed by early Jim
Jarmusch with an assist from Edward Burns, and you have some idea
what to expect from ``Judy Berlin.'' Or maybe you don't; if those
names don't mean anything to you, it's a good indication that you
should pass on this ready-made cult movie.
</P>
<P>
   For every nine people who are bored or baffled by this movie,
one will be enthralled by its wistfulness and black-and-white
cinematography. ``The Sopranos''' Edie Falco, starry-eyed and
idealistic here, plays the title character _ but the movie isn't so
much about her as it is about the town of Babylon, which the movie
defines as a Long Island Railroad stop and a place where it's not
unusual for thirtysomethings to run into people they went to high
school with.
</P>
<P>
   Judy, who has dreams of escaping to ``the coast'' to pursue her
acting career, runs into former schoolmate David Gold (Aaron
Harnick), a cynical wannabe filmmaker who returned to Babylon after
his dreams were dashed. David's mother (Madeline Kahn, in her last
role) is a dreamer on the verge of a nervous breakdown; her husband
(Bob Dishy) is the local elementary-school principal, who's
contemplating an affair with one of his teachers (Barbara Barrie).
During the course of a talky hour-and-a-half or so, they all work
through their angst.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Magnolia,'' ``Judy Berlin'' features an unusual natural
phenomenon _ in this case, an unusually long solar eclipse, which
gives Babylon an eerie surreality. If ``Magnolia'' is always played
at a high pitch, though, ``Judy Berlin'' is played at almost no
pitch, and its laconic, meandering nature makes its 96 minutes feel
like ``Magnolia's'' three hours.
</P>
<P>
   _ Robert Philpot
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Judy Berlin''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Length: 93 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: Not rated
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
