<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7248 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-AREA-CODES-HNS &LR;      02-24 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AREA-CODES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LAWMAKER SEEKS AREA CODE FOR WIRELESS SERVICES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VANESSA HUA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Faced with the rapid growth of communications, a
California lawmaker has introduced legislation that would preserve
existing area codes by assigning codes specifically for wireless
phones, pagers and data lines.
</P>
<P>
   Although the proposal does not comply with existing federal
regulations, the Federal Communications Commission is considering
amending rules to allow so-called overlays for wireless technology.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Debra Bowen, a Democrat from Marina Del Rey,
introduced the bill that would require the state Public Utilities
Commission to adopt a special code for the wireless services and
determine how to implement it.
</P>
<P>
   The advent of the Internet, wireless telephones and the
popularity of additional home telephone lines has forced regulators
and telephone companies nationally to add area codes as telephone
numbers are exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, this was done by carving up a geographic area and
assigning it a new code. More recently, regulators in some states
have allowed overlays _ essentially new area codes within existing
ones _ to avoid requiring residential and business customers to
change their existing area codes.
</P>
<P>
   In such overlay areas, a home or business may have a phone line
with one area code and a new phone, fax or Internet line with a
different three-digit code. Such overlays often are fraught with
opposition because callers must dial the area code as well as the
seven-digit phone number every time they place a call.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we look around the state at what's happening, area code
after area code is changing,'' said Bowen, chairwoman of the Senate
Energy, Utilities, and Communications Committee. ``It doesn't make
any sense to wait until we're near a crisis and running out of
numbers, to then go and change numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   A representative of the largest wireless provider in the San
Francisco area protested the legislation, saying that if approved
it would require customers to dial additional digits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not customer-friendly,'' said Pam Johnstone, a
spokeswoman for Cellular One.
</P>
<P>
   A technology overlay also could complicate billing and possibly
drive up incremental costs for consumers, Johnstone said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the California PUC splits geographic areas to add new
codes, and has recently approved measures to conserve and
distribute numbers within each code.
</P>
<P>
   Residents have long been asking for a technology overlay,
consumer advocates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes up consistently at virtually every meeting I've
attended,'' said Natalie Billinglys, an analyst at the Office of
Ratepayer Advocates, the PUC's independent consumer arm. ``When
they're told we're running out of numbers because of the growth in
demand for cell phones and pagers, they ask `why don't you put the
people causing the problem into the new area code?''
</P>
<P>
   However, some questioned the sweeping nature of the bill, which
prohibits the PUC from approving a geographic overlay or split
unless it has already established and exhausted a technology
overlay.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is well-intentioned bill, but we have look carefully to
make sure it's used in situations to produce positive results,''
said Regina Costa, a telecommunications analyst at the Utility
Reform Network in San Francisco. ``There might be some cases where
it might not work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
