   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY _ With fewer than a dozen days remaining before a
critical round of primaries, former New Jersey senator Bill Bradley
has made a tactical decision to spend nearly half that time in
Washington state. Bradley hopes a win in the state's Feb. 29
primary will give him some momentum heading into March 7. But some
analysts question whether the gambit can succeed in a state that is
typically ignored and in a contest that has no nominating delegates
at stake. Tuesday's balloting is a preference primary only; actual
delegates are chosen at party caucuses a week later. (Foskett,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25'.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH _ News of the day on the Bush campaign. (Heath, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN _ San Diego Mayor Susan Golding is endorsing Sen. John
McCain for president today, becoming the second prominent
California Republican to join the Arizona senator's camp in recent
days. (Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   MINORITY-BUSH _ After George W. Bush took a right turn in South
Carolina to secure the party's conservative vote, we explore what
bridges he may have burned when it comes to the minority community.
His appearance at Bob Jones University, which prohibits interracial
dating, has some blacks incensed. While we see evidence that some
blacks in Michigan are working against Bush, they may be doing it
for a different reason. We explore. (Greenberger, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
