<P>
   OZONE-MIDWEST _ A year-long study by the Ohio Valley, Ozone
Alley, found that people in the Midwest are exposed to dangerous
levels of ozone pollution up to 75 percent more often than those in
big East Coast cities like Boston and New York. Hospital admission
rates for smog-related problems, such as asthma attacks and
emphysema, also were higher for the Midwest than the East Coast.
(Dayton Daily News). 30. COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS
OF THE NYT NEWS SERVICE
