<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DAUMIER-EXHIBIT (Washington) _ Honore Daumier aided, abetted and
recorded the emergence of so many aspects of modern art and life as
we know it that you may have trouble keeping track. Look in any
direction in the sprawling, illuminating retrospective of his work
at the Phillips Collection here _ the largest Daumier show ever
held in this country _ and you'll see the start of something big:
the modern newspaper, the modern city and public transportation,
working-class consciousness, agitprop and political caricature,
popular art and entertainment. By Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   APPLES-ATLANTA (Atlanta) _ This is a city without a historic
core, a city in constant evolution _ a Deep South version, you
might say, of Los Angeles. It has a past, of course, a real one as
well as the one that Margaret Mitchell so vividly imagined in
``Gone With the Wind.'' A decisive Civil War battle was fought over
this ground, and the momentous civil rights movement of the 1960s
had its principal headquarters here. That most American of
products, Coca-Cola, was invented here. But Atlanta, a city in a
hurry, keeps putting its past behind it. If not for the Cyclorama
depicting the fighting of 1864 and the superlative Atlanta History
Center, with its evocations of Henry W. Grady, the great newspaper
editor, and Bobby Jones, the golfer, and, yes, William Tecumseh
Sherman, who burned the city down, a visitor might easily come here
and miss Atlanta's past altogether. This, after all, is the
vibrant, business-minded capital of the New South, proud to have
played host to the 1996 Olympic Games, pleased to promote itself as
``The World's Next Great City'' and not another tradition-bound
vestige of the Old South. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (Story will move with a ``t'' travel code.)
</P>
