<DOCNO> NYT20000224.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7298 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-ELECTION-$ADV2     02-24 1658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ELECTION-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOR JADED RUSSIANS, PUTIN PRESIDENCY MAY BE REALITY BOOST THAT
COUNTRY NEEDS
 &HT;    (1400&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With bio box attached at end of story.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Feb. 27 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ Here in Vladimir Putin's hometown,
folks have many names for their most famous native son: Sphinx,
Gray Cardinal, Efficient Manager, Nice Guy.
</P>
<P>
   Critics and confidantes debate whether Putin is a reformer
(given his track record in city government here in Russia's
second-largest city) or more bent on authoritarianism (given his
history in the secret services and his brutal war campaign in
Chechnya).
</P>
<P>
   Still, with one month until Russia's presidential elections,
friend and foe alike agree he will win the race because he has done
one simple thing: He's gotten people to believe that they can be a
great nation again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite often we hear that Russia has imperial ambitions, but
this is not true. Russia has only one ambition _ to enjoy respect
from other nations,'' Putin said in January, one of the rare
insights into his vision as a national leader. ``We can count on a
worthy future only if we manage to naturally combine the principles
of a market economy and democracy with Russia's realities.''
</P>
<P>
   An avid churchgoer, who recently revealed that he and his family
celebrated Christmas even during the atheist Soviet times, Putin
added that ``any program should start from the revival of people's
morals. It is essential to begin with the restoration of moral
values, not with taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   This overall message _ although vague _ is music to most of the
country's ears. Russians are jaded after nine years of failed
reform and need something to believe in again.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great leader because he's tapped into something deep,
some yearning,'' said Igor Shokhan, a St. Petersburg documentary
filmmaker. ``He's the type of patriot we need. The Soviet past is
dear, but he's looking to the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with old neighbors, friends and colleagues of Putin
here in St. Petersburg reveal a vibrant, smart, reserved man. One,
who above all feels a call to duty and service, not to power, and
has the organizational, can-do qualities to get a job done.
</P>
<P>
   The balding, blond 47-year-old with a slight build is described
as a man of integrity. He doesn't drink. He's athletic _ friends
say Putin swims every day even after 15 hours in the office. He
likes to joke, and knows when someone is lying to him.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has made a concerted effort in the last couple of weeks to
show a more human face. In sharp contrast to the glassy-eyed stare
and schoolmasterish style witnessed at previous public events, he
has posed on television with the family's fluffy white poodle,
Tosya, and donned a new casual wardrobe. At the funeral of his
long-time boss and mentor, Anatoly Sobchak, Putin broke down in
tears.
</P>
<P>
   The window into his family life has opened only a crack,
however.
</P>
<P>
   According to Shokhan, the leader is reserved and private. ``His
family is his rock and fortress,'' Shokhan said.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has insisted on keeping his two pre-teen daughters, Katia
and Maria, and wife, Ludmilla out of the press spotlight. Since he
unexpectedly became acting president on Dec. 31, his daughters
stopped going to the German-language school they usually attend,
and are being home-schooled.
</P>
<P>
   A fashionably coiffed brunette, Ludmilla Putin was a stewardess
when she met her future husband. She reportedly has dabbled in
business, but now is a full-time mother. She has appeared in public
with her husband a few times, but never on her own. When requesting
her birthday from the presidential press service, the reply given
is: ``It's a state secret.''
</P>
<P>
   His parents, who Putin describes as ``normal, simple folk,''
were working-class. They moved from a provincial village to the
city of St. Petersburg, the intellectual heart of the country,
before World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike former presidents Mikhail Gorbachev and Boris Yeltsin,
Putin's family had no ties to the Communist Party elite, or to
politics. Putin's father was a foreman at a machine-building
factory; his mother was a housewife. They both died of cancer
within the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   In a quiet, unassuming neighborhood off St. Petersburg grand
boulevards that were home to the former imperial palaces of
Russia's czars and dukes, sits the Putin family's old apartment.
Like other buildings on the block, paint is peeling from the
entranceway of the eight-story edifice, and the yard looks forlorn
and neglected.
</P>
<P>
   His old neighbors say Putin would say hello as he passed them in
the hallway, usually early in the morning or after midnight, when
he left and returned for work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought having a (political bigwig) around would mean
changes,'' said Marina Valentinova, a 53-year-old teacher who still
lives in his building. ``He could have used some pull to get the
streetlights working. But they're still not working.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin's life as an officer in the KGB, which for some conjures
up sinister images of 1930s gulags and repression, seems only to
enhance his stature as an ``Everyman Made Good'' among Russians
who, like Putin, grew up in the post-Stalin years, said Valery
Golubev, an old friend of the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``He chose it (the career) out of a sense of duty to his country
_ not to the Soviet government or Communism, but the place where he
was born, the system that gave him an opportunity to go to
college,'' said Golubev, who met Putin when the two shared an
office in the 1970s in their first years with the KGB. ``It was a
romantic career, and a respected one, like an America, when you
work for the police or in the army.''
</P>
<P>
   The Soviet-era KGB was a monolithic government institution,
containing both domestic security and international espionage, as
if the American FBI and CIA were combined. Putin spent his career
in the foreign department. He learned German as an adult, and spent
five years living in the former East Germany.
</P>
<P>
   His political career began in 1990, when he became a deputy to
Anatoly Sobchak, a prominent democrat of the perestroika era who
left academia to become the globe-trotting mayor of a
then-notoriously corrupt city, St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   Officially in charge of foreign investment for St. Petersburg,
Putin cut deals with some of the most successful multinational
companies, like Atlanta-based Coca-Cola Co., doing business in
Russia. He quickly rose in importance, taking charge of running
day-to-day operations in the city of 5.5 million people during
Sobchak's frequent trips out of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand hesitation about Putin (because of his past),
but I worked with him for six years,'' Sobchak said in an interview
just days before he died of heart failure on Feb. 20. ``Putin
always gave the impression of utter reliability and
self-confidence. He worked hard out of a sense of duty, not
(monetary) reward.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin's six years in the city administration put him at odds
with the city council, and, critics say, the politicians. While
efficient, smart and capable, Putin made his share of mistakes,
like fostering a closed system of private business deals and
monopolies.
</P>
<P>
   These deals provoked numerous scandals. In 1991 the city, which
was experiencing food shortages in the final months before the
collapse of the Soviet Union, got special permission from the
Kremlin to export oil and minerals. The money made was supposed to
come back to the country as food supplies. Putin gave out contracts
for the deal, but much of the food never arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``He chose obscure companies, didn't use a tender process, and
everything was done without oversight,'' said Anatoly Bellayev, a
city council deputy who was in charge of a probe into the scandal.
It ended without any criminal charges being brought.
</P>
<P>
   More recent criticism has come as a result of Putin's war
strategy in Chechnya, in which he's allowed the Russian military to
use indiscriminate force against civilians to help defeat the
Islamic rebel forces. Some human rights groups have called the
attacks ``genocidal acts.''
</P>
<P>
   Strict information control about battles and war developments,
as well as the disappearance of war journalist Andrei Babitsky _
who had covered the story from behind enemy lines _ have both human
rights groups and journalists afraid that Putin will cut back on
freedoms as Russia's elected leader.
</P>
<P>
   Putin defenders here, however, say that doesn't sound like their
hometown hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Jewish and I couldn't be friends with Putin if he were a
racist or a dictator,'' said Shokhan the film director. ``He
doesn't enjoy war. He's not Hitler, or Stalin. He's a leader that
knows what has to be done and does it.''
</P>
<P>
   --------------------------------------------------------------------
------
</P>
<P>
   VLADIMIR VLADIMIROVICH PUTIN
</P>
<P>
   Born: Oct. 7, 1954 in St. Petersburg
</P>
<P>
   Married: July 28, 1983 to Ludmilla; children, two daughters,
Katia and Maria
</P>
<P>
   Career:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  in 1975, began work for the KGB;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  in 1985, moved with family to East Germany for five years;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  in 1990, joined staff of St. Petersburg Mayor Anatoly Sobchak;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  in 1996, left city politics when Sobchak failed to win
re-election;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  in June 1996, moved to Moscow for job at Kremlin property
department;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  in March 1997, named deputy head of the presidential
administration and head of the Kremlin's audit department;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  in July 1998, became head of the Federal Security Service, the
modern KGB, where he slashed jobs and streamlined departments;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  in 1999, appointed head of the Russian Security Council;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Aug. 16, 1999, President Boris Yeltsin appoints Putin prime
minister, announcing him as his preferred successor.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dec. 31, 1999, becomes acting president of the Russian
Federation.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
