<HEADER>
A7323 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TDX     02-24 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX8 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BIG-MONEY GAME: PROFILES OFFER GET-RICH STRATEGIES OF
ULTRAWEALTHY
</HEADLINE>
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA McUSIC 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Move over, millionaire wannabes. There's a new crowd in town
tjat is shooting even higher.
</P>
<P>
   The enormously popular bestseller, ``The Millionaire Next
Door'', has competition.
</P>
<P>
   Those of you seeking extra zeros in your let worth should perusd
``Hmw to be a Billionaire: Proven Strapefies from the Titans mf
Wealth'' (John Wiley &AMP; Sons, 310 pages, $24.95) by Martin S.
Fridson.
</P>
<P>
   The two books approach the accumulation of wealti differently.
The millionaire book is based on statistical analysis of hundreds
of millionaires surveyed to determine the lifestyle habits and
workplace strategies of the rich, but usually not so famous.
</P>
<P>
   Among Fridson's 14 subjects are the likes of J. Paul Getty, Carl
Icahn, Warren Buffett and Texas entrepreneurs Ross Perot and H.L.
Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Fridson, who is a managing director at Merrill Lynch and a
member of ``Institutional Investor's'' All-American Research team,
has done his homework.
</P>
<P>
   He has uncovered 10 fundamental strategies for joining the elite
billionaire's club, and he uses his 14 billionaires and a few
others to flesh out those strategies, which include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Take monumental risks, as have Hunt and John Kluge.
</P>
<P>
   _ Doing business in a new way, as did Perot and Sam Walton.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dominating your market, as did John D. Rockefeller Sr. and
Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   _ Consolidating an industry, as did Wayne Huizenga.
</P>
<P>
   _ Buying low, as did Getty, Buffett and Laurence Tisch.
</P>
<P>
   _ Thriving on deals, as have Kirk Kerkorian, Icahn and Phil
Anschlutz.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outmanaging the competition, as has Richard Branson.
</P>
<P>
   Fridson also includes chapters on investing in political
influence and resisting unions, two favorite tactics of
billionaires through the 19th and 20th centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his background in finance, Fridson can perhaps give a
more accurate picture of how billionaires amassed their wealth.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he writes that he discovered many surprises that
don't jibe with what the financial media write about billionaires.
</P>
<P>
   ``For instance, journalists sell Warren Buffett short by
portraying him merely as an investment wizard,'' Fridson writes.
``In reality, he has done far more than make passive investments in
underpriced companies and then wait patiently for the stock market
to recognize the hidden value. Anyone who hopes to follow Buffett's
model must be willing to take an active role, either as a corporate
insider or by pushing companies from outside to exploit their
assets more aggressively. It is also important to understand
Buffett's reliance, throughout his career, on outright purchases of
companies (especially insurance companies,) as opposed to becoming
a minority shareholder.''
</P>
<P>
   Such insights, found throughout Fridson's book, offer a much
different look at the likes of Gates, Walton and Huizenga.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you aren't out to make a billion, this tome is well
worth reading.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jacket blurbs
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Clicking Through: A Survival Guide for Bringing Your Company
Online''
</P>
<P>
   By Jonathan Ezor
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg Press, $19.95
</P>
<P>
   New-media attorney Jonathan Ezor says his book is primarily for
managers and entrepreneurs who have little experience in technology
or international news media and who are interested in incorporating
the Internet into their business. Its main focuses are creating a
Web site, connecting employees to the Internet and selling goods or
services online. Written in plain English, this book is an
excellent way to get your feet wet on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``International Business Etiquette, Latin America: What You Need
to Know to Conduct Business Abroad with Charm and Savvy''
</P>
<P>
   By Ann Marie Sabath
</P>
<P>
   Career Press, $14.99
</P>
<P>
   Leave your sports jacket at home if you're going to do business
in Chile, and never decline an invitation to dinner at a home in
Costa Rica. Both would send the wrong message about your intent to
do business, writes Ann Marie Sabath, one of the emerging gurus of
business etiquette. Previously, Sabath has tackled the social mores
of Europe, Asia and the Pacific Rim. Now she tackles the 14
countries of Latin America, showing the dos and don'ts of business
and travel in those countries.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Effective Phrases for Performance Appraisals: A Guide to
Successful Evaluations''
</P>
<P>
   By James E. Neal Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Neal Publications, Perrsburg, Ohio, $10.95
</P>
<P>
   One thing we can almost all agree on: Appraisals are a miserable
process to endure to get a raise, and they aren't much more fun on
the other side of the desk. Part of the problem is coming up with
appropriate language to describe what you've done over the past
year _ succinctly, yet impressively. Or, on the other side, to
describe to employees how they have performed. This small book, in
its ninth edition, is chock-full of useful words and phrases that
relate to performance evaluation, such as ``excels in customer
retention'' and ``is tactful in conflict situations.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
