<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MISSJULIE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEETING `MISS JULIE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a guy who's not exactly a household name, director Mike
Figgis sure has been busy, releasing three movies within the space
of a year. Somehow, he also found the time to film ``Miss Julie.''
</P>
<P>
   Figgis (''Leaving Las Vegas'') loves to challenge himself, but
the results tend to be pretty hit-and-miss. He's fascinated with
sexual politics _ the subject of ``Miss Julie'' _ and his films
have a dreamlike moodiness. They also, all too frequently, are
pretentious, dreary and/or silly.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because Figgis didn't write ``Miss Julie,'' it largely
dodges those traits _ not that there aren't traces of them,
especially dreariness. Still, it's not exactly mainstream as it
adapts August Strindberg's play about a count's daughter (Saffron
Burrows), who gets more than she bargained for when she attempts to
seduce the count's footservant (Peter Mullan). What follows is a
dialogue-heavy examination of sex and class differences, but at
least the dialogue is good, given cinematic rhythms through Helen
Cooper's astute screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   The focus is on the acting, and Mullan, in particular, explodes,
tempering his anger with a sense of sadness and desperation. If
he's turning into one of our great unheralded actors, Burrows is
still trying to find her niche. Her indignant poutiness is put to
good use here, but she could still stand to gain a sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Not that humor has much of a place in ``Miss Julie.'' People
most familiar with Strindberg have a head start; Figgis' admirers
will probably also be pleased. For everyone else, though, ``Miss
Julie'' will be a slow, grim sit.
</P>
<P>
   _ Robert Philpot
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Miss Julie''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Length: 100 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
