<DOCNO> NYT20000224.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7325 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-KNOCKOUT-TEX     02-24 0361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-KNOCKOUT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHT THE URGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A bitterly funny short film on the festival circuit called
``Maid! Madonna! Whore!'' laments the limited opportunities casting
directors provide for Latina actresses: If you're not Salma Hayek
or Jennifer Lopez _ and sometimes if you are _ you're likely to be
pigeonholed as one of those three stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   A few indie/orphan movies have tried to change that. The latest
is ``Knockout,'' a Latina boxing drama that trades cliches that
discriminate for ones that don't. And regardless of ethnicity or
gender, they're still cliches.
</P>
<P>
   Isabelle (Sophia-Adella Hernandez) scraps her way up from
ambitious amateur to million-to-one title contender. She has an
irascible trainer/father (Tony Plana), a boxer-turned-cop who's
dedicated to saving kids from the street life. Eduardo Yanez is her
shy love interest, her father's partner and one of those kids he
saved from the streets.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a formidable opponent known as ``The Terminator,''
whose bout with Isabelle's best friend (resulting in her
hospitalization) is the inspiration for Isabelle's vengeful return
to the ring.
</P>
<P>
   And, if that isn't enough, her mom (Maria Conchita Alonso) died
young, showing up in flashbacks to spread bumper-sticker
inspirationalism such as ``let your light shine,'' a message the
movie takes very seriously.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to want to root for ``Knockout'' because it's a
well-meaning, low-budget movie aimed at an underserved audience.
But it's just not very good, and the low budget is part of the
problem: Aside from Plana, who's pretty good as Isabelle's dad, the
performances range from competent to amateurish; the screenplay
lacks the humor that could balance out its overbearing earnestness;
and the fight scenes are among the most poorly choreographed in
history.
</P>
<P>
   _ Robert Philpot
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Knockout''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Length: 100 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
