<DOCNO> NYT20000224.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7327 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX     02-24 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MODERN ECHO OF THE FUROR OVER JACK JOHNSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watching a replay of Dennis Rodman tossing his jersey to fans in
Reunion Arena recently after being ejected from a game, I thought
of Jack Johnson, the first African-American heavyweight boxing
champion of the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, it is a bit of reach to connect the newest member of
the Dallas Mavericks to someone like Johnson. Despite being one
tremendous athlete, Rodman will not rate a footnote in the history
of the progress of African-Americans after he finishes strutting
and fretting his bizarre hour on the world stage.
</P>
<P>
   However, Rodman's flamboyant flouting of conventional norms of
behavior and appearance struck me as being, on a very basic level,
quite similar to the defiance that Johnson exhibited after he took
the heavyweight title from Canadian fighter Tommy Burns on Dec, 26,
1908.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson had every right to expect a hero's welcome home when he
returned to the U.S. Instead, he was greeted with scorn and abuse.
White America did not want a black champion because of the powerful
symbolism of boxing's highest achievement.
</P>
<P>
   The Johnson-Burns fight was scheduled for 20 rounds, but it was
stopped in the 14th round because Burns' face was swollen to twice
its size, and both his eyes were shut.
</P>
<P>
   Novelist Jack London led calls for a great white hope to take
the title from Johnson: ``The battle was between a colossus and a
pygmy. Burns was a toy in his hands. Jim Jeffries must emerge from
his alfalfa farm and remove the golden smile from the Negro's
face.''
</P>
<P>
   That golden smile was to the white bigots of that day kind of
like Rodman's yellowed hair to some of today's bigots. But where
Rodman's hair, tattoos and body-piercings evoke sarcasm and
laughter, Johnson's golden left front tooth infuriated the Jack
Londons of his day.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Johnson's fights were staged outdoors, and he would
smile broadly to catch the reflection of the sun, while he tattooed
his opponents with lefts and rights and taunted them.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson might have behaved differently had it not been for his
rejection by the white public. After all, he'd come a long way from
Galveston, Texas, where he was born on March 31, 1878, and where as
a youth he fought in the battles royal. Those were spectacles in
which black men and boys battered each other for the amusement of
white patrons.
</P>
<P>
   He was not officially recognized as champion until his first
title defense, when he knocked out Victor McLaglen. And the
drumbeat went on for Jeffries to return and take the title back for
the white race.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in 1910, Jeffries yielded to the pleas. The fight was
preceded with a barrage of laudatory publicity about Jeffries and
vilification of Johnson by the white press. That racist coverage
elicited angry responses in the black press, and the stage was set
for a social explosion.
</P>
<P>
   After Johnson pounded Jeffries into submission in 15 rounds,
race riots erupted across America. Scores were seriously injured,
and seven were killed. The Texas Legislature banned the showing of
films of any of Johnson's fights out of fear of setting off more
riots.
</P>
<P>
   Adding insult to the injury of his whipping up on all white
comers, Johnson lived a flamboyant and lavish lifestyle that
included marrying three white women. Because of that latter offense
to white sensibilities, charges that he violated the Mann Act _
which forbade transporting white women across state lines for
immoral purposes _ were trumped up against Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   He was forced to flee the country for several years and to fight
and perform in theatrical spectacles in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In 1915, Johnson gave up his title to Jess Willard in a fight in
Havana. He threw the fight under the condition that he be allowed
to return to the U.S. The fight was supposed to end in the 10th
round, but Johnson prolonged it until the 26th, when he received a
sign from his wife that she had received all of the money promised
him.
</P>
<P>
   He was ahead on all scorecards when he took the dive.
</P>
<P>
   Even then Johnson was betrayed, and he finally came back home
five years later and spent a year in a federal prison.
</P>
<P>
   He went on to put on several exhibition fights and pursued other
businesses before being killed in an automobile accident in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was a proud, audacious black man at a time when it took
real guts to be that way. His defiance expressed the hidden
feelings of most of black America and inspired many others in
avenues of life beyond boxing.
</P>
<P>
   He was a role model for Muhammed Ali, and something tells me
that fellow Texan Dennis Rodman has heard of him.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can reach him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
