<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7366 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-POPE-ISRAEL-NYT &LR;      02-24 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-ISRAEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RABBIS ASK POPE TO CANCEL PLANNED MASS ON JEWISH SABBATH 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ A group of senior rabbis Thursday asked Pope John
Paul II to cancel plans for a daytime Saturday mass in Nazareth
during his visit to Israel next month, contending that security
arrangements would cause ``massive desecration'' of the Jewish
sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, far-right religious factions put up wall
posters in Jerusalem's Orthodox neighborhoods denouncing the pope
as ``the wicked one'' and condemned planned papal prayer services
here as acts of ``mass idolatry in the heart of Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   And in a speech to an international gathering here of Jewish
World War II military veterans, a prominent American rabbi assailed
the pontiff's alleged wartime acquiescence to the Nazi persecution
of Polish Jews. Israel should receive the pope with ``respect'' but
not ``celebration,'' said Rabbi Arthur Hertzberg, a former chairman
of the Conference of Presidents of Major American Jewish
Organizations, in remarks reported widely here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Hertzberg also said the planned Saturday mass ``is a slap in the
face of Jewish dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican has declared that a major aim of the pope's
pilgrimage to the Holy Land is to further the cause of
reconciliation between Roman Catholics and their ``elder
brothers,'' as Pope John Paul has called the Jews. Israeli
political leaders, most of whom welcome warmer relations with the
Vatican, are planning to turn out in force to welcome the pope when
he arrives on March 21. The trip will be the first state visit by a
Catholic pontiff to Israel, which established diplomatic relations
with the Vatican just five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But as preparations for the papal visit intensify, there are
increasing signs of ambivalence among Jewish religious leaders here
_ and growing indications that the pope may be greeted with
organized hostility by Jewish fundamentalists.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctity of the sabbath _ always a charged issue in the
secular-religious divide within Israel _ has become a focus of
growing unease about the pope's trip.
</P>
<P>
   In a petition presented Thursday to the Vatican's chief
diplomatic representative, a delegation of rabbis asked ``His
Honor'' John Paul II ``to please change your schedule'' and cancel
activities between sundown Friday and sundown Saturday, the
penultimate 24 hours of the pope's six-day visit to Israel and
adjacent Palestinian-ruled territories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our apprehension about Shabbat desecration arises from the
fact that thousands of security men and police will be mobilized
for the needs of security for the visit, most of them Jews who will
be required to desecrate Shabbat against their will,'' the document
stated.
</P>
<P>
   Though organized by the rightist opposition United Torah Judaism
Party, the petition was signed by 2,137 rabbis and laymen
representing almost every Israeli municipal rabbinical council and
a spectrum of religious views.
</P>
<P>
   In what both sides later described as a cordial and
``respectful'' exchange, the rabbis and the papal nuncio, Msgr.
Pietro Sambi, discussed further details of the pope's trip. The
chief rabbi of Haifa, Shear Yeshuv Cohen, said he had proposed
advancing the planned Saturday mass to after sundown. ``That is
about six in the evening,'' he said later. ``From 6 to 12 there are
still six hours to this holy day.''
</P>
<P>
   In an itinerary coordinated months ago with the Israeli
government, the Vatican scheduled a midday mass for Saturday, March
25, at the Basilica of the Annunciation in Nazareth, an Israeli
Arab town with a mixed Christian and Muslim population. This
itinerary keeps the huge papal entourage far from major Jewish
population centers on the sabbath holiday, organizers noted. On
Sunday, March 26, the pope plans to return to Jerusalem to
celebrate mass in the Church of the Holy Sepulchre.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be frank,'' Sambi said after the meeting Thursday, ``I have
to say that from the beginning the government of Israel has made us
conscious of this sensibility, and we have collaborated fully with
the government to reduce to a minimum the disturbance from the
activity of the pope during Shabbat.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel and the Vatican face another religious headache in
Nazareth: Fundamentalist Muslims are camped out next to the
Basilica in a public plaza where they were granted government
permission to build a mosque _ but only after the pope leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli authorities say that if the Muslims don't vacate the
site voluntarily, they will be forcibly dislodged, and permission
to build the mosque will be revoked. But Muslim leaders are
refusing to move, and say they are planning their own welcoming
ceremony for the pontiff.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican is not expected to alter its long-set plans for the
Nazareth mass. Even if the service was rescheduled, security
preparations for the pope's visit to the city would still need to
be in place hours beforehand. And the itinerary as it stands takes
into consideration the aging pope's frail health, scheduling just
one major event and minimizing travel each day.
</P>
<P>
   But the pope will not be traveling on the Sabbath with the
Israeli air force, as originally planned. Responding to rabbinical
pressure, the Defense Ministry said Wednesday that it was canceling
plans to fly John Paul to Nazareth for the Saturday service.
Alternative transportation will be arranged, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
