<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7385 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CLOSER-FILM-REVIEW-NY     02-24 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLOSER-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLARNEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 `THE CLOSER YOU GET': WANTED: AMERICAN SWFs WITH A THIRST FOR(Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Lush green fields ... tiny villages by the sea.'' The young
narrator of ``The Closer You Get'' is dutiful enough to keep the
boredom out of his voice, but the theater will fill with tired
sighs from the audiences attending another high-concept Irish
Spring comedy _ collect 'em all! _ from the folks at Fox
Searchlight.
</P>
<P>
   After the success of ``The Full Monty'' and the, er, release of
``Waking Ned Devine,'' apparently someone felt that the hunger for
comedy featuring pale, badly dressed, hearty men clutching pints of
stout hadn't quite been satisfied yet.
</P>
<P>
   So fill your eyes with ``The Closer You Get'' _ from the
producer of ``The Full Monty'' _ where the blarney's as high as an
elephant's eye. Where the men of a seaside town, bored and
impatient over their lack of prospects with women, decide to place
an ad in an American newspaper in hopes of attracting babes from
the States.
</P>
<P>
   The men prepare for the anticipated onslaught of American women
in different ways. Kieran (Ian Hart), the town butcher, dyes his
hair an iridescent blond generally seen only in the World Wrestling
Federation or on a Dixie Chicks tour. He trumpets his new
sophistication to his assistant, Siobhan (Cathleen Bradley), who
loves him. But he's blind to her affection; no doubt his pupils are
still smarting from his hair dye.
</P>
<P>
   Siobhan deduces that turnabout is fair play and invites a pack
of swaggering virile Spaniards, who apparently double as the Gipsy
Kings in their off time, to play the town dance. Only then does
Kieran realize that he loves _ oh, who cares?
</P>
<P>
   It's a little funny that after Kieran is punched by one of the
Spaniards, his bloody nose matches his red velvet suit. It's the
closest he's come to achieving the fashion synchronicity he's been
bragging about all along, and the film misses a chance to get a
joke out of it.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of the few times an opportunity for corny, predictable
humor is squandered. This underpopulated burg has more winsome gags
than inhabitants. For example, when Father Hubert (Risteard Cooper)
orders up ``The Ten Commandments'' for a showing at the tiny church
and, instead, ``10'' unspools on the screen. (``The Red Sea,''
someone cracks as Bo Derek lolls in the surf with Dudley Moore.)
This happens after he decides to replace the church bells with a
tape recording of ringing.
</P>
<P>
   Later Hubert compares dating to buying a new suit. When he
starts going on about ``slipping in and out of new suits'' and
``silky fabrics against your skin,'' you want to applaud the actors
for not rolling their eyes so far back they pass out.
</P>
<P>
   By the time a little girl trains her brown eyes on her mother
and asks, ``How long before I have breasts?,'' you may bite your
lip in hopes that the film won't last long enough for that to
happen, although it certainly feels that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Closer You Get'' is so relentlessly adorable that the
Irish accents lose their charm, and much sooner than you'd think. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `The Closer You Get' is rated PG-13 (parents strongly
cautioned). It includes a bit of randy language and stereotypical
stout-drinking fests. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE CLOSER YOU GET' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Aileen Ritchie; written by William Ivory, based on a
story by Herbie Wave; director of photography, Robert Alazraki;
edited by Sue Wyatt; music by Rachel Portman; production designer,
Tom McCullagh; produced by Uberto Pasolini; released by Fox
Searchlight Pictures. Running time: 92 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   With: Niamh Cusack (Kate), Sean McGinley (Ian), Ian Hart
(Kieran), Ewan Stewart (Pat), Sean McDonagh (Sean), Cathleen
Bradley (Siobhan), Pat Shortt (Ollie), Deborah Barnett (Ella) and
Risteard Cooper (Father Hubert). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
