<DOCNO> NYT20000224.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7387 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JAPAN-BANK-ART-480&AMP;AD     02-24 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-BANK-ART-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFTBANK CORP. WINS RIGHT TO NEGOTIATE FOR JAPAN'S NIPPON CREDIT
BANK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ A group led by Softbank Corp., the global Goliath of
Internet-related investment, on Thursday won the exclusive right to
negotiate for the acquisition of Nippon Credit Bank, one of two
failed banks nationalized by the government in the depths of
Japan's financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of Nippon Credit, which has long served the political
establishment here, to a nonfinancial company that thrives outside
Japan's insular network of bureaucrats, big business and banks has
the most far-reaching implications for the Japanese banking
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``From an overall viewpoint, this is very exciting,'' said Dean
A. Yoost, the partner in charge of the financial services practice
at PriceWaterhouse Coopers in Tokyo. ``It is clear evidence that
things are changing in Japan and that banking, which we have long
thought of as a traditional, stodgy environment, is now becoming
something more open and dynamic.''
</P>
<P>
   The potential deal is in some ways more startling than the sale
last summer of Long-Term Credit Bank, the other, larger
nationalized bank, to a group led by Ripplewood Holdings , at the
time a little known U.S. investment firm. The sale to Ripplewood
marked the first time a Japanese bank had been purchased by a
foreign investment group. Unlike Ripplewood, however, Softbank is a
total nonfinancial entrant in the clubby world of Japanese banking.
</P>
<P>
   The Softbank-led group intends to spend 101 billion yen, roughly
$907 million at current exchange rates, to buy and recapitalize
Nippon Credit, which collapsed in 1998 with 3.98 trillion yen, or
$36.2 billion, worth of bad loans. The government has since
disposed of most of those loans.
</P>
<P>
   If the sale goes through, the Softbank group intends to break
the mold of Japanese banking by redirecting Nippon Credit's lending
to high-risk, entrepreneurial businesses seeking to capitalize on
the information technology revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The bank will use that same technology to teach Japanese
borrowers and depositors the virtue of Internet-based banking, thus
establishing a much leaner cost structure than its more traditional
competitors. Nippon Credit's relatively few branch offices make an
online strategy even more attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Those plans alone could force Japan's lumbering banks to
intensify their own reform efforts. They must also contend with the
entrance of companies like Sony Corp. and Itoyokado, a major
retailer, which have applied for banking licenses in an effort to
exploit the vast opportunities to provide banking services to
average consumers long shunned by Japanese banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This presents a good opportunity for the traditional banks
that want to be winners to accelerate the speed of their
restructuring and reconsider their competitiveness anew,'' said
Setsuko Akiba, a banking analyst at Deutsche Bank in Tokyo.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Such pressure comes against the backdrop of signs that Japan's
banks, many of them still struggling with mountains of bad loans,
have stalled in their efforts to change their lending practices and
become profitable.
</P>
<P>
   The government itself has intervened recently to slow the
progress of bank reform. It has been propping up weak banks rather
than forcing them to close. And it has postponed a plan to limit
deposit insurance, which would have caused a dramatic customer
shift to strong banks.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a sense that the drive to draw foreigners into the
banking system has lost momentum since last summer, when the
government chose Ripplewood to purchase the Long-Term Credit Bank.
</P>
<P>
   That sale was hotly contested, with the head of the Financial
Reconstruction Commission, Hakuo Yanagisawa, supporting Ripplewood
and a battalion of politicians offering their opposition.
Yanagisawa won because the only alternative would have been to sell
Long-Term Credit to two relatively weak Japanese financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Yanagisawa lost his job when the Cabinet was shuffled last
October and was replaced by Michio Ochi, a former bureaucrat turned
politician and widely regarded as less aggressive about reform.
</P>
<P>
   But in awarding the negotiating rights to buy Nippon Credit,
Ochi was in some ways forced to make an even more remarkable choice
than his predecessor. There were only two bidders for Nippon Credit
_ the other was Cerberus Partners, a U.S. investment fund that
specializes in buying distressed assets.
</P>
<P>
   Cerberus faced deep opposition from politicians, a person with
knowledge of the dealings said. They did not want another Japanese
financial institution purchased by foreigners, although Cerberus
had promised to strengthen the bank and take it public in a stock
offering, thereby returning it to Japanese hands.
</P>
<P>
   So the regulators were left with one choice, a group of
impressive investors headed by a nonfinancial Japanese company that
has made risky bets on Internet start-ups and carries a speculative
grade investment rating.
</P>
<P>
   But one of Softbank's investment goals is to build a system for
financing young companies often neglected by traditional financial
institutions in Asia in general and Japan in particular. Softbank
has itself provided seed money for roughly 120 ventures related to
the Internet, including those in insurance, online securities
trading and leasing.
</P>
<P>
   It recently teamed with Lehman Brothers to create an online bond
trading business. Softbank is also working with the National
Association of Securities Dealers to establish Nasdaq Japan, which
is expected to attract companies like the ones Softbank has
invested in.
</P>
<P>
   The increasing concentration of financial power in Softbank's
hands is starting to raise questions about whether Softbank is
getting too big.
</P>
<P>
   Masayoshi Son, Softbank's founder and a pioneer of the online
world, often refers to the disparate collection of companies that
comprise Softbank as a ``net batsu,'' a play on ``zaibatsu,'' an
old Japanese term that refers to agglomerations of businesses
clustered around a bank that provides all their financing needs.
</P>
<P>
   Such arrangements historically helped to suppress the
development of a competitive banking market in Japan. Some analysts
fear Softbank's move into banking could prove to be a modern
version of this same relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is vital that they quickly establish a fire wall between
the bank's lending decisions and its management and the aims and
aspirations of its largest shareholder, i.e., Softbank,'' said J.
Brian Waterhouse, the senior banking analyst at HSBC Securities in
Tokyo. ``It is going to require very strict controls to ensure that
a situation doesn't arise wherein this bank is being used as a
virtual piggybank for its owner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
