<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   INSURGENT-CANDIDATES (Seattle) _ If the nation's capital didn't
exist, insurgent presidential candidates such as John McCain and
Bill Bradley would have to invent it. Washington state's slew of
independents, quickly shifting partisan alliances and the high-tech
economy make this fertile ground for the anti-establishment
candidates. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARIES-TURNOUT (Washington) _ At a time when election experts
bemoan low turnout in recent elections, the candidacy of Sen. John
McCain has driven up the numbers of voters taking part in
primaries. Much like Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura, McCain is
drawing voters who otherwise might not cast ballots. Will such
voters' interest last into the general election? Yes, some experts
say, if McCain manages to stay in the race. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-McCAIN (Sacramento, Calif.) _ John McCain draws crowds
numbering in the thousands as he wins more establishment
endorsements in California and portrays himself as a ``Reagan
Republican'' with broad appeal. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BRADLEY (Dobbs Ferry, N.Y.) _ Al Gore picks up a key
environmental endorsement as opponent Bill Bradley continues to
hammer him for his conservative record that Bradley says was out of
step with Democratic primary voters. At a scenic site at the edge
of the Hudson River in Westchester County, Gore, who has worked
hard over the years to polish his environmental credentials,
receives the support of the New York League of Conservation Voters.
By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-GOP (Austin, Texas) _ Susan Weddington, the chairwoman of
the Republican Party in Texas, calls Arizona Sen. John McCain a
``home wrecker'' for reaching out to Democrats and independents in
his bid to defeat Texas Gov. George W. Bush for the Republican
presidential nomination. Drawing heavily on independent and
moderate voters in the North and Northeast, McCain has so far
foiled Bush's march to the nomination. By PEGGY FIKAC.
</P>
<P>
   MOSBACHER-McCAIN (Houston) _ A lawsuit by businesswoman and
author Georgette Mosbacher suggests that her support for Republican
presidential candidate John McCain was a factor in her former
husband's cutting off her $32,064 in monthly alimony. Houston
oilman Robert A. Mosbacher was secretary of Commerce under
President George Bush and is a friend of his son, Gov. George W.
Bush, who is locked in a tight primary race with McCain. By RAD
SALEE. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EXECUTION-TEXAS (Huntsville, Texas) _ Betty Lou Beets, a
62-year-old great-grandmother, is scheduled to die by injection at
7 p.m. EST. Beets would be only the second woman executed in Texas
since the Civil War. Beets' lawyers are seeking action in federal
court to stop the execution. By JOHN WILLIAMS and KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   BEETS-BUSH (Huntsville, Texas) _ The execution of convicted
husband-killer Betty Lou Beets poses an interesting political
dilemma for Gov. George W. Bush. With the primaries of California,
New York and Illinois still ahead _ states that are less
conservative on the death penalty _ will he want to appear more
cautious than usual and give Beets a 30-day reprieve? By JOHN
WILLIAMS and KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Kissimmee, Fla.) _ Feature on All-Star second
baseman Craig Biggio of the Houston Astros. By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Just who is Warren Rudman? When he
was a U.S. senator, he was much admired for common sense, integrity
and fair-mindedness. But then he became Sen. John McCain's campaign
co-chairman and a target of the religious right, which is out to
defeat McCain any way it can. Pat Robertson of the Christian
Coalition calls Rudman a bigot, an outrageously wild charge based
on nothing more than Robertson's fury that McCain is doing so well.
By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-REFORM (Washington) _ Sen. John McCain's presidential
campaign has put new energy into efforts to reform the campaign
finance laws. McCain got his zeal for reform as the result of the
``Keating Five'' savings and loan scandal 10 years ago, an event
that he says changed his life. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
