u w BC-DAY-TRADING25-COX     02-24 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAY-TRADING25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DAY TRADING FIRMS PROFIT WHILE MOST CUSTOMERS LOSE, SENATE FINDS
 &HT;    With DAY-TRADING-DATA. Moving in (w) Washington and (f)
financial categories.
 &HT;    With photos.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Scott Webb moved to Atlanta expecting ``to be rich
and have a lavish lifestyle,'' his mother told a Senate
subcommittee Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, her 30-year-old son plunged deeper into debt and
depression before being shot to death by a fellow day trader, said
Alyce Wenzel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The loss of my son continues to haunt me today,'' said Wenzel,
testifying at a hearing at which senators suggested tighter
regulation may be needed to control the fast-paced stock
speculation known as day trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I knew as much back then about this practice as I do
now,'' Wenzel told the Senate Permanent Subcommittee on
Investigations, ``because I would have done everything within my
power to keep Scott from getting involved in day trading in the
first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb was among nine people killed last July 29 by Mark Barton, a
disturbed day trader. Barton killed himself later that day as
police approached his car at a gas station.
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy highlighted the computer-driven practice of day
trading _ buying and selling stocks within minutes to try to profit
from small fluctuations in price. An investigation by the
subcommittee found that most day traders lose money, while day
trading firms make huge profits from commissions on their
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day trading firms we investigated charged an average
commission of $16 per trade,'' said subcommittee chairwoman Susan
Collins, R-Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The average day trader executes about 29 trades per day, and
thus has to make $450 every day just to break even. Not
surprisingly, most don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best evidence suggests that a significant majority of all
day traders _ more than 75 percent _ lose money,'' said Collins.
She said, ``I believe day trading can be fairly compared to certain
types of gambling.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the 15 day trading firms examined by subcommittee
investigators had aggregate revenues of more than $541 million in
1999 and aggregate profits of about $144 million. The revenues of
these firms grew by 276 percent from 1997 to 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no intention of proposing a ban on day trading,''
Collins said. ``But if day trading firms fail to disclose the risks
and entice unsophisticated investors with misleading ads or
exaggerated claims of profitability, regulators _ and the industry
_ must put a stop to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Webb was among thousands of Americans who saw day trading
as the solution to financial problems. Before moving to Atlanta
from the Midwest, he had lost jobs with Enterprise Rent-a-Car and
Dean Witter, the financial brokerage. His credit record was such
that his father had to co-sign a car loan. To open a trading
account with Momentum Securities Inc. in Atlanta, Webb borrowed
$30,000 from his father, Roy Webb, and another $30,000 from a
Momentum customer to whom he promised to pay 18 percent interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son lost money from the beginning,'' Wenzel said. ``His
girlfriend described him as depressed often about his financial
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering his financial failings, she testified that she was
amazed to learn that ``he was hired by Momentum to train other
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Justin Hoehn, the branch manager of Momentum Securities in
Atlanta, testified that Webb had portrayed his financial situation
differently, mentioning income from a trust fund and rental
property. Momentum now requires day traders to initially deposit at
least $50,000 and show a minimum net worth of $100,000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time his friend and roommate Webb began trading, Hoehn
explained, the requirements were more ``circumstantial.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoehn, who was out of the office when the shooting occurred,
said he did not know how much Webb had lost day trading, but that
his account contained about $20,000 on the day of his death.
</P>
<P>
   Other witnesses told the subcommittee that they were
ill-prepared for day trading and never informed of the substantial
risks. They all lost money.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee investigation found that ``many firms allow _
and even encourage _ unsuitable customers to day trade,'' said
Deborah Field, an attorney with the Securities and Exchange
Commission who led the probe. But these actions are mostly ``under
current regulatory framework _ entirely legal,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The top officers of four day trading companies _ Momentum
Securities, Providential Securities, All-Tech Direct _ and
officials from federal agencies and the securities industry are
scheduled to testify Friday before the subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
