<SLUG> BC-CLAIRE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CLAIRE DOLAN': A WOMAN WHO NEEDS A NEW JOB 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Lodge Kerrigan's elegantly gloomy film ``Claire Dolan,''
Midtown Manhattan is a forest of chilly glass towers whose
inhabitants gaze forlornly through floor-to-ceiling windows at
other glass towers in which only a few fitful stirrings of human
activity can be glimpsed.
</P>
<P>
   The opening scenes, in which the camera methodically surveys the
geometry of the architecture, establish a mood of glum urban
alienation that recalls certain 1960s European art films (and
several more recent Taiwanese films) that equated modernism with
sterility and anomie.
</P>
<P>
   The decor inside those towers is as spare and functional as
their facades. There are no signs of the glamorous interiors that
became popular in the upper echelons of corporate America during
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's title character, played with a quiet, smoldering
intensity by Katrin Cartlidge (an actress memorable for her
performances in Mike Leigh's ``Naked'' and Lars Von Triers'
``Breaking the Waves''), is an Irish immigrant who works as a
prostitute, servicing business executives in their offices and
hotel suites.
</P>
<P>
   Grim and unsmiling, Claire dispenses her favors with a cold,
mechanical self-possession. More than once one of her clients tells
her she is a ``very beautiful woman.'' But Cartlidge, with her
closely set dark eyes, thin lips and air of guarded
self-containment, is just one step away from being plain.
</P>
<P>
   Furnished with little more than a bed and a telephone answering
machine, Claire's apartment in an anonymous Manhattan high-rise
mirrors the minimalism of the offices she visits. Strangely, she
hasn't bothered to acquire the accouterments or the seductive
manners of a high-priced prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   She dresses neatly but drably. Beyond regaling regular clients
on the telephone with insincere romantic flattery
(anachronistically, she doesn't use a cell phone or a beeper but
relies on public pay phones when out of the house), she discharges
her tasks without the usual teasing wiles. When affronted by a
client, she gives as good as she gets, lashing out with a bitter,
venomous fury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Claire Dolan'' is the second feature film by Kerrigan, whose
impressive, scary debut, ``Clean, Shaven,'' went about far as a
movie could go in entering the consciousness of a schizophrenic
man. ``Claire Dolan,'' like ``Clean, Shaven,'' is also largely an
interior landscape, but one numbed with dread and cauterized
emotion.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is deliberately cagey in giving out information about
Claire. We meet her pimp, Roland Cain (Colm Meaney), who has known
her since she was an adolescent in Dublin and who brought her to
the United States. Claire has been selling her body to pay off a
sizable debt to him, but the whys and wherefores of their
arrangement are never revealed. Nor are we ever given an insight
into their relationship, although Roland obviously hates her. (Does
he have any other women working for him? The movie doesn't say.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bleakness of her circumstances, Claire isn't
entirely anesthetized. In the movie's early scenes, she is
devastated by the death of her mother (Muriel Maida) from cancer.
And when she meets and falls in love with Elton Garrett (Vincent
D'Onofrio), a rough-edged cabdriver who has his own heavy personal
baggage, the relationship that develops is intensely passionate.
</P>
<P>
   The story, such as it is, follows Claire's attempts to extricate
herself from the life she has been leading by paying off her debt,
establishing a relationship (she longs for a child) and eventually
fleeing New York.
</P>
<P>
   But the movie devotes so much of its energy to building and
sustaining a mood of urban desolation that the story never quite
jells. Especially toward the end of the film, there are huge,
frustrating gaps in the narrative.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Cartlidge's beautifully still performance, mournful one
moment, defiant the next, lets you see into Claire's soul without
editorializing or begging for our empathy. If only the movie had
done a better job of connecting the dots of her life, ``Claire
Dolan,'' which opens Friday in New York and inaugurates the new
quarterly American Independent Visions series, would be a fully
realized film. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `CLAIRE DOLAN'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Lodge Kerrigan; director of photography,
Teodoro Maniaci; edited by Kristina Boden; music by Ahrin Mishan
and Simon Fisher Turner; production designer, Sharon Lomofsky;
produced by Ann Ruark; released by the Film Society of Lincoln
Center and the Independent Feature Project, in association with
Time Warner Cable and the Sundance Channel. Running time: 95
minutes. This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Katrin Cartlidge (Claire Dolan), Colm Meaney (Roland
Cain), Muriel Maida (Claire's Mother) and Vincent D'Onofrio (Elton
Garrett).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-00 1632EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
