<SLUG> BC-IVOR-BENJAMIN-BRATT-IN-THE-NEXT-BEST-THING-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LADIES' MAN: BENJAMIN BRATT ON JULIA, MADONNA AND `THE NEXT BEST
THING' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Benjamin Bratt
with Madonna in a scene from ``The Next Best Thing.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It's every man's fantasy: At night you come home to Hollywood's
reigning female superstar _ and she's as crazy about you as you are
about her. And every morning you go off to work ... kissing
Madonna.
 &HT;    Yes, Benjamin Bratt is having a good time these days. Best known
as one of the most popular stars of television's ``Law and Order,''
he stars opposite Madonna and Rupert Everett in ``The Next Best
Thing,'' which will open March 3. Offscreen, his leading lady is no
less than Julia Roberts.
 &HT;    The movie, Bratt's first major big-screen role, casts him as the
odd man out in an unusual family relationship: He's in love with
Madonna, but she lives with her gay best friend (Everett), raising
their baby together.
 &HT;    Everett, himself openly gay, was impressed with Bratt's aplomb
in handling the controversial story line.
 &HT;    ``Ben doesn't have the classic redneck kind of attitude about
his woman or about a gay man,'' the English actor says.
 &HT;    As for Bratt, it wasn't the script that impressed him as much as
Madonna herself.
 &HT;    ``During her first break she began doing yoga,'' he recalls.
``At one point she had her right foot over her left ear and her
left foot over her right ear, and then she went into this handstand
while her feet were still pretzeled behind her neck.
 &HT;    ``I thought, `That's some woman.'''
 &HT;    Sitting in a New York hotel, Bratt _ sporting a new, wispy
goatee _ is some man, devastatingly handsome in dark slacks and a
long-sleeved, cream-colored shirt. It's not hard to believe that
Madonna would be attracted to him _ or, for that matter, that
Roberts would.
 &HT;    Since he shot the film, he says, everyone's been asking him
about the Material Girl.
 &HT;    ``She is witty, definitely sarcastic, she keeps you on your toes
and she's much prettier in person,'' Bratt says.
 &HT;    ``Someone asked me if she's a good kisser,'' he adds. ``I said,
`Well, it's a safe bet she is. She's never had any complaints.'''
 &HT;    Of course, his relationship with Madonna ended when the camera
stopped. His relationship with Roberts is far more complex, because
it takes place in the real world.
 &HT;    One minute, Bratt recalls, he was fairly anonymous, blending in
with the ``Law and Order'' ensemble as the sensitive Detective
Reynaldo ``Rey'' Curtis. The next moment, his every move was a
magnet to an army of paparazzi.
 &HT;    The actor, one of five children of a single, divorced mother of
Peruvian extraction, says that bringing Roberts home to meet the
folks in San Francisco was an experience worthy of Roberts' recent
movie-star-in-love film, ``Notting Hill'' (1999).
 &HT;    ``Oh boy,'' he says. ``On some level it was initially surreal
for them _ how could it not be? It's a great a tribute to Julia
that, after the first 10 minutes, her real down-to-earth nature
comes out, and I don't think there's any more thought about having
a star sitting in the kitchen.
 &HT;    ``When all is said and done,'' Bratt says, ``she is extremely
bright, beautiful _ a star, but a down-to-earth, simple woman, and
very accessible. I'm really thankful that she and my family got on
so well together _ I get along with her family, too.''
 &HT;    The real problems arise not in their private lives but in the
public arena, the actor says.
 &HT;    ``The worst is when you are traveling through Europe, and you're
in a hotel and you think you're enjoying your privacy,'' he says.
``Then you see someone's head pop behind a fence with a lens, being
followed by a camera-toting paparazzi.
 &HT;    ``We're not really hassled by people,'' he adds. ``Walking on
the streets of New York or any other city in America, there's
almost an invisible bubble that's created around us. People are
respectful. When they do break that bubble, it's mostly done in a
complimentary way, not fanatical.''
 &HT;    Actually, he says, dating a superstar is almost a no-win
proposition.
 &HT;    ``You get a better seat in a restaurant. It stops there,'' he
says. ``Actually, otherwise it becomes a bit of a nuisance. There's
a huge tradeoff with this kind of visibility. You lose one of your
God-given rights of privacy. That's something I hold very, very
dear and close to me, and when that gets invaded I feel threatened
and defensive about it.
 &HT;    ``But I'm learning it's part of the situation, and I have to
practice patience.''
 &HT;    Roberts, of course, is used to the limelight, and Bratt tries to
emulate her serenity in the face of its onslaught.
 &HT;    ``She knows how to handle it,'' he says. ``The only advice she's
ever given me is `No matter what you do, smile.'''
 &HT;    The constant media attention, usually accompanied by speculation
as to the state of their relationship and its future, doesn't
matter to him, the actor says.
 &HT;    ``I'm not daunted by all that stuff,'' he says. ``How we get
along with each other is what counts to us ... We are two extremely
normal _ and you can put quotes around normal _ individuals outside
of the craziness of this celebrity that she is exposed to.
 &HT;    ``And we relate like most normal couples,'' he adds. ``I'm sure
of it. We're not partygoers _ in the two and half years we've been
together, we can probably count on two hands the number of times
we've been out socially to premieres or things of that nature.
 &HT;    ``We're both homebodies,'' the actor adds with a laugh. ``We
have a close circle of friends and family that are dear to us. We
enjoy being together, going to a lot of films and going out to
dinner.''
 &HT;    Speaking of films, Bratt left ``Law and Order'' last year to
pursue a film career, and the early indications are that the gamble
has paid off. Besides ``The Next Best Thing,'' he's completed ``The
Last Producer,'' an independent feature co-starring Burt Reynolds,
and has recently returned from Australia, where he shot the
science-fiction epic ``Red Planet,'' which co-stars Val Kilmer, Tom
Sizemore and Terence Stamp.
 &HT;    ``It's one of those big blockbuster movies, about the first
manned mission to Mars,'' he says. ``I'm an action hero of sorts.
They have plans to make a doll, so I guess that makes me an action
hero.''
 c.2000 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The Next Best Thing,'' consult
the official Website at www.nextbestthingmovie.com. And don't
forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood Stars
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
