<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7402 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      02-24 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DAVE KEHR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Path To a `Psycho'
</P>
<P>
   Edward R. Pressman has been living with ``American Psycho'' for
eight years, ever since Stuart Gordon, the director of the
``Re-Animator'' films, gave him a copy of Brett Easton Ellis'
notorious best seller in 1992. ``I remember it vividly because I
was reading the book at my home in the Hollywood Hills, and I could
see downtown in the distance,'' Pressman said. ``It was ablaze, the
sky was bright with fire, and on TV people were lugging away
television sets and air-conditioners.''
</P>
<P>
   It was, in fact, the height of the Los Angeles riots. ``It was a
very impressionable period,'' he said. ``So I bought the rights.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Pressman, an independent producer based in New York
whose films include ``Badlands,'' ``Sisters'' and ``The Crow,''
that was only the beginning of the long process that led to the
premiere of ``American Psycho'' at the Sundance Film Festival last
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stuart wanted to do a real X-rated version, black and white,
very hard-core and very true to the novel,'' Pressman said. ``I
felt that was a very difficult challenge to make work, and I
started to explore other ways to solve it.''
</P>
<P>
   Other writers and directors came and went, he said, including
David Cronenberg, Oliver Stone, Rob Weiss and Ellis himself, whose
script, ``was completely pornographic and ended with a musical
number.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I saw `I Shot Andy Warhol' and set up a meeting with the
director, Mary Harron,'' Pressman said. ``She was very interested
in tackling it and thought she could find a solution to the script,
which she would do with Guinivere Turner. She reduced the
pornographic and physically disgusting elements in the book because
what she was really interested in was the social satire.''
</P>
<P>
   To play Patrick Bateman, the novel's serial-killing yuppie,
Harron had only one actor in mind: the former child star Christian
Bale (``Empire of the Sun'').
</P>
<P>
   But then an executive at Lion's Gate, the Canadian company that
had become Pressman's partner, sent the script to Leonardo
DiCaprio, red-hot from the success of ``Titanic.'' ``And lo and
behold,'' Pressman said, ``he responded, and said, `I love the
script and I want to do it.' No one, including Mary, took it too
seriously. But for a couple of months, Leonardo insisted that he
was going to do it but just wouldn't give a date. He never said no,
actually. Finally, after a couple of ultimatums, we said, `We've
got to go on and do it without you.' And so we went back to Mary,
and she was still committed to it. She stuck to what she thought
the film should be throughout all of this Hollywood madness. In the
end, she made the film she wanted to make, and we're all very happy
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, everybody but the Motion Picture Association of America,
which wanted to slap a commercially fatal NC-17 rating on the film.
Apparently it wasn't the sex or violence that disturbed the ratings
board, but a sequence in which Bale watches himself in the mirror
while sporting with two prostitutes. ``It's a scene about
self-absorption,'' Pressman said. ``If it were eliminated, it would
hurt the film significantly.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, it won't be. On Tuesday, the association
granted the film an R rating after Harron agreed to shorten a few
explicit shots of sexual positions in the controversial sequence.
Pressman's long odyssey will reach an end on April 14, when
``American Psycho'' is scheduled for a wide release.
</P>
<P>
   School Days
</P>
<P>
   Once it was called ``Strike,'' and Miramax was supposed to
release it two summers ago. But this teen comedy, starring Kirsten
Dunst, Gaby Hoffman and Rachael Leigh Cook as boarding school girls
who take drastic measures to prevent their beloved institution from
going coed, never found a place on Miramax's crowded schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Now the film's writer and director, Sarah Kernochan, and
producer, Ira Deutchman, have persuaded Miramax to let them release
the film on their own. And Deutchman, an adjunct professor in the
graduate film division of Columbia University and a respected
veteran of the independent film movement, has found a different way
to tackle the complicated logistics and limited financing of a
genuinely independent release: he has made it into homework.
Posting notices on bulletin boards at Columbia and New York
University, Deutchman recruited graduate students in film and
business who wanted some hands-on experience in movie marketing.
</P>
<P>
   He and his apprentices have come up with a new title for the
film, a new ad campaign and a new marketing strategy that will use
the Internet and a network of prep school volunteers _ ``junior
marketeers,'' Deutchman calls them _ to attract the hard-to-reach
pre-teen female audience.
</P>
<P>
   At the weekly marketing meeting in Deutchman's office on Park
Avenue South, Kernochan passed out Chupa Chups lollipops to her
volunteer staff members (cigars are no longer the oral
gratification of choice in the movie business), all bright young
minds in their early 20s. One reported on the status of the
all-important Web site (www.alliwannado.com) and another on
attempts to secure sponsorship from one of the magazines for
teen-agers, while a third hoped to obtain free samples from the
manufacturers of Midol (a product that figures prominently in ``All
I Wanna Do'') to place in the goodie bags for the film's premiere.
</P>
<P>
   ```Their energy level reminds me of what it was like when we
were younger,'' Deutchman said. ``There's no fear; it's like, come
on, let's go, what's next, what do we do now?''
</P>
<P>
   What they need to do now is find a place for the premiere party,
persuade the film's stars to appear on MTV and book the film into
two more theaters in Manhattan for its March 24 debut. ``It's at
that stage now where it's time to get relentless,'' Deutchman
concluded, sending his foot soldiers out into the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Cesar Awards &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A dark-horse candidate dominated the French Cesar Awards, the
Gallic equivalent of the Oscars, at Saturday's ceremony in Paris.
Beating popular favorites like Luc Besson's ``Jeanne d'Arc''
(called ``The Messenger'' during its brief U.S. release) and
Patrice Leconte's ``Girl on the Bridge'' was Tonie Marshall's
intimate comedy-drama ``Venus Beaute (Institut),'' which won four
awards, including best film and best director. Shown in last year's
Rendez-Vous With French Cinema series at Lincoln Center's Walter
Reade Theater, Marshall's film stars Natalie Baye as a lovelorn
beautician; it still does not have an American distributor.
</P>
<P>
   Karin Viard was named best actress for her performance as a
woman suffering from breast cancer in Solveig Anspach's ``Haut les
Coeurs!,'' which can be seen in this year's edition of Rendez-Vous
on March 11 and 12.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
