<HEADER>
A7407 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-ALAMO-HARRIGAN-1000(2     02-24 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALAMO-HARRIGAN-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORICAL NOVEL BY TEXAN BEING TOUTED AS A CAN'T-MISS BESTSELLER
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by ALAM0-REVIEW) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It seemed, for a long time, that Stephen
Harrigan was destined to be a talented writer whose books got
better reviews than sales.
</P>
<P>
   He has supported his wife and three daughters by writing
screenplays and magazine articles and by teaching. Their home in
Austin is comfortable, but wouldn't be mistaken for a mansion. The
51-year-old Harrigan's favorite accomplishment to date is earning
the respect of peers like Texas writers Jim Magnuson and Elizabeth
Crook, who praise him as a rare talent.
</P>
<P>
   But now, Harrigan's circle of admirers could be expanding.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Knopf will publish ``The Gates of the Alamo,'' a
grandiose 577-page novel of the Texas revolution that centers on
the famous battle fought in San Antonio on March 6, 1836. The novel
took Harrigan eight years to write, sandwiched between the
screenwriting and magazine gigs that paid the mortgage and the
kids' college tuition. Advance reviews from publishing's most
prestigious periodicals go beyond raves: Publishers' Weekly calls
the book ``heart-stopping, realistic ... an artful depiction of a
certain time and place,'' while Kirkus judges Harrigan's opus ``as
fine a historical novel as any in recent memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Knopf has ordered a 100,000-copy first printing, a sure sign the
publisher plans to put its full marketing force behind the book.
Harrigan, a writer with two of five previous titles already out of
print, is about to get the Stephen King/John Grisham kind of
publicity treatment. If ``The Gates of the Alamo'' makes it as
expected to the top of every bestseller list, if Harrigan and his
agent can parlay that success into a megabucks movie deal, then
middle-aged, unassuming Steve Harrigan may actually, finally,
become rich and famous.
</P>
<P>
   Or the book could sell only in the thousands, and Harrigan could
remain a relative unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Harrigan says he can handle it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all uncertain, out of my control,'' he says. ``The only
thing I'm sure of, I guess, is that I've wanted to write this book
about the Alamo for a long, long time.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   In 1955, Stephen Harrigan was 7 years old, living with his
parents in Abilene. That year, he recalls, Disney released ``Davy
Crockett: King of the Wild Frontier'' and, like kids everywhere,
Harrigan was mesmerized by actor Fess Parker fighting to the bitter
end at a movie-set Alamo.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, my parents took me to the real Alamo, and it was
just an epiphany,'' Harrigan says during lunch at an unpretentious
Mexican restaurant in north Austin. ``I still had the movie in my
head, that unforgettable ending, and to see the real ground where
it happened was overwhelming. It lodged in my imagination. By the
time I was 14 or 15 and wanted to be a writer, I thought some day I
would write a book about the Alamo.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrigan, a slight, balding man, grins as he recalls his
stumbling path to becoming an author.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to UT (Austin) and wandered through my time there
aimlessly with no educational goals,'' Harrigan says, his soft
voice almost drowned out by the clatter of utensils and buzz of
conversation from adjacent booths. ``I majored in English
literature because I wanted to be left alone to read. I graduated
in '71 and lingered in Austin, working in the school co-op and then
forming a one-man lawn-mowing company. I started trying to write
magazine articles, and eventually got one into Rolling Stone and
then a couple into the Texas Observer.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Monthly was starting up in Austin about the same time; in
1980, Harrigan joined the staff and stayed 10 years, earning a
reputation as a crack chronicler of Texas wildlife and outdoor
adventures. ``Aransas,'' his first novel, was published in 1980,
and established the pattern for his next books: It received good
reviews, sold a few thousand copies and went out of print.
</P>
<P>
   In ``1985 or so,'' Harrigan and a friend decided to try their
hand at a screenplay. ``Ocean of Storms'' was optioned by Sidney
Pollack, but has yet to be produced. Many other Harrigan
screenplays have; ``The Last of His Tribe,'' written for HBO,
garnered several awards. Recently, CBS broadcast Harrigan's
``Beyond the Prairie: The True Story of Laura Ingalls Wilder,'' and
he is currently completing a script about the late singer John
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   With regular screenplay assignments, magazine work and income
from teaching, Harrigan was financially comfortable. But his
favorite endeavor remained writing books, and there was always, in
the back of his mind, that one he wanted to write about the Alamo.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to start working every day at 8:30 in the morning, and
keep going at least until 5 p.m.,'' Harrigan says, settling in
front of his word processor in the small, backyard guest house
that's been converted into his office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason `The Gates of the Alamo' took me eight years was
that I never had more than one or two days in a row to work on it.
Finally I cleared out my schedule for a while so I could finish it.
But it seemed like it took me forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrigan first pitched an Alamo-themed novel to a publisher in
1990 ``as a book steeped in natural history, and with Jim Bowie and
Davy Crockett as protagonists. I started reading and thinking and
talking to Alamo historians. I realized right away there was a sort
of endless swamp in terms of knowledge I needed to amass. After a
while, the story just started to come out, not in a rush but
gradually, and after I got into it there was really nothing that I
had to go back and seriously reconsider.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Magnuson, director of the Texas Center for Writers at
UT-Austin and Harrigan's close friend, says he got his first
glimpse of the manuscript ``when it was about 100 pages long. You
could tell even then the book was going to be special. I thought
the world of Texas he was creating was unlike any I'd ever read
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrigan's Texas was populated by Indians and alligators and
boarding house owners and recognizably normal men, women and
children, as well as towering historical figures like Sam Houston
and Stephen F. Austin and Davy Crockett. Terrell Mott, the
fictional teen-aged boy who eventually finds himself in the middle
of the Alamo tussle, is human enough to soil himself when the first
bombardment begins; his mother, a widow, makes the mistake of
falling in love with a decent, but weak, botanist. The characters
in the book who resonate most are those least like the made-up
super-protagonists who populate most historical fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess because I'm smaller than life myself, I wanted
characters whose actions made sense to me, whose scale I could
identify with,'' Harrigan says. ``If I'd been alive in that time, I
wouldn't have been like Sam Houston or Travis. I would have been
some insignificant guy trying to live his life amid the
revolutionary chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   But in ``The Gates of the Alamo,'' Harrigan makes readers care
about the Motts, and about the Mexican soldiers under Santa Anna
and the Comanches being forced off their land by encroaching
settlers. Harrigan grew to love his own creations. One of the
book's final scenes has a key character dying in the arms of
someone who could have been, but never was, his lover.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had trouble writing that, and for now, at least, I still
can't read it,'' Harrigan admits. ``I've sort of been with these
people for eight years. When all of a sudden one of them is dead,
it's odd.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Harrigan knows his life is going to change for the next
few months. Knopf is ready to send him around the country touting
``The Gates of the Alamo.'' He could be buried under fan mail.
People could come from miles around to look at his house, just as
they do the home of actor Matthew McConaughey, who lives down the
street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that kind of larger success could be temporarily
welcome,'' Harrigan says. ``There was a time in my life when I
suspect I would have liked to be famous. But it has no appeal to me
now. I know how superficial celebrity is.''
</P>
<P>
   Knopf anticipates Harrigan having to cope with newfound fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe `The Gates of the Alamo' will be a bestseller,''
says Knopf publicist Kathy Zuckerman. ``People who have read it
have compared it to `Lonesome Dove.'''
</P>
<P>
   It is helpful to recall that, before ``Lonesome Dove'' (and the
success of ``Terms of Endearment'' as a film), Archer City's Larry
McMurtry was, like Harrigan, considered a talented but regional
writer. ``Lonesome Dove'' won McMurtry the Pulitzer Prize for
fiction, and the ensuing TV miniseries based on the book cemented
his reputation with the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gates of the Alamo'' could do the same for Harrigan. He
admits the possibility is intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if, let's say, `The Gates of the Alamo' sells 40,000
copies instead of 400,000, that's still 10 times more than any of
my other books have sold,'' Harrigan says. ``So if things don't go
the way the publisher expects, I'll just try to write my next book.
I've got my life to live.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gates of the Alamo'' has already provided one lasting
career benefit for its author.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real lesson to me here is about subject matter,'' Harrigan
says. ``The Alamo still resonates with everybody. Previously, I've
written about obscure things. From now on, I want to write about
things people are interested in.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7720, or e-mail:
jguinn(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
