<SLUG> BC-TV-BEACHBOYS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BEACH BOYS' NOTHING TO SING ABOUT, BUT DAD MAKES BIG SPLASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watching the second night of ``The Beach Boys: An American
Family'' is like being hooked up to an IV drip of daytime drama, so
it's hard to say the four-hour ABC miniseries is a bona fide
chart-topper. But it's easy to say why the first night is so much
better. Two words: Kevin Dunn.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn doesn't play one of the Beach Boys. At least not one of the
Beach Boys America embraced in the early '60s. He plays Murry
Wilson, the tough-loving father of Brian, Carl and Dennis Wilson,
uncle of Mike Love. Portrayed as a frustrated songwriter who was
always the next tune away from getting his music played on ``The
Lawrence Welk Show,'' Murry knew enough about the business to be
dangerous. Extremely dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Proud of his boys and intensely jealous at the same time, he
controlled their early rise to pop stardom thoroughly and
ruthlessly. He became the de facto leader of the band because
Brian, the oldest Wilson son and acknowledged musical prodigy, was
reluctant to stand up to his dad, who he assumed was acting in the
band's best interests.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn's powerful performance carries Sunday's first installment
on a wave of intimidation so convincing, it's a wonder any of the
Beach Boys ever grew up to be a man. Monday's second part offers
substantial evidence that the process was certainly a difficult
one, especially for Brian and Dennis Wilson. But, with Dunn getting
less screen time, it also offers viewers little in the way of
compelling performance.
</P>
<P>
   Brian is the focal character in Part 2, which begins at a point
where he has stopped performing with the band to concentrate on
song-writing and, it would appear, drug-taking. Though adept at
mimicking Brian's idiosyncratic mannerisms, particularly his
crooked-mouthed way of speaking and singing, Frederick Weller never
successfully connects with Brian Wilson's complex, troubled psyche.
Near the end, Weller's performance is more cartoonlike than
live-action, especially as Wilson gains weight, grows a beard and
withdraws from family and society.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Love, Brian's cousin and co-writer on many of the
group's hits, says: ``There is just too much bad karma out there.''
Maybe so, but the real problem with ``The Beach Boys: An American
Family'' is inadequate support for Dunn's spectacular turn as Murry
Wilson. With the possible exception of Matt Letscher, who plays
Love with a measure of passion approaching Dunn's, none of the
other band members makes a splash. And Alley Mills, as Murry's
long-suffering wife, Audree, seems stuck in the same maternal
character she played on ``The Wonder Years.''
</P>
<P>
   The film comes from Craig Zadan and Neil Meron, the closest
thing television has to producers of Broadway-style musicals.
They're responsible for this season's remake of ``Annie,'' last
season's ``Cinderella'' and an upcoming movie about Judy Garland.
But ``The Beach Boys,'' while providing snippets of many popular
tunes, is less about the music and more about the melodramatic
conflicts between Murry and the band, between the band members and
their girlfriends/wives, and ultimately between each member of the
group. It's good, theatrical conflict, precisely the sort of
material that was missing from last week's two-hour film about
Little Richard on NBC, but where ``Little Richard'' was too much
music and not enough story, ``The Beach Boys'' ends up being
exactly the opposite, despite Sunday night's well-balanced
introduction to a band that asked the question ``Wouldn't It Be
Nice?'' but never seemed to get a satisfactory answer.
</P>
<P>
   The Beach Boys: An American Family. Four-hour TV miniseries
about the band that popularized the California surf sound of the
1960s. Starring Kevin Dunn, Alley Mills, Frederick Weller, Nick
Stabile, Ryan Northcott, Matt Letscher, Ned Vaughn, Jesse Caron and
Dublin James. Sunday and Monday on ABC. Parental guideline rating:
TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: First night, B+
</P>
<P>
   Grade: Second night, C-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-00 1644EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
