<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7410 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-ALAMO-REVIEW-1100(2Ta     02-24 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALAMO-REVIEW-1100(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMBER THIS: `ALAMO' RIVALS `LONESOME DOVE'
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies ALAMO-HARRIGAN) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gates of the Alamo''
</P>
<P>
   by Stephen Harrigan
</P>
<P>
   Fiction
</P>
<P>
   Knopf, $25
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   We have the first great American novel of the 21st century. It
is ``The Gates of the Alamo,'' a book by Stephen Harrigan whose
subject is obvious from the title and whose quality is almost
inestimable. Harrigan has given us a story with everything _ brisk
pace, sufficient grounding in history, fictional characters whose
engaging personalities help them blend perfectly with real-life
icons like Davy Crockett and Jim Bowie, and yet with the latter
presented as human beings, too, not glossy caricatures. This is
storytelling at its finest, and an opportunity to learn and be
royally entertained at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Any work of historically based fiction must be, essentially,
responsible speculation on the part of the author. Popular
knowledge of the Alamo is based as much on legend as on fact. We
know that William Barret Travis, Davy Crockett, Jim Bowie and their
small band of defenders died on the morning of March 6, 1836, when
Mexican President-General Santa Anna concluded a short siege by
sending his army over the walls to annihilate the outnumbered
rebels. Soon afterward, a Texican rabble-army commanded by Sam
Houston returned the bloody favor at San Jacinto, and Texas had won
its independence.
</P>
<P>
   But within these limited events is room for unlimited
supposition. The creative staff members working for Walt Disney
used their imaginations, causing most Americans of a certain age to
still believe Davy Crockett looked just like actor Fess Parker.
Proud Texans dismiss as fable any rumors that Crockett was
summarily executed after surrendering instead of dying valiantly,
crushing a few last Mexican skulls with the butt of his rifle.
Travis did, or didn't, draw a line in the courtyard dirt with the
point of his sword and ask all those willing to give their lives
for Texas freedom to step across it and die defending a
strategically questionable church/fort in the face of
insurmountable odds.
</P>
<P>
   We view Harrigan's interpretation through the eyes of one of the
finest fictional casts assembled in years. The author bookends
events of the 1820s and '30s with a 1911 parade through the streets
of San Antonio. An honored participant in the procession is
91-year-old Terrell Mott, a former city mayor, but, more
gloriously, ``messenger of the Alamo and last surviving hero of San
Jacinto.'' Mott, responding to his driver's question about whether
Travis really drew that line in the dirt (he didn't), is moved to
think about all those events of oh, so many years ago ...
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen-year-old Terrell Mott is, at least nominally, Harrigan's
protagonist. Other main fictional characters (as opposed to real
men and women who populate these pages) include Terrell's mother,
Mary, a widow operating an inn in Refugio; Edmund McGowan, a
middle-aged botanist whose contractual agreements with Santa Anna
and the Mexican government conflict with his eventual role in the
defense of the Alamo; Telesforo Villasenor, ``third son of a Pueblo
wool merchant,'' who believes he can satisfy burning ambition by
impressing Santa Anna with his willingness to carry out any order;
and dozens of other men, women and children, American Indians as
well as Mexicans and Texicans.
</P>
<P>
   It's a colorful human stew, fully flavored with lingering
appearances by real-life figures. Stephen F. Austin wanders ``City
of Mexico'' streets while still under house arrest for possible
sedition. Jim Bowie puts together shady land deals. Santa Anna
wonders if Mexico's southernmost holdings might offer financial
windfalls from the harvesting of primitive chewing gum. Imagined or
real, Harrigan's entire ensemble interacts wonderfully. Through
them, readers understand that the events of the Texas revolution
were less accidental than inevitable. Neither side in the emerging
conflict is presented as either saintly or demonic.
</P>
<P>
   Harrigan is especially adept at describing the near-casual
violence that was so characteristic of colonial Texas. Readers will
flinch at an early scene in which Mary Mott is disfigured by
marauding Indians but understand why, after such a horrifying
experience, she can go on with her life, scarred but still strong.
</P>
<P>
   The honesty implicit in every line of the book is exemplified by
Mary's relationship with Terrell. They argue at one point, and he
leaves, going off to join Jim Bowie's Texas volunteers. Mary
follows, accompanied by the prissy McGowan, who isn't certain how
to court her. Mother pursues son in part because their quarrel was
her fault, in part because she senses the immensity of events yet
to come. But nothing, from her search for Terrell to the young
man's reaction when he finally is joined by his mother, is tossed
off to fill a few pages between more explosive events. Readers will
be enthralled by the big scenes because they have learned to care
about the characters in smaller ones.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``The Gates of the Alamo'' portrays history before and
after the battle it describes without glorifying, the core of the
book is found in the long section focusing on the mission/fort in
San Antonio. All the major characters come together here, and while
we know the battle's outcome, we can't be certain how each will be
affected by it.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   Harrigan doesn't betray his readers by sanitizing events, or by
allowing previously three-dimensional characters to suddenly become
faultless superheroes. Davy Crockett is engagingly outgoing, but
his easy familiarity smacks, to Terrell, of a politician who can't
stop hustling votes. Travis is an immature commander whose
posturing compromises otherwise sound judgment. Bowie is brave but,
in some ways, morally reprehensible. As for the attacking Mexicans,
Harrigan does a superb job depicting them as equally flawed _ and
decent.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the book's finest scenes depict Santa Anna's army
overcoming incredible misfortune to reach the Alamo at all. Readers
may remember the best of Harrigan's brilliant passages describing a
freak blizzard and its effect on the men trying to survive trudging
through it:
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally it became apparent that the army could travel no
further. The road was lost beneath the snow, and in the tumultuous
whiteness all human instincts about which way to go were buried as
well. ... They cringed in the cold wind, clutching their
pathetically thin blankets over their shoulders. Their mustaches
and eyebrows were sheathed in ice. Each one of their faces bore a
look of perfect, abject pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Harrigan makes us identify so much with these men (and
the women following them), we care when, having survived this
frostbitten ordeal, many die in the attack on the Alamo.
</P>
<P>
   All these things add up to something wonderful. But a reviewer's
frustration in describing this or any other novel as ``great''
comes from the necessity for comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Potential readers want to know which classic the new novel is
most like. Among earlier Alamo-related literature, Harrigan
acknowledges debts to Stephen L. Hardin's ``Texian Illiad,'' Jeff
Long's ``Duel of Eagles'' and Walter Lord's ``A Time to Stand.''
These are all quality works, but none parlayed literary excellence
into overwhelming public response.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gates of the Alamo'' has the potential to join
history-based novels such as ``Gone With the Wind'' and ``Lonesome
Dove'' as eternal bestsellers, as well as critically acclaimed
titles. It is similar to these two evergreens in that its fictional
characters, presented against the backdrop of history, pulsate with
fascinating qualities. Scarlett and Rhett, Call and Gus, Terrell
and Mary are as real to us as the Civil War and cattle drives and
the Texas revolution. And, like ``Gone With the Wind'' and
``Lonesome Dove,'' ``The Gates of the Alamo'' should someday make
an epic movie.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also differences. After reading Margaret
Mitchell's ``Gone With the Wind,'' we think about the great love
story between Scarlett and Rhett rather than the Civil War. In
``The Gates of the Alamo,'' Harrigan's made-up characters are
mesmerizing, too, but within the context of history. Larry McMurtry
gave us printed-word wonders in ``Lonesome Dove,'' but his
characters there, Call and Gus and Blue Duck, are all sort of
literary superheroes, larger than life even amid the elasticized
boundaries of fiction. Harrigan offers us ``people,'' and their
flaws are on a human scale. When the first cannonballs fall on the
Alamo, Terrell Mott soils himself. It's not heroic, but it's very
natural.
</P>
<P>
   So ``The Gates of the Alamo'' is and isn't the same as any other
wonderful historic fiction you've previously read and loved.
Reading it in the expectation it will be exactly like something
else will only be a disservice to Harrigan's magnum opus and the
other books to which it might be compared. Calling a book ``great''
ought to imply that it can stand on its own merits. ``The Gates of
the Alamo'' certainly can _ but if comparing it to ``Gone With the
Wind'' and ``Lonesome Dove'' will induce more people to read it,
then by all means compare away.
</P>
<P>
   It may also be necessary to point out that ``The Gates of the
Alamo'' will remain a stunning literary achievement even if it
doesn't make any bestseller lists. Quality doesn't dictate sales;
otherwise, authors like Paul Auster, Pam Houston, John Edgar
Wideman and Bill Bryson would be rubbing financial elbows with Bill
Gates and Ross Perot.
</P>
<P>
   Harrigan, 51, has written five other books, fiction and
nonfiction, but they're mostly out of print. So, even if ``The
Gates of the Alamo'' only sells in the tens of thousands instead of
hundreds of thousands, it won't be the last novel we read by
Harrigan. As a seasoned pro, he'll shrug and try to write something
even better.
</P>
<P>
   But ``The Gates of the Alamo'' is such a gift to readers that it
would be more tragic for its potential audience than its author if
it doesn't sell well. Superior authors _ and Harrigan obviously is
one _ write first for the sake of the work, not income or fame.
</P>
<P>
   It would be nice, for Stephen Harrigan, if ``The Gates of the
Alamo'' becomes the all-time blockbuster it clearly deserves to be.
Books, ultimately, though, should be written for readers, and ``The
Gates of the Alamo'' will reward anyone who turns its pages. Knopf
promises the book will be in local stores on Tuesday. Do yourself a
favor _ buy it, read it, savor it.
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7720, or e-mail:
jguinn(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
