<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7413 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-JUDY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      02-24 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JUDY BERLIN': IN SLEEPY SUBURBIA, A TOTAL ECLIPSE OF THE HEART 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: This is a recap review) 
(af) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Judy Berlin'' was shown as part of last year's New
Directors/New Films series. Following are excerpts from Stephen
Holden's review, which appeared in The New York Times last March
26. The film opens Friday in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Much of ``Judy Berlin,'' Eric Mendelsohn's evocatively eerie
meditation on modern suburbia, takes place during what may be the
longest solar eclipse known to movies. That solar event in the
middle of a sleepy late September afternoon draws the lonely,
withdrawn inhabitants of a middle-class Long Island town out of
their immaculate houses to wander through the deserted streets like
zombies stirring to life after a long, silent sleep.
</P>
<P>
   As they encounter one another in an apocalyptic gloom, in which
the street lights seem to cast a nuclear glow, they tentatively
reach out to reconnect in ways they haven't in years.
</P>
<P>
   The first feature film of Mendelsohn, a former costume design
assistant to Woody Allen, ``Judy Berlin'' is set in Babylon on Long
Island, but it feels more like that eternal television limbo of
dark shadows and anxious faces, ``The Twilight Zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Suburban alienation and boredom may have been done to death by
movies and by ``The Twilight Zone'' itself, many of whose episodes
were saturated in suburban angst. But Mendelsohn's fusion of
science fiction and Chekhovian melancholy finds a fresh perspective
on a familiar theme.
</P>
<P>
   The black-and-white cinematography helps give this contemporary
story a timeless aura. Like ``Pleasantville,'' which ``Judy
Berlin'' sometimes resembles, the movie has the stifling ethos of
an eternally rerunning 1950s sitcom whose characters are either
tranquilized or sleepwalking.
</P>
<P>
   The movie feels especially '50s when it goes indoors and the
camera lingers over furniture, kitchen appliances and cabinets full
of neatly arranged bric-a-brac.
</P>
<P>
   It is the filmmaker's subtly drawn characters that keep ``Judy
Berlin'' from becoming mired in suburban-angst cliches. Madeline
Kahn and Bob Dishy are Alice and Arthur Gold, a compulsively talky
housewife and her taciturn husband, an elementary school principal
who exudes a deep unspoken disappointment and fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   The couple have a 30-year-old son, David (Aaron Harnick), an
aspiring filmmaker recently returned from Los Angeles who wanders
around the house in a state of agitated depression, fighting back
tears.
</P>
<P>
   The movie crosscuts among members of the Gold household, their
neighbors and the school where Arthur presides as principal. The
fall term has just begun, and Sue Berlin (Barbara Barrie), an
excessively polite and buttoned-up teacher, is instructing the
pupils on how to view the imminent solar eclipse without hurting
their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of her demonstration, Dolores Engler (Bette
Henritze), a retired teacher with Alzheimer's disease, wanders into
the classroom and momentarily commands the children's attention.
The clash of authority, in which Arthur intercedes, leaves Sue in
tears. As Arthur comforts her, their unexpressed romantic feelings
well up unexpectedly.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to Sue's unhappiness is the imminent departure for Los
Angeles of her spunky daughter Judy (Edie Falco), an aspiring
actress who has been working in period costume as a milkmaid in a
historical village.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's wittiest scene follows a group of tourists around
this make-believe 1857 farm as a guide explains in wooden tones the
grueling rituals of mid-19th-century agricultural life on Long
Island. The comparison between then and now is tacit. Life may not
be as hard today, but it is just as boring.
</P>
<P>
   Judy, whom Falco plays with a winning verve, is the only live
wire in this heap of downed power lines. Garrulous and optimistic,
she is about to undertake the same journey westward that David
made. And when the two, who were high school classmates, run into
each other on the street, you can feel the attraction of opposites.
Her optimism rushes to fill his despair, while his gloom tugs her
down to earth.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the dramatic tension of a movie that at times moves too
slowly derives from a sense that the filmmaker is biting his tongue
to keep from turning these people into biting satirical
caricatures. At first Kahn's Alice seems like the kind of
insufferable yammerer who would drive anyone mad.
</P>
<P>
   But as the movie goes along, her inane chatter seems more like a
desperate psychic survival tool. And at a moment when she fears she
has lost her husband, she shows a flash of insight. ``I ground him
down,'' she observes bluntly.
</P>
<P>
   Dishy gives the film's deepest performance as a man so weary and
long-suffering that all his dialogue comes in carefully measured
murmurs. ``Judy Berlin'' is the rare movie in which the pauses,
silences and things that remain unsaid by the characters are as
eloquent as anything that comes out of their mouths.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
