<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7418 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT &LR;      02-24 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A 10th Life For `Cats'?
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With sales like this, it should have closed years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the five days since ``Cats,'' the longest-running show in
Broadway history, announced that it would close in June, something
close to pandemonium has set in at the box office at the Winter
Garden Theater. Sales have gone from torpid to torrid, with $1.1
million worth of tickets sold by midday Thursday and requests
coming from around the world. Nearly 400 television stations in the
United States reported on the closing, said Bill Evans, a spokesman
for the show, in addition to outlets from Argentina to Japan. Even
Keith Richards, he of the Rolling Stones, made a special request
for tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen years after it opened, ``Cats'' is the hottest show on
Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   All of which prompts the inevitable question: Might it (gulp) be
extended?
</P>
<P>
   Phil Smith, an executive with the Shubert Organization, which
owns the Winter Garden, was slightly oblique on this issue, saying
that the closing date of June 25 was set, but allowing that such
intense sales _ if they persist _ could not be ignored. (Show
officials did discount tabloid reports that the show might move to
another theater.) Unsold tickets for the three shows on June 24 and
25 have been pulled from the box office, presumably to ensure that
VIPs have seats for the closing weekend.
</P>
<P>
   If, of course, that is the closing weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting in the Wings
</P>
<P>
   An opening Thursday night, 350 miles to the northwest, that may
well determine the final entry of the spring season: ``Enigma
Variations,'' by Eric-Emmanuel Schmitt, at the Royal Alexandra
Theater in Toronto. The play, about a reclusive writer who is
visited by a young journalist, stars Donald Sutherland and John
Rubinstein.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation is that it will transfer to the Brooks Atkinson
Theater in April if the reviews are strong. ``Enigma Variations''
played in Los Angeles last spring, receiving generally good
reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from Toronto, Emanuel Azenberg, the play's producer,
said that reviews were expected Friday and Saturday in the Toronto
papers, meaning a decision on a transfer to Manhattan would
probably be made by early next week.
</P>
<P>
   Revivals With Ambition
</P>
<P>
   The fall season is beginning to take shape. In Los Angeles,
producers said that the revival of ``Finian's Rainbow'' would play
in the Ahmanson Theater from July 12 to Sept. 3 in what is expected
to be a pre-Broadway run. The revival of the 1947 musical, by
Burton Lane and E.Y. Harburg, received almost unanimously good
reviews in Cleveland and Miami last fall, but producers were unable
to book a Broadway house in an especially packed season.
</P>
<P>
   The booking at the Ahmanson confirms the postponement of another
musical: ``The Night They Raided Minsky's,'' which was to play at
the theater this summer. The director of that musical, Mike
Ockrent, died of leukemia in December and no new director has been
named.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, rehearsals will begin in early October for ``A
Thousand Clowns,'' a revival of the 1962 comedy by Herb Gardner. In
a Magnum-size stage debut, Tom Selleck is to play the role of
Murray Burns, the surly, underemployed writer whose idea of
foreplay is to strum the ukulele. He said it was a character he has
wanted to play since he was a drama student in Los Angeles, his
hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``In acting class, when they'd say, `Put up a scene for us,' I'd
bring in Murray Burns,'' he said. Directors did not approve, mind
you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 6 foot 4,'' he said. ``I was always being asked to do the
other guy, the guy who always gets the girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Selleck, 55, said he had approached Gardner in 1996 about doing
the play but that another version was already in the works for the
Roundabout Theater Co. That production received poor reviews after
its star, Robert Klein, and its director, Gene Saks, left shortly
before its opening.
</P>
<P>
   This time plans are for a short run in Austin, Texas, in
November before a move to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Selleck, who has never been paid to act in a play, said he was
``appropriately terrified.'' But, he said, there is at least one
collateral benefit: ``I've never been able to play an instrument
and got to get serious about the ukulele now.''
</P>
<P>
   Big Man on Stage
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Vilanch is not exactly typical star material. With a
basketball belly, a head of blond Chia Pet hair and ever-present
pink-rimmed glasses, he looks slightly like a Teletubby crossed
with Animal, the crazed drummer from ``The Muppet Show.''
</P>
<P>
   But the fame factor has been growing for the witty Vilanch, who
has written celebrity patter for the Academy Awards for the last
decade. A regular on ``Hollywood Squares'' since last year, he was
also the subject of a documentary, ``Get Bruce,'' and he was
caricatured on ``Saturday Night Live'' last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's confirming his new star status with a one-man show,
``Almost Famous,'' which will open at the Westbeth Theater Center
in the West Village on April 25. Vilanch, a former reporter and
``sit-down comic,'' said the show would include ``musings on my
life in the comedy gulag, some of my journalistic misadventures, a
few songs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I don't have,'' he added, ``is a nightmare
decent into booze and pills.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-00 1654EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
