<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7430 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ZIMBABWE-AIDS-$ADV26-     02-24 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-AIDS-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN AIDS-RAVAGED ZIMBABWE, GROUP OF FORMER PROSTITUTES SPREAD
WORD OF SAFE SEX, AIDS PREVENTION
 &HT;    (800&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Feb. 26 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GWERU, Zimbabwe _ In back of the Msika beer hall, a ruckus is
being raised.
</P>
<P>
   As the bemused men _ many of them peering through bloodshot eyes
_ look on from the shade of the Msika's veranda, about 20 women in
blue denim skirts and white blouses cavort joyfully to their own
songs and drums.
</P>
<P>
   In a swaying semi_circle, they swing their hips and clap their
hands. In their native Shona language, they sing catchy tunes about
the virtues of wearing condoms and going to the hospital as soon as
AIDS symptoms appear.
</P>
<P>
   These women know what they are talking about: Each is a former
prostitute, and each is on a mission.
</P>
<P>
   The women are part of a 350_member organization known as the
GWAPA _ Gweru Women AIDS Prevention Association _ which began here
six years ago as a grassroots campaign to do something about the
epidemic that threatens to decimate Africa.
</P>
<P>
   New statistics show that 23.3 million people in sub-Saharan
Africa are infected with the AIDS virus, compared to less that one
million in all of North America. In Zimbabwe, about 26 percent of
the country's 12 million people have AIDS. Among prostitutes, the
infection rate is twice as high.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the United States and Europe, AIDS in Africa infects more
women than men, and the HIV virus most often is transmitted through
heterosexual contact.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS prevention officials believe that curbing the region's
prostitution trade _ or at least making their business safer _ is
key to getting the spread of HIV, the virus that causes AIDS, under
control.
</P>
<P>
   While countless programs sanctioned by governments and
humanitarian organizations have failed to make much of a dent in
the AIDS crisis here, GWAPA _ whose members are most often referred
to respectfully as ``the ladies'' _ seems to be working.
</P>
<P>
   While no scientific study has been performed of the program,
which seems to have sprung up nearly spontaneously in 1994, city
officials swear by it. ``I can say honestly that we have seen a
reduction in HIV infections,'' said Elisabeth Xaba the medical
director of Gweru, a largely agricultural city of about 200,000 in
the central Zimbabwean plains.
</P>
<P>
   Xaba believes that GWAPA is an example of a traditional African
approach to solving problems that may work better than programs and
solutions imposed from the outside. ``That tradition of saying,
'What do we need to do to solve the problem, and then solving it,'
that's what we have not had.''
</P>
<P>
   The city has been supportive of the ladies' boisterous crusade
through the town's 11 beer halls. It started with about 30 members
and continues to recruit more, focusing not only on prostitutes but
also widowed and divorced women who often end up as prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the ladies have plied their trade in the same beer halls
they now enter to preach the gospel of monogamy and safe sex. They
also try to recruit working prostitutes, who descend on beer halls
each day in search of customers with a few dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was addicted to the beer halls,'' says Gertrude Chaidende, a
cheerful 40-year-old woman who says her husband divorced her
because she couldn't have children. ``I had a real reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   As with many of the GWAPA women, Chaidende became a prostitute
largely because there are few other ways for a single woman to make
money in Zimbabwe, which has an unemployment rate of more than 50
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Many have children and say they were reduced to turning tricks
for the equivalent of US$3.50 to US$7.50 each so they could get
money for food, school fees and uniforms. Zimbabwe offers no free
education.
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Nyamhunda, a 34-year-old mother of three, said she had no
choice. ``My husband left me in 1996 and went to South Africa,''
she says. ``I was forced into prostitution, and it was a very big
problem to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   GWAPA's motto is ``Making Up for the Lost Time.''
</P>
<P>
   The group _ which practices a robust and straightforward
democracy under the gentle guidance of city health workers _ has
taken on the task of seeking alternate ways for its members to make
a living.
</P>
<P>
   It divided the membership into groups that intend to generate
income by catering, growing and selling produce, soap-making and
raising poultry.
</P>
<P>
   The group also supports the 30 children left behind by the 14
members _ many of them from among the founders _ who have died from
AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, the city signed a $10-a-year lease with the
ladies on an abandoned 11_acre farm, where they already have
installed a corn crop and a few dozen chickens. They are trying to
raise money to renovate the dilapidated brick house on the property
as a headquarters and teaching center. The U.S. and British
embassies here have kicked in enough to renovate two rooms and
provide some tables and chairs.
</P>
<P>
   The city's mayor, James Bwerazuva, is obviously proud of the
program and believes it can be exported to other African cities.
``AIDS has been the scare that has overtaken everybody,'' Bwerazuva
said during a brief conversation this week at City Hall. ``It was
imperative that the city do something to check the advance of AIDS
in the community.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In addition to their frequent appearances at beer halls and
brothels, the ladies _ and even a few male members _ also take
their message to workplaces.
</P>
<P>
   The message seems to be getting through.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the Msika beer hall. The women move table to table using
a wooden model to demonstrate the proper techniques in putting on
and removing condoms.
</P>
<P>
   Sipping at the large plastic container of the pungent,
tea-colored local beer, the men and women study intently, breaking
into laughter when the lesson becomes too explicit.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Binga, a man in his 40s, pauses from his beer to offer
his support.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're doing is good because some people can't learn any
other way,'' he said, taking a sip and gesturing toward the GWAPA
women. ``And these ladies, they know what they're talking about.
</P>
<P>
   (Contributions to GWAPA should be sent to: GWAPA Project
Coordinator; c/o Gweru City Health Department; Box 278; Gweru,
Zimbabwe).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
