<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7431 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-APPLES-ATLANTA-4TAKES     02-24 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLES-ATLANTA-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CITY IN FULL: VENERABLE, IMPATIENT ATLANTA 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This is a city without a historic core, a city in
constant evolution _ a Deep South version, you might say, of Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   It has a past, of course, a real one as well as the one that
Margaret Mitchell so vividly imagined in ``Gone With the Wind.'' A
decisive Civil War battle was fought over this ground, and the
momentous civil rights movement of the 1960s had its principal
headquarters here. That most American of products, Coca-Cola, was
invented here.
</P>
<P>
   But Atlanta, a city in a hurry, keeps putting its past behind
it. If not for the Cyclorama depicting the fighting of 1864 and the
superlative Atlanta History Center, with its evocations of Henry W.
Grady, the great newspaper editor, and Bobby Jones, the golfer,
and, yes, William Tecumseh Sherman, who burned the city down, a
visitor might easily come here and miss Atlanta's past altogether.
</P>
<P>
   This, after all, is the vibrant, business-minded capital of the
New South, proud to have played host to the 1996 Olympic Games,
pleased to promote itself as ``The World's Next Great City'' and
not another tradition-bound vestige of the Old South.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta had never been a true Old Southern city like Savannah
or Charleston or Richmond, where wealth had originated with the
land,'' Tom Wolfe wrote in his novel ``A Man in Full'' in 1998.
``Atlanta was an offspring of the railroad business. It had been
created from scratch barely 150 years ago, and people had been
making money there on the hustle ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   Quite so. Atlanta, or rather the Atlanta region, is one of the
global capitals of New Money, much of it made in real estate. It
goes to build the trophy houses in the ritzy residential area along
West Paces Ferry Road in Buckhead, near the History Center, and to
buy the BMWs and Land Rovers that clog the parking lots around
Buckhead's many shopping centers and to pay for the fine food and
drink in the neighborhood's glossy restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   That is one face of Atlanta, but there are many more. Start with
Downtown, bustling by day, much less so at night; people work there
but don't play there, and Centennial Olympic Park, created for the
1996 games, has not quite pulled the area together the way the city
fathers had hoped. Then there is Midtown, staging a comeback as a
pleasant place to live, as well as the poorer and shabbier and
mostly African-American south side of town.
</P>
<P>
   It is in Virginia-Highland, a walkable neighborhood of bars,
boutiques and bookshops, and close-in Inman Park that the city
shows its charm, especially in spring, when dogwood blossoms
brighten the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Put all that and more together, and you have a compact,
relatively small city of 400,000.
</P>
<P>
   A Truer Picture
</P>
<P>
   But that defines Atlanta only in a governmental sense. To get a
truer picture, you must focus on an unruly 17-county sprawl
spreading ever outward, with no mountains or seacoast in the way,
across Cobb and DeKalb, Gwinnett and Forsyth and Cherokee and a
dozen other counties, home to some 3.5 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the nation's 10 fastest-growing counties lie within
commuting range of Atlanta, and their exploding populations have
helped make Georgia the 10th largest state. But with growth, with
prosperity, with the shady trees and tidy yards of the suburbs,
have come problems: higher taxes to pay for infrastructure, air and
water pollution, and nerve-shattering drives to and from work.
Drivers here endure the longest average commute in the country _ a
34-mile round trip every working day, often snarled by gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club calls Atlanta the most sprawl-threatened large
city in the United States; an official of the American Farmland
Trust termed it ``the poster child for sprawl.'' Stung by those
descriptions, the state government is working on tactics to bring
greater order to the region.
</P>
<P>
   How much such things bother you depends on where you sit. My
friend Colin Campbell, a newspaper columnist, lives in Midtown and
wishes more suburbanites would move there. It still has a slightly
hollowed-out feeling, he said. But our host at lunch, former Mayor
Sam Massell, now known as the unofficial mayor of Buckhead, which
houses 15 percent of Atlanta's population and pays 45 percent of
its taxes, said the only real option to more sprawl was greater
density in town, with more smog and bigger traffic jams.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation Hub
</P>
<P>
   Originally, Atlanta was called Terminus, but that was a
misnomer. It has always been about linkage. It came into being as
the place where the railroads from the bustling port cities of
Mobile and Charleston and Savannah met the line running south from
Chattanooga, which is what made it such a strategic objective in
the Civil War. Later, Atlanta became the southeastern hub of the
highway system, where Interstates 20, 75 and 85 meet.
</P>
<P>
   The civil aviation network, too. Even on your way to heaven,
Southerners used to say, you have to change planes in Atlanta.
Atlanta's airport pioneered instrument approaches and air traffic
control, and today it vies with Chicago's O'Hare for the title of
the nation's busiest.
</P>
<P>
   Several generations of visionaries have made possible the city's
rise from the ashes of defeat. They thoroughly disproved the
prophecy of a Union soldier, Pfc. Theodore Upson, who wrote in his
diary after the Battle of Atlanta in September 1864: ``We have
wholly destroyed Atlanta. I don't think that any people will want
to live there now.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Grady was the first. As the editor of The Atlanta
Constitution, he argued after the Civil War that the salvation of
his ruined city, state and region lay in attracting northern
investment to a ``New South,'' a phrase he coined. In a famous
speech in New York in 1886, he assured the New England Society that
Southerners had accepted the outcome of the war and bore the North
no ill will.
</P>
<P>
   His vision of good race relations _ ``sunshine everywhere and
all the time,'' as he put it _ was never realized in his lifetime.
The South remained the nation's economic stepchild, and Atlanta's
history was marred by several spasms of intolerance, including the
1906 race riots, in which whites attacked blacks, and the 1913
lynching of Leo Frank, a Jew from Brooklyn. Anti-semitism reared
its head more recently in the 1958 bombing of a synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   When the federal government ceased enforcing black rights, Jim
Crow laws brought on segregation in restaurants, hotels and other
public places. Blacks were denied the vote. But they built
successful parallel institutions, including churches, newspapers,
radio stations, banks, insurance companies and two of the nation's
best predominantly African-American colleges, Morehouse for men and
Spelman for women. Between the world wars, Auburn Avenue (``Sweet
Auburn'') became a regional mecca for blacks.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola, Atlanta's first great international business, was
built by Robert W. Woodruff, who took a tonic developed in 1886 by
Dr. John Stith Pemberton, a local chemist, and peddled it around
the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Woodruff philanthropies, large and small, are inescapable in
Atlanta. The World of Coca-Cola, a self-aggrandizing corporate
museum where the Coke is free but the admission isn't, has a
blinking electronic sign informing wide-eyed visitors that more
than 6 trillion, 39 billion bottles have been sold. So the recent
news that the company was changing CEOs and eliminating 6,000 jobs
worldwide, including 2,500 in Atlanta, hit the city like a tornado.
</P>
<P>
   Where King Started
</P>
<P>
   The great visionary of the civil rights movement, of course, was
the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., born in a clapboard and
shingle house that still stands on Auburn Avenue, not far from
Ebenezer Baptist Church, where King and his father preached. He won
the Nobel Peace Prize in 1964, at the age of 35, the youngest
person ever to do so. He is buried in a marble tomb in a reflecting
pool at the Martin Luther King Jr. Center for Nonviolent Social
Change, also on Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street at a National Park Visitors Center the still
photographs of Birmingham and Selma by Charles Moore and James
Karales evoke that era of strife and accomplishment. But the genius
of the place lies in the films of King delivering his unforgettably
eloquent speeches, in that prophetic voice mingling calm,
cultivation and steely determination.
</P>
<P>
   I heard many of them in person as a young reporter, and like
many of my generation I can recite bits of several from memory _
``Free at last, free at last, thank God almighty, I'm free at
last'' _ but neither my wife, Betsey, nor I was prepared for the
powerful waves of emotion that washed over us as we listened.
Atlanta offers no experience to match it, and not many other cities
do either.
</P>
<P>
   King had important co-workers, including Jesse Jackson and
Andrew Young, later a member of Congress, ambassador to the United
Nations and mayor of Atlanta. A large black middle class helped
lend stability to the city when others, potential rivals for
Southern leadership, fell apart. Mayors William B. Hartsfield and
Ivan Allen pronounced their city ``Too Busy to Hate,'' and Ralph
McGill preached moderation in his column in The Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Carter and Turner
</P>
<P>
   Today, the city's leading citizen is former President Jimmy
Carter, much more admired out of office than in, who builds houses
for Habitat for Humanity, lectures, writes books and travels the
world with his wife, Rosalynn, promoting peace and working to
eradicate disease and ease hunger. When not on the road, they
divide their time between the little farm town of Plains and an
apartment at the Carter Presidential Library here.
</P>
<P>
   But he has a rival in Ted Turner, the voluble entrepreneur who
turned an underpowered UHF television station into the Superstation
viewed across the country. He invented CNN, based in downtown
Atlanta, which has become the world's channel of choice when big
news is breaking. He built the Atlanta Braves, winner of eight
division titles under the imperturbable Bobby Cox, into one of the
nation's most successful sports franchises. He married (and split
from) Jane Fonda. He gave $1 billion to the United Nations. And he
owns 1.6 million acres of ranch land, more than any other American.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is full of success stories, from Delta Airlines to Home
Depot and UPS. Over the years, it has built important institutions
like Georgia Tech and Emory University, a superb liberal-arts
school less well-known than Tech because it lacks the Ramblin'
Wrecks' sports legends, and the national Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention. (Emory's well-regarded Michael C. Carlos
Art Museum was renovated and expanded by the post-modernist Michael
Graves in 1993.)
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta boasts tourist attractions like the zoo, with a winsome
pair of pandas, Lun Lun and Yang Yang, two of only five in the
country, and the Stone Mountain Monument, a kind of Confederate
version of Mount Rushmore, out to the east of the city.
</P>
<P>
   I must not forget the Art Deco-style Varsity, the nation's
largest drive-in, where they move the customers through at
double-time, all day every day. And I must mention a curiosity of
Atlanta nomenclature: there are 32 streets, lanes, drives, circles
and roads named Peachtree in the metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   Culturally speaking, Atlanta remains a stripling, and it has
suffered two important losses this year. Ned Rifkin, the director
of the High Museum of Art, left to run the Menil Collection in
Houston, complaining of a chronic dearth of arts financing, both
public and private. And Harriet Sanford, the director of the Fulton
County Arts Council, announced she would leave in April to take a
similar position in Charlotte, N.C. _ ``a place,'' she said, ``that
just has a different level of appreciation for the arts.''
</P>
<P>
   Better Days Anticipated
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta likes to think of itself as a much more important city
than Charlotte and as a legitimate rival to Houston. So it was not
surprising that The Constitution ran an editorial chastising both
business and local governments for failing to commit the big bucks
needed to move the city into the artistic big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   But better days seem to lie ahead for the 56-year-old Atlanta
Symphony Orchestra, the largest performing arts organization in the
Southeast, with a budget of $21 million and an endowment nearing
$70 million. It was built, to a considerable degree, by Robert
Shaw, the noted choral conductor, who died last year; but it has
not flourished under Yoel Levi, the Romanian-born conductor who
leaves in May after 12 years as music director.
</P>
<P>
   As the orchestra struggled with a deficit, it endured a 10-week
strike at the beginning of the 1996-97 season, as well as a
protracted conflict between the orchestra's board and management,
on the one hand, and a vocal band of Levi supporters who charged
that he was being forced out.
</P>
<P>
   This month, however, the Symphony named Robert Spano, the
38-year-old leader of the Brooklyn Philharmonic, to succeed Levi.
One of the most highly regarded young American conductors, he had
been mentioned as a possibility for a half-dozen other orchestras,
some of them bigger. Spano made his name in Brooklyn with an
emphasis on the modern, but this, he said, is ``a very different
city'' that might require a different approach.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta will be getting not one but two marquee names; Donald
Runnicles, the Scottish-born, German-trained music director of the
San Francisco Opera, was named the orchestra's principal guest
conductor.
</P>
<P>
   For many years until 1987, the Metropolitan Opera came to
Atlanta every year on tour. When the touring ended, the Atlanta
Opera, which had begun as an amateur outfit, transformed itself to
fill the void. Starting, in the words of William Fred Scott, its
artistic director, with ``somebody who answered the phone and a
sextet of well-meaning ladies in station wagons,'' it has grown
into a company with an annual budget of almost $5 million. More
than 50,000 people attended its productions last season.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   This ``meteoric growth,'' the British magazine Opera Now said
last year, is ``creating noises everywhere.'' In 2000 Atlantans
will see three performances each of four operas _ ``Rigoletto,''
``Cosi Fan Tutte,'' ``Lucia di Lammermoor'' and ``Turandot'' _ in
the glorious, 4,518-seat Fox Theater, an Art Deco movie palace that
retains its ``Thousand and One Nights'' decor. For the first time,
all four presentations will be Atlanta Opera productions.
</P>
<P>
   A Theater Co.
</P>
<P>
   If any Atlanta arts organization embraces the whole city, black
and white, urban and suburban, it is the Alliance Theater Co., a
repertory group based at the Woodruff Arts Center. Its guiding
spirit is Kenny Leon, who must be one of the few artistic directors
around who stands outside after some performances, greeting the
audience members like a parish priest.
</P>
<P>
   Leon, who is black, has cast African-American actors and
actresses in traditionally white roles in ``A Christmas Carol'' and
``Medea,'' which featured the ``Cosby'' star Phylicia Rashad.
Shortly after his appointment in 1990, ticket sales dropped to
13,000 from 20,000, but then rebounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think controversy is probably my middle name,'' Leon said on
the CBS News program ``Sunday Morning'' a year ago, ``not because I
want to be controversial but because I want to ask questions that
will make us better human beings. I think the theater can be a
place where we can come and realize that we all bleed the same
blood, we all walk the same way, and we all want the same things.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the company's offerings this year are Shaw's ``Heartbreak
House''; August Wilson's ``Jitney''; ``Shadowlands,'' a love story
drawn from the life of C.S. Lewis, the Oxford theologian; and
``Wit,'' the 1999 Pulitzer Prize winner written by Margaret Edson,
an Atlanta kindergarten teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Builders and Buildings
</P>
<P>
   As befits a city whose main business for the last century has
been building itself, most of Atlanta's architecture is developer
architecture. The city's most important home-grown architect in the
postwar period was John Portman, himself a developer, who built
many of the postmodern towers that define downtown Atlanta,
including the vast Peachtree Center, the Atlanta Merchandise Mart
and the 70-story Westin Peachtree Plaza Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   But he will be best remembered for the Hyatt Regency Hotel, in
which he adapted and expanded the atrium lobby that had been used
in 19th-century hotels like the Brown Palace in Denver. The Hyatt's
22-story skylit courtyard, with bedrooms opening onto cantilevered
balconies hung with vines and transparent ``bubble'' elevators
whisking awed guests to their floors, was copied all across the
United States soon after it opened in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Johnson and John Burgee contributed a pair of skyscrapers
in the late 1980s, the more successful of the two forming an anchor
for the Midtown neighborhood. Called the IBM Tower, it is a
neo-Gothic campanile, refined in its ornament and satisfying in its
proportions.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few other notable buildings scattered here and
there, including a series of elegant mansions designed in the 1920s
and 1930s by Philip T. Shutze, a gifted classicist who took his
stylistic cue from the best Regency and Federal models.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, the clumsy McMansions that have joined them along the
wealthy, wooded byways of Buckhead in the last two decades have
none of Shutze's finesse. Meant to resemble Venetian palazzos,
Georgian country seats, Tuscan villas or French chateaus, they
succeed only in looking hugely expensive. A scroll pediment here
and a Palladian window there don't cut it.
</P>
<P>
   The High Museum
</P>
<P>
   Only one of the country's leading modernists can be seen at the
peak of his game in Atlanta, and that is Richard Meier, whose High
Museum (1983), clad in dazzlingly white porcelain-enameled steel
panels, resembles a space station that has settled gently onto the
greensward along Peachtree Street. A big, colorful Calder mobile (a
lunar explorer?) sits alongside it, and a series of curving ramps
lead into and through the exhibition spaces.
</P>
<P>
   The High's collection is skimpy in spots, but it has significant
strengths, including the spectacular Virginia Carroll Crawford
collection of 19th- and early 20th-century American furniture and
decorative arts (several Herter Brothers pieces are of special
note) and an idiosyncratic group of objects made by Howard Finster
of Summerville, Ga., one of the nation's best-known outsider
artists.
</P>
<P>
   I especially like the way in which unlikely juxtapositions of
pictures or the like have been created: a Rothko next to a Martin
Johnson Heade, one abstract, one not, but both divided into three
horizontal bands; an old Yoruba door from West Africa next to a
door painted in New Orleans by a black artist named Herbert
Singleton, born in 1945; children as seen by three portraitists,
Mary Cassatt, Samuel F.B. Morse and George Bellows. The pedagogy is
not heavy-handed, but the lessons are there for those who seek
them.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHAT TO DO  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By R.W. APPLE Jr. &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sampling of attractions, along with travel
information:
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   RITZ-CARLTON BUCKHEAD, 3434 Peachtree Road, (404) 237-2700. Set
in a sterile suburban sea of shopping malls, office towers and
parking lots, the Ritz nonetheless conveys a feeling of graceful
luxury. The public rooms are lush; the bedrooms benefit from thick
carpets and thicker towels, but you may wonder why faxes take so
long to reach you. Renovations are under way. The dining room (see
below) has been a superstar since it opened in 1984. Double room:
From $195 on weekends; $235 on weeknights.
</P>
<P>
   FOUR SEASONS, 75 14th St., (404) 881-9898. Strategically
positioned between Buckhead and downtown, only a few steps fom the
High Museum of Art and the Woodruff Arts Center, this opulent
property occupies the bottom 20 floors of a postmodern high rise.
Offices and condominiums take up the top floors. Corridors and
bedrooms are bright and amply proportioned, and room-service
breakfasts are delectable. Modern computer linkups. Double room:
$165 to $325.
</P>
<P>
   RITZ-CARLTON DOWNTOWN, 181 Peachtree Street NE, (404) 659-0400.
The Buckhead property is the chain's flagship, but this ``other''
Ritz clearly ranks as the best hotel in downtown Atlanta. Acres of
marble, fine Oriental rugs, a 17th-century Flemish tapestry and an
18th-century chandelier lend the lobby all the luxury anyone could
ask for, although the overall feeling is just a little bit
institutional. Some of the rooms have fourposter beds. Double room:
$139 to $295.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   SWISSOTEL, 3391 Peachtree Road, (404) 365-0065. Adjacent to
Lenox Square, Atlanta's grandest shopping mall, this streamlined,
sparklingly white building bears a certain resemblance to the High
Museum. Inside, Biedermeier furniture and modern paintings soften
the geometry and lend a human scale; the 365 rooms are up to date
and carefully kept, if not particularly distinctive. A branch of
New York's Palm steakhouse is in the hotel. Double room: $150 to
$390.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   BACCHANALIA, 1198 Howell Mill Road, (404) 365-0410. Newly
installed in a former slaughterhouse west of downtown, Bacchinalia
expends vast effort in tracking down prime raw materials: Niman
ranch pork, lamb and beef; cherry-red Ahi tuna from Hawaii; cheeses
from not only Italy, France and Britain, but also North Carolina,
California, Arkansas and New York. Amazing Meyer lemon souffle for
dessert and great California cabernets.
</P>
<P>
   BLUEPOINTE, 3455 Peachtree Road, (404) 237-9070. At the moment,
this is gastronomic ground zero for Hotlanta, a bold blend of
primary colors, hard edges and wait staff in black Mandarin tunics.
The fusion food is terrifyingly good-looking on the plate and
packed with flavor. Try the Thai chicken and coconut soup, or the
peanut-crusted grouper atop bitter choy sum greens. The atmosphere
at lunch is less frenzied than at dinner.
</P>
<P>
   BRASSERIE LE COZE, 3393 Peachtree Road, (404) 266-1440. A cousin
of Le Bernardin in New York, this is a genuine brasserie, with
white tile floors and Lipp-like mosaics between tall pier mirrors.
Parisian dishes (onion tart, roast skate) as well as
Franco-American specials (soups, salads, a roast lamb sandwich on
olive bread with garlic mayonnaise) _ almost all good. Perfect for
a lunch break during a shop-till-you-drop day at Lenox Square.
</P>
<P>
   FUSEBOX, 3085 Piedmont Road, (404) 233-3383. No short-circuits
here, in one of Atlanta's current hot spots. Tiny sheets of silver
leaf cover the ceiling, and a boat-shaped, marble-topped common
table makes lone diners welcome. The chef, Troy Thompson, has
mastered a broad range of dishes, from delicate Shanghai dumplings
to lobster with pasta and Thai basil to a stunning terrine of duck
confit, suckling pig and foie gras. Shad roe wrapped in a filament
of bacon and slowly sauteed takes on an exquisite texture.
</P>
<P>
   DINING ROOM AT RITZ-CARLTON BUCKHEAD, 3434 Peachtree Road, (404)
237-2700. The United States is full of synthetically sophisticated
Continental restaurants. This, on the other hand, is the real
thing: immaculate service, directed by Peter Krehan; counter-snob
wine advice from Yves Sauboua; and lean, mean, flavor-packed
cuisine fashioned by the brilliant Joel Antunes, whose London
restaurant, Les Saveurs, earned two Michelin stars. Try his lamb
loin in puff pastry, flavored with coriander, curry and basil.
</P>
<P>
   SEEGER'S, 111 West Pace's Ferry Road, (404) 846-9779. Gunther
Seeger introduced world-class cooking to Atlanta, and he continues
to push out its margins at his small, understated restaurant in
Buckhead. His kitchen is bigger than his dining room; his style is
intellectual and abstract. One example: a filet of sea bass,
marinated in sake, covered with an edible Japanese cherry leaf. You
will wonder whether you deserve such refinement.
</P>
<P>
   Attractions
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA HISTORY CENTER, 130 West Pace's Ferry Road, (404)
814-4000. ``Requiem: By the Photographers Who Died in Vietnam and
Indochina'' opens Sunday. Through June 26. Hours: Mondays through
Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 5:30 p.m.; Sundays, noon to 5:30 p.m..
Admission: $10; $8, students and the elderly; $4, ages 6 to 17.
</P>
<P>
   MARTIN LUTHER KING JR. CENTER FOR NONVIOLENT SOCIAL CHANGE, 449
Auburn Ave., NE, (404) 526-8900. Hours: Daily, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.
Free. The National Park Visitors Center is across the street. There
are self-guided tours of the Ebenezer Baptist Church and Dr. King's
birthplace. Guided tours of the birthplace every hour to Memorial
Day; every half-hour in summer.
</P>
<P>
   ZOO ATLANTA, 800 Cherokee Ave., (404) 624-5600. Hours: Daily,
9:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. Admission: $12; $10, the elderly; $8, ages 3
to 11.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH MUSEUM OF ART, 1280 Peachtree St. NE, (404) 733-4400.
``John Twachtman: An American Impressionist,'' ``American Art Circa
1900'' and ``Art at the Edge: Todd Murphy'' open Friday and run
through May 21. Hours: Tuesdays through Thursdays and Saturdays, 10
a.m. to 5 p.m.; Fridays, to 9 p.m.; Sundays, noon to 5 p.m.
Admission: $6; $4, students and the elderly; $2, ages 6 to 17.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA SYMPHONY ORCHESTRA, Woodruff Arts Center, 1280 Peachtree
St., NE, (404) 733-5000. Danielpour's ``Celestial Night'' and
Berlioz's ``Symphonie Fantastique,'' Friday and Saturday at 8 p.m.
Tickets: $19 to $49. ``Casual Classics,'' with works by Berlioz,
Saturday at 2 p.m. Tickets: $20. Zdenek Macal conducts.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA OPERA, Fox Theater, 660 Peachtree St., NE (404) 881-8885
or (800) 356-7372. The season begins April 6 at 8 p.m. with
``Rigoletto.'' Tickets: $18 to $120.
</P>
<P>
   ALLIANCE THEATER COMPANY, Woodruff Arts Center, 1280 Peachtree
NE (404) 733-5000. Nilo Cruz's ``Two Sisters and a Piano,'' Friday
night at 8; Saturday at 2:30 and 8 p.m.; Sunday at 2:30 and 7:30
p.m. Through March 5. Tickets: $21 and $27.
</P>
<P>
   CARTER PRESIDENTIAL LIBRARY, 441 Freedom Parkway, (404)
331-3942. Hours: Mondays through Saturdays, 9 a.m. to 4:45 p.m.;
Sundays, noon to 4:45 p.m.. Admission: $5; $4, the elderly; 16 and
younger, free.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD OF COCA-COLA, 55 Martin Luther King Jr. Drive, (404)
676-5151. Hours: Mondays through Saturdays, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.;
Sundays, noon to 6 p.m. Admission: $6; $4, the elderly; $3, ages 6
to 11.
</P>
<P>
   VARSITY DRIVE-IN, 61 North Ave., NE, (404) 881-1706. The
nation's largest drive-in has car hops and seats 800 people.
</P>
<P>
   Getting There From New York
</P>
<P>
   BY AIR: Delta Airlines, (800) 221-1212, offers nonstop flights
from all three New York City airports to Hartsfield Airport in
Atlanta. The 21-day round-trip fare starts at $349 with
restrictions; 14-day, from $198; 7-day, from $242. The last-minute
round-trip fare is $323.
</P>
<P>
   BY TRAIN: Amtrak, (800) 872-7245, offers daily train service
between Penn Station and Atlanta Station. The round-trip adult fare
is $282; $714 for a private room with sleeping berths, dinner and
breakfast. The trip is about 19 hours.
</P>
