<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7438 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-ANGIE-APARO25-COX     02-24 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGIE-APARO25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aparo gets label off to good start
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Ala. _ With his dark clothes, a triangle tattoo of
hair beneath his lower lip and a knit skullcap pulled down below
his ears, singer-songwriter Angie Aparo sticks out in a
jock-oriented sports bar like a bug on a windshield.
</P>
<P>
   As Jacksonville State University students high-five and swill
beer under a ceiling decorated with red pennants, he's hunched over
a green salad talking about life, God, the universe and holistic
healing guru Deepak Chopra.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Chopra) has a great explanation of beginner's luck,''
Aparo, who is somewhere in his 30s but won't be more specific,
muses over the pounding Top 40 music. ``A beginner goes into a
situation not knowing what he's supposed to do, so his mind is
actually operating at a higher level. He has so many more
possibilities than someone who has been doing it forever. Once you
think you know what something should be, you've eliminated the
possibilities of what it could be. That's kind of my approach to
music.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based artist is in this college town for yet another
one-night stand, part of a Southeastern tour to promote his dreamy,
experimental first album, ``The American,'' and the single that's
climbing the alternative charts, ``Spaceship.'' The project is not
only Aparo's national debut, but the first music to come out of
fledgling Atlanta rock label Melisma Records, owned and operated by
Grammy-winning producer Matt Serletic.
</P>
<P>
   The significance of Serletic's backing isn't lost on Aparo, who
kicked around the Atlanta music scene for years in cover bands, as
a session vocalist and then an acoustic singer-songwriter. Between
the times when the young producer first heard Aparo in a set at the
Cotton Club and when he signed him to a record deal, Serletic had
become one hot property as the wizard behind Matchbox 20 and Carlos
Santana's comeback single, ``Smooth.'' As a result, Melisma got the
backing of powerful music man Clive Davis and his label, Arista,
which is helping to launch Aparo with a lavish promotional
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The album, to be released March 7, has been hyped for weeks in
movie theaters, where audiences have watched a darkly surrealistic
trailer of Aparo between previews and concession stand ads. There's
a slick Web site (www.angieaparo.com) and a concert tour,
culminating in Saturday's performance at the Fox Theatre as part of
the 99X Chinese New Year concert.
</P>
<P>
   But Aparo says he's ``way over the whole star thing.'' His
passion is his music _ a spacey, layered, somewhat ethereal sound
that Matchbox 20 lead singer Rob Thomas describes as ``Cat Stevens
meets David Bowie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the first station in the country to play Angie
Aparo,'' says Leslie Fram, program director of Atlanta's 99X. ``His
music is brilliant. I kept hearing about him from other musicians,
who all said he had the best voice you'll ever hear. When I heard
what Matt did with him, I was blown away. We rushed the record on
the air _ it was that good.''
</P>
<P>
   Aparo is a rare act in a world of comfy, manufactured pop groups
and MTV. He's an intriguing lyricist who explores the ``what ifs''
with his words, often examining politics, personal matters and
spirituality in an approach that is provocatively abstract. On
``The American,'' his songs address deforestation (``Green Into
Gold''), God and technology (``Spaceship'') and the manipulation by
insincere politicians of the holiday honoring the Rev. Martin
Luther King Jr. (``Memphis City Rain'').
</P>
<P>
   Aparo says he writes most of these tunes while driving in his
car, using a tool called a Groovebox, a kind of musical
sound-effects machine not unlike keyboard toys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about the size of a laptop, with a little eight-track
recorder in it and a little keyboard, with about 600 sounds,'' he
explains. ``You can compose pieces on it and store them as songs.
Matt (Serletic) encouraged me to not write with a guitar, but start
going at it on the Groovebox at an organic level.''
</P>
<P>
   When the time came to record ``The American,'' Serletic booked a
month of studio time, then sent the backing band he had hired home.
``All right _ what do you want to do?'' he asked Aparo. The two
listened to the demo of ``Spaceship'' on the Groovebox, while
Serletic tinkered with his computerized keyboard. A drummer laid
down a beat, and then a bassist. ``Two hours later, we had 40
tracks'' for the song, Aparo says.
</P>
<P>
   The unjaded ``beginner's approach,'' as Aparo calls it, seems to
be working. 99X is playing ``Spaceship'' regularly, as are about 30
other new-rock stations around the country. Aparo has little time
to spend at his McDonough home these days, touring in an RV with a
band in tow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a journey,'' he says. ``It's not about all that stuff:
record deals, being a star. It's about what's inside. That's what
makes a great artist, like (Bruce) Springsteen. A great artist is
somebody who can take what's inside of them and touch the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   99X Chinese New Year
</P>
<P>
   With Angie Aparo, Our Lady Peace and 311. 7 p.m. Sold out
($34.99). Fox Theatre, 1280 Peachtree St. N.E. 404-249-6400.
Benefits the Upper Chattahoochee Riverkeeper Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
