<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7439 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MICHAEL-DOUGLAS25-COX     02-24 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICHAEL-DOUGLAS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A change of pace on-screen and off
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Douglas, the Oscar winner who wore tailored suits in
``Wall Street'' and a chief executive's bravura in ``The American
President,'' stands unshaven and maybe a little overweight in a
lilac chenille bathrobe.
</P>
<P>
   The sop cap on his head doesn't add much prestige either.
</P>
<P>
   In his newest movie _ ``Wonder Boys,'' directed by Curtis Hanson
(``L.A. Confidential'') _ Douglas plays Grady Tripp, a 50-year-old,
pot-smoking liberal arts professor who's a bit more than down on
his luck. Seven years ago he wrote the Great American Novel. Since
then it's been one long drought.
</P>
<P>
   In one weekend, Douglas' character ricochets from one outlandish
mishap to another, eventually donning that chenille bathrobe, in an
unusual comedy with co-stars Frances McDormand, Tobey Maguire,
Robert Downey Jr., Katie Holmes, Rip Torn and Richard Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking for something different,'' Douglas says about
accepting a role nothing like his usual screen fare. ``I'd done the
sort of prince-of-darkness roles back to back.'' That would be ``A
Perfect Murder'' and ``The Game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One time, of course, there was my sex trilogy.'' Could anyone
forget ``Fatal Attraction,'' ``Basic Instinct'' and ``Disclosure''?
</P>
<P>
   ``And earlier was my white-collar thing.'' As in ``Wall
Street.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Douglas says, he took a big pay cut and launched into
``Wonder Boys,'' a quirky, esoteric tale set in the wintry, wet
Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a movie about making choices and people
procrastinating from making a choice,'' he says. ``You don't know
where the movie's going. And that's so refreshing. You know the
ending of most movies in the first 20 minutes. This one's not like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   At 55, Douglas is changing more about his life than just screen
roles.
</P>
<P>
   He marked the start of a new century by getting engaged to
30-year-old Catherine Zeta-Jones, the Welsh actress from
``Entrapment'' and ``The Mask of Zorro.'' They met at a film
festival 18 months ago and began dating last March; she's expecting
their first child this summer. (Douglas has one son, Cameron, 21,
from a previous marriage.)
</P>
<P>
   To promote ``Wonder Boys,'' Douglas chatted by phone recently
about his new movie and a recent visit to Atlanta. He also revealed
a tidbit about his relationship with Zeta-Jones: the pickup line he
used on her.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did you first become interested in ``Wonder Boys''?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's a great screenplay. Really good writing. It's from Steve
Kloves, who directed ``The Fabulous Baker Boys'' (and adapted
``Wonder Boys'' from Michael Chabon's novel). I read it and liked
it. I wanted to do something heroic and a romantic comedy at the
same time.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did Curtis Hanson get involved?
</P>
<P>
   A: I sent the script to him. We sat down for a couple of hours,
and it became a marriage. He looked at me and I looked at him and
we married. Making a movie is a kind of commitment.
</P>
<P>
   I knew it wasn't going to be a vanity production.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Even though you're obviously the star of the movie, it did
come across as an ensemble production.
</P>
<P>
   A: I was most proud of that. It's pretty seamless between all
the characters. Curtis has an incredible sense of timing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Aren't you a United Nations representative for disarmament?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. And it brought me to Atlanta a couple of weeks ago. I
was at the Carter Center for the first time. What a great location.
What a view of downtown. We're trying to reduce the threat of
nuclear weapons, and President Carter was kind enough to sponsor a
meeting. I've always been a fan of his.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's your reaction to the recent Oscar nominations?
</P>
<P>
   A: I certainly love the fact that it's an open year. I'm happy
to see ``The Insider'' in it. And ``The Cider House Rules.'' ``The
Sixth Sense'' was close to my favorite picture of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Farnsworth and Sean Penn were healthy to see (in the
best actor race). It's the most wide-open category in a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've read where once you saw Catherine Zeta-Jones in ``The
Mask of Zorro,'' you were like ``a heat-seeking missile.'' So the
first time you met her, what line did you use?
</P>
<P>
   A: I can't recall exactly what I said to her when I first met
her. But within the first couple of hours, I said, ``I'm going to
father your children.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: And how did she respond to that?
</P>
<P>
   A: She said, ``You know, I've heard a lot about you and read a
lot about you and seen a lot of your movies, and it's refreshing to
see that every bit of it is true.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you a diaper-changing kind of guy?
</P>
<P>
   A: Oh, yeah. It's exciting. You know, when you have your career
squared away you can look at life a whole new way.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
