<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7443 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-FRANKENHEIMER2     02-24 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-FRANKENHEIMER25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Frankenheimer loves film game
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Director John Frankenheimer has worked successfully with a lot
of big, demanding stars: Marlon Brando, Burt Lancaster, Kirk
Douglas, Robert De Niro. But the club sandwich that Frankenheimer
has in his fist right now is being just too difficult. It's got to
go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't like this sandwich,'' he barks to an assistant,
waving the offending lunch away with his hand. Ditto the soup,
which he earlier shoved aside after a single gulp.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the Mobil five-star rating at the Four Seasons.
Frankenheimer has a big suite in the Midtown hotel, and he's giving
the room-service food hell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can they bring up a ham sandwich or something like that? On
whole wheat bread. Something they can't (expletive) up? A ham
sandwich with a little butter and English mustard. You know?''
</P>
<P>
   The assistant wonders meekly whether a grilled cheese might do.
</P>
<P>
   ``A grilled cheese would be fine,'' Frankenheimer says
emphatically. ``With very. Crisp. Bacon. But it has to be hot, and
that already gives you the (expletive) factor. Where if you just do
the ham sandwich. ... Because the soup was ice cold. Just a ham
sandwich on whole wheat bread with English mustard on the side. No
lettuce. No mayonnaise. Just put three slices of ham on two pieces
of bread with a little butter on top.''
</P>
<P>
   The next instant, he's laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nicholson,'' he says, referring to Jack Nicholson and his
explosive chicken salad sandwich escapade in ``Five Easy Pieces.''
``I can just never get over that scene. One of the great movie
scenes ever done. And I've played that over and over again in my
life, but I can't do it without laughing. He is unforgettable in
certain scenes.''
</P>
<P>
   At 70, Frankenheimer has created his own share of indelible
screen moments. Laurence Harvey looking down a rifle barrel at a
presidential contender in ``The Manchurian Candidate'' in 1962. De
Niro speeding through a tunnel in the astounding chase sequences in
``Ronin'' in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   He's also known for helming 1952's Oscar-nominated ``Birdman of
Alcatraz'' with Lancaster; 1964's intriguing ``Seven Days in May''
with Lancaster, Douglas and Ava Gardner; and 1996's failed remake
of ``The Island of Dr. Moreau'' with Brando.
</P>
<P>
   Now Frankenheimer, a four-time Emmy winner (TNT's ``George
Wallace'' and ``Andersonville'' and HBO's ``The Burning Season''
and ``Against the Wall''), is promoting his latest big-screen
effort, ``Reindeer Games.'' It stars Ben Affleck in the modern-day
action tale of a fresh-from-prison auto thief who finds himself
caught in a risky plan to rob a casino. ``Games'' also stars
Charlize Theron, Gary Sinise and Clarence Williams III.
</P>
<P>
   During Frankenheimer's recent visit to Atlanta, he talked about
making ``Reindeer Games,'' his love of the city and several
potential future projects.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did you get interested in ``Reindeer Games''?
</P>
<P>
   A: Bob Weinstein (of Miramax) loved ``Ronin,'' and having seen
that, he gave me the script to ``Reindeer Games.'' I loved the
script. I thought it was just so smart.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I assume you got Gary Sinise involved since he worked with
you on ``Wallace.''
</P>
<P>
   A: I got everybody involved. First guy we had to get was
Affleck. I couldn't put Gary Sinise into it until we cast the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There's a lot about this movie that says ``action flick.''
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, to me it's a character-driven thriller, and that's what
I made. It's got some action sequences in it, but it's a
character-driven thriller.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've always loved Atlanta and said you'd live here if you
couldn't live in Los Angeles. Why the affinity for this place?
</P>
<P>
   A: It has everything I want. It gives you privacy. I can drive
in this city. I like the climate. I love to play tennis, and this
is the biggest tennis city in the United States. And I like the
restaurants. I like the cosmopolitan air of the city without it
being overpowering like New York. I like the fact that there's some
space here. Good theater. Good films.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Your old yearbook lists you as a ``highway menace.'' What
kind of car do you drive now?
</P>
<P>
   A: I have a Mercedes SL. It started life out as a 600 SL, but it
was made for the Sultan of Brunei. So it has a 7.3-liter,
600-horsepower engine in it. Twelve cylinder. It's quite a car.
There's that part of me that likes speed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So will we ever see chase scenes like in ``Ronin'' in more of
your films?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't ever want to do another car chase again. I don't
think I could ever do it any better than that. I had these great
drivers, and I had great situations and cities that cooperated 100
percent. Both Paris and Nice.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's up with your deal with Turner?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are three projects we are working on. All depend on
casting or script approval. We are working on trying to put
together ``Across the River and Into the Trees.'' Hemingway's book.
We have a miniseries we're working on on Robert Kennedy. Then a guy
I've always wanted to work with is Alec Baldwin. ... And so we're
talking about doing ``The Pentagon Papers.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Brando and De Niro. Which one is better or, really, easier to
work with?
</P>
<P>
   A: De Niro.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Brando just must be something. Did you ever figure out what
he's doing and what he means and what he's about?
</P>
<P>
   A: No.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is Kirk Douglas like he is on-screen? He seems so commanding
and at the same time so completely full of himself.
</P>
<P>
   A: He manages to convey exactly the same thing in real life.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And Burt Lancaster?
</P>
<P>
   A: He was great. He was all the things Kirk Douglas wasn't and
all the things Kirk Douglas wanted to be. I loved him. He walked
like he talked. He was rough. He did not suffer fools lightly. But
he gave what he expected. ... He treated people well. He wasn't a
bully like the other guy. And he was genuinely a good person.
Unlike the other guy.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
