<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7446 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-WONDERBOYS25-C     02-24 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-WONDERBOYS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In the satirical `Wonder Boys,' Michael Douglas plays a
professor coming of age in his 50s
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This weekend, scruffy, scattered English lit professor Grady
Tripp (Michael Douglas) has more to do than grade the whiney short
stories from his creative writing class. No, in ``Wonder Boys,'' he
has to deal with his hyper New York editor; a transvestite tuba
player; a talented, suicidal student; another student who has a
crush on him; and his married girlfriend, who informs him that,
oops, she's pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   Plus there's Grady's own wife, who has just packed her bags and
walked out of the marriage. And there's a blind but vicious dog
that would like nothing better than to make dinner out of Grady's
legs.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Michael Chabon's novel, ``Wonder Boys'' is partly a
satire of the academic life, partly a coming-of-age tale. It just
happens that this coming of age occurs for a man already in his
50s. Grady, like a graying adolescent, has let his life become a
series of accidents waiting to happen. In the space of 48 hours,
most of them do. This comedy-drama is a picaresque adventure, a
series of events that verge on implausible but actually make weird
sense.
</P>
<P>
   Acclaimed for his first novel, published seven years before, the
hangdog Ph.D. hasn't exactly suffered writer's block since then. On
the contrary, Grady's follow-up book is already more than 2,600
pages long. And he can't seem to end it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't really make any choices,'' his sexy student (and
tenant) Hannah (Katie Holmes) says after skimming his book in
progress. It's the heart of Grady's dilemma. Especially when it
comes to deciding what to do about his lover, Sara (Frances
McDormand), the college chancellor whose husband (Richard Thomas)
happens to be the head of the English department.
</P>
<P>
   The catalyst for the weekend is gloomy but gifted student James
Leer (Tobey Maguire), the sort of kid who can reel off a list of
Hollywood suicides alphabetically and carries a tiny pistol with
him. Grady takes him under his wing, even as he fends off the
attentions of his manic editor, Terry (Robert Downey Jr.), who
comes hoping to read Grady's novel. Terry also has a statuesque
cross-dresser (Michael Cavadias) on his arm.
</P>
<P>
   For anybody expecting the usual single-goal plot of many
Hollywood movies, ``Wonder Boys'' requires an adjustment. Like many
novels, it's full of episodes and digressions that are as
interesting as the final destination. It's a feast for actors, who
make the most of tiny, telling moments: for example, the drag
queen's one-word advice to McDormand on the key to wearing high
heels. Or Rip Torn, in a cameo as a best-selling author, summoning
up the worst of literary pomposity when he proclaims to a fawning
audience, ``I ... am a writer.''
</P>
<P>
   The chain of mishaps is held together by Douglas' bemused gaze,
peering through a haze of reefer smoke (Grady's drug of choice).
While Douglas has never been an actor of great depth or complexity,
it's good to see him turn in his Movie Star badge, grow stubble and
shuffle around in a ratty lilac bathrobe.
</P>
<P>
   While Maguire's blank shapelessness has left a hole in the
center of other films, here he delivers a real performance rather
than just his wide-eyed presence. He radiates a deadpan, impish
intelligence behind his man-in-the-Moon-Pie face. Downey does his
usual up-for-anything performance, while McDormand sketches the
sense of midlife resignation that gives the movie its tinge of
melancholy.
</P>
<P>
   The film bumbles in its final moments with a too-tidy Hollywood
wrap-up that goes against its general tone of sweet, forgivable
shagginess. But the wonder about ``Wonder Boys'' is that director
Curtis Hanson knew exactly the sort of movie to make after his
stylish, complex film noir, ``L.A. Confidential.''
</P>
<P>
   Grady's problem could be a sly reference to Hanson's own
situation. How do you follow up one of the best American movies of
the 1990s? But the director doesn't have Grady's difficulty making
choices. He has created a movie unlike his commercial thrillers
(``The Hand That Rocks the Cradle,'' ``The River Wild''). And he
proves that the world of a college professor can be just as
complex, but much funnier, than the lives of Los Angeles cops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonder Boys''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Michael Douglas, Tobey Maguire and Frances McDormand.
Directed by Curtis Hanson. Rated R for profanity and drug content.
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 57 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A small but sweet wonder for anyone looking for a
movie that's not about teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
