<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7454 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-WEEKEND-2TAKES-NYT     02-24 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 `THE 10th KINGDOM': A FAIRY TALE FOR ADULTS (WATCH FOR SNOW(EDS: Production notes at end of review. Time, channel are for New
York area. Check local listings.) 
(bl) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can a plucky young waitress from New York find happiness with a
half-man, half-wolf from a seedy fairy-tale realm who pursues her
through a magic mirror? Could you possibly want to hang around for
10 hours to find out?
</P>
<P>
   Don't be too quick to answer that second question. There's magic
afoot. Real-life network wizards are gambling real-life money
(reluctantly, by several reports) on their make-believe marathon,
``The 10th Kingdom,'' which begins Sunday. Once you nibble this
enchanted mushroom, you may have a strange urge to stay.
</P>
<P>
   At this length ``Kingdom'' is leaning against the limits of a
mini-series, not to mention the limits of viewers' attention spans.
NBC is presenting ``Kingdom'' in five two-hour installments:
Sunday, Monday and Wednesday, plus March 5 and 6. So consult your
crystal ball, or at least your calendar, before proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   The saga's mythical challenges only begin there. On its quest to
win your heart, this film is carrying one of the most ephemeral
elements a television project can bear, whimsy. And by refusing to
take itself seriously or wallow in soupy emotion, it flings aside
the most potent talismans of the mini-series form.
</P>
<P>
   So some strong spell must be brewing, because this goofy project
succeeds. Oh, it stumbles now and then along its meandering route
through haunted forests and down enchanted rivers. But it lives up
to its billing as a fairy tale for adults, stirring childlike
wonder while providing a smattering of grown-up wit.
</P>
<P>
   The tale begins simultaneously in two off-kilter worlds. One is
contemporary Manhattan. The other is the Nine Kingdoms, once the
realm of Snow White. She's long dead, and the place is ``in a bit
of disarray,'' explains Prince Wendell (Daniel Lapaine), ruler of
one of the kingdoms. ``Happily ever after didn't last as long as we
hoped.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendell is not himself when he says this. He's a golden
retriever, thanks to the sorcery of the evil Queen (Dianne Wiest),
who has also put the dog into Wendell's body.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell (in the dog's body) escapes through the Queen's magic
mirror and onto a path in Central Park, where he collides with the
bicycle being ridden by that plucky waitress, Virginia (Kimberly
Williams). She befriends the dog and soon guesses that he's not
your regulation pooch. To retrieve him, Queenie dispatches Wolf
(Scott Cohen), who looks pretty human but has some wolfish
longings, as well as a trio of dimwitted trolls. They all follow
through the mirror and, like many first-time visitors to New York,
begin to have misadventures. (The trolls decide that this
unfamiliar place must be the 10th Kingdom.)
</P>
<P>
   The trolls _ Bluebell, Burly and Blabberwort _ are clearly meant
to be slapstick fools, three stooges with pointy ears and very bad
teeth. Later you'll meet their even more revolting dad, the Troll
King (Ed O'Neill), and sit through lots of bits about the trolls'
shoe fetish. The whole troll clan is tiresome, the biggest
miscalculation in the script by Simon Moore, who adapted
``Gulliver's Travels'' into a 1996 mini-series. (Others on this
creative team worked on television extravaganzas like ``Merlin''
and ``Alice in Wonderland.'')
</P>
<P>
   But Moore more than redeems himself with the creation of Wolf,
played to the hilt by Cohen as a wild-eyed parody of every
overheated man and every overacting ham. He finds his way to the
apartment that Virginia shares with her father, Tony (John
Larroquette), whom Wolf bribes with a magic bean that offers six
wishes. ``It's a standard multiple-wish deal,'' Wolf explains, eyes
aflame. ``No going back on wishes once made. No making five wishes
and wishing for a thousand.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf catches up with Virginia at (where else?) Grandma's house.
When Wolf finally sees Virginia, he is overcome with deeply
conflicted desire. ``Perfumes are not for me,'' he pants. ``No, I
respond to the audacity of a woman who flaunts her own aroma. And
you, Virginia, you smell like Sunday lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   In the story's first solid indication that Virginia is on her
way to self-confidence (yes, there is a point to all this), she
flings Wolf out the window. This being Manhattan's Upper East Side,
he meets a psychoanalyst. Soon Wolf is toting an armload of
self-help books, trying to gain control of his animal nature.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of other stuff happens, and soon Virginia, Tony, the
trolls, Wolf, the self-help books and the princely retriever are
all tumbling back through the mirror. As the first episode ends,
the Queen is hatching her plans to take over the Nine Kingdoms,
passing off the prince's body with the dog's brain as the real
Wendell. (There are housebreaking issues. Wolf is trying to sort
out his feelings and loyalties. And Tony is locked up in Snow White
Memorial Prison, where baked beanstalk is served at every meal.
``It tastes like an old mattress,'' Tony protests. No, says a
wizened fellow inmate, ``old mattress has a sweaty, meaty taste.'')
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The four remaining chapters don't quite match the inventive fun
of the first, but they often come close. One highlight is Camryn
Manheim's cameo appearance as Snow White. (Yes, she's dead, but
that doesn't stop her from telling Virginia her familiar story from
an unfamiliar viewpoint that Freud would have appreciated.) Under
the direction of David Carson and Herbert Wise, the actors
winningly play it straight, never descending into camp. Wiest makes
a scrumptious villain; Williams and Cohen pursue a memorably
off-kilter courtship; and Larroquette endearingly softens and
deepens his signature character, the vain bungler.
</P>
<P>
   The production, designed by Rob Hinds and Julian Fullalove, is
rich in visual details, both funny and wondrous. And the special
effects serve the story without overwhelming it. Tune in early
enough to catch the stunning opening-title sequence in which New
York morphs into a land of make-believe.
</P>
<P>
   A few moments of violence, coarse language and the not-so-subtle
suggestion of off-screen sex make the film unsuitable for the
youngest children. That's another miscalculation. And while the
ending does tie things up, the clear suggestion of sequels may
indicate overconfidence among the producers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is a trip worth taking. Literal-minded grumps will
be tossed overboard. But those with a taste for loopy fantasy will
enjoy the ride.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE 10TH KINGDOM'
</P>
<P>
   NBC, Sunday night at 9
</P>
