<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7460 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-REFORM-$ADV27-     02-24 1464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-REFORM-$ADV27-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MCCAIN'S SUCCESS RENEWS FOCUS ON CAMPAIGN REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, Feb. 27)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John McCain's presidential campaign is
reviving public attention on how money influences politics, an
issue he has made his personal crusade since being embroiled in the
``Keating Five'' influence-buying scandal a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush even adopted the cause of campaign
finance reform after exit polls in the New Hampshire primary
earlier this month showed McCain's focus on the issue was the top
reason voters gave for preferring him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a huge, dramatic leap forward for the issue,'' said
Sen. Russ Feingold, D-Wis., McCain's ally in their Senate drive to
ban ``soft money,'' the unlimited contributions that individuals,
businesses and unions can make to political parties.
</P>
<P>
   While Feingold and McCain have long complained about the role
campaign contributions play in gaining access to politicians, ``We
simply did not have the megaphone'' to place the issue squarely in
front of the public, Feingold said.
</P>
<P>
   That has now changed, Feingold said, because the McCain
candidacy has made campaign finance reform `` a national cause.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day that he goes forward, he makes the cleaning up of
our government more possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain-Feingold bill to ban soft money has been stalled in
Congress for the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Lewis, executive director for the Center for Public
Integrity, a campaign finance watchdog group, said he senses
``change is in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The achievement of McCain, whatever happens to his candidacy,
is that he has forced America to talk about the subject,'' Lewis
said. ``It's possible McCain will have goosed the politicians,
goosed the media and goosed the country to finally address the
subject of political reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Meredith McGehee, vice president and legislative director of
Common Cause, said McCain's history as a war hero and former POW
gives him a credible image to take the issue of campaign finance
reform to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an issue that's been waiting to happen,'' McGehee
said. ``What's happened with McCain is now you have a messenger for
the message.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's zeal for campaign finance reform stems from his searing
experience as one of the Keating Five when he was accused of
trading influence for campaign dollars.
</P>
<P>
   McCain still describes the Keating probe as ``a nightmare.'' He
says that period was one of the most painful of his life ``because
my integrity and honor were under attack.'' McCain also said: ``The
thing I learned was that It's not only impropriety that counts,
it's the appearance that is just as important.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said the Keating scandal ``scalded'' McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had an epiphany and pledged from that day on to start
thinking about (campaign finance reform) and dealing with it,''
according to Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and the other four senators were accused of improperly
intervening with federal regulators on behalf of Charles H. Keating
Jr., owner of the Lincoln Savings and Loan Association. Keating,
then Arizona's largest homebuilder whose companies made him the
state's sixth largest employer, had steered about $1.4 million in
campaign contributions and gifts to the five lawmakers between 1982
and 1987.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1986, Lincoln's finances were under investigation by
the Federal Home Loan Bank Board because the S&AMP;L was making risky
investments in speculative real estate, jeopardizing the
government-insured deposits.
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulators in February 1987 also toughened rules
governing how thrifts could invest their money. In March, Keating
sued, challenging the regulators' authority to tighten the
investment rules.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1987, McCain joined with Sens. John Glenn, D-Ohio,
Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., and Alan Cranston, D-Calif., and met
with federal regulators to ask them to loosen rules on how thrifts
could invest their money and to delay disciplinary action against
Lincoln Savings.
</P>
<P>
   During the Washington session, McCain questioned the propriety
of the meeting and said he was concerned that the regulators might
feel pressured when faced with the senators, according to a later
report by the Senate ethics committee. McCain also advised Keating
afterward not to expect special favors, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   A week after the Washington meeting, Sen. Don Riegle, D-Mich.,
joined the four senators at a meeting with federal regulators who
had examined Lincoln's records because the thrift was making risky
speculative investments in real estate, jeopardizing federally
insured deposits. The senators urged the regulators to end their
two-year investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Those meetings embroiled the five senators _ the ``Keating
Five'' _ in a Senate ethics investigation that included 23 days of
televised congressional hearings.
</P>
<P>
   While the five senators argued they were only trying to help a
constituent and ensure that federal regulators were correctly
interpreting the law, the regulators insisted they felt intimidated
and pressured to dish up special treatment. ``The Keating Five''
became synonymous with the corrupting influence of money in
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Karp, then chief of staff to DeConcini, describes the
Keating Five scandal as ``hellish'' for the senators. ``It took on
a life of its own to the point where it was terrible beyond
belief,'' Karp said. ``Being one of the targets of it was
nightmarish.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain was chummy with Keating: He had received $112,000 in
campaign donations from him, and had flown nine times on Keating's
jets _ including three trips to the banker's Bahamas vacation home
_ from 1982 to 1987.
</P>
<P>
   During the hearings, McCain said he was sorry that he had
attended the meetings and for creating an impression of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   He sent the U.S. Treasury a check for $112,000, the same sum he
had received as campaign contributions from Keating.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Senate ethics panel let McCain off the easiest,
saying he had not acted improperly but that he had ``exercised poor
judgment'' in intervening with regulators on behalf of a major
campaign contributor. Cranston received the toughest penalty _ a
reprimand _ based on the panel's finding that Cranston ``engaged in
an impermissible pattern of conduct in which fund-raising and
official activities were substantially linked.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulators eventually seized the Lincoln thrift in 1989;
its collapse left taxpayers with a $3.4 billion bailout bill, the
most expensive failure of the savings and loan debacle.
</P>
<P>
   Keating was later found guilty in 1992 of selling $250 million
in worthless junk bonds issued by Lincoln's parent company,
American Continental Corp. of Phoenix, to hundreds of retirees who
lost their life savings. Keating served five years of a 10-year
sentence before being released in October 1996 when his convictions
were thrown out because of juror misconduct. Federal prosecutors
unsuccessfully appealed the case.
</P>
<P>
   DeConcini's career was so tarnished by the Keating affair that
he retired from the Senate and now runs a Washington lobbying firm.
He describes the ``Keating Five'' scandal as ``the worse thing that
ever happened to me.''
</P>
<P>
   DeConcini says the ``Keating Five'' incident prompted McCain to
take up campaign finance reform in an effort to clear his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it helped him to become a real zealot on campaign
reform,'' DeConcini said.
</P>
<P>
   DeConcini said he believes McCain rebounded better than the rest
of them because he was so quick to issue a public apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never came forward and said I'm sorry I did the wrong
thing,'' DeConcini said. ``I said what I did turned out to be a
political error. McCain came forward and said, `I made a mistake
I'm sorry.' It turned out to be a much better spin.''
</P>
<P>
   Cranston, 85, like McCain, cites campaign finance as a top
priority. The presence of so much money in politics ``leads to the
suggestion of corruption even if there is none,'' Cranston said.
``If somebody contributes to you and then has a problem, that opens
the senator up to the charge that he's been bought. But what do you
do? The only solution is to reduce and end the flow of money in
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if there is no buying or selling of votes, the person who
contributes gets an advantage,'' Cranston says, adding it's only
natural that a busy senator will see someone whose name they
recognize.
</P>
<P>
   ``Access does give an advantage. At least you get to present
your case. It's inevitable that you are going to help somebody who
helps you.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or by e-mail at
Judy(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
