<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   `Mr. Smith' Goes to DVD
</P>
<P>
   ``He should have seen it coming but didn't,'' Frank Capra Jr.
said the other day. By 1939 his father, who died in 1991, had
directed films like ``It Happened One Night'' and ``Mr. Deeds Goes
to Town.'' When he went to Washington to plan ``Mr. Smith Goes to
Washington,'' released this week in a fine DVD edition by Columbia
Tri-Star, his reputation helped speed the preparations. ``He had
some very good help from the Senate and the Washington press
corps,'' Capra said.
</P>
<P>
   But in his film he turned around and, precipitating one of the
movies' more celebrated flaps, depicted politicians and reporters
as venal frauds and irresponsible hacks. Or so it was thought at a
time when furors over movies might involve matters other than
excessive sex and violence.
</P>
<P>
   By then Capra was known for films that made positive statements
about freedom and the American tradition. In Capra movies,
individuals made a difference by battling well-oiled machines.
That, of course, describes Jefferson Smith (James Stewart), the
fumbling bumpkin shipped east by a canny old pol (Claude Rains) and
a press tycoon who buys politicians (Edward Arnold) to serve out a
Senate term.
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring only to secure a few federal dollars to build a boys'
camp, Smith finds himself forced to his feet in the Senate chamber
for a filibuster that in the none-too-subtle Capra style upholds
democracy against a cynical and corrupt establishment.
</P>
<P>
   In a commentary on the disc, Capra says his father actually
wanted to make a movie about Chopin, but Harry Cohn, the head of
Columbia Studios, felt that as a subject Chopin threatened his two
rules of movie making: finish on budget and make money. Instead
they chose a novel: ``The Gentleman From Montana.''
</P>
<P>
   Capra disliked screen tests, preferring to sit down and talk
with actors. Told that left-handed people were eccentric, he hired
left-handed Thomas Mitchell to play the rumpled reporter Diz Moore,
who isn't quite a fall-down drunk but has all the other raffish
characteristics generally ascribed to the loudmouthed scribblers of
the Washington press corps.
</P>
<P>
   About the only dependable adult around is Smith's wise and
worldly assistant, played by the truly incomparable Jean Arthur.
``She was unbelievably difficult to work with, hard to rehearse,
very shy,'' Capra says on the disc. Brash and outspoken on screen,
Arthur dived for her trailer after every scene. ``She was very
self-deprecating, worried about her performance,'' Capra said.
</P>
<P>
   Out on the Senate floor, the members carry on like arrogant
schoolboys. Capra notes on the disc that when his father scouted
the real chamber, he found senators' initials carved on their
desks. The clock was locked because senators liked to push the
hands forward so they could get out early. ``We tell them what
phonies and crackpots make their laws,'' a reporter says,
explaining his job to Jefferson Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Alben Barkley, then a real-life Senator from Kentucky and later
Harry S. Truman's vice president, attacked the film as a grotesque
distortion as did many other officials. When the film was screened
by the Washington Press Club, someone was sent to shut it off, but
the place was so crowded he couldn't get in.
</P>
<P>
   Random Hearts
</P>
<P>
   A Washington policeman, Van Den Broeck (Harrison Ford, with
Kristin Scott Thomas), called Dutch, and a New Hampshire
congresswoman, Kay Chandler ( Thomas), discover that his wife
(Susanna Thompson) and her husband (Peter Coyote) were lovers and
sitting side by side when they died in a plane crash. So Dutch and
Kay have an affair of their own. That established, Sydney Pollack's
movie drifts off into the nuances. A hard case at work, Dutch is
domesticated at home, which makes his wife's infidelity
particularly hard to work through. Kay is more the brisk, efficient
type. Although she and Dutch don't make the coziest couple, Pollack
watches them ``with a stylistic polish and keenness of observation
not often found in American films anymore,'' Janet Maslin wrote in
The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   _1999. Columbia Tri-Star. $108.97; DVD, $24.95. 133 minutes.
Closed captioned. R. Release date: Feb. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Stigmata
</P>
<P>
   Who is this beautician from Pittsburgh, and why is she talking
in that baritone? When Frankie Paige (Patricia Arquette) receives a
mysterious rosary, candles flicker and Frankie starts acting
crazily in ways that interest the Vatican. A special investigator
(Gabriel Byrne) is dispatched and decides that it may all have to
do with a new biblical text that could undermine the authority of
the church. Then it's up to Frankie to keep things jumping in a
film that is ``little more than a series of music-video style
eruptions'' (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   _ 1999. MGM.$107.37; LD, $24.98. 103 minutes. Closed captioned.
R. Release date: Feb. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Lovers on the Bridge (Les Amants du Pont Neuf)
</P>
<P>
   Ah, Paris and life around and under the Pont Neuf. In a great
plywood cream puff of a movie, a section of the city is constructed
to contain the briefly flaming romance of Michele (Juliette
Binoche), an artist going blind, and Alex (Denis Lavant), a sad
young vagrant in residence beneath the span. But the affair, a
sentimental blend of realism and surrealism, is no match for the
architecture. Scamming for money, Alex and Michele do some
wine-soaked celebrating in a tale that isn't ``easy to stomach
unless you have a high tolerance for whimsy'' (Vincent Canby).
</P>
<P>
   _ 1992. Miramax. $104.16. 126 minutes. French with English
subtitles. R.
</P>
<P>
   Get Real
</P>
<P>
   A principled gay British high school student, Steven (Ben
Silverstone) accidentally falls into a feverish affair with a
popular fellow student (John Gorton), an Oxford-bound athlete with
a model for a girlfriend. Not the first movie to present such a
situation, Simon Shore's film has some cliched characters and sudsy
moments but ``offers a far more realistic and compelling vision of
teenage growing pains and peer pressure than any of the recent high
school movies from Hollywood'' (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   _ 1999. Paramount. $64.10; DVD, $29.99. 111 minutes. Closed
captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   THE FARMER'S WIFE. In David Sutherland's intimate and generally
unsentimental documentary, shown on ``Frontline'' in 1998, a young
Nebraska farm couple, Juanita and Darrel Buschkoetter, battle
drought and bankers to save their farm and stand up to the stress
that ends their marriage. ``Living hell'' is far too mild a
description for that kind of pressure, endured with especially
steely resolve by Juanita, who in the end holds it all together. At
six hours the story gets long and grinding, but, Walter Goodman
wrote in The New York Times, ``few lives are made for television,
and their troubles deserve attention.'' Warner. $49.98; three
cassettes.
</P>
<P>
   DANCEMAKER. ``Sometimes I think if I asked them to jump out the
window, they would,'' the choreographer Paul Taylor says of his
dancers in Matthew Diamond's Academy Award-nominated documentary.
Performance, rehearsals, a trip to India and the backstage scene
are part of the story in a film that had a theater run and was
shown on PBS's ``American Masters'' series last month. 1999.
Docurama. $24.95; DVD, $29.95. Release date: Feb. 29.
</P>
<P>
   WOMAN WANTED. A housekeeper (Holly Hunter) with influence beyond
her station opens a rift between father (Michael Moriarty) and son
(Kiefer Sutherland). Sutherland's film won the Slamdunk
best-picture award that is handed out in Park City, Utah, at the
same time the Sundance Film Festival is being held, but it has
appeared only on cable and not in theaters. 1999. Touchstone. 100
minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
