<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISON-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PRISON GUARDS INDICTED ON SAME DAY AS DEADLY RIOT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRESCENT CITY, Calif. _ It doesn't have the name recognition of
Leavenworth, Sing Sing or any other high-profile hellhole for the
nation's convicts. But despite its brief history, Pelican Bay State
Prison has a reputation in law enforcement circles as one of the
worst maximum security lockups in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Only 10 years old, the overcrowded prison on 275 acres in
northwest California has been the scene of riots, the subject of
litigation accusing guards of violent misconduct, and the focal
point of a harsh human rights report by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday _ the same day guards shot 13 inmates, killing one,
while halting what the authorities said was a race riot _ two
former Pelican Bay guards were charged by federal authorities with
arranging violent attacks on inmates, one of whom died.
</P>
<P>
   At nearly the same time Pelican Bay's yard became a battleground
for 200 black and Hispanic prisoners, a federal grand jury
indictment was made public in San Francisco accusing guard Edward
Michael Powers, 54, and former guard Jose Ramon Garcia, 44, of
violating inmates' civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   FBI spokesman George Grotz said there was no link between the
riot and the indictments.
</P>
<P>
   Powers and Garcia, both from Brookings, Ore., allegedly
conspired to instigate attacks between 1992 and 1995 by inmates on
other prisoners convicted of sexual offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Powers, a sergeant, and Garcia, a former officer, each face up
to 10 years in federal prison and a fine of $250,000 if convicted.
They are scheduled to be arraigned March 13 in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Powers has been on paid administrative leave since being
escorted off prison grounds in March 1998. Garcia was later
convicted on substantially the same charges in Del Norte County
Superior Court and sentenced to four years and eight months at a
prison that was undisclosed for safety reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer who represents Powers and formerly represented Garcia
said both men would deny the federal charges.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Marjorie Knoller of San Francisco, asserted that
Powers and Garcia were whistle-blowers who were being paid back by
vindictive prison officials.
</P>
<P>
   California Department of Corrections spokeswoman Jeanie Esajian
said her agency would have no comment on the indictments.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Fama, an attorney for the Prison Law Office, a San Rafael
prisoners' rights group, called the indictments emblematic of ``a
deliberate policy of allowing excessive force'' at Pelican Bay
during the early and mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Fama said the use of deadly force to quell the riot Wednesday
and the prison's own internal review of the incident would be
investigated by a federal court monitor appointed in 1995 to
oversee reforms at the prison.
</P>
<P>
   The current monitor, San Francisco lawyer John Hagar, will
report to U.S. District Judge Thelton Henderson on the incident and
Pelican Bay's response, Fama said.
</P>
<P>
   Ruling in a landmark prisoners' rights case, Madrid vs. Gomez,
Henderson found in early 1995 that the prison was guilty of
widespread civil rights violations, particularly with regard to the
use of force and the provision of medical and mental health care.
</P>
<P>
   According to Hagar, who worked on the Madrid case, Pelican Bay
has made progress in meeting Henderson's demands for change, but
remains obliged to demonstrate to the monitor that it has made all
the improvements required.
</P>
<P>
   Knoller said Wednesday's riot at Pelican Bay and abuses
throughout the state correctional system were the products of
``specific policies'' carried out by the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The CDC sets it up that way,'' Knoller charged. ``Basically
they put enemies out there and expect them to behave. The more
violence they have, the greater their budgets will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoller has a civil racketeering lawsuit pending against the
Department of Corrections in federal court. She said hostilities
typically erupted between prison gangs whose members often could
trace their origins to street gangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the nature of the beast,'' she said. ``Northern Mexican
prisoners hate southern Mexican prisoners. The Crips hate the
Blood. And among the whites there are the Skinheads and the Nazi
Low Riders.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoller said members of the Aryan Brotherhood, a white racist
gang allegedly responsible for at least three inmate killings, no
longer were allowed to mingle with the general population on prison
yards.
</P>
<P>
   According to state corrections critics, these rivalries have
been systematically exploited by prison guards, generally to
maintain tight control but in some instances for purely sadistic
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The guards' union, a major contributor to both political parties
in California, has denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you find 50 inmate-manufactured weapons on the yard, I
don't know that (the riot) falls within that category,'' said
another corrections spokeswoman, Terry Thornton.
</P>
<P>
   She dismissed any suggestion that underlying official policies
and practices had set the stage for Wednesday's riot.
</P>
<P>
   The indictments of the former guards were hailed by U.S.
Attorney Robert Mueller as the result of a crackdown on
correctional system abuses that he said had the full cooperation of
the Department of Corrections.
</P>
<P>
   The indictments were unveiled only nine days after the
conviction of another former Pelican Bay guard, David E. Lewis, in
a 1994 inmate shooting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-00 1726EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
