<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Antiques Roadshow' causing stir in publishing
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everything old is suddenly new again. The collectibles craze,
fueled by the ``Antiques Roadshow'' on PBS and online auction sites
such as eBay, has created a miniboom in the book business.
</P>
<P>
   Workman's recently released ``Antiques Roadshow Primer'' has
sold nearly 330,000 copies. Membership in Doubleday Select's
Antiques and Collectibles Book Club quadrupled when it changed its
name to the Antiques Roadshow Book Club. And publishers are rushing
to print with related books.
</P>
<P>
   Projects in the works include another ``Antiques Roadshow''
tie-in by Workman on 20th-century collectibles and a page-a-day
calendar for 2001. And this fall, Warner will publish ``Hidden
Treasures'' by two of the show's appraisers, twins Leigh and Leslie
Keno.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Oprah touch: Oprah Winfrey's impact on book sales doesn't
seem to be diminishing. Until the talk show queen selected Robert
Morgan's ``Gap Creek'' (Algonquin, $22.95) for her TV book club,
the North Carolina native expected to sell 10,000 copies. Shortly
after Winfrey's announcement, Morgan's publicist called to say they
were printing another half-million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told somebody it felt as though all heaven was breaking out
at once,'' said Morgan, who teaches creative writing at Cornell
University. ``With the lottery, you have to go out and buy a
ticket. I didn't even do that.''
</P>
<P>
   That Morgan is an author at all is as incredible as his
selection by Oprah. A high school dropout, he managed to get
admitted to Emory College at Oxford and later to the University of
North Carolina as a mathematics major.
</P>
<P>
   The math course he wanted to take was filled, however, so he
signed up for a creative writing class under Guy Owen, author of
``The Flim-Flam Man.''
</P>
<P>
   One day Owen brought in a story Morgan had written and said, ``I
read this story and wept.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hooked after that,'' Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of his stories have been inspired by his Appalachian
childhood. ``Gap Creek,'' which follows the fortunes and
misfortunes of a young woman at the turn of the century, is based
on events in his maternal grandparents' hardscrabble lives.
</P>
<P>
   Things were not much better for the 55-year-old when he was
growing up near Hendersonville. His father worked as a stonemason
and farmer and his mother was a cotton mill worker, department
store clerk and beautician.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have a car,'' Morgan said. ``We didn't have a
television set, either, because my parents were very religious and
didn't believe in it. I saw my first movie in 1961 in Atlanta. It
was Fellini's `La Dolce Vita.'''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of watching TV or movies, Morgan's family told stories
that would form the basis for much of his fiction. ``They would
tell stories about my grandmother keeping a fire burning all night
to keep a panther from coming down the chimney. And my
great-grandmother could remember the Civil War. It was a writer's
dream.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In the news: Atlanta writer Thomas Stanley's new book, ``The
Millionaire Mind'' (Andrews McMeel, $26.95), lands at No. 4 on The
New York Times Bestseller List Sunday. His previous book, ``The
Millionaire Next Door'' (Pocket, $14), is still going strong at No.
7 on the paperback list.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
