<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7467 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS27-COX     02-24 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `City of God' reflects era's uncertainties
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Feb. 27.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Critics should acknowledge their prejudices or find another line
of work. Criticism uninformed by point of view _ an impossible
thing to hold together without the glue of preferences, beliefs,
prejudices _ collapses into summary and recapitulation. When it
does, the abdication of judgment masks itself as objectivity. But
criticism is, and should be, subjective in the fullest sense. It is
a response to what is being offered, whether that be a movie, a
meal or a novel.
</P>
<P>
   E.L. Doctorow's ``City of God'' is a novel about many things at
once and nothing for very long. It is one part cultural
kaleidoscope, one part inquiry into the validity of religion at a
time when science, popular culture and all else have diminished
what is sacred and exalted what is profane. But it is also a novel
whose scaffolding _ or a goodly part of it _ happens to be New York
City. Specifically Manhattan. There is no particular reason a novel
set on the Nebraska prairie should have a stronger claim to
authenticity than one set in New York, any more than the cliches of
Southern fiction should ring truer than those rooted anywhere else.
We have our prejudices. And yet there are more complex
considerations as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manhattan,'' Elizabeth Hardwick wrote last fall in ``American
Fictions,'' ``is not altogether felicitous for fiction. It is not a
city of memory, not a family city, not the capital of America so
much as the iconic capital of this century.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is precisely why ``City of God'' could hardly have been
set anywhere else. New York is the nerve center of our culture, and
in that sense emblematic of what we have become. And so ``City of
God'' is not a linear story of the conventional kind _ beginning,
middle, end _ but a meditation on the disconnectedness of our
lives.
</P>
<P>
   The plot, such as it is, centers on a brass cross that has
disappeared from an Episcopal church in the East Village and later
turns up on the roof of the Synagogue of Evolutionary Judaism on
the Upper West Side. The cross thus represents an act of double
desecration, and one that brings together the Rev. Thomas
Pemberton, pastor of St. Timothy's, and rabbis Joshua Gruen and
Sarah Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   In setting out to resolve the mystery of the cross _ a phrase
resonant with meaning for Christians _ the three find themselves
also seeking to justify to one another the meaning and purpose of
religion. Intellectually and in other ways, they encounter false
leads and unforeseen complications. The latter come to include,
somewhat predictably, those of the heart as well as the soul.
Rabbis Gruen and Blumenthal are married and young; Thomas
Pemberton, who is older, is having problems with doubt. In Sarah
Blumenthal _ who is grieving for her father, killed in the
Holocaust _ he finds something more than a sympathetic listener.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is narrated in different voices, but it is the voice
outside the story _ that of a New York novelist named Everett _
that lends perspective to the whole. Everett, whom many will take
to be a stand-in for Doctorow, comes upon a news item describing
the stolen cross just when he is in need of an idea that will
germinate into a novel. What the reader is reading, in fact, is
only Everett's diary.
</P>
<P>
   As a fictional device, this is neither new nor reader-friendly.
Doctorow, what's more, has borrowed from history and documented
fact before, notably in ``Ragtime'' and ``World's Fair.'' Here he
does so with insouciant ease. The century that began with Einstein
and ended with e-mail is compacted into a collage of snapshots,
vignettes, pastiches and paste-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our minds today,'' Doctorow told an interviewer recently,
``are buzzing with information, our thought is contingent, as if
we're a patchwork of Web sites, hopping from one claim on our
attention to the next. Our mental rhythm is not what it was 50
years ago. We're no longer exclusively linear in our thinking. We
find meaning in discontinuity. We're the culture of the short
take.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this is, of course, true in varying degrees _ more for
some than for others. Yet the idea of disconnectedness is
double-sided, like the heist of the brass cross. We seek it even as
we deny seeking it. But at the center of ``City of God'' _ hinted
at by the title's allusion to St. Augustine's contemplation of the
material world and the spiritual _ is the idea of permanence,
something other than the material. It transcends place, even New
York, and yet it is hard to locate. Is it within us? Within a God
whose presence seems ever fainter as war and cruelty grow more
frequent?
</P>
<P>
   ``The center does not hold,'' T.S. Eliot wrote 23 years into the
century. In E.L. Doctorow's often maddening, occasionally brilliant
novel, it still doesn't. The old certainties _ of faith, of mind
and heart _ are undone by new confusions of purpose, even by denial
of purpose.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  City of God. By E.L. Doctorow. Random House. $25. (Audio:
Random House. $25.95.
</P>
<P>
   6 hours, abridged. Read by John Rubinstein.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
