<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7470 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MIFUNE-FILM-REVIEW-NY     02-24 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIFUNE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MIFUNE': A BARE BONES SETTING FOR MORAL COMEUPPANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1995 the Danish filmmakers Lars von Trier and Thomas
Vinterberg promulgated a list of 10 principles _ the now notorious
Dogma 95 ``vow of chastity'' _ in the hope of rescuing world
cinema, once again, from decadent bourgeois individualism.
</P>
<P>
   To earn the Dogma 95 seal of approval, a film must forswear such
emblems of false consciousness as props, genre conventions and
``temporal and geographical alienation.'' Cameras must be hand
held, only available light and sound may be used and all traces of
directorial personality, including the director's credit, must be
expunged.
</P>
<P>
   Soren Kragh-Jacobsen's ``Mifune'' is the Dogma collective's
third official production, after Vinterberg's ``Celebration'' and
Von Trier's ``Idiots.'' (Harmony Korine's ``Julien Donkey-Boy,''
released last year to widespread critical perplexity, was made
according to dogmatic tenets but without the group's imprimatur.)
</P>
<P>
   Knowing this should not necessarily influence your response to
the film; you pay your money to watch a movie, not a theory, and
``Mifune'' is, by any standard, a pretty good movie. But being
aware of the self-imposed constraints has an effect similar to
knowing the production budget of ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   Kragh-Jacobsen's asceticism is, in its own way, as ostentatious
as James Cameron's profligacy. Watching a rigorously low-tech Dogma
95 picture and watching a state-of-the-art, super-expensive
Hollywood blockbuster are similar experiences: both nudge your
awareness of filmmaking technique.
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds like a distraction, it is also, in the case of
``Mifune,'' a source of pleasure. When the sun begins to set over
the rural Danish backwater in which most of the film takes place,
you feel a pang of anxiety for the actors and the crew, wondering
where they will find the necessary illumination.
</P>
<P>
   Simple actions like lighting a candle or a cigarette, or the
accidental tipping over of a lamp, flicker with aesthetic
importance. The range of tones and shadows that twilight, cloudy
skies or low-watt light bulbs impart to a single face seems
revelatory. The occurrence of music becomes magical.
</P>
<P>
   In its stringent suppression of auteurism _ all signatories to
the vow of chastity ``swear to refrain from creating a `work''' _
dogmatism, at least as applied by Kragh-Jacobsen, derives
impressive aesthetic authority from ordinary sights and sounds. The
camera does not create beauty, but rather discovers it.
</P>
<P>
   Kragh-Jacobsen's camera also discovers a story, one that is at
once arresting in its strangeness and strangely conventional.
``Mifune'' is a classic tale of moral comeuppance and sexual
redemption. Its lesson _ that love, loyalty and friendship matter
more than status or material things _ is the perfect allegorical
correlative to its formal creed.
</P>
<P>
   It has also been, I hasten to point out, a staple of bourgeois
cinematic false consciousness from Frank Capra to Barry Levinson.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps inspired by Dogma 95's cinematic Lutheranism, perhaps by
Hollywood's secular myth making, Kragh-Jacobsen delivers a homily
on the doctrine of the fortunate fall, the idea that suffering is
the sinner's surest byway to grace. The sinner in question is
Kresten (Anders W. Berthelsen), a Copenhagen businessman who seems
to take his cell phone, his BMW and his new trophy wife (Sofie
Grabol) as the visible signs of God's love.
</P>
<P>
   Kresten has never told his bride or her wealthy family the truth
about himself, which is that he grew up in the Danish translation
of a Tennessee Williams play. But a telephone call summons him home
to a rotting farmhouse on the rustic island of Lolland, where he
finds his father's corpse laid out on the dining room table, decked
out with weeds.
</P>
<P>
   Hiding under the table is Rud (Jesper Asholt), Kresten's
mentally disabled brother, whose inner world is governed by a
private mythology involving crop circles, comic books and the
legendary Japanese movie star Toshiro Mifune, obligingly
impersonated by Kresten. Later, we learn that Kresten and Rud's
mother hanged herself from a nearby tree.
</P>
<P>
   Grace arrives in the form of Liva (Iben Hjejle), a prostitute on
the run from a nasty pimp and a psychopathic telephone stalker, who
answers Kresten's classified ad seeking a housekeeper. Their
eccentric menage is rounded out by Liva's younger brother, a
raffish boarding-school refugee named Bjarke (Emil Tarding).
</P>
<P>
   What transpires among these characters is, in retrospect, quite
predictable, but the director and his dedicated cast manage to keep
the story, and the audience, off balance for most of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   The brusque realism of Kragh-Jacobsen's style _ his careful
suppression of style _ allows a surprising sweetness to emerge.
``Mifune,'' which unblinkingly records scenes of cruelty and sexual
degradation, ends with a slow dance, by dim lamplight, to found
music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even cretinous people can be religious,'' a local clergyman
says of Rud, who is, indeed, the film's designated holy fool.
``Mifune'' demonstrates, perhaps inadvertently, that even a
dogmatist can be romantic.
</P>
<P>
   `Mifune' is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying parent or
adult guardian). It contains sex scenes, both ecstatic and
desultory; a few acts of violence; and the deliberate soiling of an
expensive Persian rug. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `MIFUNE' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Soren Kragh-Jacobsen; written (in Danish, with
English subtitles) by Kragh-Jacobsen and Anders Thomas Jensen,
based on a story by Kragh-Jacobsen; director of photography,
Anthony Dod Mantle; edited by Valdis Oskarsdottir; music by Nulle
Og Verdensorkestret; produced by Birgitte Hald and Morten Kaufmann;
released by Sony Pictures Classics. Running time: 99 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   With: Anders W. Berthelsen (Kresten), Iben Hjejle (Liva), Jesper
Asholt (Rud), Sofie Grabol (Claire), Emil Tarding (Bjarke), Anders
Hove (Gerner) and Paprika Steen (Pernille). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-00 1731EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
