<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Feb. 25, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A broad flow from the south will continue to direct unseasonably
mild air over most of the East. Afternoon temperatures near
record-setting levels will be common from the southern Great Lakes
and Ohio Valley. Meanwhile, a strengthening low-pressure system
will produce areas of snow along many slopes of the northern
Rockies as well as bands of showers and potent thunderstorms in the
eastern Plains.
</P>
<P>
   The day will begin with thunderstorms developing over central
and eastern parts Texas and Oklahoma as an approaching cold front
lifts warm, humid air. Strong, shifting winds will impart rotation
to some of the storms, raising the risk of a few tornadoes,
especially during midday and afternoon. Farther north, potent
thunderstorms will erupt across the lower Missouri River valley.
Localized damaging wind gusts and hail will occur with a few of
these storms.
</P>
<P>
   Rain will develop over the Dakotas and northern Mississippi
Valley during the day as a vigorous low-pressure system emerges
from over the central Rockies. In the colder air west of the storm
center, areas of heavy snow will shift from the northern Rockies
Friday day to the western Dakotas Friday night. West of the
Rockies, drier conditions will develop, although showers will
persist near the Northwest coast.
</P>
<P>
   Cooler air will spill into New York and New England as high
pressure expands in eastern Canada. A front marking the leading
edge of the cooler air will be the focus for showers and areas of
drizzle. Meanwhile, the Southeast will stay mild and dry.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Midwest Meltdown
</P>
<P>
   Snow vanished rapidly over the upper Middle West this week, but
warmth was not the salient factor in the meltdown. Indeed, wind and
moisture helped to accelerate the melting of snow. When air in
contact with a snowpack is moist, net condensation occurs more
readily. In the process, latent heat of condensation is released, a
bonus source of energy for melting snow. In turn, feisty winds from
the south continuously imported moist air, in essence adding fuel
to the fire. Had the weather in the upper Middle West been warm,
dry and calm, the meltdown would have proceeded much more slowly.
</P>
</TEXT>
