<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGGER GOES ON A QUEST TO CLIMB HIS FAMILY TREE 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE TIGGER MOVIE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the voices of Jim Cummings, Nikita Hopkins, Ken Sansom &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Narrated by John Hurt &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Jun Falkenstein &QL;
</P>
<P>
   G 76 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A.A. Milne's ``Winnie the Pooh'' bunch via Disney animation
pitches in to help their companion Tigger cope with the fact that
he is the only one of his breed and thus has no family. Each friend
helps in his own way, which means that Owl lays on plenty of
pontification, Pooh is constantly distracted by the need for honey,
the ponderous Eeyore can't get out of his own way, Piglet frets too
much to be effective and Rabbit, who is the most capable, has other
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Tigger is left to deal with the problem more or less by himself.
When Owl suggests that a family tree might be the best place to
start determining one's roots, the tiger bounds off through the
Hundred Acre Wood gazing up every tree trunk wondering if it could
hold knowledge of the whereabouts of what he is sure must be a
flock of relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Alternating between moods of euphoria and despair, Tigger and
little Roo, his most persistent and energetic ally, sweep the
countryside but come up with no signs of kin or forebears. To cheer
him up, Owl and the others concoct a letter that appears to come
from long-lost family. Determined to invite them all to a reunion,
he prepares the Tigger lair. (Everybody lives in great-looking tree
houses.)
</P>
<P>
   When the attendees turn out to be his well-meaning pals
disguised in tiger outfits, Tigger takes off into the blizzard on
another ancestor hunt. Maybe somebody is missing the point here,
which is that such loyal friends might be family enough. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-8 This film will eventually get a stiff workout in the
VCR, but there is just enough message and production value to
justify a trip to the theater, where it has been going full tilt at
the box office. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SNOW DAY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chevy Chase, Chris Elliott, Mark Webber, Schuyler Fisk,
Emmanuelle Chriqui &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Chris Koch &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG 89 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Never ones for complexity, generic ``family'' films seldom are
quite this free of mental taxation. Dad (Chase) is an overly
amiable television weatherman. Forced to wear idiotic get-ups that
match inclement conditions, he still has the meteorological smarts
to predict the season's big snowfall down to the last granule.
</P>
<P>
   Next morning everybody wakes up to No School: hog heaven for
students and bother for parents facing a day juggling the
offspring.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of related story elements then insert themselves. Out
to clear the streets and spoil the fun, a character with amazingly
bad teeth called Snowplowman (Elliott) barges around in a huge
truck that like a B-17 in World War II bears the logo of a scantily
clad woman and is named Clementine.
</P>
<P>
   Cartoonishly nasty, Snowplowman keeps the small children
occupied pelting him with snowballs and diving out from under his
truck, which brakes for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Dad's teen-age son, Hal (Webber), who uses the day
off to pursue Claire (Chriqui), the school siren. Not too
surprisingly, she already has a bigger boyfriend. Fortunately, he's
also a lot dumber, which lets the very clever Hal toy with him like
a matador with an enraged bull while charming Claire with a
television appearance and by digging a huge likeness of a whale
(her favorite animal) in the snow.
</P>
<P>
   Really, though, Hal belongs with Lane (Fisk), a bright,
attractive classmate who has a crush on him. While that situation
sorts itself out, the bravest small fry clash with Snowplowman.
Hostages are taken and traded: Snowplowman's pet crow for a fat
little boy with flatulence. Eventually, the children steal the
truck with an eye to unplowing the streets. A second snow day? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE In other hands (Wes Craven's, for instance), the
snowplow would make a fine engine of death and destruction. Here it
roars and charges but succumbs to general harmlessness. That leaves
the violence to snowball fights. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX A couple of sanitary kisses. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-6 Parents could make far bigger mistakes than taking
small children to this movie. There is nothing too disturbing, and
the storytelling is on their level. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 7-10 The one and only age for this film. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE BEACH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Leonardo DiCaprio, Virginie Ledoyen, Guillaume Canet, Tilda
Swinton, Robert Carlyle, Paterson Joseph &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Danny Boyle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   R 120 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brimming with notions of taking life to the edge, an American
tourist named Richard (DiCaprio) alights in Bangkok, where he
swills snake blood on a dare and otherwise proclaims his lust for
challenge. In a flophouse full of like-minded European and American
adventure-seekers, he meets Daffy (Carlyle), who gives Richard a
map with the location of an island beach so rarefied one mentions
it only in garbled terms and then only on pain of the most dire
consequences if its whereabouts were to become common knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Shorter on judgment than he is on wanderlust, Richard makes a
copy of the map and plants it for others to find. Then he and a
young French couple, Francoise (Ledoyen) and Etienne (Canet),
strike out for the beach on a journey that requires swimming across
a channel that could hold a shark or two and jumping off a 100-foot
cliff.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way they discover that a large field of marijuana they
miraculously come across is patrolled by guards who will kill them
on sight. Scooting from that scene, they happen onto a commune of
similar escapees from civilization, who introduce them to the
beach.
</P>
<P>
   A life of frolic ensues, overseen by Sal (Swinton), the kind of
person who naturally takes charge of loosely organized situations.
An attractive, charismatic lad, Richard assumes some prominence
himself, scores with Francoise and Sal and experiments with
feverishly delusional visions of empowerment. It's fun for a while,
but watch out. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE Young backpackers are shot down by the marijuana
farmers, two commune members are gorily torn up in a shark attack,
and there are other violent incidents. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Richard and Sal have sex on screen, while his tryst with
Francoise goes mostly unseen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Quite a bit and full-strength. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 12-14 DiCaprio brings them flocking to a movie that is
strictly for teen-agers. Parents should be aware. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 14 AND UP It's the old story: keeping them away, if that's
the intent, could prove difficult. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-00 1734EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
