<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7477 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT     02-24 0206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPOTLIGHT ON A NEW ALBUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By ANN POWERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRACY CHAPMAN: ``Telling Stories'' (Elektra).
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Chapman is one of those quiet ones you have to watch. She
speaks not for the cool, who hold their tongues, but for the shy,
who struggle to say things that won't misrepresent them. Her plain
melodies and simple lyrics serve the confessions people usually
can't bear to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``Telling Stories,'' Chapman's fourth album in 11 years, relates
an epic in modest glimpses. Its subject is the tension between
spirit and flesh. The disc begins with rueful glances at a failed
romance, but soon finds its theme in songs that compare a distant
lover to an immanent deity, both cruel and irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Only One,'' with harmonies by Emmylou Harris, is a
religious mother's grieving song, and the striking ``First Try''
uses a West African arrangement to capture the pain of wanting more
than an ordinary life.
</P>
<P>
   Although Chapman sometimes seeks relief in her weakest style,
that of the generically uplifting ballad of social concern, at its
best ``Telling Stories'' wrenchingly captures the still, small
voice within that utters what is most difficult.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
