<P>
   L I F E S T Y L E &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ A question for the answer guy: ``In `It's a Wonderful
Life,' Sam Wainwright cabled Bedford Falls from London authorizing
his local office to advance George Bailey up to $25,000 to help
him. How much would this money be worth in today's dollars?'' By
ROGERS CADENHEAD. Story has moved in ``l'' lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   E N T E R T A I N M E N T &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ALAMO-HARRIGAN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ After years of relative obscurity, Texan Stephen
Harrigan has penned an epic tale about the Alamo that could be the
first literary blockbuster of the century. The novel, ``The Gates
of the Alamo,'' is being touted as a can't-miss bestseller that
might do for the unassuming Texas native what ``Lonesome Dove'' did
for Larry McMurtry. By JEFF GUINN. Story has moved in ``e''
entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ALAMO-REVIEW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ How good is ``The Gates of the Alamo''? Star-Telegram
books editor Jeff Guinn, says it may be on par with ``Gone With the
Wind'' and ``Lonesome Dove.'' Guinn says that author Stephen
Harrigan has written a masterpiece, combining real historical
figures with compelling fictional characters to tell the story
about Texas' war of independence and the famous battle that defined
it. By JEFF GUINN. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REINDEER GAMES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ The tongue-in-cheek crime drama ``Reindeer Games'' was
originally supposed to open in December, but any movie that opens
with a bloody, lifeless Santa Claus lying in the snow isn't gonna
do much for your holiday spirit. By ROBERT PHILPOT. Story has moved
in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-WONDER BOYS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ As the first frames unspool of Curtis Hanson's
delightful new film ``Wonder Boys'' (his follow-up to the
Oscar-winning ``L.A. Confidential''), the picture envelops you like
an engaging novel savored slowly in front of a crackling fire on a
snowy afternoon. It's fitting praise, especially for a film that
largely concerns itself with the art of writing, but the simile
rings true throughout. By TODD CAMP. Story has moved in ``e''
entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-KNOCKOUT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ It's easy to want to root for ``Knockout'' because
it's a well-meaning, low-budget movie aimed at an underserved
audience. But it's just not very good, and the low budget is part
of the problem. By ROBERT PHILPOT. Story has moved in ``e''
entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
