<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7480 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-24 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IN DEFENSE OF WHAT'S HIS NAME 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Well now, just who is Warren Rudman?
</P>
<P>
   The former New Hampshire senator is hardly a household word,
neither a hero nor a knave.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he retired from the Senate in 1993, however, Rudman
had earned an enviable reputation in Washington as a worthy
legislator known for common sense, integrity and fair-mindedness.
He compiled an impressive record, from co-authoring Congress'
budget control measure of 1985 to acting as vice chairman of the
Senate Iran-contra committee, where he helped produce a
tough-minded bipartisan report that refused to whitewash Ronald
Reagan aide Oliver North and other administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   Since then Rudman has quietly practiced law and crusaded for
cutting the federal budget deficit. In short, this is a good guy.
He is not a creepy politician of bad character.
</P>
<P>
   But he had the temerity to become Arizona Sen. John McCain's
campaign co-chairman, and in the grand tradition of guilt by
association, that makes him a target of the religious right.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Robertson, the founder and president of the Christian
Coalition, set out to demonize Rudman as a ``vicious bigot'' in
South Carolina and Michigan with radio ads and automated phone
calls aimed at arousing conservative voters. The fact that the
charge is outrageous was irrelevant to Robertson, who never met an
exaggeration he didn't like.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson also has plenty of nasty stuff to say about McCain,
but for the recent primaries he threw in Rudman for good measure.
The true Christian spirit apparently does not interfere with the
instinct for a mean smear campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In his calls to voters, Robertson accused Rudman of having
written ``that conservative Christians in politics are antiabortion
zealots, homophobes and would-be censors.'' But what Rudman really
said in a book is that SOME Christian conservatives are bigots
while others are decent folks.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson, demonstrating his own zealot credentials, is
basically ticked off because Rudman, who is pro-choice, strongly
backed fellow Yankee David Souter, a moderate on the abortion
issue, for the Supreme Court. On that subject Robertson has no
tolerance for any point of view not his own.
</P>
<P>
   McCain fueled Robertson's fury by once musing that Rudman, a
close friend, would make a fine attorney general in a McCain
administration. As the nation's highest legal officer, the attorney
general can influence Supreme Court choices.
</P>
<P>
   Rudman says he doesn't want the job, and McCain says he wasn't
promising it. But Robertson is so fixated on overthrowing Roe v.
Wade, the Supreme Court decision giving limited constitutional
protection to abortion, that he doesn't care. He operates on fumes,
not facts.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a little question of money and political influence
here. McCain has denounced single-issue groups like the
anti-abortion crusaders for turning their cause into a business on
which they make money.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson fears that McCain's campaign finance reforms would
restrict the amount that the Christian Coalition can spend to
influence elections. Rudman had nothing to do with that, and in
fact McCain has amended his original proposal to add protections
for independent advocacy groups. But Robertson is still sore
because, he says, the concept alone is potentially ``very
damaging'' to the Christian Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The religious right, once powerful, has been collapsing
internally the past decade. Partly, the reason is that its air of
moral superiority and doctrinaire extremism grate on mainstream
voters. In part it is because the movement frittered away its
energies on fringe presidential candidates who had no hope of
winning. And in part it is because a majority of voters don't think
abortion is the only issue in the world and don't want it banned
outright even though many favor some limitations.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson and his troops rallied around Texas Gov. George W.
Bush early for the same reason other Republicans did. He looked
like a winner.
</P>
<P>
   Bush moved to the philosophical right to please them in South
Carolina, and they delivered for him. But now he is stuck with
Robertson for better or worse.
</P>
<P>
   And it is likely to get worse. Robertson may have been an asset
in the South, but he is like a fine wine _ he doesn't travel well.
In other regions, Robertson's smear tactics will backfire unless
Bush disavows him. Bush says he didn't know what Robertson was up
to in Michigan, a cop-out if there ever was one.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Rudman can't defend himself. He said he wouldn't
respond in kind, however, because he has a policy of ignoring what
he considers to be ``trash commercials written by a group of
imbeciles.'' So there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a recent column, a numbers gremlin played with my computer
keys. Maryland Republican gubernatorial candidate Ellen Sauerbrey
was defeated in 1998, not last year. And California Sen. Dianne
Feinstein was re-elected in 1994, not 1996. She is running for a
third term this year.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
